## Chapter 1: Big Daddy (continued)

### The Dawn of Hedge Funds

- At the cusp of the 21st century, hedge funds emerged as capitalism's "unofficial kings"
- 2003-2006: Top 100 hedge funds doubled to **$1 trillion** — enough to buy all Shanghai Stock Exchange shares or Canada's entire annual economic output
- Hedge funds not new or unprecedented: **New York** magazine profiled them similarly in both 2004 and 1968
- 1968 article cited a fund manager who made **20% in a week, for seven weeks in a row**
- Both eras characterized by same traits: arrogance, secrecy, clandestine behavior

> "If you really know what's going on, you don't even have to know what's going on to know what's going on... You can ignore the headlines, because you anticipated them months ago."

### Alfred Winslow Jones: The Founding Father

- **Alfred Winslow Jones** invented the "hedged fund" in 1949
- Born **September 9, 1900** (9th hour, 9th day, 9th month) — fact he'd repeat tediously
- Son of expatriate American running **General Electric's** Australian operations; family owned first car in Australia
- Graduated **Harvard** 1923, but uncertain about career direction
- Spent year as purser on tramp steamer touring the world
- Worked as export buyer, statistician for investment counselor
- Joined **State Department** via foreign-service exam

### Berlin and Political Awakening

- Posted to **Berlin, December 1930** as vice-consul
- Germany in crisis: 8% output drop, 4.5 million unemployed
- **National Socialist Party** won 107 Reichstag seats three months earlier
- Met **Anna Block** — Jewish banker's daughter, socialite, left-wing anti-Nazi activist
- Anna operated underground from Berlin hospital maternity wing, later Paris underground
- Jones became "servant of her purposes, political and personal"
- Married Anna secretly; forced to resign State Department May 1932
- Returned to Berlin fall 1932 as "Richard Frost," working secretly for **Leninist Organization**
- Moved to London 1933 as "H. B. Wood," lobbying British Labour Party for military action against Hitler
- British authorities suspicious; discovered he attended **Marxist Workers School** in Berlin (organized by German Communist Party)

### Return to America and Academic Career

- Divorced Anna, returned to New York 1934
- Enrolled at **Columbia University** sociology graduate program
- Married **Mary Elizabeth Carter**, middle-class plantation girl from Virginia
- 1937 honeymoon in war-torn Spain; hitchhiked to front lines with **Dorothy Parker**
- Met **Ernest Hemingway**, who treated them to Scotch whiskey

### Witnessing America's Turmoil

- Europe's disintegration mirrored America's own turmoil
- **The Great Gatsby** → **The Grapes of Wrath**; Jazz Age → Depression
- October 1929 crash followed by brokerage collapses through early 1930s
- Financial canyons near stock exchange so quiet "you could walk the famous canyons near the stock exchange and hear only the rattle of backgammon dice through the open windows"
- Despite youthful adventures with undercover Left, Jones emerged **moderate and levelheaded**

### Doctoral Work and Political Evolution

- Late 1930s: researched doctoral thesis on whether same calamity could befall America
- Focused on links between Americans' economic conditions and attitudes toward property
- Goal: determine "to what extent, in our basic ideas, we are a united people, and to what extent we are a house divided"
- Decamped to **Akron, Ohio** with Mary; organized team for **1,700 field interviews**
- Statistical analysis concluded: **acute economic divisions did not carry over into polarized world-views**
- Repudiation of socialist assumptions from his youth; testimony to vitality of American democracy

### Launch into Journalism

- Thesis published as **Life, Liberty and Property** (1941) — became standard sociology textbook
- **Fortune** magazine published condensed version, offered Jones a job
- 1942 essay warned **Roosevelt's** economic statism needed dismantling post-war
- Respect for markets confirmed retreat from socialism toward political center
- Writing for Fortune mixed continued interest in redistributive programs

> "As conservative as possible in protecting the free market and as radical as necessary in securing the welfare of the people."

### "Fashions in Forecasting" (1948)

- March 1949 Fortune essay gave Jones opportunity to turn mind to finance
- Attacked "standard, old-fashioned method of predicting the course of the stock market"
- Traditional approach: examine freight-car loadings, commodity prices, economic data to determine stock pricing
- Jones cited moments when stocks shifted sharply **without changed economic data**
- Turned attention to **predictable patterns in investor psychology**
- Money = medium through which greed and fear expressed themselves; **barometer of crowd psychology**
- Natural fit for sociologist to find this hypothesis attractive

### The Feedback Loop Theory

- Investor emotions create trends in stock prices
- Stock market rise → investor optimism → further rise → more optimism
- Feedback loop drives prices up, creating **self-fulfilling trend**
- Trick: bail out when psychology turns around — greed turns to fear, pendulum reverses
- Profiled forecasters who believed stock charts held secret to financial success

### Ignoring Academic Economics

- Jones oddly ignorant of **Alfred Cowles** (father of statistical economics)
- Cowles published 1933 and 1944 studies reviewing thousands of investment recommendations
- "Can Stock Market Forecasters Forecast?" — three-word abstract: **"It is doubtful"**
- Jones cited Cowles selectively, mentioning evidence of trends in monthly prices
- Neglected to mention Cowles found **no trends in three-week intervals** or daily prices
- Cowles concluded any appearance of patterns was **too faint and unreliable to be traded upon profitably**
- Despite superficial reading, both agreed: **successful forecasters could not sustain performance**
- Forecasting a trend likely to destroy it; money follows advice, cutting trend in infancy
- Forecasters would "speed up the workings of the market while working themselves out of a job"

### Anticipating Hedge Fund History

- Jones anticipated decades of hedge fund history
- Financial innovators spotted profit opportunities; once understood by sufficient investors, **opportunity faded** (markets grew more efficient)
- 1950s-1960s: Jones destined to impose new efficiency on markets
- Nature of that change **not what he expected**

### Launching the First Hedge Fund (1949)

- By March 1949, launched world's first hedge fund
- Not sudden passion for finance; more preoccupied with political migration liberalism→socialism→back
- Late forties, two children, expensive New York tastes
- Needed money; efforts to earn more in journalism fizzled
- Left **Fortune** staff hoping to launch new magazine; two blueprints failed to attract financial backing
- Raised **$60,000** from four friends, put up **$40,000** of own money

### Twenty-Year Track Record

- By 1968: cumulative return of **just under 5,000%**
- Investor who gave $10,000 in 1949 now worth **$480,000**
- Five years to 1965: returned **325%**, dwarfing 225% return on hottest mutual fund
- Ten years to 1965: earned **almost two times as much as his nearest competitor**
- Performance rivaled even **Warren Buffett**

### The Innovation: Leverage and Short Selling

- Started in shabby office on Broad Street
- Investor **Winslow Carlton** (dapper, blue shirts, white collars, drove magnificent Packard convertible)
- Office: Royal typewriter, dictionary on stand, stock-exchange ticker, electromechanical calculating machine, couch for naps
- **True innovation: structure of fund**
- Standard practice: load up with stocks when market expected to rise, hold cash when expected to topple
- Jones improved: used **leverage** (borrowed to be 150% long) and **short selling** (borrowed stocks from others, sold expecting price fall)

### The Magic of Hedging

- Leverage and short selling used in 1920s (mostly by speculators with own money)
- 1929 trauma gave both techniques bad name
- Jones's innovation: "**speculative means for conservative ends**"
- Routine short selling as precaution insured portfolio against market risk
- Freed him to load up on promising stocks without worrying about Dow Jones collapse

> "You could buy more good stocks without taking as much risk as someone who merely bought."

### 1961 Prospectus Example

- Two investors, each with **$100,000**
- **Traditional investor**: $80,000 in best stocks, $20,000 in safe bonds
- **Hedged investor**: borrows $100,000 for total $200,000, buys $130,000 good stocks, shorts $70,000 bad stocks
- Hedged investor superior diversification in longs ($130,000 vs $80,000)
- Less market exposure: **net $60,000** vs $80,000
- Less stock-selection risk (diversification) and less market risk (hedging)

### Performance Comparison Tables

**Bull Market (20% rise):**
- Traditional: 30% gain on $80,000 = **$24,000**
- Hedged: 30% gain on $130,000 longs = $39,000; 10% loss on $70,000 shorts = -$7,000
- Net hedged gain: **$32,000** vs $24,000 traditional

**Bear Market (20% fall):**
- Traditional: 10% loss on $80,000 = **-$8,000**
- Hedged: 10% loss on $130,000 longs = -$13,000; 30% gain on $70,000 shorts = $21,000
- Net hedged gain: **$8,000** vs -$8,000 traditional loss

- Result defies basic investing rule: **higher returns by assuming higher risk**
- Hedged investor earns **third more**, even with less market risk and less stock-selection risk

### Understanding Volatility: The "Velocity" Concept

- Some stocks bounce more than others: different **volatilities**
- Buying $1,000 inert stock vs $1,000 volatile stock does not provide real hedge
- If market rises 20%: inert stock might rise 10%, volatile stock might rise 30%
- Jones measured volatility of all stocks — called it **"velocity"**
- Compared with volatility of **Standard & Poor's 500 Index**
- **Sears Roebuck** since 1948: swings 80% as big as market average → relative velocity of **80**
- **General Dynamics**: relative velocity of **196**
- Must adjust position sizes for volatility to create true hedge

### Separating Alpha from Beta

- Jones distinguished money made through stock picking (**alpha**) from money made through market exposure (**beta**)
- Later became commonplace terminology
- Jones tracked from the start with statistics honed amid Akron's industrial tensions
- Each evening (sometimes with children's help) looked up closing prices in **World Telegraph** or **Sun**
- Noted in pencil in dog-eared leather book
- Constructed chains of reasoning to decompose returns

**Example Calculation:**
- Long stocks worth $130,000 should have risen $1,300 (1% market rise)
- Actually rose $2,500
- Difference ($1,200 = 1.2% of $100,000 equity) = **alpha from stock selection**
- Short stocks worth $70,000 should have risen $700
- Actually rose only $400
- Difference ($300 = 0.3% of equity) = **alpha from short selection**
- Net long $60,000; 1% market rise = $600 (0.6% of equity) = **beta**
- Total gain: 2.1% of equity (1.5 percentage points from stock selection, 0.6 from market exposure)

### Conceptual Sophistication

- Calculations impressive in precomputer age
- Jones and small staff performed for **~2,000 firms at two-year intervals**
- More impressive: **conceptual sophistication**
- Techniques anticipated breakthroughs in financial academia of 1950s-1960s

### Anticipating Modern Portfolio Theory

- **1952**: **Harry Markowitz** published "Portfolio Selection"
- Twenty-five-year-old graduate student insights:
  - Investment art = maximize **risk-adjusted return**
  - Risk investor takes depends on stocks owned AND **correlations among them**
- Jones's velocity calculations effectively controlled risk (as Markowitz advocated)
- By balancing volatility of long/short positions, anticipated Markowitz's insight about portfolio risk depending on component relationships

### Practical vs. Theoretical

- Jones more practical than Markowitz
- 1952 paper ignored on Wall Street (impossible to implement)
- Correlations among thousand stocks = **half million calculations** (computer power unavailable)
- Mid-1950s: Markowitz attempted correlations for 25 stocks, demanded more memory than Yale economics department could provide
- **William Sharpe** developed variation rendering Markowitz's work useful
- "A Simplified Model for Portfolio Analysis" replaced calculating multiple stock relationships with calculating **single correlation between each stock and market index**
- Precisely what Jones's velocity calculations were designed to do
- By 1963, Jones implementing Sharpe's advice for over a decade

### Anticipating Separation Theorem

- Jones anticipated **James Tobin** (Nobel Prize winner)
- **1958**: Tobin proposed **separation theorem**
- Investor's stock choice should be separate from risk appetite question
- 1950s advisers assumed: widow shouldn't own go-go stock (Xerox); business executive shouldn't own stodgy utility (AT&T)
- Tobin's insight: choice of stocks separable from risk amount
- Risk averse: buy best stocks, commit only part of savings
- Risk hungry: buy same stocks, borrow money to buy more
- Nine years before Tobin published, Jones was onto same point
- Fund made one judgment about companies, second about risk level
- Adjusted risk using **leverage**

### Secrecy and Avoiding Regulation

- 1950s-1960s: almost nobody understood Jones's methods
- Secrecy deliberate (multiple reasons)
- Wanted to protect investment methods from competitors
- Brokers visiting A. W. Jones offices cross-examined about stocks, left with no idea what Jones men were thinking
- Wanted to avoid tax loopholes devised by **Richard Valentine** (attorney at Seward & Kissel)
- Valentine creative genius, cartoonishly absentminded (once phoned colleague's five-year-old, launched into lengthy tax exposition)
- Valentine realized: if managers took share of investment profits (not flat management fee), could be **taxed at capital-gains rate**
- Personal tax rates: could mean **25% to Uncle Sam vs 91%**
- Jones charged investors **20% of upside**
- Claimed inspired by Mediterranean history (not tax law): **Phoenician merchants** kept fifth of profits from successful voyages
- Performance fee (termed "**performance reallocation**" to distinguish from ordinary bonus attracting normal income tax) embraced by successive hedge fund generations

### Escaping Regulatory Oversight

- Reasons for secrecy: anxious to escape regulation
- Declined to register under **Securities Act of 1933, Investment Company Act of 1940, Investment Advisors Act of 1940**
- None applied because funds were "private"
- **Essential**: these laws restricted funds from borrowing or selling short (two central components of Jones's hedging strategy)
- Also imposed fee restrictions
- To sustain idea funds were private: **never advertised publicly**
- Marketed by word of mouth (sometimes = word between mouthfuls at dinner table)
- Much capital from network of intellectual friends: **Louis Fischer** (Lenin biographer), **Sam Stayman** (bridge convention inventor "Stayman over no-trump")
- 1961: set up second partnership rather than allow first to cross **100-member threshold**

### The Price of Secrecy

- Stealth allowed Jones escape regulatory oversight
- **Came at a price**: secrecy piques public curiosity
- Mid-1960s: hedge funds began attracting breathless commentary
- "Wall Street's last bastions of secrecy, mystery, exclusivity, and privilege" (**John Brooks**)
- "The parlor cars of the new gravy train"
- Threat of deadening regulation made Jones's clandestine style inevitable
- Thanks to pattern established early, **hedge funds forever mysterious, shadowy, resented**

### The Price of Ignoring Cowles

- Jones paid price for ignoring **Alfred Cowles's** writings
- Verdict: trends in market prices too faint to be profitable — **proved correct** (at least Jones's case)
- Efforts to call overall market direction **failed as often as they succeeded**
- **1953, 1956, 1957**: Jones lost money on market calls, leveraging himself when market did poorly and vice versa
- **1960**: Cowles published update reversing earlier finding of faint trends in monthly prices — **concluded they did not exist after all**
- Jones carried on trying to time market with no better results
- Early 1962: **net long 140%** of capital, whereupon market fell
- Turned bearish, but market turned up
- **August 1965**: particularly excruciating moment — net exposure of **minus 18%** (shorts exceeded longs by 18% of capital)
- Market embarked on hot rally
- Future hedge-fund managers proved **trend surfing can be profitable**
- Future academics revised Cowles's findings
- **Jones never turned profit by betting the charts** (even though chartism provided premise for hedged fund)

### The Real Source of Success

- Statistical methods revealed precisely how much money losing from bad market calls
- Funds still performed marvelously
- Reason: discovery stumbled upon almost accidentally
- Began with theories about trends created by investor sentiment → **blind alleys**
- Invented hedged strategy → **conceptually brilliant but not itself source of profits**
- Having designed hedged portfolio, **needed to choose stocks to put inside it**
- Through skill and temperament coincidence, devised way of assembling stock pickers who **beat the pants off Wall Street**

### The Model Portfolio System

- Jones knew he could not be great stock picker himself
- Investment novice; company balance sheet details never captured imagination
- Created system to get best out of others
- Starting early 1950s: invited brokers to run **"model portfolios"**
- Each man selected favorite shorts and longs, phoned in changes as though running real money
- Jones used paper portfolios as source of stock-picking ideas
- Statistical methods (separated stock selection from market effect) pinpointed each manager's results precisely
- Compensated brokers according to how well suggestions worked
- **Marvelous and unique**: getting brokers to phone in hot ideas before giving to others

### Competitive Edge in the 1950s

- System gave Jones edge over competitors
- 1950s Wall Street: **sleepy, unsophisticated place**
- Universities and business schools: practically nobody took finance courses
- Harvard investment course dubbed **"Darkness at Noon"** (unpopular lunchtime slot to save classroom space)
- Old investment institutions: trustees compensated by volume of assets, reached decisions by committee
- Jones's method broke mold: **each stock picker for himself**
- Substituted **individualism for collectivism**, **adrenaline for complacency**
- Even in 1960s (enterprise grown big, half dozen stock pickers on payroll), continued cultivating **Darwinian system**
- Convened remarkably few investment meetings (found committees intolerably tedious)
- Allotted each in-house manager segment of partners' capital, laid down desired market exposure, left manager to invest
- Year-end: managers who performed best = best rewarded

### The Information Advantage

- Could see results in how Jones men operated
- Wall Street 1950s-1960s: **information didn't reach everyone at once**
- No blast e-mails from brokers, no instant cable TV analysis
- Investment team with most hustle beat out sleepier rivals
- Jones men hustled hardest
- Model portfolio managers rushed to call in hot ideas
- In-house segment managers worked phones, scrambling for gossip and insights ahead of competitors
- Even in 1960s (Wall Street shrugged off postcrash stupor): **sheer diligence could set man apart**
- **Alan Dresher** (Jones stock picker): had idea of going to SEC offices to read company filings **the moment they came out**
- Extraordinary: **he was all alone** (rest of Street waiting for filings from post office in bundle)

### Linking Compensation to Results

- Linking compensation to results = **key to Jones's formula**
- When broker passed stock tip to normal mutual fund: **no connection between tip quality and broker payment**
- Mutual funds lacked Jones's system for tracking stock recommendations
- Mutual-fund companies paid thousands to salesmen who brought in investors' capital (little money to reward excellent research)
- Jones meticulous in paying for good research ideas, **paid handsomely**
- Young broker could see salary double if model portfolio recommendations generated profits
- Funds' performance fees divvied among Jones's in-house managers (according to whose segment did best)
- Jones devised two further sharpening incentives:
  - Each year successful segment managers given **extra capital to manage** (increased chances of generating profits in coming year, earning large bonus)
  - Unsuccessful managers received **less capital to play with**
- Innovation anticipating hedge funds of later times: Jones required **partners to have own capital in funds** (wealth and income riding on performance)

### Creating Competitive Multimanager Structure

- Without realizing significance, Jones created **competitive multimanager structure** used to great effect by later hedge funds
- Same structure reinvented 1970s by firm in Princeton, New Jersey
- Later dozens of hedge funds used it
- 1950s-1960s: combination of **Darwinist individualism** and **top-down risk control** almost unique to Jones
- Gave powerful advantage
- Market may be efficient (information reflected in prices to extent existing institutional arrangements allow)
- **Jones blew up those institutional arrangements**
- Scrapped staid committee meetings, paid people to perform
- **Created edge that brought in serious money**

### The Lunch with Barton Biggs (1964)

- Start of 1964: Alfred Jones invited young analyst to lunch at Manhattan club
- Jones in late fifties, achieved material comfort sought fifteen years earlier
- Family graduated from Dodge station wagon → Citroën DS → monstrous Mercedes
- Jones peered at young analyst, asked: **"When you go to pee in a restaurant urinal, do you wash your hands before or after you pee?"**

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

### The Decline of A.W. Jones

- **Barton Biggs** persuaded Jones's longest-serving fund manager to quit and start a rival fund, taking some of Jones's clients with him
- Every great investor's edge eventually unravels — techniques are understood and copied; profits foster jealousies among partners; defections follow
- By 1969, there were 200-500 hedge fund imitators; many run by former Jones employees or brokers
- **The Economist** reported $11 billion under management in the new industry — five times the figure from two years earlier
- The term "hedge fund" (a corrupted version of Jones's "hedged fund") entered the Wall Street lexicon

### The Hedge Fund Boom of the Late 1960s

- **Fortune** profiled Jones in 1966 as "the best professional manager of investors' money," though the magazine got a large photo of him
- Investors rushed to get money into Jones funds; ambitious young analysts sought jobs
- Jones himself earned "something in the millions"; his defectors acquired penthouses, helicopters, wine cellars, and bodyguards
- **New York** magazine proclaimed in 1968 that A.W. Jones was hedge funds' "big daddy"

### Regulatory Scrutiny

- In 1968, the **New York Stock Exchange** and **American Stock Exchange** began considering restrictions on members' dealings with hedge funds
- January 1969: **Securities and Exchange Commission** sent questionnaires to 200 hedge funds demanding information about their organization and market impact
- SEC wanted hedge funds to register under federal acts; complaints about the new upstarts seemed curious:
  - Hedge funds accounted for half the short interest in certain stocks
  - Nobody explained why short selling (which prevents unsustainable valuations) might be pernicious
  - Hedge funds turned over portfolios more aggressively than mutual funds, but this boost to market liquidity was portrayed as bad
  - Hedge funds were envied and adored while also being objects of irrational resentment

### Jones's Indian Summer and Decline

- 1966-1968: Jones's investors pocketed returns (after fees) of 26%, 22%, and 47%
- But this concealed trouble: The Jones funds were losing their edge
  - Stock pickers defected to set up rival firms
  - Jones's hedging principles no longer seemed relevant
  - The hedged-fund model deserved to drop its *d*: caught up in the bull market, they regarded shorting as a sucker's game
  - They pushed the boundaries of leverage, with each segment manager buying as many go-go stocks as possible
  - Velocity calculations fell by the wayside
  - Because the stock market was roaring and Jones was increasingly absent, stock pickers did what they wanted

### The End of the Go-Go Era (1969-1973)

- Jones had been lucky: he opened his hedged fund just as the crash trauma was wearing off
- 1950: only 1 in 25 American adults owned stocks; by late 1950s, 1 in 8 did
- S&P 500 rose from 15 at Jones's launch to a peak of 108 in late 1968
- The new financial culture changed: trustee bankers were eclipsed by go-go types for whom the crash was ancient history
- Blissful optimism found its apotheosis in **the Great Winfield** (**Jerry Goodman**, the financial writer and broadcaster known under the pseudonym "Adam Smith")
- Goodman/Winfield entrusted his money to twentysomething managers with no memories and no fear

> "Show me a portfolio, I'll tell you the generation. You can tell the swinger stocks because they frighten all the other [older] generations." — The Great Winfield

### Jones's Fatal Flaw: The Multimanager Structure

- The multimanager structure empowered go-go segment managers, but wasn't designed to save Jones from a sudden reversal
- The more the market rose, the more Jones's performance-tracking system rewarded aggressive segment managers who took the most risk
- No mechanism for getting out before disaster struck
- May 1969: stock market started to fall, shedding a quarter of its value over the next year
- Year ending May 1970: Jones lost 35% of client money
- September 1970: Jones's 70th birthday party at his country house — he fretted that segment managers would resent his spending: "I hate the boys seeing me spending money like a drunken sailor"
- After two decades of eminence, Jones's investment edge was gone; the markets had caught up with him

## Chapter 2: The Block Trader

### The Economic Watershed (1969-1973)

- 1969-1973 marked a watershed for the American economy
- Previous two decades: jobs plentiful, wages rose, finance almost quaintly stable
- Dollar pegged firmly to gold; interest rates moved within a narrow range capped by regulation
- Late 1960s: inflation tore this world apart
  - Below 2% in first half of decade, hit 5.5% in spring 1969
  - Federal Reserve jammed on monetary brakes, squeezing the stock market
- 1971: **Nixon administration** forced to acknowledge inflation had eroded the dollar's value, abandoned the gold standard
- Suddenly money could be worth one thing today, another tomorrow — fueling further inflationary pressure
- Another round of monetary tightening followed; market crashed again in 1973-74
- Go-go era was over; the 1960s were over

### The First Hedge Fund Era Ends

- Close of 1968 to September 30, 1970: the 28 largest hedge funds lost two thirds of their capital
- Their claim to be hedged turned out to be a bald-faced lie; they racked up hot performance by borrowing hard and riding the bull market
- By January 1970, only 150 hedge funds remained (down from 200-500 one year before)
- The crash of 1973-74 wiped out most of the rest
- SEC gave up on regulating a sector now too small to bother with
- 1977: **Institutional Investor** magazine asked where all the hedge funds had gone
- 1984: a survey by **Tremont Partners** identified only 68 hedge funds
- The **A.W. Jones partnership** withered: from $100 million+ managed in late 1960s to $35 million in 1973 and $25 million a decade after that
- Performance fees dried up in an era of nonperformance

### The Rise of Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz & Company

- Adversity did not rule out success; the first winner amid the new uncertainty was **Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz & Company**
- Dominant partner **Michael Steinhardt** became a legend — both for his success as a trader and his personality
- Raised by a single mother in hardscrabble Brooklyn; father confrontational, short-tempered, addicted to gambling
- Admitted to **University of Pennsylvania** at 16; graduated at 19
- By mid-1960s (age ~25), he had become "the hottest analyst on Wall Street"
- Short, barrel-chested, prone to terrifying outbursts — face and temples would turn red, unleashing a bloodcurdling torrent of abuse

### Launching the Hedge Fund (1967)

- Steinhardt quit the brokerage business in 1967, launching a hedge fund with **Jerrold Fine** and **Howard Berkowitz**
- Bull market still very much alive
- Equipped offices with a pool table, proclaimed intellectual superiority of youth, ignored their lawyer's advice
- Sounded too much like a Jewish delicatessen
- First full year (1968): loaded up on story stocks of the era
  - **King Resources** (claimed to have discovered new oil and gas reserves)
  - **National Student Marketing** (believed in the youth market)
  - Technology companies with names featuring "Data" or "-onics"
- Year-end result after subtracting fees: "My God, I am rich" — Jerry Fine
- They were up 84%; each had become millionaires

### Surviving the 1969-70 Bear Market

- 1969: The bull market ended; other go-go funds blew up
- **Fred Mates**, the top-performing mutual-fund manager of 1968, found himself working as a bartender
- Almost alone among gunslingers, Steinhardt, Fine, and Berkowitz sensed the long postwar expansion had finally overreached and uncertainty was beginning
- They had read **Benjamin Graham**, who 15 years earlier made the fateful decision not to buy shares in **Xerox/Haloid**, saying he saw no reason to buy stocks on future growth
  - Haloid sextupled in the next two years
  - The cult of the growth stock had since gone unquestioned
- But in 1969, the troika concluded this cult had gone too far; it was one thing to pay a premium for bright prospects, another to pay so much that uninterrupted, supersonic growth was extrapolated into the hereafter

### Actually Hedging

- Start of 1969: Steinhardt and friends shorted enough story stocks to balance their long positions — unlike most hedge funds, they were actually hedging
- When S&P 500 fell 9% that year, the firm preserved all but a sliver of its capital
- Following year (S&P 500 dropped another 9%), the troika actually made money
- Having survived 1969-70, the firm went on the offensive in 1971, catching the bounce from the bear market
- When **Fortune** published its list of top 28 hedge funds that year, Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz was the only one to have actually expanded during the shakeout
- Partnership racked up a return of 361% since opening in July 1967 — 36 times better than the stock market index over that period

### The Contrarian Turn (1972)

- 1972: the young troika turned pessimistic again, going beyond the cult of growth investing
- The edifice of America's postwar confidence seemed to be cracking:
  - Nixon administration covering up the truth about failures in Vietnam
  - Covering up inflation with an impractical wage-and-price-control program
  - America's finest companies covering up the truth about themselves with accounting shenanigans
- **Jerry Fine** and **Howard Berkowitz** found red flags in footnotes of annual reports regularly
- **Leonard Spacek**, chairman emeritus of **Arthur Andersen** (most respected accountant of the era): "financial statements are a roulette wheel"
- "The research reports that were released in the early seventies were so simplistic that we looked at them as nonsense" — Howard Berkowitz
- "Deferred this, different tax rate that, capital gains that they put as operating earnings" — Jerry Fine

### Positioned for the Crash

- Stock market was trading at levels that reflected broad political and financial delusions
- 1969: the young troika shorted enough stocks to protect themselves from a downturn
- 1972: they positioned their portfolio so short positions greatly outweighed their longs, and waited for the crash

### The 1973-74 Payoff

- At first, it did not happen — market sailed along for rest of 1972
- Fund was down 2% in the year to September, when S&P 500 rose 9%
- Then the payoff came: S&P fell 2% in the year to September 1973 and a shocking 41% the following year
- Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz racked up gains of 12% then 28% after fees — extraordinary performance in a bear market
- Young partners were raking in the money while just about every other portfolio manager was losing his proverbial shirt
- Results looked great but were not universally popular
- As stock market careened downward, desperate sellers called up the troika's trading desk, knowing the firm had borrowed shares to sell them short, urging that now would be the time to buy shares back to cover their positions
- **Michael Steinhardt** generally gave these supplicants the cold shoulder
- The troika watched their short positions generate ever bigger profits as the market rout continued
- Old prejudice against short selling came back with a vengeance: Steinhardt, Fine, and Berkowitz were resented as arrogant, greedy, and even un-American
- Betting against American companies portrayed as one step away from treason
- Thinking back on that period, Steinhardt recalls: "That was, for me, the height of professional satisfaction"

### The Success Formula: Contrarianism

- The success of Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz demonstrated the capacity for contrarianism that marked later hedge funds
- A.W. Jones invented the hedge-fund structure to control market exposure
- His go-go imitators turned it into a way of maximizing market exposure
- The troika made it into something else — a vehicle for betting against conventional wisdom
- Aggressive contrarianism became a sort of company credo, especially for Michael Steinhardt

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

### Block Trading Ethics and Market Impact

- **Block trading collusion**: Brokers tipped Steinhardt about large institutional orders before execution, allowing him to short ahead and profit from the price drop
- **Will Weinstein** (Oppenheimer): "Everyone had a hundred behind it" — described practices as "not collusive but just honest attempts to protect each other"
- Steinhardt's frank admission: "I was being told things that other accounts were not being told. I got information I shouldn't have. It created a lot of opportunities for us. Were they risky? Yes. Was I willing to do it? Yes."

### Steinhardt's Trading Record

- **28 years in markets, only 4 losing years** — probability of 1 in 11,000
- Block trading "represented a meaningful portion of the noise, but not the profits" (though likely understated)
- Focus on trading was the partnership's most distinctive edge among the founding partners

### SEC Investigation and Regulatory Response

- **January 1970**: SEC alleged Steinhardt purchased Seaboard Corporation block to help broker boost price ahead of public offering
- **1976**: Settled without admitting wrongdoing
- Suspicion of collusion remained unproven throughout 1970s
- Regulators acknowledged own failings in **1975 and 1978**, attempted reforms:
  - Created **"consolidated tape"** to print all stock transactions
  - Required bids and offers be similarly reported
  - Goal: spread trading information evenly, eroding Wall Street's insider edge

### Economic Benefits of Hedge Funds

Two stabilizing contributions from the troika (Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz):

1. **Contrarianism dampened market swings**: Sold during 1972 bubble, went long at end of 1974 crash
2. **Monetary analysis innovation**: Applied **Tony Cilluffo's** analytical techniques to asset pricing, making future bubbles less likely

**Block trading as liquidity provision**: Institutional investors needed to trade large chunks of stock; Steinhardt provided liquidity they could use or ignore. The service likely outweighed the wrongdoing. Outsider investors (mutual funds, pensions) were the losers — while Steinhardt's investors were the winners.

### Post-1987 Market Changes

- **Black Monday aftermath**: Big block-trading desks pulled back from business
- *New York Times* (December): 25,000-share blocks now disrupted prices as much as 100,000-share blocks had before — market became horribly unstable
- Rumor of block sale in Ford or IBM could drive share price down
- SEC promised to investigate the "troubling lack of block trading"
- Ironic reversal: Fast-trading hedge funds became preferable to their sudden absence

### Steinhardt's 1978 Sabbatical

- Fall 1978: Took sabbatical to "shrink his waistline and expand his head" — seeking meaning beyond wealth
- Skeptics doubted commitment: "There's as much chance of Michael giving up Wall Street for a year as there is of Vladimir Horowitz giving up the piano permanently"
- Returned fall 1979, broke up with partners, marched into the 1980s

## Chapter 3: Paul Samuelson's Secret

### Samuelson's Efficient Market Paradox

**1967 congressional testimony**: **Paul Samuelson** cited PhD dissertation showing randomly chosen stock portfolios beat professionally managed mutual funds
- Committee chairman sounded incredulous about "random" meaning dice or darts
- **1970**: Samuelson won Nobel Prize
- **1974**: "Most portfolio decision makers should go out of business—take up plumbing, teach Greek, or help produce the annual GNP by serving as corporate executives"

> "Even if this advice to drop dead is good advice, it obviously is not counsel that will be eagerly followed."

But left room for exceptions: "People differ in their heights, pulchritude, and acidity. Why not in their P.Q. or performance quotient?"

- Exceptional investors wouldn't rent themselves cheaply — they'd form small partnerships to capture gains
- These would be **hedge funds**
- **1970**: Became founding backer of **Commodities Corporation**

### Commodities Corporation Origins

- Among first boutiques for hard-core "quants" — computer-wielding modelers called **"rocket scientists"**
- Premise: Harness "large scale econometric analysis, impossible prior to the introduction of computers"
- **Paul Cootner** (MIT colleague): Contributed to efficient-market theory
- Hired Apollo project programmer — literally a rocket scientist
- Structured as corporation rather than partnership, but otherwise typical hedge fund
- Used both long and short positions, used leverage

**Samuelson's investment**: $125,000 stake, became active board member

### F. Helmut Weymar — The Driven Leader

**PhD dissertation**: Anticipated cocoa price using historical data on economic growth, chocolate consumption, drought/humidity in West Africa

- Tall, bespectacled, distinguished Northern European air, high cheekbones
- Moved cities frequently as child — left him independent, determined to make money "beholden to nobody"

**Graduate student cocoa trade**: Built mathematical model of frozen-orange-juice industry predicting price would double
- Borrowed $20,000 to buy warehouse consignment
- Price shot up as predicted
- Local supermarkets refused to buy wholesale from student — had to sell back to warehouse, losing one-fifth of profit

**Nabisco cocoa trading**: Model predicted prices would fall below forecast, so Weymar bought cocoa futures by the truckload
- CFO worried about "smoke screen of quantitative jargon"
- Cocoa prices almost doubled after African crop failures
- Weymar sold stockpile at vast profit

> "This wasn't a period of maximum modesty or self-doubt in my life."

### Founding Commodities Corporation

**Frank Vannerson**: Bearded, subdued economics PhD — contrasted with Weymar's sunny confidence
- Described as "medieval friar with leather sandals and corded robe" or "friendly psychotherapist"
- PhD thesis on wheat market complemented Weymar's cocoa expertise
- Raised **$2.5 million** in start-up capital
- **Princeton, New Jersey farmhouse headquarters** — flowering trees, acres of lawn

**Office culture**:
- Weymar: Huge walnut desk, big red leather chair
- Vannerson: Polo shirt, khakis, dog named Peanuts
- Informal, egalitarian — cook invited to meetings
- German shepherd **Cocoa** (lost leg to car collision)
- Seven professionals, six support staff
- Horseshoes at lunch, softball after markets closed

**Philosophy**: Not about salesmanship or *looking* like market insider — about beating market with computer models, math, superior information
- Trading theories discussed at regular seminars, blackboard with formulas
- Long way from stock-jockey ethos at A.W. Jones or pizza-strewn chaos of Steinhardt

### Team Composition — Fundamental Analysis Focus

**Econometricians built models** predicting where prices ought to be — profits when reality caught up with forecasts

- **Vannerson**: Wheat
- **Paul Cootner** (MIT): Pork-belly market econometric model
- **Kenneth Meinken** (Rutgers economist): Soybeans and feed grains
- Goal: Diversify exposure across commodities to avoid concentration in any one market

**Weymar's cocoa model data**:
- Tracked correlation between weather and cocoa yields in Ivory Coast and Ghana
- Predicted harvest before official reports by tracking rain and humidity patterns
- **Hans Kilian** (German): Toured African countryside in Land Rover, counted cocoa pods (25 per tree), recorded number/length/condition
- Land Rover frequently broke down
- Battled to get Ghanaian currency to pay local workers
- Effort confirmed or corrected supply projections from weather patterns

### The Corn Blight Fiasco (1971)

**U.S. cornfields hit by fungal disease** (corn blight)
- Plant experts predicted reappearance the following year on bigger scale
- Corn futures moved up in expectation of scarcity
- Weymar and colleagues saw chance for edge

**Retained plant pathologist** at Rutgers University (advising New Jersey state):
- Increased research budget, covered conference travel expenses
- **Investigation conclusion**: Blight fright was overdone — plethora of scare stories more infectious than alarmist bias of media
- **Pathologist's verdict**: Corn prices would come down
- Traders built vast short positions in anticipation

**Friday night CBS News special on corn blight**:
- Featured **Illinois state plant pathologist** — state with far more corn than New Jersey
- Illinois expert predicted **catastrophic corn harvest**

**Monday opening**: Corn futures jumped so steeply trading immediately suspended
- Commodity exchanges limit daily movements to dampen extreme swings
- Couldn't exit positions until Tuesday
- **Firm's $2.5 million start-up capital reduced to $900,000**
- Weymar's company crashing before his eyes

**Resolution**:
- Rutgers pathologist eventually proved right — no corn blight
- Closed short positions at absolute top of market
- Brought firm within hairbreadth of closure

### Post-Crisis Recovery and Philosophy Shift

**Relationships frayed** after corn debacle:
- Cofounder kept shotgun in office to shoot rabbits and pheasants
- Several founding board members wanted to withdraw capital
- Despite quantitative sophistication and PhDs, team "appeared to lack that high 'performance quotient' that Samuelson was after"

**Weymar's response** — romantic hero approach:
- Had lost all money as student on bad bets, recovered at Red Sox game bleachers over beers
- "No more ready to give in" — fascinated masochism, wallowing in adversity
- **July 1971 board meeting**: Agreed to give Weymar last chance — firm would close if lost another $100,000

**Four of original seven founding professionals left** (including Cootner)
- Recovery came soon
- Laid foundations for one of most successful trading operations of the era

### New Risk Management Philosophy

**Rethinking after 1971**: Experience taught humility
- Data crunching could turn into curse — exaggerated faith breeds hubris leading to unsustainably large positions
- "Most dangerous people in the world are very smart traders who had never gotten their teeth kicked in"
- Colleague suggested "putting Weymar in charge of risk controls was like putting Evel Knievel in charge of road safety"

**First-year risk system** (designed by **Paul Cootner**):
- Mathematically elegant but too complex to enforce effectively
- Trading capital in one big pot
- Traders could dip freely but charged penal interest on large, volatile positions
- Theory: Trader must be brimming with confidence to double up in turbulent market
- Reality: Corn blight proved brimming confidence alarmingly abundant
- Clerical staff too far behind tracking exposure — effectively no risk control

**New system post-Cootner**:
- Resembled segment-manager system at A.W. Jones
- Each trader treated as independent profit center, allocated capital pot reflecting previous performance
- Forced traders to control bets — crucial in volatile commodity markets
- **Position limits**: If trader lost half initial capital, had to sell all positions and take month off
- Required memo explaining miscalculations

### Trend Following Emerges

**Fresh respect for price trends** developed after corn debacle
- Efficient-market theory: Trends don't exist (random-walk consensus dominant 1970s–1980s)
- Hard to get alternative views published in academic journals

**Frank Vannerson's discovery**:
- Obtained **Dunn & Hargitt** (Indiana firm) historical commodity price data
- Spent year at Nabisco analyzing daily prices for 15 commodities
- By March 1970 opening: Satisfied price trends really existed, regardless of academic assertions
- Devised computer program for automated trading — **Technical Computer System (TCS)**
- One of first automated trading systems spawned by hedge-fund industry

**Weymar initially skeptical**: Trend-following seemed disarmingly simple
- Buy things going up on theory they'll continue up; short things going down
- Vannerson's program tried distinguishing lasting trends from temporary upticks
- Weymar doubted anyone could make serious money from something so trivial

**Summer 1971**: Weymar reversed himself
- Corn episode humiliation: Virtue of automated system was risk controls programmed in from start
- TCS proved superior at calling market
- Weymar's cocoa model misjudged direction expensively during first year
- Vannerson's trend-following made money consistently

**After corn blight**: Allocated more capital to TCS
- Risk-control system prohibited traders from committing >10% capital betting against trend
- Trends for controls were ones identified by Vannerson's program
- **Paul Samuelson** won over despite trend following having little academic standing

### Michael Marcus — The Generalist Trader

**1974 recruit**: Far removed from Weymar's econometrician conception
- Not specialized in one commodity
- Lacked economics degree
- No use for computers, little for math
- Dropped out of psychology PhD program
- One of first hired without doctorate

**Ten-year performance**: Increased trading account value by **2,500%**
- Years when profits exceeded all other traders combined

**Personality**: Intense, quiet, fearsomely controlled
- Believed most foods contained poisons, monitored intake
- Once purified with raw vegetable/fruit diet, became so emaciated hired dietician-driver to restore equilibrium
- Splashed winnings on elaborate parties and exotic travel
- Owned ~10 homes, sold some without spending single night
- Chartered jet, bus converted to traveling dwelling with entourage
- Took kickboxing lessons with international champion

**Trading approach** — combined fundamentals and charts:
- Arrived in office with oversized briefcase packed with market reports
- Used sticky tape to attach handwritten notes to key pages
- Scanned newsletters, data on supply/demand drivers
- Thought through threatening scenarios for portfolio
- Keen student of price charts — "window into psychology of investors"
- Focused on interaction between charts and fundamentals
- If fundamentals bad but charts showed uptrend, investors had digested setback possibility — "nowhere to go but upward"

**Respect for trends from cotton exchange experience**:
- Watched traders respond to tempo of colleagues
- Crescendo of shouting vs. falling back exhausted
- If commodity headed past prior day's high, decent chance it would keep riding upward on excitement wave
- Took large positions at crossover moments with stop-loss protection
- "Like mounting surfboard, ready for wave" — catch wave on less than half attempts, but winning rides worth 20-30x small losses

### Marcus and Currency Trading

**Natural pioneer in currency trading** after Nixon abandoned dollar-gold link
- Chicago Mercantile Exchange began trading futures in seven free-floating currencies (May 1972)
- Investor psychology generated same waves in currency markets as commodities
- By mid-to-late 1970s: About 1/3 of Marcus's trading in currencies
- By end of decade: 2/3 in currencies
- New "macro" trader emerging — became scourge of central bankers in 1980s and beyond

**Libertarian political outlook** proved useful in stagflationary 1970s:
- Markets destabilizing while governments are heroes (some eras)
- Stagflationary 1970s: Libertarian view that big government screws up frequently vindicated

**Nixon price controls** (early 1970s):
- Functional equivalent of misguided currency controls of later years
- Example: Plywood fixed at $110 per thousand square feet
- Construction boom created plywood demand
- Builders willing to pay much more than mandated price
- Warehouses shipped to Canada and back to evade controls, or performed "added-value services" (shaving sliver off planks, charging $150/thousand square feet)
- Builders who wouldn't pay black market prices couldn't get wood
- Started buying in futures market (not regulated)
- Marcus bought plywood futures by truckload — value virtually doubled

**Post-1973 inflation surge**:
- Incompetent government debasing currency by inflating money supply
- Trader likely to get rich by leveraging up, holding huge positions in grains, beans, metals
- **1974**: Coffee up 25%, rice up 67%, white sugar doubled
- Anyone buying commodities on margin multiplied money

**Commodity reversal**:
- Food commodities embarked on equally tradable downward trend
- Sugar lost 67% of peak value, cotton and rubber lost 40%, cocoa fell >25%

**Carter administration stimulus**: Dollar drop by 1/3 against yen and deutsche mark
- Big moves in new currency-futures markets created ample opportunity

### Saudi Arabia Currency Peg (Early 1975)

**Marcus spotted intervention as enticing as Nixon price controls**:
- Saudi Arabia pegged currency to dollar
- As export revenues ballooned with oil price, economy flooded with money
- Created upward pressure on exchange rate
- Revaluation uncertain — Saudi Arabia could live with capital inflows and inflation

**Logic**: Following currency speculators who later attacked pegs everywhere
- If no revaluation, devaluation inconceivable
- **Hugely attractive one-way gamble**: Near guarantee of not losing, no guarantee of winning

**March 1975**: Saudi Arabia abandoned dollar link and revalued
- Marcus took huge riyal positions, leveraging with borrowed money
- "Sleeping perfectly soundly"
- **Made another killing**

### Triumph of Flexibility — 1970s Success

**By end of 1970s**: Commodities Corporation prodigiously successful
- Corn-blight fiasco faded memory
- Trend surfing (Michael Marcus style) delivering 50%+ returns for many traders
- Capital swelled from <$1 million low point to ~$30 million
- Farmhouse acquired extra wing, new building commissioned
- Hired new traders, research assistants to track charts, new administrative staff
- **1980 profits**: Astronomical $42 million
- After $13 million bonuses to 140 employees, outearned 58 of Fortune 500 companies
- Flew employees and families first class to Bermuda company retreat
- Traders hijacked occasion to lambaste Weymar for free-spending ways
- "Recognized that Commodities Corporation was a phenomenon"

**Triumph of flexibility**: Moving beyond econometric analysis to focus on trends
- Pragmatism crops up repeatedly in hedge fund history
- Innovation often depends less on grand academic breakthroughs than on humble trial and error
- Willingness to go with what works, never mind theory

**Examples**:
- A.W. Jones expected chart following would call broad market, turned out to be blind alley, succeeded by improvising incentive system for stock pickers
- Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz started as equity analysts, succeeded via block trading plus eccentric monetary policy focus

**Commodities Corporation benefited from 1970s context**:
- Financial markets are mechanisms for matching risk-avoiders with risk-takers
- **1960s**: Not many sought commodity price fluctuation insurance
- Government minimum prices for agricultural products, surpluses prevented price rises
- Chicago Board of Trade traders whiled hours reading newspapers on soybean pit steps
- **Inflationary 1970s**: New volatility created rush for insurance
- Food companies hedged high price risk, growers hedged low price risk
- New volatility in exchange rates created currency hedging rush
- Multinationals recognized dollar rise/fall could upend performance
- **First half 1970s**: Chicago Board of Trade turnover rose rapidly, pit traders had no time for newspapers

**Insurance seekers profited speculators** (insurance sellers):
- Farmers and food companies bought/sold futures to shed risk, not from sophisticated price direction views
- Speculators with sophisticated views had upper hand
- Earned especially good profits due to relatively little competition
- Exchanges imposed limits on contracts a speculator could buy (limiting "insurance" supply, boosting value artificially)
- Commodities Corporation pocketed higher insurance premiums, arranged off-exchange trades with wholesalers to circumvent restrictions

**Most important factor**: Firm's conversion to trend following
- By developing TCS and demonstrating random walkers were wrong, **Vannerson** gave confidence to hire trend followers like Marcus
- Turned combination of fundamental analysis and charts into company credo
- **Years later**: Financial academia caught up with Vannerson's discovery
- **1986**: *Journal of Finance* paper found trend following in currency markets earned sizable profits
- **1988**: Study found same for commodity futures
- Amusing symmetry: **Scott Irwin** (1988 paper author) prompted to investigate by encounter with **Dennis Dunn** (Dunn & Hargitt firm provided Vannerson data for TCS)
- Examining same price series Vannerson worked on almost two decades before, Irwin reached same conclusion

### Bruce Kovner — The Next President

**1977**: Michael Marcus placed ad for assistant trader
- Answered by unlikely character: Harvard PhD program dropout working part-time as cab driver
- Marcus called Weymar: "Helmut, I have in my office the next president of Commodities Corp."

**Bruce Kovner**: Love at first sight for Marcus
- Young man tall, imposing, big head topped by thick hair
- Exuded confidence and natural ease
- Striking intellectual range
- Part of political scientists circle at Harvard (James Q. Wilson, Daniel Patrick Moynihan)
- Devoted time to full-time music study
- Worked on political campaigns
- Contributed freelance articles to *Commentary* on subjects from music to economic growth purposes
- Trading just another learned skill

**Trading backstory**:
- Conversation with friend prompted futures market study
- Borrowed $3,000 against MasterCard, turned into $22,000
- Marcus and Weymar tested candidate with finance questions and discussions
<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

### Bruce Kovner's Success at Commodities Corporation

- **Bruce Kovner** impressed Weymar with deep reading of financial classics: Charles Mackay's *Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds* and contemporary newsletters
- Hired directly as trader, not assistant, based on intellectual richness
- Averaged 80% gains per year over next decade, launched **Caxton Corporation** hedge fund
- Became major figure in conservative politics, arts patron, philanthropist
- **Michael Marcus** noted Kovner's psychological strength: could let go of distractions, didn't overthink trades, had nerverless temperament
- Took massive hit on silver position but showed up at administrative meeting unfazed

### Kovner's Trading Methods

- Combined fundamental analysis with chart attention—confirming shift away from Weymar's pure model-driven approach
- Hired assistants to track numbers and compose charts, never overpaying them
- **Contrarian insight**: Most profitable opportunities arise when you have *no* fundamental information—sudden market moves without discernible reason suggest insiders know something not yet public
- Example: Dollar unexpectedly strengthened; Kovner and Marcus assumed insiders caught wind of Carter dollar support program announcement and immediately bailed out, avoiding annihilation
- **"Carry trade" strategy (1981)**: Kovner and **Roy Lennox** bought currencies trading at big discount in forward market vs. spot market
- Traditional view: low forward rate signals coming depreciation (compensates for high interest rates)
- **Kovner's insight**: Low forward rate usually reflects *high interest rates*—signals currency might *rise*, not fall
- Example: Spanish banks paying 7% interest → peseta worth 7% more in spot than one-year forward → discount was compensation for missing interest, not depreciation signal
- Carry trade raked in glorious profits for next decade until rivals caught on

### Commodities Corporation's Decline

- Weymar's success brought challenge: New York brokers pressed Marcus and Kovner to manage outside capital directly
- Traders already tempted to go independent due to Weymar's vast administrative overhead
- Wall Street offered alternative funding source plus fat fees
- After internal argument, traders won; Kovner soon managed millions of Wall Street cash
- By 1983 Kovner launched Caxton Corporation—already independent hedge-fund mogul in all but name
- **Paul Tudor Jones** and **Louis Bacon** received seed capital from Commodities Corporation, learned from firm, eventually went independent
- Bacon hired **Elaine Crocker** from Commodities Corporation as president of **Moore Capital**
- Jones turned down job offer from Weymar, happy to take seed money but not join
- 1984 internal revolt forced Weymar to promise lower overhead and return to "the simple life"
- Center of gravity shifted from Weymar to younger generation of New York hedge funds

## Chapter 4: The Alchemist

### George Soros's Early Life and Education

- Arrived at **London School of Economics** in 1949 as young Hungarian refugee
- Survived Nazi occupation in Budapest by separating from family, assuming Christian identity, hiding with father's acquaintances
- Witnessed corpses in streets, mangled figures with bound hands and crushed heads
- Hawked jewelry to black-market dealers to help family survive
- Left Hungary in 1947, worked as dishwasher, house painter, busboy, headwaiter in London
- Found job as lifeguard at swimming pool—read Adam Smith, Thomas Hobbes, Niccolò Machiavelli
- **Karl Popper** most inspired Soros: fled Austria to escape Nazism, central contention that humans cannot know truth, best approach is groping through trial and error
- Popper's *The Open Society and Its Enemies* gave Soros lifelong desire to make contribution to philosophy
- Political dogmas (Nazism, communism) claimed intellectual certainty to which neither was entitled
- Named his future philanthropy the **Open Society Institute**

### Soros's Financial Career

- Left LSE with mediocre grades, sold handbags in northern Wales, eventually landed job with Hungarian brokerage in London
- Found way to New York in 1956, figured he could stomach Wall Street for five years to save for life as independent philosopher
- Too good at investing to quit
- 1967: head of research at **Arnhold and S. Bleichroeder**, venerable Wall Street brokerage specializing in European stocks
- 1969: launched own $4 million long/short stock-picking vehicle, **Double Eagle Fund**, managed under Bleichroeder umbrella

### Theory of Reflexivity

- Melded Popper's ideas with knowledge of finance into synthesis called **"reflexivity"**
- Popper suggested listed company details too complex for human mind to understand—investors rely on guesses and shortcuts approximating reality
- **Soros's addition**: Those shortcuts have power to change reality—bullish guesses drive stock price up, allowing company to raise capital cheaply and boost performance
- **Feedback loop creates double uncertainty**: people incapable of perceiving reality clearly, *and* reality itself affected by these unclear perceptions
- Challenged efficient-market view: rational investors can arrive at objective valuation, market reaches efficient equilibrium
- To Popper disciple, this premise ignored elementary limits to cognition

### Applying Reflexivity to Investment

- Soros continued hiding away in study of weekend home, struggling to express philosophy on paper
- Ideas affected investment approach despite later suggestions he superimposed theory as after-the-fact rationalization
- 1970 investment note on real-estate investment trusts explained workings in explicitly reflexive terms
- Conventional security analysis tries to predict future earnings, but for these trusts future earnings depend on investors' perceptions
- If investors bullish → pay premium for share → inject cheap capital → boost earnings → reinforce bullish appearance → persuade others to buy at even greater premium
- **Soros's trick**: Focus neither on earnings course nor on psychology driving appetite, but on *feedback loop between the two*
- Predict each would drive the other forward until trusts completely overvalued and crash inevitable
- Real-estate trusts followed boom-bust sequence Soros expected; fund made fortune going up and shorting down

### Setting Up Independent Firm (1973)

- Left Bleichroeder to set up own company, rented office block away from co-op on Central Park West
- Brought along partner **Jim Rogers**: irascible, workaholic analyst
- Rogers conducted discussion while wincing and gasping on exercise bike rigged with laptop and phone for maximum multitasking
- Soros looked for moments when unstable equilibrium might reverse
- Example: financial deregulation transforming dull banking sector into sexy stock market sector—made fortune from bank stocks
- **Arab-Israeli war of 1973** changed game for defense industry: Soviet weaponry performed well, demonstrating U.S. faced greater challenge
- Soros predicted Pentagon would persuade Congress to authorize catch-up investments, plunged into defense stocks
- Willing to bet the store on game-changing moments without waiting for conclusive evidence
- If found investment idea attractive on cursory examination, figured others would be seduced too; perfect cognition impossible, no point sweating details
- **Switzerland skiing vacation example**: bought *Financial Times* at bottom of chairlift, read about British government plan to bail out Rolls-Royce, called broker from mountaintop to buy British government bonds
- Motto: **"Invest first, investigate later"**

### Early Success and Growing Fame

- By start of 1981, achieved success beyond wildest imaginings
- **Soros Fund** (1973) and **Quantum Fund** (1978) accumulated $381 million assets, multiplying initial capital almost hundredfold despite tough 1970s equity markets
- Personal fortune $100 million, becoming philanthropist
- June 1981: *Institutional Investor* profile called Soros "the world's greatest money manager"
- Rivals echoed Nastase tribute to Bjorn Borg: "We're playing tennis and he's playing something else"
- Soros celebrated own brilliance: "I stood back and looked at myself with awe: I saw a perfectly honed machine"
- "I fancied myself as some kind of god or an economic reformer like Keynes (each with his General Theory)"
- "Or, even better, a scientist like Einstein (reflexivity sounds like relativity)"
- But tragedy: success as investor required visceral as well as intellectual focus on markets, could be intensely physical
- Thought of himself as boxer in training sacrificing personal life for victory, or sick person with parasitic fund swelling inexorably inside body

### Crisis and Restructuring (1980-1981)

- 1980: parted company with Jim Rogers, blamed Rogers for driving younger employees out, frustrating hopes of spreading workload and delegating
- Distraction of search caused investment performance to crater
- After gaining 100%+ in 1980, **Quantum Fund down 23%** in 1981—first-ever loss
- Hit by wave of redemptions halving capital from $400 million to $200 million
- September 1981: humiliated Soros entrusted remaining money to other investors
- Like **Michael Steinhardt** three years earlier, took break from markets

### Return with New Balance (1984)

- Returned to full-time investing 1984 with new sense of balance
- Psychoanalyst helped slay demons during midlife crisis
- Recognized success and permitted himself to relax—knowing might kill golden goose but also knowing not doing so would render success pointless
- Visceral identification with fund ended; compared to painful operation extracting hard ball of calcium from salivary gland
- "That is what happened to my hang-ups. Somehow, they dissolved when they were brought to light"
- Starting August 1985, kept diary of investment thinking, hoping discipline of recording thoughts would sharpen judgments
- **"Real-time experiment"** dense, repetitive, filled with complex ruminations about scenarios never materializing
- True portrait of speculator at work, free of biases afflicting retrospective explanations
- Captured one of greatest triumphs: bet against dollar described as **"the killing of a lifetime"**

### The Dollar Trade (1985)

- Came out of stock-picking culture of Wall Street, but reflexive feedback loops led to thinking broadly about opportunities
- Like **Michael Marcus** abandoning cotton exchange floor to become generalist trader
- Saw no point knowing everything about few stocks hoping to anticipate small moves—game was knowing little about lot of things to spot where big wave might come
- Post-Bretton Woods floating currencies emerged as natural playground
- Dollar value based on traders' perceptions, which Soros believed were flawed and could reverse dramatically at any time

### Challenging Equilibrium Theory

- 1970s and into 1980s: most economists believed currency markets, like equity markets, tended toward efficient equilibrium
- If dollar overvalued → U.S. exports hurt, imports boosted → trade deficit → foreigners don't need as many dollars to buy American goods → relatively low demand drives dollar value down, cutting trade deficit until equilibrium reached
- Traditional view: speculators can't disrupt this process
- If anticipate currency's future path correctly, merely accelerate arrival at equilibrium
- If judge wrong, slow correction but delay won't persist because speculators lose money
- **Soros saw equilibrium theory failed to explain actual behavior**
- Between 1982 and 1985: U.S. ran growing trade deficit (implying weak dollar demand), but dollar strengthened
- Reason: speculative capital flows pushed dollar up, and these flows tended to be self-reinforcing
- When hot capital flowed into United States → dollar rose → rising dollar drew in more speculators, driving exchange rate *away* from equilibrium
- If speculators real force determining rates, currencies would exhibit prevailing boom-bust sequence
- First stage: speculators develop prevailing bias, bias reinforces itself, driving exchange rate further from trade equilibrium level
- More out of line exchange rate got, more speculators feel confirmed, more imbalance in trade keeps growing
- Eventually enormous trade imbalances overwhelm speculators' bias, reversal occurs, speculators swivel 180 degrees, new trend takes off in opposite direction

### Timing the Dollar Reversal

- Summer 1985: challenge was judging timing of dollar's reversal
- August 16: suspected moment might be close at hand
- President Reagan reshuffled administration at start of second term, new team appeared determined to bring dollar down to reduce U.S. trade deficit
- Trade fundamentals pointed same way: interest rates falling, making it unrewarding to hold dollars
- If combination of political action and low interest rates could persuade even few speculators to abandon greenback, upward trend could suddenly reverse
- In mature phase of cycle, speculators wanting to ride dollar already aboard, hardly any buyers left—takes only few sellers to make market U-turn
- Agonized about whether turn was imminent
- If U.S. growth accelerated → interest rates rise → dollar reversal less likely
- If banks entered credit contraction cycle (falling collateral values, reduced lending feeding back) → trouble in banking sector could slow economy sharply, push interest rates downward
- "Who am I to judge?" Soros wondered; then added, **"The only competitive edge I have is the theory of reflexivity"**
- Theory led him to weight risk of self-reinforcing banking mess especially heavily, inclined to bet against dollar
- Certain technical indicators pointed same direction
- Having digested arguments from economics, philosophy of reflexivity, and psychology of charts, Soros arrived at investment conclusion: **time to short the dollar**

### Building the Position

- Despite inner doubts, Soros plunged decisively
- August 16: **Quantum owned $720 million of main currencies against which dollar would fall** (yen, German marks, sterling)—exposure exceeded all equity in fund by $73 million margin
- Appetite for risk startling: "As general rule, I try not to exceed 100 percent of Fund's equity capital in any one market, but I tend to adjust my definition of what constitutes a market to suit my current thinking"
- Idea that hedge fund should actually be hedged casually discarded
- Three weeks later, September 9: experiment begun badly
- Dollar buoyed by batch of bullish U.S. economic indicators, currency bet cost Quantum $20 million
- Embarked on soul-searching, continued to focus on weak banking system
- Charts whispered luck might turn: German mark appeared following pattern suggesting sharp rise be coming
- Brought further dimension into analysis: putting himself in shoes of monetary authorities
- Argued interest rates likely to stay low even if economy proved stronger than expected
- Federal Reserve reluctant to raise rates because of responsibility as regulator of banks; wobbly lenders don't need more expensive capital
- Moreover, Fed would have room not to raise rates because Reagan's reshuffled administration determined to rein in budget deficit, relieving inflationary pressure
- Weighing options September, Soros resolved to stick with losing bet against dollar, but abandon half if market moved further against him

### Investment on Knife Edge

- Investment decisions often balanced on knife edge
- Truth: markets at least somewhat efficient, most information already in price
- Art of speculation to develop one insight others overlooked then trade big on small advantage
- Soros would pick through evidence, formulate thesis, then turn on a dime
- Stray remark from lunch guest could tip balance of argument, Soros leap up and instruct trader to get out of positions
- **Decision to hold dollar shorts in second week of September one of those close calls**—if blinked after initial loss, life story would have turned out differently

### The Plaza Accord (September 22, 1985)

- Soros did not blink
- Less than two weeks after second diary entry, September 22: **Treasury secretary James Baker** assembled counterparts from France, West Germany, Japan, Britain at **Plaza Hotel in New York**
- Five powers promised coordinated intervention in currency markets to push dollar downward
- News of Plaza accord delivered Soros overnight profit of **$30 million**
- Yen rose more than 7% against dollar next day—largest one-day jump in history
- Soros somewhat lucky: seen clearly ahead of time Reagan administration wanted to manage dollar down, but had no idea how intention would play out, no foreknowledge of Plaza meeting
- What happened after Plaza nothing to do with luck—everything to do with Soros's emergence as legend
- Rather than cashing in bet and resting on laurels, Soros piled on harder
- Turn in dollar finally come; everything he knew about reflexive feedback loops argued dollar's initial fall merely the beginning

### Doubling Down After Plaza

- Plaza Hotel meeting ended Sunday in New York, already Monday morning in Asia
- Soros immediately called brokers in Hong Kong with orders to buy additional yen for portfolio
- Next day, when firm's own traders began taking profits in small subportfolios, Soros succumbed to rare moment of fury
- Charged out of office, yelling at traders to stop selling yen, telling them he would assume their positions
- Traders wanted to throw arms around success before it ran away
- But as far as Soros concerned, top governments of world telegraphed dollar headed down—Plaza given signal, so why shouldn't he hog more yen positions?
- Over next days, Soros continued buying
- By Friday after Plaza meeting, added **$209 million to holdings of yen and German marks**, established extra **$107 million worth of short positions in dollar**
- If risk in this posture: Plaza communiqué might turn out paper tiger, declaration suspiciously thin on actionable detail, depended on uncertain commitment of governments to follow up with concrete measures
- But more than any other New York fund manager, Soros had web of political contacts in Washington, Tokyo, Europe—network encouraged him to believe Plaza was serious
- By early December loaded up on another **$500 million worth of yen and German marks**, adding almost **$300 million to short position in dollar**
- "I have assumed maximum market exposure in all directions," Soros recorded in diary

### The Killing of a Lifetime

- December 1985: Soros concluded first phase of real-time experiment
- Looked back on period begun with hypothesis dollar ripe for reversal, culminated with theory's confirmation
- Repeated conjectures about collapse in banking system had turned out red herring: "the outstanding feature of my predictions is that I keep on expecting developments that do not materialize"
- But errors dwarfed by one central success
- Soros understood nothing more substantial than slippery perceptions driven up dollar, therefore trigger could set off sudden reversal
- Because grasped system's instability, understood Plaza accord's meaning faster than others
- Plaza was trigger; didn't matter details of new policy not yet filled in
- Political jolt kick-started new trend, which would now feed on itself and become self-sustaining
- Rewards astonishing: in four months from August, **Soros's fund jumped 35%**, yielding **profit of $230 million**
- Convinced act of writing diary contributed to performance, Soros joked profit represented highest honorarium ever received by author
- When diary published two years later as part of Soros's book *The Alchemy of Finance*, reviewers mocked dense prose
- But as one commentator said, financial alchemy certainly beat boiling up mercury with egg yolks

### The Publication of *The Alchemy of Finance* (May 1987)

- Publication confirmed Soros's status as celebrity
- Diary struck chord with several younger stars in hedge-fund firmament—saw honest picture of speculator wrestling anxiously with multiple imponderables
- **Paul Tudor Jones** (whiz-kid cotton trader who received seed capital from Commodities Corporation, later built wildly successful **Tudor Investment Corporation**) made *Alchemy* required reading among employees
- In foreword to *Alchemy*, Jones declared having published, Soros should now beware—invoked scene from WWII movie *Patton*
- Great American general savors victory over Field Marshal Erwin Rommel; Patton prepared for battle by reading Rommel's tactical writings
- In climactic moment, peers out from command post, delivers Jones's favorite line: **"Rommel, you magnificent bastard. I read your *book*!"**
- Soros having too much fun to fret about warnings
- Becoming kind of public intellectual he admired at LSE; expensively tailored figure topped with large glasses and thick tangle of hair began popping up on magazine covers
- Central European accent added to exotic aura
- Profiles said Soros student of global investing years before most fund managers discovered Tokyo on map; embraced futures, options, forward currency contracts; went long and short with equal facility
- From eerily quiet trading floor in Manhattan, ruled over markets of world, hobnobbing with global financiers in five languages
- *The Economist* called him "the world's most intriguing investor"
- Cover story in *Fortune* suggested he might rank ahead of Warren Buffett as **"the most prescient investor of his generation"**
- But just as flattering profile in *Institutional Investor* in 1981 presaged that year's humiliating 23% loss, adulation of 1987 presaged calamity

### Warning Signs (September 1987)

- *Fortune* cover story appeared September 28, 1987, title posed question: **"Are stocks too high?"**
- After long bull market that begun at start of decade, stocks in Standard & Poor's index of four hundred industrial companies sold at average of three times book value—highest level since World War II
- *Fortune* introduced Soros as first expert witness on stock market's level, explained Soros was sanguine
- Fact that trend followers driven market upward did not mean crash coming soon: "Just because a market is overvalued does not mean it is not sustainable"
- For evidence to support view, Soros pointed to Japan, where stocks soared even higher above traditional valuations
- Eventually crash would come, but would hit Tokyo before Wall Street
- Soros not alone in being bullish
- Following week **Salomon Brothers** issued research note promising bull market would continue into 1988
- Week after that, **Byron Wien** (well-known Morgan Stanley strategist and Soros friend) predicted "a new high before this cycle is over"
- Era of leveraged buyout; debt-fueled takeovers driving stock prices steadily higher
- Lives of corporate raiders stuff of drooling magazine features
- Mood captured by hitherto unknown financier **P. David Herrlinger**, who announced $6.8 billion offer for Dayton Hudson Corporation
- Herrlinger appeared on front lawn to tell reporters offer might or might not be hoax—"It's no more of a hoax than anything else"
- News of apparent takeover sent Dayton Hudson stock into stratosphere
- But hoax is what it was; Herrlinger soon removed to hospital

### Reflexivity and the Buyout Mania

- Buyout mania neatly fitted Soros's ideas on reflexivity
- Takeovers feeding on themselves: as each acquisition announced, stock of every company in sector jumped, prospects of returning acquired companies to stock market at profit grew rosier
- Avalanche of loans to finance deals kept coming; spiral drove prices further from approximation of fundamental value, just as Soros theory predicted
- Of course, sooner or later takeover deals would collapse under weight of own debt, trend would reverse itself
- But seemed no strong evidence reversal would come soon
- Soros continued to pursue new avocation as Wall Street's philosopher-in-chief, holding court to journalists, appearing on television shows
- October 5: Soros invited one of new fans over to office
- Guest was **Stanley Druckenmiller**, hottest mutual-fund manager on the Street, read *Alchemy*, expressed interest in meeting
- Soros held forth grandly, offered Druckenmiller a job
- Wanted successor who could run Quantum, leaving him more time for philosophy and philanthropy; money management wearing on him
- Druckenmiller refused to be lured easily, but two struck up close relationship
- Druckenmiller tall and broad shouldered as Soros compact; plainspoken as Soros complex; unflashy and middle American as Soros exotic and middle European
- But two got along well; Soros (late fifties) would pontificate, Druckenmiller (midthirties) had ego sufficiently in check to listen
- Although shared many views about market, funds positioned differently
- Druckenmiller decided market break coming, short Wall Street; **Quantum short Japan but long U.S. market**
- Indeed, Soros recently added to team of stock pickers, Quantum racking up eye-popping returns by loading up on hot takeover stocks—**"garbitrage" stocks** as wags of Wall Street called them
- By riding market wave, Soros's team up some 60% by end of September; everything going wonderfully

### The Crash Unfolds (October 14-19, 1987)

- October 14: Soros published article in *Financial Times* reaffirming view crash would arrive in Tokyo
- Wednesday morning headed off to Harvard's Kennedy School to give talk on boom-bust theory
- After delivering lecture, emerged to find Wall Street sold off
- Newswires reporting Congress might raise taxes associated with corporate mergers—move could silence one engine of bull market
- **Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 3.8%** that day—move should have caught Soros's attention
- Knew market far from equilibrium, knew booms can be quickly followed by sharp busts
- As ruefully confessed later, **"That's when I should have been in the office and getting the hell out of the market"**
- Thursday stocks continued head down; Friday dove precipitously
- After markets closed Friday, Soros received visit from new confidant
- Three-day sell-off convinced Druckenmiller Dow given up enough ground; according to his charts, prices fallen to point from which would probably bounce upward
- That Friday afternoon, **Druckenmiller switched from short to long position**
- Soros listened to friend, spread raft of charts in front of him
- Charts prepared by **Paul Tudor Jones**, other admirer of *Alchemy*, whom Soros spoke with frequently
- Druckenmiller examined patterns, sensed panic rising in gut
- Jones's charts appeared to show he committed disastrous error
- Lines on paper illustrated stock market's historical tendency to accelerate downward whenever upward sloping parabolic curve broken
- Suggested parallel between market of 1987 and market of 1929—**maybe collapse was coming**
- Next morning Druckenmiller visited Jack Dreyfus (patriarch of Dreyfus family of mutual funds where Druckenmiller working)
- Dreyfus instructed his secretary to keep charts not just of broad market indices but of individual stocks
- "We went over all these individual charts and I knew I was cooked. What I saw wasn't bunch of stocks necessarily down lot. They had just broken out," meaning broken out of congestion point and would now accelerate downward
- "Stock after stock after stock had just made clean break right there.... Clearly I had misread the situation"
- By focusing on broad market, Druckenmiller missed alarming action in individual shares—there is old saying among chart watchers that **soldiers lead generals**
- Druckenmiller scared to death for rest of weekend
- Monday bailed out of positions as quickly as could; by late morning flipped 180 degrees, again short the market
- That day, **October 19**, went down in history as **Black Monday**
- **Dow Jones index lost 22.6% of value**—largest drop since venerable index launched fifty-one years earlier
- By flipping position so rapidly, Druckenmiller escaped worst of chaos
- Same not true of Soros: did best to bail out of market, but running more money than Druckenmiller; garbitrage stocks riding high just days earlier hard to unload in panic
- Around lunchtime, when Druckenmiller completed reversal but Soros still desperately selling, market descended into pandemonium
- "People didn't believe their stocks could go down that fast," one Wall Streeter recalled
- She steadied herself by looking out window at hot dog stand: so long as hot dogs were selling, world could not be ending
- Monday evening Soros reassessed situation
- Wall Street hit him hard, but short position in Japan paid off as Nikkei stock index fell, cushioning losses
- Rumors extraordinary collapse in New York caused by newfangled instrument known as **"portfolio insurance"**, promised investors protection against market fall
- Insurance worked by selling futures as market weakened, putting floor under investor's potential loss
- But when thousands of insurance policies triggered futures selling in weak market, result was meltdown unprecedented in history
- If this account right, obvious message for Soros: market collapse triggered by program trading rather than fundamental factors more likely to be corrected soon—perhaps rebound coming
- Tuesday morning, sure enough, market rallied
- Soros seized opportunity to pile back into market, but Japanese positions hit by extraordinary bad luck
- Established short position on Nikkei index by selling futures in Hong Kong (more liquid market)
- When stocks collapsed Black Monday, masters of Hong Kong futures exchange decided to staunch losses by closing it down
- When Wall Street began to rally Tuesday, portending rally next day in Japan, Soros could not get out of short position
- Wednesday **Nikkei leaped 9.3%**—biggest one-day gain since 1949; Soros could do nothing
- Few minutes before markets closed in New York Wednesday, Soros spoke again with Druckenmiller
- Dow rallied strongly for two days, Druckenmiller thought another turn was coming
- Studied history of crashes, seen pattern: sharp fall in market usually followed by wild two-day rally, but then market would collapse back to its low again
- That Wednesday afternoon, Druckenmiller told Soros he was short the market
- Soros not persuaded; consulted other confidants, convinced Black Monday been freak caused by portfolio insurance
- Druckenmiller early riser, woke up Thursday morning nervous as goat
- Market closed strongly previous evening; Soros might prove right historical pattern would not hold because of anomaly of portfolio insurance
- But when checked in on action in London, saw stocks were getting killed
- If New York took cue from London, Druckenmiller's short positions would come good and Soros in trouble
- Around 8:00 A.M., Druckenmiller got call from futures desk at Salomon Brothers
- **"There's an elephant in the marketplace and the futures could open under two hundred,"** broker informed him
- This was bombshell: futures closed at 258 night before; instant fall to 200 under pressure of elephant trader's selling would represent drop of almost quarter
- Druckenmiller figured might as well position himself for this drama in case really did occur
- Placed order with broker to close short positions if futures contracts fell to 195
- At rock-bottom level, Druckenmiller would be happy to take profits
- Market opened, elephant crashed down upon it
- Futures fell to 200 and below; Druckenmiller's orders with Salomon all filled, **yielding 25% return on position held only since previous evening**
- By about ten o'clock morning, elephant's selling completed, market stabilized
- Druckenmiller reckoned time for yet another flip in position
- Remembering conversation of previous afternoon, Druckenmiller picked up phone and called Soros
- **"George, I just wanted you to know I was negative last night but I think maybe this is the bottom. Some crazy person just sold the hell out of this thing. Like, really recklessly."**
- Soros sounded calm, detached: **"Right now I'm licking my wounds. I'll come back and fight another day"**
- Not until that weekend Druckenmiller realized what happened
- Picked up newest edition of *Barron's*, read that **elephant in market been none other than Soros**
- Full story, which *Barron's* reported partially, connected to trouble in Japan
- After huge leap Wednesday, Tokyo risen again Thursday
- Soros wanted out of short position in futures market, but no way could sell until Hong Kong authorities reopened exchange
- Meanwhile bleeding money
- Coming on top of losses in New York market Monday, **Quantum risked sudden evaporation of confidence that can destroy any leveraged fund**
- Once lenders sense you in trouble, start calling in loans; calls force you to sell stocks into weak market, setting off death spiral
- When Soros saw London market fall early Thursday, portending another sell-off in New York, decided time to jump for sidelines
- Been too slow to get out of market Monday, did not want to let that happen twice in week
- **"I don't understand what's going on. We've just got to move to cash. There'll be another day to play."** Then gave order to trader **Joe Orofino** to get out of market by selling S&P futures on Chicago Mercantile Exchange
- Orofino placed sell order with brokers at **Shearson Lehman Hutton**
- **Quantum's entire $1 billion position**
<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

### Soros's Worst Call: Black Monday 1987

- Soros decided to go to cash on Black Monday—"perhaps the worst call of his career"—costing Quantum ~$200 million
- Quantum went from +60% for the year to +10% in roughly a week; $840 million vanished
- Episode revealed a key weakness: **the larger hedge funds grew, the harder it became to enter/exit without moving markets**
- If Quantum had been smaller like Druckenmiller's fund, Soros could have exited swiftly Thursday without cratering prices
- Soros's trading style assumed ability to turn on a dime; when that assumption failed, he was in trouble

### The Aftermath and Soros's Recovery

- Many money managers' confidence was shattered; **Michael Steinhardt** recalled feeling depressed and alone after the crash
- Soros felt tired of running Quantum but never doubted his abilities
- His recovery after the crash "ranks among his greatest accomplishments"
- Week or two after Black Monday, Soros shorted the dollar with a gutsy leveraged position—it paid off
- Quantum ended 1987 up 13%, despite languishing in red only two months earlier
- Media reaction swift: anonymous source to *Times* of London: "It took 20 years to make George Soros a genius; four days to make him a jerk"
- *Forbes* recalled Soros's bullishness in the *Fortune* cover story weeks earlier
- By year-end 1987, rumors of Soros's financial death were premature
- *Financial World* listed Soros as second-highest earner on Wall Street (after **Paul Tudor Jones**, chartist and Patton aficionado)

### Soros and the Birth of Modern Macro Hedge Funds

- Soros's 1987 recovery cemented his status as an investment folk hero
- His example helped create what became known as the **"macro" hedge fund** in its modern form
- **John Maynard Keynes** (1924-1946) invested the College Chest of King's College, Cambridge in global markets using many modern macro techniques
- Keynes speculated in currencies, bonds, equities on global scale; went long and short; used leverage
- After WWII, stable inflation, regulated interest rates, and immobile currencies killed Keynes's macro tradition
- Keynes himself helped negotiate fixing exchange rates at **Bretton Woods conference**
- After Bretton Woods system unraveled in 1970s, macro investing began to stir again tentatively

### Two Streams Converge into Macro

- **Equity types** (like **Michael Steinhardt**) realized interest rate shifts could drive stock markets; starting in 1980s, they bet directly on interest rate movements by speculating in bonds (first US, then international)
- **Commodity investors** (like **Michael Marcus** and **Bruce Kovner**) started trading cotton, gold, etc.; as commodity markets created new contracts on currencies and interest rates, they surfed these instruments
- Until publication of Soros's *Alchemy*, equity and commodity traditions remained separate
- Equity investors came from fundamental analysis culture; commodity traders from charts and trend following
- **Soros's example bridged both tribes**: *Alchemy*'s real-time experiment combined fundamental analysis with belief in trends; combined economists' language with chart watchers' instincts
- Soros "managed to communicate with both halves of the hedge-fund house, reminding each that there was wisdom in the other"
- Within a few years, commodity people like **Paul Tudor Jones** and equity people like **Stan Druckenmiller** were simply called "macro" investors

### Post-Crash Analysis: Blaming Portfolio Insurance

- Black Monday was picked over for deeper meaning
- Modern financial engineering (later conflated with hedge funds) was blamed for the debacle
- Engineers created destabilizing feedback loop: market fall → insurance-based selling → further fall → more insurance selling
- **Mark Rubinstein**, Berkeley economics professor and coinventor of portfolio insurance, descended into clinical depression
- He fretted that weakening American markets might tempt Soviet Union to attack, making him personally responsible for nuclear conflict
- Soros believed portfolio insurance created Black Monday—but markets had crashed periodically throughout history
- Foreign markets without portfolio insurance also suffered precipitous falls
- US postmortems found that of $39 billion stock sold Oct 19 via futures/cash markets, only ~$6 billion triggered by portfolio insurers
- Low-tech villains equally important: many investors had standing stop-loss orders with brokers
- Fears of crash widespread in run-up, so psychological explanations mattered too
- *Atlantic Monthly* headlined "The 1929 Parallel"; *Wall Street Journal* superimposed graph of 1920s market decline on morning of Black Monday

> "The tools of finance were, in the end, just tools. People bought portfolio insurance or put in stop-loss orders because of the skittish atmosphere of the moment."

### Wall Street's Gyrations vs. Efficient-Market Theory

- Larger lesson: Wall Street's gyrations dealt crippling blow to **efficient-market theories** Soros long criticized
- Over one week, corporate America's value bounced like a pachinko ball—nothing efficient about this
- "The theory of reflexivity can explain such bubbles, while the efficient market hypothesis cannot," Soros wrote later—and he was broadly right
- No coincidence efficient-market thinking originated on American university campuses in 1950s/1960s—most stable enclaves in most stable country in most stable era in memory
- Soros, who survived Holocaust, war, and penury in London, had different view of life
- After Black Monday, academic consensus began coming around to him
- Crash was humiliation for Soros in investing terms but **vindication in intellectual terms**

### Three-Part Assault on Efficient-Market Theory

**1. Statistical Foundation Challenge**

- Efficient-market hypothesis based on precarious assumption: price changes conform to **"normal" probability distribution** (bell curve)
- Numbers at median frequent; numbers in tails rare to point of vanishing
- Early 1960s: **Benoit Mandelbrot** argued tails might be fatter than normal bell curve assumed
- **Eugene Fama**, father of efficient-market theory, knew Mandelbrot and conducted tests confirming Mandelbrot's assertion
- If price changes normally distributed, jumps >5 standard deviations should show up once every 7,000 years in daily price data
- Instead, they cropped up once every 3-4 years
- Fama and colleagues buried this discovery—too awkward to live with
- Rendered statistical tools of financial economics useless, since modeling abnormal distributions was largely unsolved problem in mathematics
- **Paul Cootner**, efficient-market theorist and cofounder of Commodities Corporation, complained:

> "Mandelbrot, like Prime Minister Churchill before him, promises us not utopia but blood, sweat, toil and tears. If he is right, almost all of our statistical tools are obsolete—least squares, spectral analysis, workable maximum-likelihood solutions, all our established sample theory, closed distribution functions. Almost without exception, past econometric work is meaningless."

- To prevent toppling into intellectual abyss, economics profession kept eyes trained the other way
- Mathematics of normal distributions was generating stunning breakthroughs
- 1973: trio of economists produced revolutionary method for valuing options—thrilling new financial industry born
- Mandelbrot's objections brushed off: "The normal distribution is a good working approximation," Fama contended

**2. Institutional Assumptions Challenge**

- Crash forced reexamination: in terms of normal probability distribution, Oct 19 plunge had probability of 1 in 10^160 (1 with 160 zeroes after it)
- Put in perspective: event would not be anticipated even if stock market remained open for 20 billion years (upper end of expected universe duration) or reopened for further 20-billion-year sessions following successive big bangs
- **Mandelbrot** abandoned financial economics after brush-off in early 1970s, returned with vengeance
- His Soros-like thinking on **"chaos theory"** emphasized small pieces of information could generate large price moves via complex feedback loops
- Acquired cult following among money managers

- Black Monday also forced reconsideration of **institutional assumptions**
- Efficient-market theory assumed investors always had means to act: if they knew IBM worth $90 vs. prevailing $100, they'd sell short until trading moved price down to $10
- Assumed knowledgeable speculators could find enough IBM stocks to borrow to sell short
- Had to gloss over fact that real-life "knowledge" IBM worth $90 would be less than certain
- Speculation always involved risk; only so much risk speculators could shoulder
- They could not necessarily be counted on to move prices to their efficient level

- Before 1987, these quibbles seemed insignificant
- Great mass of ordinary investors might lack means/confidence, but efficient-market theory pinned hopes on exceptional minority
- Would take only small handful of investors armed with information and capital to pounce on mispricings and correct them
- **Black Monday demonstrated sophisticated investors would not always succeed in correcting prices**
- In chaos of market meltdown, brokers' phone lines jammed with calls from panicking sellers; hard to get through and place order
- Any leveraged investor feared credit lines might be canceled; access to borrowing (assumed straightforward in efficient-market models) was uncertain in reality
- Most important: sheer weight of selling made it too risky to go against trend
- When whole world selling, doesn't matter whether sophisticated hedge funds believe prices fallen too far—buying is crazy

**3. Homo Economicus Challenge**

- At minimum, efficient-market hypothesis did not apply to moments of crisis
- Crash raised further question: if markets were efficient, why had equity bubble inflated in first place?
- Answer seemed to lie partly in institutional obstacles faced by speculators
- Summer 1987: investors could see plainly stocks selling for higher multiples of corporate earnings than historically
- But if market determined to value them that way, it would cost money to buck it
- Hedge fund managers knew better than anyone that borrowing stocks to short is difficult; few skilled operators who do this have limited war chests
- Because of these institutional realities, overvaluation might well last
- **Efficient-market assumption of wise speculators pushing prices into line was, at minimum, exaggerated**

- Third post-1987 assault on efficient-market theory went after protagonist at center of economists' models: **impeccably rational figure known as *Homo economicus***
- When investors could revise valuation of corporate America by 25% in single day, something other than rational analysis was in play
- *Homo* was not fully *economicus*
- Economists suddenly open to ideas explaining extent of divergence
- 1988: **Richard Thaler** of University of Chicago began publishing regular features in *Journal of Economic Perspectives* pointing out instances where human choices violated economists' expectations of rational beings
- To Soros, who obsessed about limits to cognition since student days in London, it was another victory

### Vindication for Hedge-Fund Industry

- Triple attack on efficient-market theory (statistical, institutional, psychological) was in some ways vindication for hedge-fund industry
- Helped explain how **Michael Steinhardt's** block trading or **Helmut Weymar's** commodity speculators could have done so well
- Showed market practitioners had often been ahead of academic theorists
- Realization that market efficiency is imperfect encouraged wave of finance professors to launch own hedge funds
- Persuaded sophisticated endowments to pour money into their coffers, triggering industry's headlong growth after 1987
- **Darker side**: If markets not always efficient and rational, their effects on society might be pernicious too
- Boom-bust sequences could distort and destabilize economy, damaging ordinary workers and households
- If markets could be demons, surely fast-trading hedge funds must be demons on steroids?
- This suspicion, however exaggerated, haunted hedge funds repeatedly as they entered golden era of expansion

## Chapter 5: Top Cat

### Warren Buffett's Coin-Flipping Contest

- Late spring 1984: Columbia Business School hosted clash of financial titans
- **Michael Jensen** (academic finance dean) made case for efficient-market view
- **Warren Buffett** challenged him
- Jensen rehearsed random walkers' argument: if stock pickers remain in business, only because befuddled laymen have "psychic demand for answers" about where to invest
- Answers are worthless; money managers who appear to defy random-walk hypothesis are merely lucky
- Sure, some beat market for five years straight—but if you asked million people to flip coins, some would flip five heads in a row
- There is no skill in coin flipping, and investment is no different

### Buffett's Rejoinder: The Orangutan Parable

- Buffett delivered rejoinder that could serve as **hedge-fund manifesto**
- Began by playing along with Jensen's argument
- Invited audience to imagine national coin-flipping contest
- Start: everyone in America flips coin; those who turn up tails withdraw
- After 10 rounds, 220,000 flippers left—human nature being what it is, survivors would get cocky
- Rarities would occasionally admit to attractive opposite sex their technique and marvelous insights into flipping
- After 20 rounds, 215 remaining contestants would start to wax insufferable, publishing fatuous books on art/science of coin flipping
- Then some business-school professor would point out: if 225 million orangutans engaged in coin-flip-a-thon, results would be same
- 215 egotistical orangutans with 20 straight winning flips

- Having made Jensen's argument better than Jensen, **Buffett proceeded to cut holes in it**
- If 215 winning orangutans distributed randomly about country, their success could be dismissed as luck
- But if 40 of 215 winners hailed from same zoo, wouldn't something else explain their coin flipping?
- Phenomena that appear statistically random can appear altogether different when you consider their distribution
- If rare cancer common in particular village, you would not put that down to chance—you would analyze the water

### Stock-Picking Success Not Randomly Distributed

- Buffett argued stock-picking success is not randomly distributed
- On contrary, **clusters of excellence spring from certain "villages"** (defined by approach to investment, not geography)
- To demonstrate: Buffett laid out records of nine money managers from **value-investing tradition** started by **Ben Graham** (Buffett's mentor)
- Three had worked at Graham-Newman Corporation mid-1950s; others converted to Graham approach by Buffett or his associates
- Buffett insisted he had not cherry-picked examples; reporting results of *all* Graham-Newman alumni for whom records existed and all fund managers he'd won over to value-investing method
- Without exception, without copying one another's stock choices, each of Ben Graham's heirs had beaten the market
- Could this be simple fortune?

> "Buffett's general point was indisputable. When investment managers are viewed merely as sets of performance numbers, the handful of success stories can be dismissed as products of chance—the equivalent of ten-heads-in-a-row coin flippers. But if investment managers are understood as belonging to distinct intellectual 'villages' or styles, their success may be concentrated in a way that is not random."

- Story of hedge funds features several high-performance clusters
- Most famous created by booming North Carolina native: **Julian Robertson**

### Julian Robertson and Tiger Management

- Masters of market can sometimes be aloof—no use for flattery and tolerance that lubricate human affairs
- Just facts; you make money or you don't; social skills won't change bottom line
- Visiting legendary macro trader **Louis Bacon** in his office one day, fellow hedge-fund manager found Oz-like figure hidden behind banks of screens
- When Bacon later bought private island, seemed little to be gained—he was already as isolated as he could be

- **Julian Hart Robertson** came from different tradition
- Charmer in southern way, networker in New York way; far from being coldly in control, mood could swing alarmingly
- Tall, confident, athletic of build—guy's guy, jock's jock
- Hired in his own image
- To thrive at Robertson's **Tiger Management**, you almost needed the physique; otherwise hard-pressed to survive Tiger retreats

### Tiger Retreats and Culture

- Tiger retreats involved vertical hikes in outward-bound contests in Idaho's Sawtooth Mountains
- Tigers would fly out west on Robertson's private plane, taken to hilltop
- Split into teams, each equipped with logs size of telephone poles, rope, two paddles
- Heave equipment down to nearby lake, lash logs together, race out to buoy—with twist that not all team could fit on raft
- Some had to plunge into icy water
- Even away from adventure holidays, exercise quotient at Tiger remained exceptional
- Firm retained private trainer; if analyst showed signs of shirking workouts, trainer would come up: "You're going to a business dinner in fifteen minutes? Do you have time to run two miles and shower before that?"

### Robertson's Background and Connections

- Like Soros and Steinhardt, Robertson inspired to set up hedge fund by **A. W. Jones's** example
- While working at Kidder Peabody in 1970s, Robertson befriended **Bob Burch**, A. W. Jones's son-in-law
- Occasionally friends would take old patriarch to lunch; Robertson would quiz Jones on mechanics of his partnership
- Robertson close to fellow southerner **Alex Porter**, who moved to New York in 1960s, bunked in Robertson's apartment, became A. W. Jones segment manager
- Robertson's sister was *Fortune* magazine journalist who had written about Jones-style funds
- Through her Robertson got to know **Carol Loomis**, the *Fortune* writer who first explained hedged investment structure
- Few years after Robertson launched Tiger, Bob Burch entrusted him with $5 million (a fifth of Jones money that remained)—wise decision

### Tiger's Launch and Performance

- Robertson launched **Tiger in 1980**, at relatively advanced age of 48
- During first winter, heating in tiny office broke; he caught cold and lost voice, squeaking out buy/sell orders
- Brought along carefree partner **Thorpe McKenzie**—no doubt who was in control: "When we disagreed, I caved," McKenzie recalled later
- Throughout reign at Tiger, Robertson kept close hold on responsibility for buying/selling rather than delegating to segment managers beneath him
- In most other ways, faithful to Jones model
- Picked stocks long and short, hedging out part of risk in market
- Dismissed commentary about market's overall direction as "gibberish"
- Promised clients he would prosper through stock selection
- As fund grew, Robertson picked stocks internationally, not just US
- Played in commodities, currencies, bonds, so original Jones method acquired macro-investing overlay
- Sometimes hedged market exposure with futures or options (method unavailable to Jones)
- Emphasized these speculative instruments being used for conservative ends, echoing Jones's language

### Tiger's Extraordinary Returns

- Between inception (May 1980) and peak (August 1998), **Tiger earned average of 31.7% per year after subtracting fees**
- Trounced 12.7% annual return on S&P 500 index
- **Fact that stock picking succeeded in this period was affront to efficient-market hypothesis**
- Understandable A. W. Jones could prosper in earlier era, when rivals at bureaucratic trust banks made investment decisions by committee
- Understandable Michael Steinhardt could make money being inside charmed circle of block traders
- Quants and trend surfers at Commodities Corporation were ahead of rivals
- Perhaps even George Soros, autodidact and seer, had feel for turning points in markets
- **But Robertson made no claim to have discovered institutional weaknesses in markets, fancy quantitative strategy, or philosophical vision**
- Once summed up approach in letter to **Robert Karr** (Tiger's man in Tokyo): sheer blandness of message underlined mystery of success
- Tiger should manage portfolio aggressively, removing good companies to make room for better ones
- Should avoid risking more than 5% of capital on one bet
- Should keep swinging through bad times until luck returned to him
- Simple truth: big jock and his lieutenants (handful at outset, perhaps dozen later on) just analyzed companies, currencies, commodities and bet on their prospects
- **Exactly what efficient marketers believed to be impossible**

### Tiger's Launch Timing and Market Context

- Efforts to explain anomaly mostly unsatisfying
- Like Jones funds, Tiger undoubtedly launched at propitious time (start of equity bull market)
- **401(k) retirement plan invented in 1981** (year after Robertson opened for business)
- By time Tiger closed doors, 401(k) pensions ubiquitous; owners stashed 75% of assets in equities
- For long stretches, market rode skyward on back of corporate mergers and buyouts
- Between 1981 and 1988: almost 1,550 American companies went private
- Every transaction made remaining public stocks scarcer and more valuable
- Good time to be equity investor

### Robertson's Merger-Boom Strategy

- Robertson certainly made most of bonanza
- Instinctively in tune with merger boom
- Aim as stock picker: look through price of company as announced by market and discern its true value
- Process often led him to buy stocks also attractive to takeover artists
- 1985: Tiger bought **Empire Airlines** at $9/share, taken out by corporate acquirer that bid $15
- Bought **Aviall** (distributor of aviation parts) at $12.50/share; taken out at $25
- End of that year: Tiger up astonishing 51.4% after subtracting fees
- Robertson broke news to investors with note of mock warning: "Bluntly, if you are not planning on buying emeralds or diamonds, don't show your wife this letter"

### Tiger's Short Portfolio

- Would be wrong to presume Robertson generated record simply by riding bull market upward
- Because of shorts in portfolio, fund not set up to rise as fast as market—but he nearly always beat it
- Some Tiger alumni suggest he achieved this by focusing on small companies
- According to theory: market price of big corporation (like United Airlines) likely efficient because Wall Street analysts pore over its books
- Lesser firms escape scrutiny
- True Tiger did seek out small companies lazier investors missed
- But made money on big ones too—including, spectacularly, on that very same United Airlines
- **Deeper objection to small-stock theory**: logic is debatable
- Fact that small stocks underanalyzed does not tell you there are easy profits from them
- Majority of investors may never have heard of particular provincial retailer or third-tier bank, but they are not ones holding the stock
- When Tiger bought shares in those companies, it was buying from people who knew enough to own shares themselves—and also knew enough to want to become sellers

### Tiger's Freedom to Short

- Tiger's success in stock picking undoubtedly owed something to **freedom to go short** (option denied to majority of fund managers)
- Nearly all Jones-style hedge funds washed out in early 1970s, so competition among short sellers was modest
- Even better for Robertson: **Wall Street analysts was congenitally bullish**
- On one reckoning, brokers at major houses issued 10 buy recommendations for every sell recommendation in early 1980s
- No analyst wanted to put sell recommendation in writing for fear of losing relationship with companies he covered
- Especially since investment bankers at his firm coveted advisory fees from those same companies
- So Robertson would call up analysts and sweet-talk them into divulging best short ideas over telephone
- "I know you all consider these companies to be your children, but just call me with your least favorite child," Robertson would coax them

### Robertson's Skepticism and Contrarianism

- Robertson was temperamentally a skeptic, and short selling came naturally
- Typical letter to investors (July 1983): complained of bullishness gone wild
- "The media, public and analysts, virtually everybody, are so bullish that they could be described as 'eating grass,'" Robertson declared
- "When this happens it may be best to crawl in a log and slurp some honey"
- When market hit weak patch, Robertson's skepticism paid off
- 1984: S&P 500 index rose just 6.3% while Tiger returned 20.2%; more than half of Robertson's returns came from short investments
- Following year: portfolio manager **Patrick Duff** began to suspect hotel chain **Prime Motor Inns** was in worse position than accounts suggested
- Duff did nothing about it (working for conventional pension fund at time)
- When he joined Tiger in 1989, persuaded Robertson to short the company
- Within a year, Prime Motor Inns fell from $28 to $1, demonstrating how profitable short selling could be
- Robertson had arrow in quiver that conventional funds lacked

> "It's me and the patsies," he once told an associate.

### Tiger's Edge Beyond Short Selling

- But Tiger's defiance of efficient-market presumptions cannot be explained entirely by short selling
- In most years Robertson would have beaten market even without profits from shorts
- Suggests he had edge precisely where theory said no edge was possible: in traditional stock buying
- Moreover, Robertson's record (like Buffett's) was not isolated phenomenon
- Just as Buffett part of investment "village" (cluster of superstars schooled in Ben Graham's value-investing style), so Robertson was village headman
- On one count in 2008: 36 former Tiger employees had set up **"Tiger cub" funds**, collectively managing $100 billion
- Robertson seeded further 29 funds after restructuring firm in 2000
- These Robertson protégés did well: test of Tiger cubs' performance (presented in first appendix to book) shows they beat not only market but also other hedge funds
- Moreover, test covers years 2000-2008 (period when profusion of long/short equity hedge funds had long since ended whatever easy profits might have existed in short selling during 1980s)
- If Robertson's achievement had stood by itself, might have been possible to dismiss him as lucky coin flipper
- **But success of Tiger's numerous offshoots puts paid to that thesis**
- **Whatever source of Robertson's investment edge, it was profitable—and transferable**

### The Real Explanation: Robertson's People Management

- Real explanation for Robertson's success begins with **updated version of A. W. Jones innovation**
- Jones revolutionized money management by paying for performance
- Rewarded segment managers in proportion to returns; created incentives for outside analysts to bring him good ideas
- Tracked profits they generated and handed out commissions accordingly
- Likewise, Robertson put rocket fuel in veins of employees, but did it differently—not just about money

### Robertson's Charismatic Leadership

- There was something about Robertson that made you want to please him
- Would zero in on people with Carolina charm, flattering and drawling until they purred like sleepy kittens
- "Pah-wah-ful, Bob," he might address young subordinate
- "Ah find mah-self utterly pah-ra-lyzed without your pah-wah-ful assistance"
- Rich pleasure of basking in Robertson's attention spiked with knowledge that his mood might turn
- "Why, you petty tin-pot dictator," he might say, voice ice cold
- "You Latin American dictator"
- Robertson would assemble lieutenants each Friday around long table to listen to fruits of week's work
- Emotional payoffs were extreme
- "That is the be-yest idea Ah ever saw," he might exclaim after listening to square-shouldered twentysomething analyst deliver stock pitch
- Young hunk would be whooping and high-fiving himself inside swollen head for rest of meeting
- "That is the dumbest idea Ah ever heard," Robertson might also say
- Six-foot-plus of Wall Street alpha male would shrivel pitifully

### Working for Tiger: A Special-Forces Unit

- Working for Tiger was not merely a job—**like joining special-forces unit**
- Commander made you bigger, brighter, tougher than you were before
- Made you believe you could beat market, year after year, because you were part of team that would outthink and out-hustle every rival
- For first dozen years or so of Tiger's history, commander operated from desk out in open, next to his young men
- They watched him schmooze and hose down phone, sucking information out of vast network
- Robertson's two assistants operated pair of giant Rolodexes, almost size of wagon wheels
- If Tiger analyst pitched investment to boss, Robertson would soon be testing idea on three old friends who worked in that same company
- Analyst might say, "I think it's time to short Boeing"
- Robertson might respond, "I know the guy who used to run Boeing's international marketing"
- Assistants would work wagon wheels, former marketing chief would crackle on speakerphone, Robertson would tell twentysomething analyst to defend his short recommendation

### The High-Pressure Environment

- For young man with wits to thrive in environment, sky was limit
- So long as you were doing well, you basked in attention of boss
- He would call you "big tiger" and show you off to exalted buddies
- Robertson introduced one young analyst to **Jerry Reinsdorf** (owner of Chicago Bulls), saying, "This man is *my* Michael Jordan"
- Introduced lieutenant who loved golf to **Jack Nicklaus** and **Ely Callaway**
- Took prized employee to White House to visit **Bill Clinton**: "Bill, this is Lou. He can do anything in the world. He is unbelievable"
- But as always with Robertson, risks could be as great as rewards
- Eighteen months after introduction to Clinton, that same Lou was gone—from White House to shit house in record time

### Robertson's Recruiting Through Personality

- Robertson drew people in by sheer force of personality
- Met singer **Paul Simon** and persuaded him to invest in Tiger on strength of shared passion for baseball
- Writer **Tom Wolfe** was Tiger investor too; Robertson knew how to use these stars to recruit others
- 1986: set sights on hiring Goldman Sachs analyst **Michael Bills**
- Never mind Goldman's big pooh-bahs promising young man great Goldman future
- Robertson gave Bills full charm treatment
- Wheeled in **Lew Lehrman** (financier, philanthropist, history buff who had campaigned for New York governorship in 1982, wearing trademark red suspenders)
- In all his long experience, Lehrman earnestly told Bills, he had never encountered investor to compare with Julian Robertson—not anyone, not ever
- Then Robertson brought out trump: **Tom Wolfe** called Bills to talk about young man's father
- Bills senior had served as military pilot; no better tribute to military pilots than Wolfe's book *The Right Stuff*
- Pretty soon Wolfe and Bills were sharing profound feelings about flying and honor and courage
- By end of twenty-minute call, Goldman Sachs had lost its man—Bills signed on with Tiger

### Tiger's Network-Based Investing

- Tiger's roster of investors crammed with captains of industry and finance
- Robertson never hesitated to call on them for insights
- Letters to partners frequently encouraged them to call in ideas, "or, particularly in the case of ladies, intuition"
- Early 1980s: Tiger tripled money in stock called **Metromedia**, which Tiger investor had recommended
- Early 1990s: fund's best stock picks included **General Instrument Corporation** and **Equitable Life Insurance**; in both cases Tiger friends connected to those firms urged Robertson to buy them
- Around same time, Robertson began buying stock in **Citicorp**, mainly because bank seemed poised to recover strongly after clearing out real-estate losses
- Also because Tiger friend willing to vouch for **John Reid** (Citi's chief executive)
- **Robertson was not engaging in insider trading**: contacts offering broad guidance, not secrets on upcoming earnings announcements with immediate impact on stocks
- But he was consciously building network and cashing in on it brilliantly

### Robertson's Talent for Judging People

- To those who watched Robertson up close in heyday, there was no doubt about his talent
- Could drop in on meeting with chief executive and demonstrate grasp of company detail rivaling that of analyst who tracked it
- Could listen to presentation on firm he knew nothing about and immediately pounce on detail that would make or break it
- Could play golf with chief executive, see man nudge ball into better position when it landed in rough, write himself mental note never to buy stock in man's company
- **Jim Chanos** (celebrated short seller who ran money for three hedge-fund titans of 1980s—Robertson, Soros, Steinhardt) remembers Robertson as most intellectually engaging of bunch

> "If I had had to give my own money to any of them, I would have given it to Robertson. I knew that he knew stocks better than anyone."

### Robertson's Edge: Getting the Best Out of People

- Robertson's personality, his ability to get best out of people, constituted his clearest advantage
- But this sort of edge could be tricky to define
- People who knew Robertson less well than Chanos could be forgiven for missing it
- *Institutional Investor* profile (May 1986) set out to describe what magazine billed as "the red-hot world of Julian Robertson"
- But made special sauce seem bland: "It's not that Robertson does anything dramatically different from other money managers; it's just that he does it so well"
- Meanwhile, Robertson's supposed knack for judging managers could sometimes misfire
- Writing off company because its boss cheated at golf fell short of scientific method
- Yet although Robertson's approach was neither formal nor original, **he was right more than he was wrong—and that is the definition of success in money management**
- No system (human or computerized) is correct all the time
- Mathematicians who build state-of-the-art quantitative systems are delighted when they call market right on six out of ten occasions

### Long-Termism vs. Wall Street Short-Termism

- Same six-out-of-ten rule applied to another hallmark of Tiger style: **long-termism**
- Wall Street brokerage firms typically feed clients 12-18 month view
- Hedge funds frequently do well either by being more short-term or more long-term
- Robertson firmly in long-term camp
- His ideal investment—a *fah-bulous* investment, as Robertson would say—was something that might plausibly double in three years
- If Robertson believed he had found such investment, willing to hang on, gritting teeth through hard times until world caught up with his analysis
- 1983: Robertson decided oil prices would come down; took big short positions in oil and oil-service stocks
- Bet hurt for while, but it was right: three years on, crude had halved in value
- 1984: Robertson shorted generic pharmaceutical makers, believing there could be no durable profit margin in nonbranded products
- Again, bet lost money, but Robertson kept faith
- Two years later, celebrated collapse of **Zenith Labs**, whose stock crashed 45% in space of one quarter

### Tenacity and Conviction-Based Investing

- **Tenacity, like character judgment, is not sort of edge that pays off every time**—and sometimes when it did, luck was crucial factor
- 1987: young lieutenant **John Griffin** persuaded Robertson to short small appliance maker whose manufacturing based in China
- Company proceeded to rack up terrific Christmas sales; stock shot up from $20 to $25
- Griffin and Robertson stuck with convictions, but news did not improve
- Company powered its way into spring; stock hit $35
- 1988: Griffin went off to business school at Stanford but begged commander to keep faith with trade—it would come good! He was convinced of it!
- Robertson indulged Griffin, even though stock had by now doubled to $40—meaning bet had so far cost Tiger 100% of original stake
- One day at Stanford, Griffin got fax from big man—no words on paper, just said "$50!"
- Months passed
- Then April 1989: 100,000 demonstrators marched into **Tiananmen Square** in China's capital
- Demonstrations gathered momentum; protesters pressed political reform; full-blown revolution seemed possible
- Not surprisingly, American companies with factories in China saw stocks fall off cliff
- Tiger's short was no exception
- Griffin ran excitedly to pay phone—at last he was redeemed! He was ecstatic to speak to mentor

> "Julian, I told you it would work! You stayed with it! You believed in me! It worked! I KNEW it would work!"

- Seated on other side of American continent, Robertson listened to outburst

> "Now, John, now, John. The way *Ah* see it, is that it took a revolution of a *bihl-lion* people for your darn short to work out."

- If this story shows how Robertson's tenacity could hurt in absence of sheer luck, **it also shows his genius**
- Young hotshot like Griffin, who would later run his own multibillion-dollar hedge fund, had left Tiger for business school
- But psychologically he had not left at all; still running to get big man on phone, desperate for redemption
- Even quarter century later, bond remained intense
- In speech in 2007, Griffin described enduring sense that Robertson was watching over him, judging his decisions
- "All money managers wish they had little birdie on their shoulder who might whisper correct market move from time to time," Griffin declared

> "Well, my little birdie has a deep southern drawl and a bald head. Sometimes I hear him chirp: 'Big guy, don't do that.'"

### Robertson's Lieutenants: Pre-Internet Hustle

- Under Robertson's tutelage, young men like Griffin hustled harder than they might have elsewhere
- In pre-Internet era, hustle counted hugely
- Search engines and terminals that later made data ubiquitous had not yet been born
- If Tiger analyst wanted to know how Ford's sales were shaping up, he would get on phone until he had talked to Ford's customers, competitors, suppliers; to car dealers, part makers, Detroit rivals; to anyone who might have useful angle
- One analyst considering possible stake in **Avon Products** developed her own edge by becoming Avon representative
- Another contemplating short in Korean carmaker whose engines said to malfunction, so he bought two of cars and hired mechanic to test them
- When **Mexico defaulted** at start of 1995, most New York investors worried American banks might take hit
- But Tiger's analyst flew to Mexico and found **Citicorp** was not exposed and, further, that Mexicans eager to do business with Citi now that their own banks weakened
- As panicky New Yorkers hammered Citi's stock, Tiger snapped up more at bargain prices

### Robertson's Personality as Competitive Edge

- Robertson's gregarious personality marked him off from other hedge-fund titans
- Gave him edge
- **Allowed him to set up contest between workaday masses and his own special-force unit—it was him against the patsies**
<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

### Robertson's German Misadventure

- Robertson and Griffin traveled to East Germany after reunification, discovering German companies were undervalued by American standards
- German stocks were "ludicrously cheap" relative to assets owned, but managers cared more about employees than shareholders
- At **Bayer**, Robertson experienced lavish corporate culture: company flying club where employees could train for pilot's licenses
- Robertson's verdict by 1994: Germany was a "giant flab bag of inefficiency"
- The German adventure showed expansion risks: betting American value investing would translate cross-culturally proved wrong
- Similar problem in Japan: big banks traded at huge multiples despite bad loans and negligible profits
- Tiger's Japan analyst admitted in memo: "I don't know the answer to that question" about why bank stocks refused to collapse

### Tiger's Dangerous Expansion

- By 1990, Tiger became third hedge fund to manage over $1 billion
- After 1990 magazine profile, Tiger grew from wealthy individuals to endowments
- Robertson had proclaimed "small was beautiful" in 1980s, but now abandoned caution
- Chased $1 billion milestone behind Soros and Steinhardt; by end of 1993 ran $7 billion
- Robertson obsessed with Quantum comparison: "In 1981 we beat him to death; [in 1982] he beat us; [in 1983] we beat him to death; [in 1984] we beat him to death again"
- Expansion forced diversification beyond core strengths—U.S. equity markets couldn't sustain multi-billion fund
- Small-cap stocks became "virtually off limits" for large fund sizes

### Macro Trading Challenges

- Tiger dabbled in currencies, earning over quarter of huge 1985 gain from dollar bet (smaller version of Soros's Plaza accord play)
- Bought Australian and New Zealand bonds (16-24% interest rates), borrowed in countries with sub-10% rates, locked in difference—classic **carry trade**
- In 1991, hired **David Gerstenhaber** (Japanese-speaking currency specialist from Morgan Stanley) and **Barry Bausano**
- **Jim Chanos** vouched for Robertson's stock-picking but noted macro trading requires different mindset than value investing
- Value investors buy stocks with little/no leverage, hold long-term, double down when price falls—build **rock-solid convictions**
- Macro investors take leveraged positions, must jump out quickly if bet moves against them, have no reliable method to determine "value" of a currency
- Robertson's macro team struggled to adapt: he rejected charts as "hocus-pocus, mumbo-jumbo bullshit"
- When macro men suggested temporary hedge for European bond position, Robertson exploded:

> "Hedge? Why, that just means that if I'm right I'm going to make less money."

- Robertson refused risk management: "Why would I want to do that? Why? Why? That's just dirt under my fingernails."

### Robertson's Peak Performance (Late 1980s-Early 1990s)

- Through 1980s and early 1990s, Robertson's strengths outweighed weaknesses
- After Plaza accord: identified weak dollar would benefit U.S. exporters, rode them to great profits
- Correctly shorted banks after 1990 U.S. real estate collapse when bad property debts cleared
- Tiger's bonds and currencies march, though dangerous, paid off spectacularly
- 1988-1992: Tiger beat S&P 500 for **five straight years**
- 1993: returned 64% after fees; **Business Week** estimated personal earnings at $1 billion

### The Changing Robertson

- Robertson spent more time away, less on business
- Ten-week period in early 1993: five long weekends skiing in Sun Valley, hunting sailfish in Costa Rica, three days at Augusta National Golf Club, full fortnight in Kenya
- Remodeled Tiger's premises with elegant corner office distancing himself from lieutenants
- Hired psychiatrist **Aaron Stern** to manage people and mood swings, creating buffer between himself and analysts
- Intensity and passion grated more as he became less present
- Psychiatrist warned: "If you bleed easily, you won't be happy here"—many analysts left within a year

### Lieutenants Depart

- Fall 1992: Robertson introduced macro men at Tiger party: "Meet David and Barry, who earned $1 billion last year"
- Reference made it easy for duo to raise capital independently
- Spring 1993: Gerstenhaber and Bausano quit to set up **Argonaut fund**
- Tiger's success made lieutenants feel they should run their own shows
- Robertson refused to share control, toyed with subportfolios idea but never ceded real authority
- Quitting became seductively easy: wealthy investors sought next generation of stars
- Within two months, Gerstenhaber and Bausano ran $200 million in Argonaut (vs. Tiger's $8.5 million start in 1980)

## Chapter 6: Rock-and-Roll Cowboy

### Hedge Fund Boom of Late 1980s

- After 1987 crash, hedge fund industry transformed
- By 1990: six hundred hedge funds; by 1992: over a thousand
- 1993 celebrated as "the year of the hedge fund"
- The **"Big Three"**: Soros, Robertson, Steinhardt
- Younger rivals expanding fast: **Julian Robertson** related by marriage to **Louis Bacon**; **Michael Steinhardt** briefly partnered with **Bruce Kovner**
- Hedge-fund moguls hunted and fished together, sat on charitable boards, gathered annually at Lyford Cay in Bahamas
- Their presence in one room signaled birth of new force on Wall Street

### Paul Tudor Jones II: Background

- Born 1954 to Memphis family with deep cotton ties
- Grandfather prospered as cotton merchant; uncle **Billy Dunavant** was industry baron
- After undergraduate economics at University of Virginia, apprenticed with cotton trader in New Orleans
- Moved to New York Cotton Exchange after two years
- On trading floor, hard to believe markets reflected all available information efficiently
- Key drivers weren't economic data but "wild guys screaming in your face"—cotton cowboys downing martinis at lunch, wheeling into battle
- Floor operator made $10 million following inflation report release, then asked: "By the way, what was the number?"

### Jones's Trading Style: Psychology and Bluff

- Left cotton exchange 1983 to build **Tudor Investment Corporation** (still under 30)
- **Commodities Corporation** invested $35,000, connected him to veteran community
- Emerged as prodigy with distinctive style: trading as game of psychology and high-speed bluff
- Not enough to analyze fundamentals and bet; had to sense what other traders were doing—greedy, afraid, poised, dangerously extended
- Watched rival traders to get inside their heads, lure them when buying mood, spook them when fearful
- If big traders nervous, could yell selling position and know they'd sell too, then pivot and buy
- Loud flamboyance helpful: described self as "cowboy in purest sense," approached markets with "violent passion of the boxer he had been in college"
- Screamed huge orders down phone, frequently reversed instructions mid-call—crazier he sounded, more he kept rivals off balance
- Varied methods: small orders through multiple brokers (staying under radar) or ambush market guns blazing
- 1986-1987: allowed documentary film team to follow him, capturing trading tantrums

### Jones's Preparation and "Scripts"

- Chief economist **Peter Borish** compensated for youth with old-fashioned suspenders, fond of pronouncing eerie parallels between 1980s and 1920s
- Borish plotted stock charts of two periods on top of each other—both rose in vertiginous line, convincing Borish spectacular 1929-scale crash coming
- In candid interview, Borish admitted fudging results: juggled starting points until he got the fit he wanted
- On this quasi-quantitative foundation, Jones built house of anecdote
- Wall Street's exorbitant pay signaled correction must be due; banks' thinly stretched capital; Van Gogh painting sold for ten times preauction estimate
- 1987 documentary: Jones predicts collapse calmly, says "It's going to be total rock and roll," eyes gleeful
- Jones's performance in mid-1980s made rivals believe anything he said: 1985 returned 136%, 1986 returning 99%
- Truth: Borish's 1920s examination incidental to Jones's success, even though crash came October 1987
- Most Wall Street players expected break sooner/later; hard thing was putting date on it
- Borish predicted crash would arrive spring 1988—forecast no better than others in investment business

### Kondratiev and Elliott Wave Theory

- Like **Tony Cilluffo** (Steinhardt's eccentric autodidact), Jones taken with **Kondratiev wave theory**: world moves in predictable twenty-four-year cycles
- Kondratiev helped Cilluffo anticipate 1973 crash, presumably meaning next cataclysm not due until 1997
- 1987: Jones nonetheless believed theory reinforced case that "total rock and roll" imminent
- More enamored of **Elliott wave analysis**, expounded by **Robert Prechter**
- Prechter asserted stocks would experience one last upward explosion before plunging at least 90%: greatest crash since South Sea bubble (England 1720)
- Jones told interviewer: "I attribute a lot of my own success to the Elliot Wave approach"
- Prechter's disaster predictions wildly overblown; even Jones agreed Prechter had no way of pinpointing when crash would happen

### Jones's Real Method: Market Psychology

- Trading profits came from agile short-term moves, not understanding multidecade supercycles
- Like Commodities Corporation traders, adept at riding market waves, ready to jump off if swell turned
- "When you take an initial position, you have no idea if you are right," he confessed
- Method: "write a script for the market," setting out how it might behave, then test hypothesis repeatedly with low-risk bets
- Years later, described mental gymnastics:

> "Every evening I would close my eyes in a quiet place in my apartment. I would picture myself in the pit. I would visualize the opening and walk myself through the day and imagine the different emotional states that the market would go through. I used to repeat that exercise every day. Then when you get there, you are ready for it. You have been there before. You are in a mental state to take advantage of emotional extremes because you have already lived through them."

### Black Monday 1987

- When S&P 500 started heading down Friday, October 16, Jones sensed expected break might finally be coming
- Didn't matter Borish's crude 1920s comparison suggested crash several months off
- Jones visualized possibility of crash; understood once market started falling, chances of monster fall significant
- Investors anticipating day of reckoning for months; confidence could crack decisively
- **Portfolio insurance** added danger: falling stocks would trigger selling by insurers, causing stocks to fall more
- Betting on decline was irresistible given market positioning
- If early Friday fall petered out, Jones might lose modestly going short or close position and await next opportunity
- But if investor skittishness and portfolio insurance caused crater, payoff could be enormous
- Balance of risk and reward "overwhelmingly attractive"

### Double Coup on Black Monday

- By Friday evening, Jones sold armfuls of S&P 500 futures
- Headed to hunting lodge in remote Virginia with Louis Bacon and European friends
- Weekend over, too many guests for private plane returning to New York
- Jones, chivalrous, offered last seats to friends; would stay back in Virginia
- Somebody said: "No. We know you've got a big position."
- Jones got on plane; morning of Black Monday at desk in Manhattan
- If guests less generous, would have missed largest one-day equity collapse in lifetime
- Stocks fell sharply in morning, then into bloodcurdling dive; Jones rode cascade all the way to bottom
- Frantic investors flooded brokers with calls desperate to sell; only people not panicking were ones numb from destruction
- Years later, Jones likened Wall Street's crash reaction to own boat crash: "I remember the time I got run over by a boat, and my backside was chewed up by the propeller. My first thought was, 'Dammit, I just ruined my Sunday afternoon because I have to get stitched up.' Because I was in shock, I didn't even realize how badly cut up I was until I saw the faces of my friends."
- Crash of 1987 paralyzed some reactions similarly; Jones had written script for market, was mentally prepared for mayhem

### The Second Black Monday Bet

- Even riding market down, Jones seized second chance to profit
- Had been thinking about how Fed would respond to collapse, writing script for markets as always
- Reasoned authorities would pump cash into banks to make borrowing cheaper, calming nerves
- Figured: might be another asymmetrical bet
- If Fed did as expected, bond market would soar; if Fed did nothing, no reason to expect market downward
- When bond market ticked up late Black Monday, Jones took that as signal script coming true
- Bought largest bond position he'd ever owned; soon turned out to be most profitable one
- Jones's double coup on Black Monday reportedly netted **Tudor Investment Corporation** between $80 million and $100 million
- Contributed to 200% return that year
- Not long afterward, revealed contrasting personality side: launched **Robin Hood Foundation**, tapping hedge-fund wealth to channel millions to New York's poorest neighborhoods

### Commodities Corporation Alumni Thrive

- Late 1980s good time for others from Commodities Corporation tradition
- **Big Three** (Soros, Steinhardt, Robertson) all lost heavily in 1987 crash
- **Bruce Kovner** and **Louis Bacon** fared well, though made less money than Jones
- Big Three and junior three shared expectation of market reversal; discussed prospect frequently
- Jones even tried persuading Julian Robertson to run portfolio of stock shorts
- One thing to expect trouble, another to respond like lightning when actually arrived
- Commodities Corporation trio proved nimbler than older group from equity tradition
- Stock pickers like Julian Robertson wedded to stocks: Tigers researched each exhaustively, hurt to unload
- Jones, Kovner, Bacon had none of that baggage; hallmark was flexibility, could turn on a dime
- Didn't care about individual stocks; traded whole market

### Post-Crash Divergence

- After stock crash, Kovner and Bacon piled into bonds, profiting from same script Jones followed
- Next year and rest of decade, continued to thrive
- Kovner reaped glorious rewards in currencies, building on carry trade developed at Commodities Corporation
- 1989-1990: reportedly highest earner on Wall Street (oil futures bets)
- Louis Bacon did well trading small account as broker at Shearson Lehman Hutton, split off to found **Moore Capital** hedge fund (1989)
- 1989: up 86%; 1990: up 29%, correctly foreseeing Iraq invasion of Kuwait's effect on equity and oil markets
- Seed money Bacon received from Commodities Corporation now dwarfed by other cash
- **Paul Jones** advised clients to invest with Bacon instead when unable to absorb all money pressed on him

### Jones and the Japanese Bubble

- Jones scored big in Tokyo like all Wall Street cognoscenti
- Late 1980s: saw bubble forming
- Japanese authorities cut interest rates aggressively after Plaza accord, seeking to offset strong yen's drag on economy
- Flood of cheap capital drove up cost of Japanese assets, including foreign assets (California golf courses, impressionist paintings)
- 1987: Japanese phone company **Nippon Telegraph and Telephone** floated on Tokyo stock market at fantastical price-earnings ratio of 250
- Market overvalued on any measure, yet continued heading upward

### Timing the Tokyo Collapse

- Challenge with all bubbles: not seeing it would crash but anticipating the moment
- Shorting Tokyo market aggressively after NTT flotation would have been suicide
- Over next two years, Nikkei gained astonishing 63%—proof few things more costly than tilting against bubble
- Jones not about to tilt early; too much trend follower to risk betting against momentum
- Bided time, watching for moment when trend might turn
- Start of 1990: Tokyo market fell nearly 4% in matter of days—signal he'd been waiting for
- Mid-January 1990: **Barron's** discussion where Jones rattled off reasons Tokyo primed for sharp fall
- Standard stock analyst observation: market trading at huge multiples to earnings
- But Jones focused with particular passion on how market players were positioned
- Wall Street 1987: **portfolio insurance** created mechanism exacerbating fall, creating asymmetrical bet for speculators
- Tokyo: Japan's financial culture created similar asymmetry
- Japanese savers expected fund managers to show 8% annual returns; because of importance attached to hurdle, managers would respond to reversal defensively by rushing into bonds (could lock in 8% returns risk-free basis)

### Jones's January 1990 Prediction

- Made all difference that Tokyo market suffered 4% correction at beginning of year
- If fallen in December after rising strongly in previous months, fund managers still above 8% hurdle might not have minded
- But fall in January was different: fund managers sitting on cushion created by earlier equity returns, fifty weeks left in year to secure 8% target by taking refuge in bond market
- If fund managers behaved defensively as Jones expected, resulting stampede out of equities could push stock market off precipice
- Jones's script soon played out in reality
- **Nikkei 225** fell 7% in February and 13% in March; by end of year lost two-fifths of value, crippling world's biggest stock market
- Jones didn't merely get big call right
- With almost uncanny accuracy, anticipated Tokyo's fluctuations on way to final destination
- Based on knowledge of patterns in previous bear markets, predicted in January Nikkei's fall would be followed by weak rally; when Nikkei stabilized in spring, duly switched from heavy short to mild long
- Maneuver underlined difference between flexible commodities trader style and dogged persistence of value investor like Julian Robertson (never traded in/out of position)

### May 1990 Barron's Interview

- Month after another interview with **Barron's**
- Magazine congratulated him on January prediction Tokyo riding for fall
- Jones modestly recalled predicting Japanese crash prematurely in 1988-1989—essence of skill was predicting such things without actually making losing bets
- Reiterated forecast: market would experience rallies on way down, diving precipitously each time after bounce proved disappointing
- Logic: investors who hadn't sold out during first crash leg desperately hoping to make money back; each time rally too feeble to recover losses, more would give up and sell
- For moment, lightly long Japan, but planned to be short again by late summer
- Jones's timing proved excellent: Tokyo's market fell steeply July through early October
- 1990: Jones estimated returned 80-90% on portfolio, largely on Tokyo trading strength

### Jones's Real Achievement: Asymmetric Bets

- Real achievement not just predicting Japan would fall, nor even predicting brief rallies on way down
- Was to spot situation where odds so good they warranted bet, even in absence of predictive certainty
- October 1987 and January 1990: Wall Street and Tokyo market could have recovered (Jones would have bailed out of shorts with small loss)
- But Jones could see decline more likely than market rise; crucially, decline if it happened would be far more dramatic than any conceivable rally
- Like gambler playing roulette game doctored two ways: two extra red numbers on wheel (giving red somewhat-better-than-even chance); croupier paying out five-to-one if red comes up (creating mouthwatering skew in reward-to-risk ratio)
- Jones had no way of being certain bets would win; but knew it was time to shove chips onto table

### Understanding Market Positioning

- Many trading successes owed something to this formula
- From cotton exchange floor, understood importance of watching how other players positioned
- If knew whether big guys sitting on cash stockpiles or already fully invested, could tell which way market might break out
- Could sense mix of risk and reward in any situation
- Pit traders knew rivals' positions by watching them yelling out bids
- Once Jones migrated off floor, ad-libbed tricks to reproduce same feel for markets
- Called brokers representing big institutional clients, checked with trading companies using commodity markets to hedge physical positions, spoke frequently with fellow hedge-fund managers
- Tracked data showing whether investors buying more call options (expecting stocks might rise) or put options (fearing crater)
- Consulted reports on balance between cash and stocks in pension and insurance portfolios
- Not enough simply to know what other investors holding; needed to know what they wanted to hold—objectives, how they'd react in different situations
- If knew Japanese fund managers obsessed with clearing 8% hurdle, knew might switch to bonds if market fell in January

### Behavioral Finance Before the Name

- Jones's method extension of psychological insights common at Commodities Corporation
- Understood behavioral quirks colored markets, tinting pure randomness imagined by efficient-market theorists
- Jones attuned to different sort of bias: if investors could buy/sell irrationally for psychological reasons, could do much same for institutional ones
- Sometimes psychological and institutional factors combined
- Cotton farmers invariably clung to part of harvest for weeks after picked, hoping prices turn higher
- End of year psychological bias against selling ran into institutional factor: had to unload crops or suffer adverse tax consequences
- Jones recognized pattern: Each year cotton market hit by wave of sell orders in December; each year market would recover lost ground in January
- Similar distortions lurked in other commodity markets
- Nearly a year for calf to gestate inside mother's belly, so cattle supply responded sluggishly to rising prices; supply could take months to catch up with demand, upward trends in cattle futures tended to be durable
- Equity market example: stocks in Dow Industrials tended to do well on closing Friday of each quarter (when arbitrage traders bought back stocks sold short to hedge expiring futures contracts)

### Exploiting Institutional Distortions

- Jones's focus on institutional distortions helps explain how he could beat market
- Allowed him to buy/sell in situations where knew getting good price because person on other side of trade was forced seller
- Efficient-market theorists demonstrated hard for investor to foresee future movement of stock/commodity because all relevant information reflected in today's price
- Jones sidestepped theory by getting something better than going price—from farmers with no choice but dump cotton at year end, or arbitrage traders forced to buy back stocks on last Friday of each quarter
- Success resembled Steinhardt's: 1970s-1980s, Steinhardt could buy blocks of equities at discount because institutional sellers needed to unload in size and willing to pay for privilege
- This sort of trading didn't require Jones or Steinhardt to predict future course of prices with godlike prescience
- Merely required them to provide liquidity when needed

### Jolting the Market

- Further element in Jones's success goes back to swashbuckling style displayed in 1987 documentary
- If Jones's method was looking for trigger that might set off sudden market move, also willing on occasion to become that trigger himself
- To jump-start reversal in market with massive trade, initiating stampede that would make script become reality
- Technique homed in on weakness in efficient-market thinking
- Theory presumes if, say, Ford's stock too low, handful of smart investors could buy Ford shares until forced price up to efficient level
- In reality, limit to smart investors' firepower; may lack sufficient cash to keep buying Ford until hits rational level
- When whole market out of kilter, smart investors especially likely to fall short
- Might know Japan's equity bubble—or dot-com bubble or mortgage bubble—makes no sense, but cannot borrow enough to bet against it with force that would deflate it
- This is why there is limit to power of contrarians; why markets swing in trends; why finance prone to bubbles

### The Limits to Arbitrage

- Insight—christened "the limits to arbitrage" by economists **Andrei Shleifer** and **Robert Vishny**—points to opportunity Jones could sense intuitively
- Markets can move away from fundamental value because speculators lack muscle to challenge consensus; trend can keep going far beyond point at which ceases to be rational
- But if you are trader with more ammunition and courage than rest, can ambush market and jolt it out of sleepwalk
- Because will have started new trend, will be first to profit from it

### Jones's Loud Trading Tactics

- Jolting market something of Jones specialty
- Seen cowboys in cotton pit wrong-foot rivals, but perhaps first trader to deploy tactic across multiple markets
- Most "upstairs traders" tried to conceal positions by placing orders discreetly through multiple brokers
- Jones saw sometimes could pay to be as loud as possible
- Documentary sequence: Jones reacts with skepticism to OPEC agreement to cut oil production
- Theory: production cut will push prices higher, so OPEC announcement starts upward trend in oil prices
- Jones knows OPEC countries seldom muster collective discipline to abide by lower quotas
- Figures upward trend has no basis in reality; challenge is to break market's baseless momentum and profit from reversal
- First proceeds with stealth: calls in multiple small sell orders, hoping to disguise intentions so upward trend won't be disturbed while building short position
- Once quiet trades done, switches to wild cowboy style: wants market to know some big swinger is selling, wants to scare daylights out of it
- "Offer a thousand!" he yells at broker. "No, offer fifteen hundred! Show 'em size! Tell him that there's more behind it! Do it! Do it! There's more behind it!"
- Having rattled market, calls friend at oil-trading firm to gauge whether macho sales have broken oil's momentum
- Doing what pit trader would do—feeling mood of adversaries
- Two talk some minutes, then Jones hangs up
- "He said, '*Those guys*, they've sold the hell out of it,'" Jones reports with evident delight
- "The people he works with don't know that it was…" and here Jones winks conspiratorially and points melodramatically at his


<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 7: White Wednesday

### Paul Tudor Jones's Market-Moving Power

- **Jones's oil ambush succeeded** — he reversed the oil rally rather than waiting for fundamentals to align with his prediction
- Spring 1987: Jones executed a **silver squeeze** mimicking General George S. Patton's tactics
  - Bought gutsy position in silver futures, contracts from floor traders, physical silver from dealers
  - Dealers rushed to replace inventory, calling silver exchange with buy orders
  - Floor traders assumed supply disruption rumors were true, rushed to buy back contracts they'd sold to Jones
  - Pandemonium erupted — speculators scrambled to protect from spiking prices, driving prices higher
  - Jones kicked off the rally at the right moment and made handsome profit

> "I can go into any market at just the right moment, by giving it a little gas on the upside, I can create the illusion of a bull market. But, unless the market is really sound, the second I stop buying, the price is going to come right down." — Paul Tudor Jones

- Jones's power lay in **triggering avalanches** in markets poised to move
  - Like boy on mountain after snowfall — could throw stone and set off cascade
  - His reputation amplified his effect — when people saw the wild cowboy coming, they assumed market would move
  - In late 1980s Treasury bond futures ($50M lots), Jones would send orders **twice that size**, triggering panicked reactions
  - **James Elkins** (S&P 500 futures trader): "Whenever he entered the market, the whole pit would run scared. My size could be bigger than his size, but his reputation was such that when he entered, it would throw the whole thing off whack"

### Jones's Self-Awareness and Behavioral Finance

- Jones understood market psychology before academic **behavioral finance** emerged in late 1980s
- He anticipated research on institutional quirks and tax-driven trading distortions
- Most distinctive: he was **self-aware** — understood how his own trading could change others' calculations, creating profitable chain reactions
- As hedge funds grew in size and stature, **billions flowed into war chests** — no longer just oil or silver traders to beware
- By 1990s, hedge funds could **move markets of all kinds, even overpower governments**

### Stan Druckenmiller Joins Soros

- Autumn 1988: **Stan Druckenmiller** agreed to join Soros Fund Management
  - Friends advised against it; Druckenmiller expected relationship to break down within a year
  - Soros had been "dangling offers," calling Druckenmiller a genius
  - Robert Soros greeted him: "Congratulations, you're my father's ninth permanent successor"

### Druckenmiller's Background and Skills

- **Stylistic opposites** — Soros loved philosophical books, Druckenmiller watched Pittsburgh Steelers
- As investors: ideal fit, both from stock-picking background but not attached to it
- Druckenmiller began as equity analyst at **Pittsburgh National Bank**
  - Promoted to research director at 25, never mastered traditional corporate balance sheet analysis
  - Combined disciplines: equities + currencies/interest rates (from PhD economics course)
  - **Technical analysis** from first boss — found charts useful for timing market moves
  - Survived 1987 crash and profited richly after (unlike pure equity managers, including Soros)

- After 4 years at bank, accosted at New York presentation: "You're at a bank! What the hell are you doing at a bank?"
  - Man offered $10k/month just to speak with Druckenmiller
  - Feb 1981 (age 28): launched **Duquesne Capital Management** as macro trader

- 1985: attracted attention of **Dreyfus** mutual-fund company
  - Managed several Dreyfus funds while running Duquesne
  - One fund shot up 40% in 3 months, making him Wall Street celebrity

- 1987: publication of Soros's *The Alchemy of Finance* revealed similar style
  - Two met over lunch, instant meeting of minds
  - When Druckenmiller eventually accepted (after initial clash over bond position), Robert Soros's lawn welcome proved well-founded

### Initial Tensions and Soros's Gamble

- Quantum's incumbent analysts clashed with new "pretender"
- Soros regarded Druckenmiller as **S&P 500 specialist** despite broader trading
- August 1989: Druckenmiller flew to Pittsburgh, discovered bond position sold out behind his back
  - Called Soros, exploded: "I feel cramped by your presence. I'm intimidated and I feel dissatisfied because I don't think I'm doing as well as I could. I want to leave"
  - Soros: "Don't leave. I'll leave."

- Soros moved family to London, giving Druckenmiller freedom (and testing him)
  - Berlin wall fell — Soros could focus on philanthropy in Eastern Europe
  - Druckenmiller's returns: **31.5% (1989), 29.6%, 53.4%, 68.8%, 63.2%** over next 4 years
  - "Like Bob Dylan in the midsixties, producing one hit album after the next"
  - Assets in Quantum: $1.8B → $5B
  - Soros Fund Management total assets: $8.3B by end of 1993

### Druckenmiller's Philosophy and Method

- Soros learned from Druckenmiller's outburst — didn't undermine him, sought "permanent successor" he could trust
- Soros behaved as younger man's **coach** — prodded with questions/advice, let Druckenmiller pull trigger
- Soros retained pot of capital for side trading; Druckenmiller firmly controlled main Quantum fund
- Druckenmiller absorbed teachings from *Alchemy*, spoke to Soros continually for 2 years
- Following Soros's practice: long/short equity portfolio + borrowed capital for S&P 500 futures + bonds/currencies
- Stayed in touch with company executives for early economic warnings
- **Key lesson from master**: "pile on with all you've got when the right moment presents itself"

### The German Reunification Trade (1989-1990)

- After Berlin wall fell: joyful East Germans flooded West, expecting jobs/social benefits
  - Associated costs seemed certain to force German government to run large budget deficits
  - **Standard logic**: budget deficits fuel inflation, eroding currency value
  - Traders dumped deutsche marks after wall fell; currency dipped vs dollar

- Druckenmiller took **different view**, recalling *Alchemy* on Reagan's early budget deficits
  - Those deficits **indirectly strengthened** dollar: tight Fed policy (high interest rates) encouraged investors to hold dollars
  - Druckenmiller saw Germany would follow same pattern: loose budgets → hawkish Bundesbank → higher rates → **strengthening currency**

- After wall fell: Druckenmiller bought **$2 billion position** in deutsche marks within days
  - Over next year, mark rose **quarter against dollar**
  - Trade built on Paul Tudor Jones insight: understanding other players (governments) creates attractive risk-to-reward ratios
  - **Central banks** particularly transparent — Bundesbank's anti-inflation determination was evident

- November 1989: enough for Druckenmiller to see Bundesbank would raise rates
  - Deutsche mark trade fueled Quantum's 29.8% return in 1990
  - Two years later: **greatest coup of career**, shattering European monetary order

### European Exchange-Rate Mechanism (ERM)

- System set up 1979 to dampen currency fluctuations within Europe
  - Allowed companies to invest/trade without worrying about wild exchange-rate swings
  - Worked well for decade+, stabilizing currencies without unifying them
  - Currencies allowed to move within narrow bands; if insufficient, country could negotiate devaluation
  - Gave national governments room to use interest rates for economic management
  - System balanced **exchange-rate stability** vs **interest-rate flexibility**

### Germany's Bundesbank Conflict

- German unification strained the compromise
  - Created inflationary pressure in Germany → Bundesbank raised interest rates
  - But other European economies in recession, needed **lower** rates
  - High German rates + low rates elsewhere → money flowed into deutsche marks
  - Weaker currencies (Italian lira, British pound) traded near bottom of permitted band, threatened to break out

- Europe's governments faced choice:
  - Germany cut rates to attract less capital
  - OR Italians/British raise rates (selling marks, buying lire/pounds)
  - OR both interest-rate adjustment and currency intervention
  - If both failed: Italy/Britain forced into devaluation

### Britain's Vulnerability (Summer 1992)

- Druckenmiller focused on **Britain**, where Quantum portfolio manager **Scott Bessent** studied volatile housing sector
  - Interest rates on British mortgages **not fixed** — when Bank of England raised rates, families felt pinch immediately
  - High German rates put Britain in tight bind: raising rates to protect pound would dent consumption during recession

- Druckenmiller saw opening for bets that could "scarcely go against him"
  - Significant chance British authorities would allow sterling to devalue
  - Virtually no chance sterling would rise vs deutsche mark (Britain's economy in doldrums)
  - Seizing asymmetrical bet: loaded up on deutsche marks, sold pounds
  - Invested **$1.5 billion** in position by end of August

### Understanding Government Politics

- Sterling trade employed **three Druckenmiller skills**:
  1. Equity research insights into economic trends (like Soros, unlike Commodities Corporation trio)
  2. Understanding currencies/interest rates (like Soros, unlike Julian Robertson)
  3. Eye for institutional factors creating good risk-to-reward ratios (like Paul Jones's Japanese fund manager insight)

- Next stage required understanding **financial politics of Europe**, especially Bundesbank pressures
  - Since hyperinflation fueling Hitler's rise, Germans prized **monetary stability**
  - **Bundesbank's mission**: exclusively fight inflation (unlike Fed's dual mandate of low inflation + full employment)
  - Germany's first instinct: refuse to cut rates while reunification caused deficits
  - If Germany hung tough, pressure on sterling would grow
  - **Maastricht Treaty** recently signed, envisaging eventual euro creation
  - Germany supported project but wouldn't fight inflation so zealously that European monetary order splintered

### The Bath Meeting (September 4-5, 1992)

- European finance ministers/central bankers met in Bath, England
  - British desperate for lower rates, egged on by Italians/French also battling recession
  - British finance minister **Norman Lamont** pressed for easing of German monetary policy
  - Lamont banged fist: "Twelve finance ministers are all sitting here demanding that you lower your interest rates. Why don't you do it?"

- **Helmut Schlesinger** (Bundesbank president) so shaken his first instinct was to walk out
  - Prized Bundesbank independence, resented political pressure (especially from foreigner)
  - Eventually said: no plan to cut rates, but saw no reason to raise rates either
  - Lamont seized statement, presented to media as concession (though nobody expected rate rise anyway)

### Schlesinger's Basel Declaration (September 8, 1992)

- Lamont's overreach infuriated Schlesinger
  - Felt compelled to correct impression of compromised independence
  - At Basel central bankers' gathering: declared publicly he could make **no guarantees** about future interest rates
  - Warned little confidence in fixed relationships among European currencies
  - Particularly alluded to **unsoundness of Italian lira**

- **George Soros** in audience — approached Schlesinger after speech to confirm German commitment
  - Asked about ECU (notional European currency preceding euro)
  - Schlesinger: liked concept of European currency but not "ECU" name — would prefer "mark"

### Schlesinger's Message and Soros's Reaction

- Answer clear: Bundesbank open to monetary union **but not at any price**
  - First priority: preserve proud tradition of inflation-proof deutsche mark
  - If other economies couldn't stomach austerity, they should devalue
  - Soros suspected Schlesinger content to see hard line sabotage EU monetary union plans
  - Union would create European central bank, supplanting Bundesbank
  - **Bureaucratic self-preservation**: Schlesinger personified tendency

- Excited, Soros called Druckenmiller in New York: **lira heading for fall**
  - Druckenmiller quickly added bet against Italian currency to existing sterling bet

### Planning the Sterling Attack

- Soros returned to NY, called **Robert Johnson** (currency expert moving from Bankers Trust to Soros Fund Management)
  - Convinced lira going down, now looking beyond that — perhaps Europe's game rules changing
  - Soros: "What do you think about sterling?"
  - Johnson wanted in-person meeting (Bankers Trust recorded calls)

- Johnson took cab to run-down Soros offices at 888 Seventh Avenue (duct tape on carpet, screens by Druckenmiller's desk)
  - Soros, Johnson, Druckenmiller sat around small conference table

- Soros asked Johnson to describe risks betting against sterling
  - Johnson: "Sterling is liquid, so you can always exit losing positions. Most you could lose is half a percent or so"
  - Druckenmiller: "What could you gain on the trade?"
  - Johnson: "If this thing busts out, you'd probably make fifteen or twenty percent"
  - Druckenmiller: "How likely is that to happen?"
  - Johnson: "On a three-month time frame, about ninety percent"

- Druckenmiller and Soros looking at each other, could hardly stay sitting in chairs
  - Soros: "How much would you do in your own fund?" (Johnson ran portfolio for Bankers Trust)
  - Johnson: might leverage **3-5 times capital**
  - Druckenmiller's eyes widened, huge frame taut: "Oh my God"

### Britain's Limited Reserves

- Johnson continued: Bank of England has only **£22 billion reserves** (~$44 billion)
  - Quantum could only sell sterling while someone willing to buy
  - After Schlesinger's comments, few private buyers left
  - Main buyers: Bank of England + other central banks supporting sterling
  - Once BoE ran out of reserves, impossible to bet further against sterling
  - **$44 billion might be the limit**

- Druckenmiller: "Maybe we can get fifteen of that" — suggesting **10x leverage** on existing position
  - Soros: "How long do you think they can hold out?"
  - Johnson: not more than few months
  - Druckenmiller got **Scott Bessent** on phone for opinion
  - Bessent went further: British government had **no stomach for higher rates**
  - Given choice between deeper recession + devaluing pound, government would choose devaluation
  - British might let sterling go **sooner than expected**

- Johnson left meeting with sense of premonition — could feel coiled energy
  - When right moment came, they would **destroy the British currency**

### The Cascade Begins (Early September 1992)

- Next days marked **watershed in relationship between governments and markets**
  - Financial tidal wave broke across Europe
  - Druckenmiller and Soros central players, but not only ones
  - Other hedge funds (including Commodities Corporation trio) + bank/treasury trading desks joined attacks
  - Through 1970s-1980s: nobody imagined private players could overwhelm central banks
  - **Plaza accord (1985)** confirmed governments' influence over exchange rates
  - Since mid-1980s: cross-border money flows roughly **tripled**
  - Hedge funds commanded large war chests; balance of power shifted

- August 1992: George H.W. Bush administration orchestrated **concerted dollar purchasing** by 18 central banks
  - But private capital sloshing through currency markets overwhelmed central banks' efforts

### Finland, Sweden, Italy Fall (September 8-11, 1992)

- **Tuesday, September 8** (day Schlesinger declared no promises on German rates):
  - Wave of speculative selling overpowered **Finnish central bank**
  - Government abandoned ECU peg; Finnish markka fell nearly 15%
  - Traders profited, whetting appetite for next victim

- **Wednesday**: run against **Sweden** — raised overnight rates to extraordinary **75%** to attract capital
  - Electronic herd stampeded **Italian lira**
  - Italian rates at 15% ordinarily enough to keep capital, but currency markets changed the game
  - Italy's currency presented **asymmetrical bet** — trend cried out to technical traders
  - Smart speculators sensed wave of money crashing down would overwhelm authorities' efforts

- **Friday, September 11**: lira broke through bottom of band permitted by exchange-rate mechanism
  - Over weekend, Italy negotiated formal devaluation

### Italy vs Finland

- **Lira's collapse especially sobering** — Finland not formally part of ERM, couldn't expect help from other European central banks
- Italy different: **first time ERM member so bloodied by markets**
  - Italy's membership entitled it to Bundesbank support
  - Bundesbank bought **DM 24 billion ($15.4B)** of lire week before devaluation — unprecedented intervention
  - Speculative selling overwhelmed Bundesbank's efforts; traders bagged another payout

- Even after lira's fall, European officials struggled to grasp new order
  - **Saturday, September 12**: while Italians negotiated with German officials, **Norman Lamont** kept schedule as if nothing amiss
  - Evening: attended **Last Night of the Proms**, singing "Rule Britannia" with great gusto
  - Next morning: assembled Treasury advisers for croissants breakfast
  - British press account: Lamont described as "**cock-a-hoop**"
  - As part of lira devaluation deal, Bundesbank promising **quarter-point rate cut** — might boost sterling

### Lamont's False Confidence

- Lamont's cheerfulness not surprising given assumptions of the times:
  - Analysts/journalists argued Italy and Britain not comparable
  - Italy: most shambolic rich country in Europe
  - Britain: governed by Conservative Party that transformed economic performance
  - Bank of England successfully fended off market pressure since August
  - September 3: improvised new weapon — borrowing **10 billion ECUs (£7.25B / $14B)** to expand sterling defense

- Day of announcement: pound experienced sharp rise
  - Currency traders believed government now had firepower to fight speculators
  - To Soros/Druckenmiller: "faintly amusing" — Britain's borrowed amount **equal to what Quantum Fund alone aspired to sell**
  - Early September 1992: nobody outside Soros offices could conceive **single hedge fund with <50 people** might muster war chest comparable to government's

### Monday, September 14, 1992

- Markets opened: Lamont's optimism appeared vindicated
  - Bank of England spent **$700 million**, lifted sterling slightly
  - Coming on top of German rate cut, modest intervention enough
  - But Lamont/advisers failed to grasp: **Monday's trading sealed Britain's fate**
  - Sterling's small rise confirmed speculators' premise
  - Bets against currencies with shaky pegs could be leveraged aggressively — worst that could happen: slight move against you

- Sure enough: pound took beating next day
  - Spain's finance minister called Lamont: "Awful"

### Schlesinger's Interview Triggers Crisis (Tuesday Evening, September 15)

- Evening: Lamont convened meeting with Treasury team + **Robin Leigh-Pemberton** (Bank of England governor)
  - Agreed to support sterling aggressively next morning; if failed, consider raising rates
  - As meeting wound down, Leigh-Pemberton read message from press office
  - **Helmut Schlesinger** gave interview to *Wall Street Journal* + German newspaper *Handelsblatt*
  - News agency report: Bundesbank governor believed **broad realignment of Europe's currencies** better than narrow lira adjustment

- **Lamont stunned** — remark tantamount to calling for sterling devaluation
  - Already Schlesinger's Bath statements triggered lira assault
  - Now German attacking Britain
  - Lamont asked Leigh-Pemberton to call Schlesinger immediately, overruling concern about interrupting Bundesbanker's dinner

- After phone call: Schlesinger granted interview on condition he could check quotations, hadn't found time yet
  - Lamont protested: dangerously leisurely response
  - Schlesinger's comments already on newswires; traders in NY/Asia would react overnight
  - Schlesinger needed quick denial
  - Leigh-Pemberton called Germany repeatedly, to no avail
  - Bundesbank press office explained Schlesinger quotations "**unauthorized**" (not yet approved)
  - Schlesinger would check article, issue statement when reaching office in morning
  - Lamont seethed — Germany's monetary master in no hurry to adapt to 24-hour trading

- That night: Lamont went to bed knowing next day would be difficult
  - Could not imagine **how** difficult
  - Memoir: thought Britain forced out of Europe's monetary system next day "simply did not cross my mind"

### Druckenmiller's Response (Tuesday Afternoon, New York)

- Druckenmiller read Schlesinger's comments Tuesday afternoon in NY
  - Didn't care whether "authorized" or not
  - **Schlesinger made obvious**: perfectly happy to see pound ejected from exchange-rate mechanism
  - Bundesbank not going to indulge weak neighbors with further rate cuts
  - Given recessionary forces in Britain, sterling's devaluation now **inevitable**

- Druckenmiller walked into Soros's office: time to move
  - Held $1.5B bet against pound since August, started doing more since Johnson conversation
  - Now trigger arrived — would **build position steadily**

- Soros listened, looked puzzled: "That doesn't make sense"
  - "What do you mean?"
  - If news accurate + almost no downside, why build steadily? Why not jump to **$15 billion**?
  - "**Go for the jugular**"

- Druckenmiller saw Soros was right — this was man's genius
  - Druckenmiller: done analysis, understood politics, seen trigger
  - Soros: sensed **moment to go nuclear**
  - When you knew you were right, no such thing as betting too much
  - **Pile on as hard as possible**

- Rest of Tuesday: Druckenmiller and Soros sold sterling to anyone prepared to buy
  - Normally left execution to traders, but got on phones themselves
  - Searched for banks agreeing to take other side of orders
  - Under ERM rules: Bank of England obliged to accept offers selling sterling for **DM 2.7780** (lowest permissible level)
  - Requirement only held during London trading day
  - With BoE closed: scramble to find buyers
  - Banks getting vast sell orders from Quantum alerted own currency traders (who'd start selling too)
  - Calls rippled around world — **avalanche starting**
  - Soon pound knocked out of permitted band, became almost impossible to find buyers

### The Night Before (Tuesday Night/Wednesday Morning)

- Late Tuesday: **Louis Bacon** called Stan Druckenmiller
  - Two discussed how drama might play out; Bacon still finding ways to dump sterling
  - Druckenmiller: "Really?" — told Bacon to wait, seconds later Soros joined call
  - Soros demanded furiously: "**Where did you get the market?**"

- Soros and Druckenmiller eventually went home, leaving traders to search for more sterling-selling opportunities
  - **Robert Johnson** beeped by Quantum's head trader while asleep in NY apartment
  - Slipped out of bed, quietly returned call (wife official at NY Fed)
  - Around 2 AM: Druckenmiller returned to office
  - Wanted at desk when London trading reopened, BoE forced to resume sterling purchases

### Wednesday Morning in London

- **Scott Bessent** (portfolio manager based in London) arrived shortly after Druckenmiller
  - Could see hulking outline of boss in dark office
  - Druckenmiller taking off coat; nighttime Manhattan skyline behind him
  - Only light: telephone (Soros on line)
  - Disembodied eastern European accent filled dark room
  - **Soros urging Druckenmiller to leverage up and redouble selling**

- When markets opened in London: expectation of BoE support restored sterling (flat at band bottom)
  - Acting on Lamont's authorization previous evening: BoE intervened twice before 8:30 AM, each time buying **£300 million**
  - Buying had **absolutely no effect**
  - Druckenmiller manning cockpit on other side of Atlantic, clamoring to sell sterling **by the billion**
  - Clamor driving legions of imitators to sell also
  - BoE intervening, not realizing how completely outgunned
  - By 8:40 AM: purchased total **£1 billion**, sterling still refused to budge

- Ten minutes later: Lamont told PM **John Major** intervention failing
  - Britain would have to raise interest rates to protect sterling

### Major Refuses Rate Hike

- To Lamont's frustration: **Major refused to authorize rate hike**
  - Responsible for taking Britain into exchange-rate mechanism
  - Feared credibility collapsing if policy seen as failing
  - Might face leadership challenge from cabinet member
  - Major pleaded: new economic data coming out later that day
  - Told Lamont to hang tough, hope markets would subside eventually

- By now central bankers worldwide on high alert
  - Another call to **Robert Johnson's apartment** from NY Fed
  - Johnson's wife spent remainder of night monitoring crisis, unaware husband helped cause it
  - Bank of England continued buying pounds (obliged by ERM rules)
  - No longer aspired to lift currency off floor — merely **providing liquidity** to Druckenmiller and cohorts
  - Every hour: hedge funds + banks sold more sterling to BoE (being forced to load up on currency sure to be devalued)
  - Britain presiding over **vast financial transfer from long-suffering taxpayers to global army of traders**
  - 10:30 AM: Lamont called John Major again to urge rate rise

### British Officials Project Confidence

- While Lamont calling PM: British officials projected confidence
  - **Eddie George** (BoE number two) ahead with long-scheduled meeting with **David Smick** (financial consultant, political intelligence to Druckenmiller/Soros)
  - Smick showed up at BoE's Threadneedle Street building
  - Found George "apparently fine form, decked out in checkered shirt and striped tie in manner of London banker"
  - George cheerily: "We have it all under control"
  - Extreme case (unlikely): BoE would raise rates by **full percentage point** to see off speculators
  - Smick wondered whether George understood weight of money crashing on Britain
  - **Avalanche begun — might be too late to stop**

- Smick summoned nerve, asked straight out: "Aren't you worried you may have slipped too far behind the curve on this thing?"
  - George's look betrayed mild annoyance, about to respond when phone rang
  - After minute of intense conversation, hung up
  - "I've learned we've just raised interest rates by **two hundred basis points**" (full 2 percentage points)
  - Rose, shook Smick's hand, left room running

### The 2% Rate Hike Fails

- Lamont's plea to PM succeeded this time
  - Announcement of dramatic rate hike set for 11:00 AM
  - Minutes before appointed hour: Lamont walked to outer Treasury office to watch Reuters screen
  - When announcement came: **pound did not respond at all**
  - Line on screen remained totally flat
  - Lamont felt like surgeon watching heart monitor, realizing patient expired
  - All that remained: unplug system

- Lamont had no time to negotiate realignment within Europe's ERM
  - Realignment would require lengthy coordination with other European governments
  - Every minute ticked by: vast transfer of wealth from taxpayers to traders continued
  - Italy lucky to get into trouble Friday (before weekend respite)
  - Britain on edge of same cliff Wednesday
  - **Lamont's only recourse**: quit European exchange-rate mechanism **unilaterally**
  - Required PM's approval

### Major's Futile Diplomacy

- PM not immediately available
  - Lamont's staff called Major's office repeatedly to stress urgency
  - No audience granted
  - Eventually Lamont led advisers team to **Admiralty House** (fine Georgian building, temporary PM residence)
  - Cooled heels for at least another quarter hour before Major would see them
  - Lamont calculated: nation losing **hundreds of millions of pounds every few minutes**
  - Boss looked annoyingly relaxed

- Major began meeting wondering aloud: room for further financial diplomacy with Germany?
  - Added: several other government ministers would shortly join to add perspectives
  - Meandering discussion ensued: Could Britain withdraw from ERM without offending European partners? If withdrew, calls for ministers' resignations?
  - Became clear: Major's objective was **share responsibility** for crisis with others in room
  - "We were there to put our hands in the blood" — shrewd maneuver from Major's perspective


<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

### Sterling Crisis Endgame: Black Wednesday

#### Britain's Final Stand

- **Admiralty House meeting** broke without decision to quit exchange-rate mechanism
- **John Major** insisted on another **3% interest rate hike** (effective next day) as last-ditch effort to save sterling
- Lamont watched on Reuters screen—again, **no effect on sterling's value**
- Druckenmiller and Soros saw rate hikes as **"act of desperation by a dying man"**—signal the end was near

#### The Capitulation

- **Piero Barucci** (Italian counterpart) suggested suspending markets to negotiate realignment
- Lamont explained: impossible to suspend continuously trading global currency markets
- **7:30 PM press conference**: Lamont announced Britain's **exit from exchange-rate mechanism**
- "The markets had won, and the government had at last recognized it"

### The Profits: "Man Who Broke the Bank of England"

#### The Numbers

- **Bank of England** spent **$27 billion** defending sterling in first half of September
- Sterling fell **14% against deutsche mark** after leaving mechanism
- **British taxpayers lost ~$3.8 billion** on their currency purchases
- **Hedge funds led the charge**—Quantum was the biggest
- Druckenmiller/Soros sold **less than $15 billion** sterling short, but still monumental

#### Distribution of Gains

- **$300 million** → **Bruce Kovner** (Commodities Corporation)
- **$250 million** → **Paul Jones**
- **$800 million** → top seven currency desks at U.S. banks
- **Soros Fund Management profit: over $1 billion**

#### Soros Goes Public

- **Gianni Agnelli** (Fiat) leaked to journalists: Quantum investment would earn more than Fiat takings that year
- **October 24, 1992**: Britain's *Daily Mail* ran photo of smiling Soros: **"I Made a Billion as the Pound Crashed"**
- Soros **enlarged personal fortune by $650 million in 1992**
- Magazine noted: Soros earned in **5 minutes** what median American family earned in full year
- Surpassed **Michael Milken's $550 million** (1987)—Soros became "the man who broke the Bank of England"
- **Hedge funds displaced 1980s buyout kings** as objects of popular envy

### Druckenmiller's Multifaceted Strategy

#### Beyond Sterling: Stocks and Bonds

- Soros funds' **full profits considerably larger** than outsiders imagined
- Like **Paul Jones** coupling equity crash short (1987) with bond bet, **Druckenmiller built out from sterling coup**
- As pound came under pressure, **Britain's equity and government-bond markets were hit**
- Traders reasoned: flight of capital from Britain would damage other asset prices
- **Druckenmiller took different view**: Britain's ejection would **free government to cut interest rates**
- Lower rates would **drive government bonds up**; weaker currency + lower rates = **good for equities**
- While selling sterling Tuesday/Wednesday, Druckenmiller was **buying British government bonds and equities**
- **Bets paid off**: over next two months, bond markets rose steeply

#### French Franc Attack

- Sterling wasn't Druckenmiller's sole focus
- After sterling's fall, speculators mounted **attack on French franc**
- Druckenmiller believed **central bank would win** against markets
- **French families not exposed to floating mortgage rates**—easier to fight with temporary high rates than British
- Druckenmiller **bought armfuls of French bonds** (soared in 1993)
- Explains why **Quantum's 69% return (1992) followed by 63% return (1993)**

#### Swedish Krona: The Secret Coup

- **Quantum's greatest post-sterling coup** was also **most discreet**
- **Robert Johnson** (joined full-time) shorted **Swedish krona** before devaluation in November 1992
- Gain: **pocketing upward of $1 billion**
- After publicity from sterling trade, **Soros/Druckenmiller made sure nobody spoke publicly about Sweden**

### Macro Trading Proves Efficient-Market Hypothesis Wrong

#### Political Motives Trump Profit Maximization

- **Governments and central banks not trying to maximize profits**
- At height of sterling crisis, **John Major effectively bought sterling from Stan Druckenmiller at absurd price**
- **Major's reason**: force political rivals to share responsibility for devaluation (appears nowhere in financial texts)

#### Currency Pegs Vulnerable in Liquid Markets

- **1950s/1960s**: fixed currencies worked because **capital controls restricted cross-border flows**
- With controls gone, governments had to **accept limits to power over money**
- Choice: use interest rates to manage currency value (dampening exchange-rate swings) OR manage economic ups/downs (dampening recessions)
- **"Flexible pegs" like exchange-rate mechanism likely to backfire**
- Contrast: **U.S. dollar floated freely**—when Bush administration tried/failed to lift dollar (August), no calamity
- **European currency pegs** (Finland, Italy, Britain, Sweden) presented targets **too appealing to pass up**
- European governments made **promise they lacked ability to keep**—"bottled up currency movements until power greater than themselves blew cork into faces"

### Political Backlash and Policy Debate

#### Politicians Attack Speculators

- **Michel Sapin** (French finance minister): suggested **guillotining** troublemaking traders
- **Edouard Balladur** (French premier): governments have **economic and moral responsibility to curb speculators**
- **Willy Claes** (Belgium foreign affairs minister): Anglo-Saxon financiers **"plotting to divide Europe"**

#### Soros's Response: Intellectual Ambivalence

- Soros proved himself **more ruthless than any other market player**
- Bank trading desks had regulators, were **reluctant to assail governments too violently**
- Soros had **no such inhibitions**
- Yet **intellectually disposed to see markets as wild things at risk of boom/bust**
- Shortly after pound's devaluation, Soros saw **Jean-Claude Trichet** (French central bank governor)
- Told him: **out of concern for destabilizing effects of own trading, would not attack franc**
- Claim **"a bit much"**—Quantum had correctly calculated franc would hold, was about to profit on this prophecy
- Nevertheless, Soros's overture **dramatized mood following sterling's fall**
- **"Greatest speculator of them all was unwilling to defend speculation"**

#### Druckenmiller's View: "White Wednesday"

- British press dubbed it **"Black Wednesday"**
- Druckenmiller thought **"White Wednesday"** more apposite
- Britain freed from **Bundesbank's high interest rates**—freed to pursue recession-fighting policies needed
- **London stock market reaction proved Druckenmiller's point**: FTSE jumped **almost a fifth** in two months
- Druckenmiller's trading **upended economic policy of British government**, but not necessarily bad
- High German interest rates (from unification) created situation where **sterling needed to exit**
- Britain's rulers failed to recognize until Druckenmiller had recognized for them
- **John Major transferred $1 billion plus taxpayers' money to Soros funds**—not entirely Druckenmiller's fault
- **If somebody fleeced country blind, it was prime minister, not speculator**

### The Academic Consensus Shifts

#### From Government Mismanagement to Speculator Power

- **Before sterling trade**: economists argued currency crises triggered by **bad economic policy** (villain = government mismanagement, not speculation)
- **During 1990s**: academic consensus **shifted from Druckenmiller's view to Soros's**
- New view: traders might **attack currencies that were decently managed**, attacks might **prove self-fulfilling**
- **Sterling collapse created tipping point** in debate
- Druckenmiller correct: Britain invited crisis with **untenable high interest rates**
- But once his trading demonstrated **power of speculators over governments**, risk of abuse became obvious
- Before: traders might only attack currencies **doomed by economic fundamentals**
- Now: might feel empowered to **attack stable ones**
- French politicians' concerns about hedge funds amassing **dangerous and excessive power** not totally baseless

### The Policy Response: Nothing

#### Clamping Down = Return to Bretton Woods

- Little was done to reduce danger
- Clamping down on speculators—**guillotining them, as French finance minister urged**—would require **taming cross-border money waves**
- Would involve **return to Bretton Woods and reimposition of capital controls**
- Most policy makers **viewed with horror**
- If free trade in goods/services beneficial, surely **free flows of capital good for same reason**
- Trade allowed **car manufacturing concentrated in countries that did it best**
- Cross-border capital flows funneled **scarce savings to places that would invest them most productively**
- **Capital controls might be impractical** (as intellectually suspect)
- Week after sterling crisis, **Spain and Ireland tried to dampen speculative attacks by restricting banks' freedom** to trade currencies
- **Controls quickly circumvented**

#### Abolish National Currencies

- If capital controls off table, one remaining way to **prevent speculative attacks**—**abolish them**
- **"Speculation can be very harmful,"** Soros told interviewer after sterling's bust
- Single European currency **"would put speculators like me out of business, but I would be delighted to make that sacrifice"**
- **Europe eventually unified currencies in 1999**, but not everybody learned
- **Emerging economies in Asia and Latin America** stuck with pegging policy
- Created **immense opportunities for hedge funds later in decade**

## Chapter 8: Hurricane Greenspan

### Michael Steinhardt's Shadowbanking Empire

#### The Setup: Fed-Assisted Arbitrage

- December 1993: **Steinhardt Partners** up **$100 million in single day**
- Running **~$4.5 billion** in capital; 1991/1992 returns: **47%/48%** after fees; 1993 heading for similar
- Magazines reporting Steinhardt's **Picasso purchase (~$1 million)**
- Steinhardt returned from sabbatical 1979, resumed **stock picking and block trading**
- Early 1990s: pioneering **early version of shadow banking system**
- Like Druckenmiller's currency trading, strategy involved **exploiting central bank policies** (this time **U.S. Federal Reserve**)

#### How It Worked

- **1990-1991**: U.S. in recession following S&L crisis
- **Fed keeping short-term interest rates low** to stimulate economy
- Created situation: Steinhardt could **borrow short-term money exceedingly cheaply, load up on longer-term bonds** yielding considerably more
- Risk: if **longer-term interest rates spiked up**, value of Steinhardt's bonds would crater
- But **sluggish economy kept demand for capital low**—price of capital (interest rate) **unlikely to head upward**
- **Longer-term interest rates fell** at start of 1990s
- Steinhardt handed **capital gain on bonds** on top of profits from gap between short/long-term rates

#### Political Economy: Major Enriching Druckenmiller, Fed Rewarding Steinhardt

- **John Major enriched Druckenmiller** to neutralize political rivals
- **Fed rewarded Steinhardt** trying to assist battered banking system
- By **increasing gap between short/long-term rates**, Fed made it **more lucrative for banks to engage in normal business** (borrow short, lend long)
- **Sharpening banks' incentive** to push money into economy

#### Steinhardt as Shadowbank

- Steinhardt **crashing this party**
- Fed wanted to help banks, so Steinhardt **turned himself into shadowbank**
- Borrowed short, lent long—**just like any bank would**
- Difference: **Steinhardt bypassed tedious business** of hiring tellers/credit officers
- Borrowed from **brokerages (Goldman Sachs, Salomon Brothers)**, then lent by buying bonds
- **No bank infrastructure**—could **charge in/out as Fed's policies shifted**

#### The Leverage Advantage

- **Steinhardt's shadowbank enjoyed further advantage**
- Real banks faced **regulatory controls on lending**
- For every **$100 customer deposits → loans**, had to set aside **~$10 in capital** (ensure repayment even if loans went sour)
- Steinhardt had **no depositors, hence no "capital adequacy" rule**
- Could **borrow whatever brokers would lend**
- Brokers prepared to lend **astronomical amount**
- For every **$100 Steinhardt borrowed to buy U.S. government bonds**, could often get away with **as little as $1 in capital**

### Europe and the Bond Strategy Expansion

#### 1993: Taking Bond Strategy to Europe

- Steinhardt/fellow speculators took bond strategy to Europe
- **Exchange-rate mechanism crises over**, Europe headed for **monetary union**
- Process forcing **interest rates across continent to converge**
- Countries like **Spain and Italy** (weak inflation record, had to compensate with high rates) now subjected to **strict inflation-fighting rules**
- Interest rates began **falling toward Germany's**
- Steinhardt/traders bought **truckloads of Spanish and Italian bonds**
- Realized **capital gain as interest rates came down**
- Jumping on opportunity **governments practically invited them to take**
- **European statesmen made no secret** of plans for monetary union, nor about resulting convergence in interest rates

### The Hedge Fund Boom (Early 1990s)

#### Industry Growth

- **Hedge funds profited hugely** early 1990s because **set up to seize such opportunities**
- Senior investment bankers **quit Goldman Sachs/Salomon Brothers** to get in on new game
- **Wall Street law firms** claimed to be **midwifing new hedge-fund partnerships at rate of two per month**
- **Helmsley Building** (foot of Park Avenue): notorious as hedge-fund hotel
- Number of hedge funds: **over 1,000 (1992) → perhaps 3,000 (next year)**
- Fees expanded almost as quickly

#### Fee Evolution

- **Dawn of industry**: **A.W. Jones** charged **no management fee**, asking only **20% profit share**
- **Second generation** (like Steinhardt): demanded **1% management fee + 20% profit share**
- **Early 1990s boom**: hot new funds demanded **"2 and 20"**

> "Perhaps never before in history have so few made so much money so fast" — *Forbes*

#### Steinhardt's Market Dominance

- Fast money **not without controversy**
- Steinhardt's energetic shadowbanking **mirrored by most other major funds**
- Caused him to **buy up vast amounts of newly issued government bonds** (at one point effective takeover of market)
- **April 1991 Treasury bond auction**: Steinhardt and **Bruce Kovner** bid for **$6.5 billion of $12 billion** paper due to be issued
- Lent bonds to short sellers, bought them back again → ended with **$16 billion bonds** (considerably more than 100% of market)
- Bonds shot up in value, **short sellers tried to get out** but couldn't buy back paper (Steinhardt/Kovner cornered market, not selling)
- Victims: **Goldman Sachs, Salomon Brothers, Bear Stearns**—hardly sharks eating innocents

#### Legal Settlements

- After **three years fighting in courts**, Steinhardt/Kovner settled without admitting guilt
- Steinhardt: **paid $40 million** compensation to short sellers
- Kovner: **paid $36 million**
- Sued again over **May Treasury auction irregularities**
- Again agreed to **settlements involving payments to plaintiffs**

### Shadowbanks Changing Monetary Policy

#### Accelerating Policy Transmission

- **Allegations of market manipulation** shouldn't have been only public concern
- **Hedge funds changing monetary policy** (generally not realized at time)
- As they responded to **Fed's low short-term rates** by aggressively buying longer-dated Treasuries, **link between short/long-term rates grew tighter**
- **Cut in Fed's rate** (old world: weeks to feed through to lower long-term rates) now **fed through a lot faster**
- **Could be good**: if Fed wanted to stimulate economy, helpful that hedge funds chased long bond rates downward
- **Could be dangerous**: bond market might respond quickly, but **real economy bound to lag**
- If Fed held interest rates down until Main Street felt benefits, **Wall Street likely to inflate giant bond bubble**

#### The Pyramiding Danger

- Bubbles threatened to be **newly scary**
- World in which hedge funds could **corner Treasury auction** = new kind of world built on **breathtaking leverage**
- **American system pyramiding debt upon debt**: government borrowed from hedge funds → hedge funds borrowed from brokers → brokers borrowed from some other indebted somebody
- **If one player collapsed, rest could lose access to borrowed funds** → force them to dump assets fast
- **Bubble could burst instantly**

### January 1994: Steinhardt's Confidence

- Start of 1994: **prospect not on anybody's mind**, least of all Steinhardt's
- January: authorized lieutenant to **buy staggering position in Canadian bonds**
- Added to bets in **U.S., Japan, Europe**
- Headed off to **China on another vacation**

### Alan Greenspan's Rate Hike (February 4, 1994)

#### The Setup

- **January 21, 1994**: **Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan** visited White House
- Economy had **recovered, then grown smoothly for 34 consecutive months**
- Inflation quiescent, but **time to preempt resurgence with small rate hike**
- Greenspan hoped to **avoid overheating forcing him to slam brakes later**
- Aimed to pilot economy toward **"soft landing"**

#### Gore's Objection

- **Vice President Gore** objected
- In past, small rate hike signaled **beginning of long series**: 1988-89, Fed's short-term rate went **6.5% → nearly 10%** in dozen small increments
- If markets expected same this time, **long rates might shoot upward anticipating more tightening**
- **Bond market would crash**
- Hard landing Greenspan wanted to avoid **might become reality**

#### Greenspan's Reassurance

- Gore raising **sort of question Greenspan loved to answer**
- Fed chairman spent career as **economic consultant in New York**
- More than most Washington figures, perhaps more than **British mandarins who lost battle over sterling**, **understood markets**
- Possibility rate hike might cause **nasty Wall Street backlash** one he'd certainly considered
- Focused above all on **reaction in stock market** (entered record territory 1993)
- **S&P 500 appeared ripe for correction**
- Bond market seemed **secondary importance**

#### The Theory

- Greenspan assured Gore: **long-term rates governed mainly by inflation expectations**
- If Fed raised short rates, would **signal authorities vigilant on price pressures**
- Result: **lower inflation expectations → lower long-term rates**
- Rate hike Greenspan proposed **should be bullish for bond market**

#### The Reality: February 4, 1994

- Fortnight later: Greenspan presided over **Fed's interest-rate committee meeting**
- Proposed to **head off inflation** with gentle rate hike of **25 basis points** (3% → 3.25%)
- Risked triggering **backlash from traditionally volatile stock market**
- Greenspan instructed colleagues: **"If we do 50 basis points today, very high probability of cracking markets... very unwise procedure"**

#### Market Reaction

- Greenspan's sense of stock market **right**
- After Fed announced quarter-point rate hike, **S&P 500 dipped** (precisely sort of gentle correction Fed chairman wanted)
- Greenspan's assurances about bond market **proved mistaken**
- Told Gore: hike in short-term rates would **calm inflation fears** (logically allow long-term rates to ease)
- Instead: **Fed's 25-basis-point tightening produced swift increase of same magnitude in ten-year Treasury rate**
- **Something mysterious was stirring**

### The Shadowbank Response: Opposite of Greenspan's Expectation

#### The New Logic

- In era before shadowbanking, Greenspan's reassurances **might have proved justified**
- **New shadowbanks not as focused on inflation** as Fed chairman expected
- Way shadowbankers saw: **first Fed hike in half decade created uncertainty**
- Uncertainty = risk
- Because even **small fall in bond market could wipe out thin capital base** of leveraged hedge funds, **mere *possibility* of fall forced them to reduce risk** by selling part of holdings
- **New logic of leverage changed central-banking game**
- In response to rate hike, shadowbanks **dumped bonds, forced long-term interest rates up**—**opposite of what Greenspan expected**

#### February 11: The Yen Shock

- Week after Fed's action (Friday, February 11): **another shock to bond market**
- **Trade talks between Clinton administration and Japan broke down**
- American side seeking revenge by **signaling stronger yen would be in order**
- Within week, **yen jumped 7% against dollar**
- Wrong-footing several hedge funds (including **Stan Druckenmiller**: **$8 billion bet against yen**, lost **$650 million in two days**)
- Traditional central-banking logic: **should have had no impact on inflation expectations and bonds**
- **Sheer scale of hedge-fund leverage ensured vicious chain reaction**
- Losses from yen shock forced hedge funds to **dump assets and raise capital**
- Since hedge funds held **lot of bonds**, bond market **knocked backward**
- Over two weeks, **ten-year Treasury yield jumped more than quarter of percent**
- **World in which hedge funds traded everything = world of unpredictable connections**

### Europe: The Contagion Spreads

#### February: Central Banks Push Rates Down

- Next victim: **Europe**
- February: central banks of **Germany, Britain, France, Belgium pushed short-term rates downward**
- Signaling: **saw no inflation risk, little reason for long rates to move upward**

#### Traders' Logic Asserts Itself

- In aftermath of yen shock, **traders' logic asserted itself once again**
- **European long-term interest rates spiked up**
- In fortnight: yield on **German 10-year bonds rose 37 basis points, Italy's rose 58, Spain's rose 62**
- Hedge funds and **banks' proprietary trading desks lost money on U.S. Treasuries and yen**
- Responding by **dumping European bonds** (never mind continent's economic fundamentals)

#### The Stampede and Margin Calls

- Once hedge funds **began to flee Europe**, stampede built on own momentum
- **Brokers that lent freely to shadowbankers** suddenly reversed
- Rather than accepting **$1 million collateral per $100 million bonds**, brokers demanded **$3-5 million** to protect from danger hedge fund might be unable to repay
- To meet brokers' margin calls, hedge funds had to **liquidate holdings on grand scale**
- If **leveraged 100:1**, and broker demands extra **$4 million in margin**, you have to **sell $400 million bonds—quickly**
- As hedge funds liquidated bond positions, **selling pressure drove remaining holdings down** → triggering **yet further margin calls**
- **Scary pyramiding of debt** (fueled bond bubble in good times) now **accelerated implosion**

#### March 1: Inflation Data Triggers More Selling

- Two weeks after yen shock (March 1): **more bad news**
- New data: **U.S. inflation more of threat than feared**
- Keeping with Greenspan view, **yield on 10-year Treasury bonds jumped 15 basis points**
- **Economic logic explained reaction in United States**, no such logic could explain what happened next
- **Bond markets in Japan and Europe cratered**
- Far from spooked by expected surge in inflation, **Japan grappling with threat of *deflation***
- Yet **ten-year Japanese interest rates jumped 17 basis points** (March 2)
- As brokers issued **more margin calls to hedge funds**, logic of leverage **transmitted trouble to Europe**
- To raise capital, hedge funds **off-loaded estimated $60 billion European bond holdings**
- **Long-term interest rates spiked upward**

### The Carnage: March 1994

#### Major Casualties

- Frenzy of selling created **sharp losses across Wall Street**
- **Paul Tudor Jones** (great strength: sense how other traders positioned) **failed to spot danger in Europe**; spring 1994 fund **down sharply**
- Same for **Bruce Kovner and Louis Bacon** (Commodities Corporation trio)
- **David Gerstenhaber** (macro trader hired by Julian Robertson 1991): running own hot fund, **blew up spectacularly**
- **Proprietary trading desks did badly**: 1994, **Goldman Sachs experienced worst year in decade**
- **Insurance industry**: reckoned to have **lost as much money on bond holdings as damages from Hurricane Andrew**
- **"I'm starting to call this Hurricane Greenspan"** — insurance analyst

#### Bankers Trust Near-Failure

- Few hours on March 2: **Bankers Trust teetered on brink of bankruptcy**
- Trading suspended on **New York Stock Exchange**
- **New York Fed president William McDonough** phoned top bankers up/down Wall Street to rally confidence
- Ultimately, **Bankers Trust survived**
- Storm of deleveraging pushed Wall Street powerhouse to edge, **but had not pushed it over—at least not this time**

### Michael Steinhardt: The Greatest Casualty

#### The Losses

- **Greatest casualty of bloodbath: Michael Steinhardt**
- Returned from China vacation to find **U.S. bond market sold off** (suffered modest losses)
- Biggest bets: **Japan, Canada, especially Europe** (accumulated **astonishing $30 billion bond portfolio**)
- Consoled himself: **Fed's tightening in United States would not hit foreign markets too severely**
- Then **logic of deleveraging kicked in**
- Every bond market whipsawed
- For Steinhardt's **vast and leveraged portfolio**, each **basis-point move upward in European rates = $10 million loss**
- By end of February: **bled stunning $900 million**
- **Down almost 20%** (troubles not yet over)

#### The Liquidity Trap

- Steinhardt not merely misjudged **markets' direction**; misjudged **liquidity**
- Supposed beauty of macro trading: **bond/currency markets could absorb huge quantities of capital**
- In **boom years of early 1990s**, hedge funds/foreign traders encountered **no difficulty establishing vast positions in European bonds**
- Bought up **about half of Germany's government and government-guaranteed bonds**
- Able to accumulate these positions **without moving price adversely**: building gradually, if particular bond difficult to buy, **no problem waiting few days**
- But when shock hit and **brokers issued margin calls**, hedge funds had to **sell out in rush**—at exactly same time as others
- **Everybody scrambled to sell to everybody else**
- **Liquidity was gone. Nobody was buying.**

#### The Personal Crisis

- In old days of equity block trading, **Steinhardt knew brokers personally** (could rely on them even in serious crisis)
- After all, **major client**—they wanted to keep his business
- **Europe's bond markets different game**
- Steinhardt dealing with **brokers based continent away—anonymous voices in different time zone**
- **European bond brokers didn't know Steinhardt and he didn't know them**
- When liquidity crunch came, **not willing to help Steinhardt get out of positions**

#### The Desperation

- Seated at **bow-shaped desk, staring at seven blinking computer screens**
- Witnessed decomposition of his fund
- **Desperate sensation of not being able to catch breath** (as though drowning)
- Ate little, slept less
- Known for **explosive blowups**, now took to **conferring in whispers** with top lieutenants behind closed doors
- Traders fought to get out of positions
- Seemed to think if they waited, **better opportunity to sell**
- But **prices kept falling like stones**
- Everybody looking for bid, but **market seemed to consist exclusively of sellers**

#### The Fire Sale

- **John Lattanzio** (veteran Steinhardt lieutenant) marched to firm's bond trading desk
- **"Just sell 'em!" Lattanzio barked. "Just sell 'em!"**
- **"I can't,"** trader answered flatly
- Seeing no other way forward, Steinhardt resolved to **dump bonds at any price**
- Even if meant offering **sort of discounts he used to extract from block sellers in good old days**
- By end of **four-day selling burst in early March**, traders had **dumped $1 billion in European bonds**
- Meanwhile, battle to escape **Japan and Canada continued**
- **Canadian central bank** would periodically call up nervously to ask whether Steinhardt's traders were done selling

#### The Aftermath

- Steinhardt fallen into trap that would **become well known in new leveraged markets**
- Failed to sense when trade had become ***crowded***
- In world in which broker's margin call could **force leveraged funds into fire sales**, key was to **beware markets in which leveraged players were concentrated**
- Looking back on 1994, Steinhardt conceded naïveté: **"Trade in European bonds was crowded, fact that totally passed me by"**
- When dust settled end of March, **Steinhardt's funds down 30%**
- About **$1.3 billion of capital vaporized**

### Askin Capital: The Fraud Collapses

#### David Askin's Pitch

- Steinhardt's humiliation **quickly followed by another hedge-fund collapse**: **Askin Capital Management**
- **David Askin** launched business **1993 glory days**
- Created **$2.5 billion portfolio of mortgage securities**
- Little experience actually managing money (financial analyst and salesman)
- Pitch: as **former head of mortgage research at Drexel Burnham Lambert**, could make money from mortgages **in any financial climate**

#### The Mortgage Derivatives Strategy

- Claimed edge in **analyzing likelihood mortgage might be paid off early**
- Mortgages with **high prepayment risk logically worth less** (prepayment would deprive investors of income stream)
- Wall Street busy **slicing mortgages into exotic instruments**
- Interest payments and principal payment on mortgage cut into **two separate "strips"**: homeowners prepaid rapidly, **interest-only strips (IOs) would lose**; **principal-only strips (POs) would gain**
- If prepayments lagged, **opposite**
- Askin dabbled in **IOs, POs, inverse IOs, inverse POs, even "forward inverse IO"**
- For firm that nailed prepayment risks, **opportunities endless**

#### The Fraud

- Askin's pitch won over **respected names** (investors: **AIG, Rockefeller Foundation**)
- Sales pitch **fraudulent**
- Askin claimed funds **"market neutral"**—make money regardless of bond market up/down
- Truth: **had little idea how clever investments might perform in crisis**
- Claimed to use **sophisticated modeling to analyze prepayment risks** (proprietary software stored on own computer)
- **No such model existed**

#### The Collapse

- When Fed raised interest rates February, **Askin's funds began to fall in value**
- Surge in long-term rates **raised cost of mortgages, removed incentive for homeowners to refinance**
- Prepayments of existing mortgages declined → **duration stretched out like chewing gum**
- Despite claims to **market neutrality**, Askin turned out to be **acutely exposed to duration change**
- For any given rise in long-term rates, **portfolio fell five times more than ordinary bond**
- First Askin **covered up discovery by misreporting results**
- Revolt within firm forced him to **come clean** (Friday, March 25): admitted funds **fallen 20% in February**
- Moreover, **assassination of Mexican presidential candidate (March 23)** ratcheted up panic
- Investors responded by **dumping Mexican bonds**, then **dumping all emerging-market bonds**, then **dumping rich-world bonds** to rebalance portfolios
- For Askin: **last straw**
- Renewed surge in interest rates guaranteed **March results would be awful**

#### The Final Days

- Morning of **Monday, March 28**: brokers began issuing **margin calls to Askin**
- **Bear Stearns** demanded **$20 million** additional capital
- **Kidder Peabody** wanted **$41 million**
- By afternoon Bear upped request to **$50 million**
- Next day **Salomon Brothers, Lehman Brothers, host of other creditors piled on**
- Soon clear: **Askin would have to sell huge portions of portfolio to satisfy creditors**
- **Team of Kidder mortgage traders** showed up uninvited at Askin's premises
- Demanded to inspect his books
- Worked through night aiming to **come up with fair price for chunk of Askin's funds**
- Soon confronted problem: **If Askin owned portfolio outright, Kidder could make bid** (providing Askin cash to stave off other creditors)
- But **Askin's holdings pledged as collateral to dozens of creditors** (whose claims could not be unscrambled easily)
- **Yet another lesson about leverage** to haunt hedge funds in future: **Not only can cause fund to crash. Can complicate burial.**

#### Wednesday, March 30: The Death Throes

- Sharks continued to circle
- Brokers issued **ever bigger margin calls** (desperate to get hands on Askin's cash before other creditors)
- **Swiss investment-management firm Unigestion** (owned one of Askin's subfunds) ordered Askin to **liquidate positions**
- Askin contacted **18 dealers**, most bids **so low as to be worthless**
- Two of Askin's positions (**"forward inverse IOs"**) **failed to attract any bids at all**
- In another premonition of future troubles, **sheer complexity of instruments made them impossible to sell**
- **Nobody on Street knew how to value them**

#### The Final Lowball Offer

- **3:45 PM Wednesday**: **Bear Stearns** offered to buy chunk of Askin's portfolio for **paltry $5 million**
- As though trying to **kill victim with one swift bite**
- Bear demanded Askin **answer yes or no within 15 minutes**
- Askin prevaricated, asked for **extra 15 minutes**
- Ultimately refused: **not going to make life easier for predators** by taking shirt off
- Brokers gave up hope of **negotiated asset sale**, began to **take possession of whatever collateral they held**
- Hedging new holdings by **dumping Treasuries**
- **Bond market reeled again** as remains of Askin's fund dismembered

### Clinton's Intervention (March 31, 1994)

#### The President's Panic

- Panic in bond market (swept from U.S. to foreign markets, from Treasuries to mortgage bonds) reached **top echelons of government**
- Morning of **March 31, 1994**: as **Askin's brokers selling life out of Treasury market**, **Bill Clinton interrupted California vacation**
- President **schooled by advisers to view bond market with special awe**
- Previous year: raised taxes on theory **smaller federal budget deficit would reduce government's demand for capital** → send bond rates lower
- **Clinton didn't love this argument**—first reaction: denounce undue power of **"bunch of fucking bond traders"**
- But advisers pressed hard
- As **Clinton's tax hike followed by fall in market interest rates** amid bond bubble of 1993, **advisers appeared vindicated**
- **Collapse of bond market early 1994** came as **rude shock**
- Interest rates shooting up again
- **Clintonomics didn't look so brilliant**

#### Rubin's Explanation

- Clinton phoned **Robert Rubin** (ex-Goldman Sachs chief, top economic adviser in White House)
- Rubin more than anyone **persuaded Clinton to believe tax hike would be rewarded by bond market**
- President demanded to know **what was going on**
- For about half hour, **Rubin labored to explain why long-term interest rates soaring**
- Trends in growth or inflation **could not provide answer**
- **Bond market behaving in new ways**; Wall Street **changing faster than anyone noticed**
- Fed raised interest rates just twice (25 basis points each, early February then same amount in March)
- Yet **bonds falling off cliff** (steepest decline in more than decade)
- **Nobody seemed to understand exactly what was going on**: not Federal Reserve chairman, not hedge-fund gurus (Steinhardt), not even Rubin

#### Clinton's Plea for Calm

- President finished telephone conversation, walked out to **face gaggle of reporters**
- **"No one believes there's serious problem with underlying American economy. Some corrective things will happen from time to time, but there's no reason for people to overreact."**

### The New Leveraged Reality

#### Standard Response, Wrong Diagnosis

- **Seen with benefit of hindsight**: president's plea **encapsulated response to financial panics standard for generation**
- Bond market confounded Clinton's gurus, as well it might have done
- Events as disparate as **Japanese trade negotiations and Mexican assassinations** linked in terrifying ways by **tentacles of leverage**
- Best president could do: **plead for calm** (in way that *misconceived challenge* posed by hedge funds)
- **"There's no reason for people to overreact"**
- Truth: in new leveraged world, **overreaction was inevitable**
- Whole point of leverage: **investors feel ripples from economy in magnified way**
- Forced to **keep fingers on hair trigger**
- **Overreaction becomes mandatory**

#### The Bond Market Transformation

- Rubin correct: **Wall Street changed radically**
- As leverage multiplied investors' buying power, **sheer size of bond market transformed**
- **1981**: according to Securities Data Company, new public issues of bonds/notes (excluding Treasury securities) totaled **$96 billion**
- **By 1993**: offerings **multiplied thirteenfold to $1.27 trillion**
- Market growing steadily **more complex and larger**
- **Askin and exaggerated analytic powers**, but other Wall Street firms **hiring physicists, equipping with supercomputers** as they designed **ever more fanciful securities**
- **Small wonder government's power to influence and even understand markets was waning**
- Just as **deepening of currency markets destroyed central banks' ability to intervene successfully** (Britain discovered 1992), **deepening of bond markets weakened governments' ability to anticipate shifts in long-term interest rates**, let alone control them

### Two Policy Tracks: Monetary Policy and Financial Regulation

#### Track One: Monetary Policy

- Policy makers' response to new world **could have proceeded along two tracks**
- First: **monetary policy**
- Fed chairman conceded **bond market's reaction to supposedly gentle rate hike had been shock**
- Three weeks into mayhem (February 28): **Fed's interest-rate committee convened by conference call**
- Greenspan said as much
- **Alan Blinder** (Princeton professor, became Fed's deputy chairman in June): lamented **bond market's capricious behavior**, denouncing exaggerated power of **"twenty-seven-year-olds in yellow suspenders"**
- **Fed's leaders recognized up against new phenomenon**
- What conclusions should they have drawn?

#### Should Fed Target Asset Prices?

- Fed could have chosen to **redefine inflation-fighting mandate**
- Traditionally set interest rates **with view to keeping consumer prices stable**
- Question raised by **bond market collapse of 1994**: concerned **stability of asset prices**
- If bond market heads into record territory (as had in 1993), shouldn't this be taken as signal **credit too cheap**—time to **raise interest rates to deflate bubble**?
- Because Fed **targeting inflation rather than bond market**, allowed bubble to expand
- Then **Steinhardt blew up; Askin blew up**; more than **$600 billion knocked off value of U.S. securities**
- Another **$900 billion or so wealth destroyed in foreign bond markets**
- Surely **earlier hike in interest rates could have reduced carnage**?
- Over next decade, **Greenspan wrestled with this question**
- Ultimately deciding **using monetary policy to deflate bubbles = bad idea**
- **Bubbles hard to identify**; besides, even if central bank allowed bubble to expand, **better to clean up after it popped** than **prick it preemptively**

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Regulatory Response to the 1994 Bond Crisis

### Fed's Clean-Up-Afterward Philosophy

- Fed Chairman **Alan Greenspan** defended post-crisis cleanup over preemptive action: bubbles were hard to identify until after they popped, and dampening asset prices would cost more in forgone growth than cleanup would cost
- After the mid-2000s credit bubble, this approach proved disastrously costly
- The case for considering asset bubbles in monetary policy and requiring financiers to restrain leverage was belatedly vindicated

### Congressional Hearings on Hedge Funds

- March 1994 bond meltdown triggered regulatory scrutiny: central bankers met in Basel, **President's Working Group on Financial Markets** formed to study hedge fund dangers
- **Representative Henry González**, chairman of House Financial Services Committee, vowed hearings to give hedge funds "extra scrutiny"
- *Business Week* called hedge funds "rogue elephants: overleveraged, undersupervised, and disruptive to the markets"
- *Washington Post* reported hearings would "light a fire" under regulators

> "Hedge funds are rogue elephants: overleveraged, undersupervised, and disruptive to the markets." — *Business Week*

### Robert Johnson's Counterattack

- **Robert Johnson**, former Soros economist who had worked on Senate banking committee, was now González's staff director
- Johnson sensed González and lawmakers were badmouthing the industry without understanding it
- Johnson organized hearings to force lawmakers to articulate concrete proposals, betting this would cool the temperature rather than ignite regulation

### The April 13 Hearings

- Regulators had no concrete plans to stop imploding hedge funds from damaging creditors
- Resorted to "plan B": assert no action needed
- **Eugene Ludwig** (comptroller of the currency): only eight national banks lent to hedge funds, most loans secured by collateral, full-time examiners monitored the eight banks
- **Fed governor John LaWare**: banks and brokers wouldn't be foolish enough to lend excessively to hedge funds

### Soros Testifies

- **George Soros** was sole witness in second session
- Johnson's calculation proved right: House staff preparing questions realized they lacked firm grounds for treating hedge funds aggressively
- González invited **Representative Tom Lantos** to introduce "fellow Hungarian American" Soros (González joked about pronunciation: "Shurush")
- Soros lectured on reflexivity, advertised his book, explained why hedge funds weren't the right regulatory target
- Soros: leverage could destabilize markets, but restrictions should apply to all financial actors—starting with big brokerages—not just hedge funds
- Few committee members understood what hedge funds actually were

> "Nowadays, the term is applied so indiscriminately. There is as little in common between my type of hedge fund and the hedge fund that was recently liquidated, as between the hedgehog and the people who cut the hedges in the summer." — George Soros, referring to Askin's implosion

### Regulatory Response Fizzles

- Clinton administration officials (**Robert Rubin**, **Lawrence Summers**) debated options but didn't push for action
- New York Fed governor **William McDonough** manned phones to save Bankers Trust during March crisis but did nothing afterward to rein in leverage
- When **Long-Term Capital Management** failed four years later, the 1994 crisis "looked trivial"

## Michael Steinhardt's Exit

### The 1994 Losses and Retirement

- **Michael Steinhardt** flirted with retirement for years: "I don't feel what I do is profoundly virtuous"
- After bond-market humiliation, resolved to exit
- His nerve was shattered—frightened to take risks, temper went from bad to horrible
- Fired employees at lunchtime and invited them back the next day; screamed with intercom on so curses relayed throughout office
- Hung on through 1995, turning in surprisingly good 27% return and recouping $700 million of losses
- Announced long-rumored retirement

### Steinhardt's Legacy

- Watershed moment: after 27 years, one of the **Big Three** was exiting
- $1 invested with Steinhardt in 1967 would be worth $480 at closing (1996)—26x more than S&P 500 index
- The 1994 bond crash cost Steinhardt's funds $1.5 billion, but he'd earned more than twice that between 1991-1993
- Overall career returns were excellent

> "I've made my investors and myself more money than I ever conceived of as a kid." — Michael Steinhardt

- Retirement gave him time to dance with **Martha**, the elegant blue crane on his country estate

## Industry Response to 1994 Crisis

### Investor Withdrawals and Media Proclamations

- By September 1994, investors had pulled roughly $900 million from hedge funds, withdrawals continuing
- Financial magazines noted indignantly that hedge funds weren't actually hedged
- *Forbes* proclaimed: "The hedge fund party is over"

### Macro Funds Return Capital

- **Paul Tudor Jones** handed back a third of his capital to investors
- **Bruce Kovner** returned two thirds in June 1995
- Both cited difficulty maneuvering with too much capital
- Macro investing contemptuously dubbed "leveraged directional speculation"

### Industry Resilience

- Similar backlash had buried hedge funds in early 1970s
- By mid-1990s, industry was more resilient: with exception of Steinhardt, famous funds forced to shrink but carried on
- Ecosystem of smaller players evolved with rich range of investment styles
- Funds betting on company mergers, funds lending to companies in bankruptcies, funds based on computer models arbitraging gaps between similar financial instruments
- Average hedge fund decline in Q1 1994: 2.2%—less than 3.3% decline for average equity mutual fund
- Hedge funds had beaten S&P 500 over past five years and were considerably less volatile
- University endowments and sophisticated investors recognized hedge funds could diversify risks from holding stocks and bonds

### Two Verdicts on Hedge Funds

- **Regulators**: confronted worrisome questions but lacking theory of how to tame the industry, ultimately chose to look away
- **Institutional investors**: reached critical verdict that despite 1994 turmoil, hedge funds promised irresistible risk-adjusted returns
- The two verdicts were effectively one: because markets aren't perfectly efficient, hedge funds raise difficult issues—they're part of an unstable game that can wreak havoc
- But by same token, market inefficiency allowed hedge funds to do well, and investors would line up to get into them

## Chapter 9: Soros Versus Soros

### Tiger's Palladium Play

- **Noril'sk** mining city in Siberian Arctic: Stalin built it with slave labor using hundreds of engineers on fabricated charges
- Perhaps 200,000 **zeks** (political prisoners) died building the mine
- By mid-1990s, 260,000 inhabitants in bleak setting with −40°C temperatures, sulfurous smog from Dickensian smelters
- 1990: **Paul Tudor Jones** and other hedge funders vacationed at fishing camp on nearby **Ponoi River**
- Visitors resolved to buy the camp; when negotiating fishing rights, heard story at meeting in Helsinki about Noril'sk's creaking infrastructure on verge of collapse
- **Thorpe McKenzie** (former partner of **Julian Robertson** at Tiger) picked up his ears: Noril'sk's mine contained more than half the world's palladium—breakdown would have global consequences

### McKenzie's Palladium Research

- McKenzie researched palladium market: three principal uses
  - Dentistry (stable demand)
  - Catalytic converters for automobiles (growing demand due to environmental regulation)
  - Cell phones (new market with promise)
- Other major palladium suppliers in Africa faced own infrastructure challenges
- McKenzie concluded demand for palladium would outgrow uncertain sources of supply
- Bought metal for his own account, passed word to Robertson
- By 1994 Tiger had bought $40 million worth of palladium

### Dwight Anderson's Siberian Investigation

- **Dwight Anderson**, young Tiger commodities specialist, dispatched to investigate
- Turbocharged young men Robertson hired had appetite for adventure
- Flew to Moscow (emerging as go-to town for Western deal makers), then ancient Aeroflot aircraft to Siberia
- Touched down in Noril'sk in half-light of bleak November day
- Airport littered with wrecked aircraft carcasses (plundered for spare parts to keep rest of fleet going)
- Anderson surprised next day at how well mine was working

### Noril'sk's Redundant Scale

- Unlike Appalachian coal mines, open-pit western US mines, or deep southern African shafts—Siberian approach was truly Soviet in scale
- Could drive underground in vast truck and tour bewildering warren of caverns
- Excavation scale exceeded anything needed to extract ore, but this excess was a blessing
- If one tunnel or trolley system developed problem, several alternative ways to get ore out
- If mechanical drill broke, two defunct ones nearby could be plundered for spare parts (like abandoned planes at airport)
- Noril'sk's redundant scale allowed it to keep going

### Rumors of Collapse Were Exaggerated

- Anderson concluded stories of imminent collapse were deliberately exaggerated
- Local officials understood rumors of collapse were bullish for palladium prices
- Since they all had stakes in mine's sales, seized every chance to tell visiting foreigners about imminent production breakdown

### Russians Selling from Stockpiles

- Anderson confirmed Russians were selling more palladium than they mined
- Ripping metal out of disused Soviet military equipment and selling it
- Plundering would have to stop eventually—by year 2000, no more missiles to be scrapped, palladium price would skyrocket
- Tiger held on to palladium position even though logic for owning it had changed
- Position lost money for next three years, but then things got interesting

## Hedge Funds and Emerging Markets

### Opening of Closed Economies

- Early 1990s: closed parts of world economy opened to Western capital
- Before 1990, westerners barred from **Kola Peninsula** (fishing or mine inspection)
- East Asia and Eastern Europe allowed only trickle of foreign money into equity/bond markets (too small for much opportunity)
- Around turn of decade, emerging markets came into their own

### Explosive Growth

- Outstanding stock of developing-country bonds shot up from ~$40 billion to $100 billion in one year
- Blistering growth continued through rest of decade
- Traditional asset managers warmed to peripheral economies gradually, but hedge funds moved fast
- By early 1990s, filling coffers with exotic names like Peru and reaping healthy profits

### New Emerging-Market Funds

- 1992: **Soros** and **Druckenmiller** launched **Quantum Emerging Growth** to take advantage of new frontier
- 1993: **Louis Bacon's Moore Capital** followed with specialized emerging-market vehicle

### Benefits and Risks

- From developing countries' perspective, much to like: hedge funds willing to provide capital when others were not
- Once hedge funds led the way, other Western asset managers would follow
- Foreigners generally sophisticated in capital choices, presence frequently boosted quality of capital and quantity
- But global spread of hedge funds entailed risks: could provide capital and juice growth for years, then yank money out and cause growth to crater
- As Britain discovered in 1992 and **Alan Greenspan** in 1994, deep and fast-moving capital markets could force wrenching movements in currencies and interest rates
- At end of 1994, **Mexico** succumbed to full-blown currency crisis
- Mexico's troubles turned out to be dress rehearsal for far bigger drama conceived at **Soros Fund Management**

### Quantum Fund Performance Under Druckenmiller

- Years after sterling trade, **Stan Druckenmiller** led Quantum to yet more profits
- 1993 (golden period for bond market): Quantum up 63%
- 1994 (despite bond crash): still battled to 4% gain
- 1995: back in stride with 39% return
- During these years, Druckenmiller began long-running debate with Soros about proper hedge fund size

### The Size Debate

- Sterling trade showed bulk could be weapon in facing down government, but also showed Quantum was unnecessarily large
- Given fund's size, they should have sold $15 billion sterling, but only able to sell $10 billion
- If fund had been one third smaller, would have aimed to sell $10 billion and actually sold that amount, yielding percentage gain on capital that would have been third higher
- For Druckenmiller: stellar performance number was main goal—earnings tied to it, ego invested in it
- For Soros: calculation was different—ego invested as much in size of empire as scale of returns
- Owning global firm made him global player, raising profile of writings and philanthropy
- Soros known as only private citizen to have his own foreign policy
- Reveled in fact that eminent statesmen beat path to his office

> "Would you like a word with him?" Soros asked Druckenmiller when Henry Kissinger was visiting. "Does he know anything?" Druckenmiller countered dismissively. "Oh, yes," Soros answered, finding way to vaunt political connections while not seeming in awe of Kissinger's star power. "I don't like him, but he does know things."

### Compromise on Fund Size

- Soros Fund Management would continue to accumulate assets, but not all would go to Quantum
- By 1996, just over half the $10 billion at Soros Fund Management was housed in three other funds:
  - **Quantum Emerging Growth**
  - **Quasar** (invested with outside hedge-fund managers)
  - **Quota** (managed by **Nick Roditi**, secretive London-based macro trader)
- To run new start-ups, Soros recruited new talent, including Princeton-trained economist **Arminio Fraga**

### Hiring Arminio Fraga

- When two men met in early 1993, Fraga (Brazilian) had just left position as deputy governor at his country's central bank
- Within days, Soros offered him partnership
- Druckenmiller eyed Fraga skeptically: "How am I supposed to run this place when I can't choose who works for me?"
- Soros: "Fine. Let's see if he's any good."

### Fraga's Performance (1993-1996)

- For next four years at Soros, Fraga performed benign function of hedge funds: financing emerging economies shunned by traditional investors
- Bought bonds of big Latin countries like Brazil and Venezuela
- Branched into exotica like Moroccan loans
- Bought shares in Brazilian utilities (absurdly cheap by international standards)

### Stan Fischer's Question at IMF

- Late 1996: Fraga attended talk by **Stan Fischer**, number two at **International Monetary Fund**
- Mood mostly upbeat: Mexico's currency had recovered from crisis, emerging markets booming
- Somebody asked Fischer: "Who do you think is the next Mexico?"
- Fischer: "I'm not sure there's another one out there at the moment. But I do see some imbalances in Asia. That might be interesting to look at."

### The Twin Crises Paper

- That comment "put a little light in my mind"
- Weeks later, Fraga read joint IMF–Federal Reserve paper titled **"The Twin Crises"**: laid out in terrifying detail how currency collapse could interact with collapse of banking system
- Casting mind back to Fischer's remarks, Fraga approached Druckenmiller: "Do you mind if I go and take a look at what is going on in Asia?"
- "Sure. Go."

## Thailand Crisis

### Fraga's January 1997 Visit

- January 1997: **Fraga** landed in Thailand
- Making rounds of local officials, company executives, economists, quickly became clear country fitted double-crisis model from IMF-Fed paper
- Thailand's exports hammered by rise of China as low-cost rival
- Thailand's currency linked to basket of currencies dominated by strong dollar, further eroding ability to compete in world markets
- Thailand running large trade deficit but refusing to adjust
- Rather than abandon link to dollar and allow falling currency to restore competitiveness, country consuming more than it produced, paying difference with loans from foreigners

### The Unsustainable Setup

- Arrangement left Thais exposed: if foreigners tired of lending, country would have to export enough to cover import bill and repay outsiders
- To boost exports and cut imports, Thai baht would have to fall—sharply
- At time of Fraga's visit, willingness of foreigners to finance Thailand already crumbling
- 1996: major Thai bank collapsed, raising doubts about wisdom of lending
- Thailand's central bank cut interest rates to stave off further bank trouble, dampening returns for foreign creditors and giving them another reason to go elsewhere
- Fragile banks and reliance on foreign capital coming together as IMF-Fed paper described
- Clear to Fraga this interaction could turn toxic: if withdrawal of foreign money drove Thailand to devalue, banks would be tipped from fragility into outright ruin
- Much foreign lending denominated in dollars, channeled into real estate and projects generating revenue in baht
- If dollar jumped against baht, these debts would become impossible to service

### Meeting at Bank of Thailand

- Tipping point came during visit to **Bank of Thailand**
- Together with **David Kowitz** (Soros's expert on Asian equities) and **Rodney Jones** (economist who worked for Soros in Hong Kong), Fraga granted audience with high-ranking central bank official
- Invoking own experience as deputy governor of Brazil's central bank, Fraga offered thoughts on Thailand's dilemma
- On one hand, government committed to defending exchange rate (keeping interest rates high to attract capital)
- On other hand, Thailand had trade deficit and wobbly banks (made devaluation and lower interest rates attractive)
- Fraga had mild manner, Brazilian background helped—seemed more like benign emerging-market peer than menacing Wall Street predator
- Official looked at Fraga and gave answer that was honest and naive
- Until now, he said simply, Thailand had accepted whatever interest rates proved necessary to maintain exchange rate within designated band
- But now priorities might have to shift: given growing troubles at banks, getting interest rates down might matter more than defending currency level

### Thailand's Currency Peg Unsustainable

- Official conceded Thailand's currency peg was unsustainable, meaning shorting the baht was no-brainer
- Fraga and colleagues could visualize suitcase full of money: cash spilling from seams
- To reel in prize, had to pretend they hadn't noticed it
- If host realized full power of his comment, could snatch suitcase back
- Central bank could hike interest rates, raising cost of borrowing baht to sell it short
- Or resort to administrative crackdown on foreign speculators
- Ever polite and self-effacing, Fraga nodded pleasantly and allowed discussion to move on
- Kowitz gently led conversation backward: "Excuse me. I'm out of my depth here. Can you just repeat what you said a few minutes ago, just to make sure I got it right?"
- Official repeated statement, Soros team got confirmation they were looking for
- Host had told them he knew the game was up—confessed and reconfessed his nakedness
- Whatever official pronouncements on Thailand's commitment to exchange-rate peg, only matter of time before baht was devalued

### Druckenmiller Approves the Trade

- After stop in South Korea, Fraga returned to New York and reported back to Druckenmiller
- Big man listened to Fraga's story and quickly approved trade
- Over space of days in late January, Soros team sold short about $2 billion worth of Thai currency
- Selling was both prediction of crisis and trigger that could bring it on
- To defend baht against pressure from Druckenmiller and Fraga, government sold chunk of dwindling foreign-currency reserves and raised interest rates by 3 percentage points—punishing hike given Thai banks were tottering
- But rate hike came too late to scare predators away
- Soros team had taken out baht loans of six months' duration and locked in low interest rates before government hiked them
- Secure in positions, Druckenmiller and Fraga could afford to wait until end of July for inevitable to happen

### Why Didn't Druckenmiller Go Bigger?

- Spirited argument would break out whether hedge funds precipitated Asia's financial crisis
- But for now, opposite question stands out: Why didn't Druckenmiller and Fraga do *more* to force Thai devaluation?
- Back in 1992, Soros team had sold $10 billion worth of sterling (around 2.5 times firm's capital)
- $2 billion Thai trade represented just a fifth of capital—fraction of selling Druckenmiller was capable of
- By repeating leverage of earlier exploit, could have sold additional $23 billion or so of baht, multiplying Soros funds' returns and wiping out most foreign-currency reserves at Bank of Thailand
- Reserves thus depleted, Thailand would probably have capitulated within days, so quick and magnificent profit apparently lay within Druckenmiller's grasp
- Why didn't he seize it?

### Soros's Reluctance for Aggressive Speculation

- In popular imagination, Soros team's ruthlessness is unbounded
- Truth: had only limited appetite for speculating aggressively in emerging markets
- Soros himself was of two minds about speculation—liked to say markets, instead of swinging like pendulum, could swing like wrecking ball, laying waste to economies
- Druckenmiller was clearer in purpose, but not focused on Thailand: taking advice from Fraga and team, so lacked intense conviction he felt when trade was his entirely
- Further down hierarchy at Soros funds, complex emotions
- **Rodney Jones** (Hong Kong–based economist) had challenged Fraga and Kowitz about morality of speculation in developing countries: if currencies crashed, millions of innocents would be forced into desperate poverty
- Back in 1992, Soros had famously urged Druckenmiller to "go for the jugular"
- But when it came to Thailand in 1997, some members of Soros team felt squeamish

### Jones and Soros Defend Speculation

- In aftermath of discussions in Thailand, Jones settled on his own way of living with what he was doing
- In book published after Thai crash, Soros offered identical defense of his funds' actions
- Defense boiled down to simple idea: speculation could benefit poor societies if it served as signal, not sledgehammer
- Function of virtuous speculator: alert governments to need for change
- In Thailand's case, that baht had to devalue
- Signaling could avoid hardship for ordinary people: the more government procrastinated about devaluation, the more brutal eventual currency collapse would be
- Reserves would dwindle to zero, so when crisis came there would be nothing left to cushion shock as capital flooded out of country
- Case for speculation potentially correct, but could only justify speculation of mild sort
- All-out attack on Thai baht would have precipitated crisis rather than prodded government to avoid one

### Thailand's Disastrous Response

- In weeks following Druckenmiller's first baht sale, Thailand's behavior revealed flaw in Jones-Soros rationalization
- Speculative signals only helpful if governments wise enough to respond to them
- Rather than prompting Thais to devalue sensibly and early, Druckenmiller's short position provoked disastrous defiance
- Government threw away foreign-currency reserves, buying baht from Druckenmiller at rate sure to leave it with loss once devaluation happened
- Meanwhile, Thai economy continued to weaken
- When **Rodney Jones** visited in last days of April, country visibly grinding to halt
- Counted hundred cranes on Bangkok skyline, but almost none were working
- Overextended real-estate companies stopped servicing loans
- 87 out of 90 finance companies in Thailand said to be insolvent
- Thailand had experienced financial crisis at end of 1970s, but Jones could see this one would be worse
- Back then, total stock of loans worth 40% of GDP
- Now, thanks to globalization of capital flows, ratio was 140%, rendering consequences of banking bust more serious for real economy
- Only silver lining: authorities still had little time to come to senses and devalue before panic forced them into it

### Crisis Precipitated

- As it turned out, Jones's visit to Thailand helped precipitate crisis he dreaded
- Thai press got wind of his visit, news that foreign hedge fund circling spooked jittery local investors
- Thai financiers and companies began to dump baht and buy dollars, forcing another round of central-bank intervention to defend currency's level
- Evening of Sunday, May 11: Prime Minister **Chavalit Yongchaiyudh** appeared on television vowing to support baht, then adding deflating message that he could not promise to succeed in doing so
- Just as in British case (continued to defend sterling even as it knew game was up), Thai leadership lacked courage to accept logic of untenable position
- Reaction from Soros team was predictable

### Druckenmiller Increases Position

- Three days after Chavalit's televised statement, Druckenmiller increased bet against baht from $2 billion to $3.5 billion
- New position still represented only third of Soros funds' capital—fraction of what Druckenmiller could have sold if leveraged up aggressively
- But now Druckenmiller no longer only player: Thai investors leading charge out of baht, other hedge funds following
- **Paul Tudor Jones** spoke with Druckenmiller several times each day, quick to put on trade
- Several other macro funds from tight-knit group around him
- Biggest player after Druckenmiller probably **Julian Robertson's Tiger**, which built short position in baht that eventually came to $2 billion

### Thailand's Reserves Depleted

- Day Druckenmiller increased position, Bank of Thailand forced to use at least $6 billion of reserves to maintain baht's level
- Over next week, onslaught continued
- But Thailand's government still refused to embrace devaluation
- Visit from IMF's **Stan Fischer** (man who had set Fraga on his path) failed to persuade it to accept inevitable
- Rather than bow to markets, Thai government counterattacked

### Political Risks and Capital Controls

- Second reason why Druckenmiller had not gone for jugular: financial traders must contend with market risks but also face political ones
- May 15 (day after Druckenmiller upped ante): Thai authorities forbade all banks from lending baht to anyone outside country
- Put short sellers in bind: could no longer borrow baht to sell them unless secured loans offshore at punitive interest rates
- Tiger financed some positions by borrowing baht on short-term basis, figuring it could roll over loans as they came due
- Now forced to renew them at vastly higher interest rates
- At one point in early June, cost of holding Tiger's position hit $10 million *per day*

### The Clampdown on Short Sellers

- Clampdown on lending to foreigners, combined with central bank's aggressive intervention, succeeded in reversing baht's fall
- In three weeks after Druckenmiller's second strike, Thai currency gained 10% against dollar and hedge funds booked perhaps $500 million in losses
- Region's English-language newspapers reporting gleefully that hedge funds losing "battle of the baht"
- Prime minister called central bank to promise staff a victory party
- Bank of Thailand said to be gunning personally for Soros
- According to one newspaper account, bent on inflicting losses on his funds of as much as $4 billion

### Druckenmiller Cuts Position

- Faced with onslaught, Druckenmiller cut short position from $3.5 billion to $3 billion
- Had he leveraged up and sold baht to max, might have precipitated devaluation
- But that was more than political system seemed likely to tolerate
- Yet although Druckenmiller not going to stick neck out, he wasn't going to walk away
- Knew Thais were closer to collapse than they admitted publicly
- Central bank's position ostensibly robust: even in late June, reported reserves of more than $30 billion
- But had effectively sold vast quantity of reserves by taking positions in forward markets, which did not show up on balance sheet
- Maneuver fooled almost all outsiders, including inspectors from IMF and members of Thai government itself
- By doggedly calling banks that executed government's sell orders in forward markets, **Jones** pieced together alarming rate at which real reserves were dwindling
- By his reckoning, Bank of Thailand used up $21 billion worth of reserves in May alone (stunning two thirds of war chest)

### Jones's Moral Justification Shattered

- Jones took little pleasure in this finding
- Moral justification for speculation had been battered
- Far from reacting to speculators by adjusting policies quickly, Thailand's leaders were digging in heels and condemning people to calamity
- Combination of high interest rates and uncertainty about Thai currency pushed financial system to breaking point
- Banks charging exorbitant rates to lend to other banks, not knowing which would survive, and money ceasing to flow through economy
- June 25: Jones worked out anguish in memo entitled **"The Economics of Deflation: What Keynes Would Say to Thailand"**

> "For a country to choose sky-high interest rates in preference to devaluation was 'sheer lunacy.'" — Rodney Jones

- Invoked Keynes's reflections on folly going back to Roman times
- A.D. 274: Emperor Aurelian's zeal to protect integrity of coinage caused deflationary misery and provoked rebellion
- Fighting ensued resulted in deaths of 7,000 soldiers and doubtless many more civilians

### Capital Flight Accelerates

- Jones's anguish could not save Thai people
- Clamping down on baht loans to foreigners turned out to be about as effective as blocking up one hole in showerhead: only accelerated pace at which capital whooshed out through other openings
- Harassing short sellers encouraged foreigners who had lent dollars to Thai businesses to demand repayment
- Businesses dumped baht as they scrambled to meet obligations
- Besides, attack on short sellers made it expensive to borrow baht but by no means impossible
- If convinced currency about to collapse, paid to borrow it at sky-high interest rates in offshore market just for short period
- As more capital fled Thailand, odds of collapse increased

### Tiger's Final Strike

- Tuesday, July 1: according to at least one account, **Julian Robertson's Tiger** unleashed barrage of baht selling, adding $1 billion to short position until Bank of Thailand finally ran out of reserves and became impossible to find buyers for currency
- Thailand finally pushed over edge
- Robertson played role analogous to Druckenmiller's in sterling crisis

### Thailand Capitulates

- Around 4:30 A.M. Bangkok time, Bank of Thailand officials conceded they had no more ammunition to defend currency
- After months of resistance, baht peg snapped
- Over next three months, it fell 32% against dollar
- Soros funds gained about $750 million from devaluation
- Julian Robertson gained perhaps $300 million
- Meanwhile, Thailand's output collapsed by 17% from peak, destroying businesses and jobs and plunging millions into poverty
- By uncanny coincidence, July 1, 1997, was day when Britain ceded control over Hong Kong
- Also day when new kind of imperialism put stamp on Southeast Asia

## Aftermath and Controversy

### Hedge Funds Vilified

- In wake of devaluation, hedge funds inevitably vilified
- Some fairness to complaints: Soros team had led selling in January, forcing government to raise interest rates and throttle weak economy
- Additional element of fairness given Tiger's role on last day (though at time almost nobody knew about this)
- But in larger sense, complaints missed point
- Roots of crisis stretched back to 1995 and 1996, when Thais refused to devalue exchange rate gradually in face of China's rise
- Speculators merely forced adjustment that was ultimately inevitable
- Besides, although Soros and Tiger were part of trigger for crisis, they were not quite villains critics imagined
- In particular, Druckenmiller refused to leverage to max, rightly fearing political backlash
- As endgame played out in June, he actually *reduced* his position

### Druckenmiller's Caution Proved Prophetic

- As Thailand's crisis spread across East Asia and beyond, image of hedge fund as superpredator proved less and less accurate

## Soros in Hong Kong (September 1997)

### Dual Persona

- Late September 1997: **George Soros** flew to Hong Kong for annual World Bank and IMF meetings
- Reception mirrored his dual persona
- Soros the speculator predictably reviled: earlier called "criminal" and "moron"
- Prime Minister **Mahathir Mohamad** of Malaysia called for ban on "unnecessary, unproductive and immoral" currency trading
- But Soros the statesman-philanthropist was toast of meetings
- Addressed packed auditorium on stabilizing world economy, lionized by press

> "The main enemy of the open society, I believe, is no longer the communist but the capitalist threat. The laissez-faire idea that markets should be left to their own devices remains very influential. I consider it a dangerous idea." — George Soros

### Soros's Preference for Statesman Role

- By late 1990s, Soros had no doubt which side of persona should dominate
- Wanted to be thinker, statesman, great public figure
- Did not want to be neoimperialist and smasher of small currencies
- Inevitably, risk this preference might color his investment views
- In discussion with **David Kowitz** and **Rodney Jones** during Hong Kong meetings, Soros declared confidently that time for shorting Asian currencies had passed
- Even though **Mahathir's** outburst against markets had triggered new sell-off in region
- Lieutenants had doubts about boss's rosy prognosis, but Soros not in mood to listen
- Although he would not micromanage funds' decisions (leave these to Druckenmiller and team), his optimistic bias was evident

## Indonesia Crisis

### Initial Position

- Bias played out first in Indonesia
- In run-up to Hong Kong meetings, Soros team bought about $300 million worth of Indonesian rupiah, believing turmoil in Thailand had spilled over to neighbors without justification
- Rather than repeat Thai error of defending unsustainable exchange-rate peg, Indonesians had let currency fall 11% in August—now rebound might be in offing
- Following visit to Indonesia by **Arminio Fraga** and **Rodney Jones** in October, Soros funds increased rupiah bet to about $1 billion

### Indonesia Differs from Thailand

- Not all hedge funds thought this sensible
- **Julian Robertson's Tiger** had bet on rupiah too, dumped holdings at end of October
- But Soros team followed technocratic consensus: IMF seemed confident Indonesia would pull through
- November 2: announced $33 billion credit line for country, designed to give central bank foreign reserves needed to bolster confidence in money
- Next day rupiah rallied healthily, Soros's position showing small profit

### Optimism Proves Misplaced

- Up until this point, Soros's optimism at Hong Kong meetings had achieved shaky vindication
- Yet by mid-November, Soros team and IMF allies losing moorings
- IMF's $33 billion credit line extended in exchange for two key commitments:
  - Indonesia would close down sixteen corrupt banks
  - It would run responsible monetary policy
- But cronies around ailing **President Suharto** determined to frustrate this plan
- Corrupt banks belonged to cronies so were impossible to close down
- Cronies also hammering central bank for loans, inflating money supply and destroying confidence in rupiah
- By late November, currency in free fall
- Early December: things got worse
- Suharto rumored to be seriously ill, prospect of power vacuum panicked country
- December 15: rupiah down 44% from high in early November, trade had cost Soros $400 million

### Soros Team Paralyzed

- Strange thing was Soros team continued to stick with currency
- In aftermath of Wall Street crash ten years earlier, Soros dumped positions as soon as they went wrong, capping losses
- But this time Soros team seemed paralyzed, despite clear signs Indonesia turned into disaster
- December 10: **Rodney Jones** got hands on data from Bank of Indonesia confirming central bank been printing money that found way to lenders run by Suharto's cronies
- Jones fired off note to Soros headquarters in New York, laying out details of monetary binge
- But funds still stuck with rupiah position

### Meeting with Finance Minister Muhammad

- Around same time Indonesian finance minister **Mar'ie Muhammad** dispatched by government to reassure foreign investors
- Muhammad spent years building reputation as respected technocrat; now task was to defend recovery program in which money was being printed to pay off undeserving friends of Suharto family
- On stop in New York, Muhammad met Soros and lieutenants at Plaza Hotel
- Though going through motions of talking up Indonesia's prospects, his heart not in it
- Soros, Fraga, and Druckenmiller posed question after question, but placed in impossible position, Muhammad refused to meet their gaze, mumbling way through series of evasive answers

> "Oh my God," Druckenmiller said as he strode back to the office. "I can't believe that we are long. I don't believe anything that guy said. I don't even believe he's from Indonesia."

### Trapped in Bad Trade

- Group made way across midtown Manhattan, back to Soros offices by Columbus Circle
- Knew they were trapped in appalling trade, but so few willing buyers for rupiah it was not obvious how to get out of it
- Casting around for some kind of exit, **David Kowitz** suggested using rupiah to buy physical commodity such as iron, which could eventually be bartered
- "That's an interesting idea," Soros said gravely, in thick central European voice
- But nobody followed up on Kowitz's proposal—not even when Indonesia's government, unable to print money fast enough, released plastic souvenir banknotes as legal currency
- Soros team followed
<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 9 (continued): Soros's Dual Persona — Indonesia and South Korea

### Indonesia: The Missed Opportunity

- **Rodney Jones** discovered South Korea's hidden crisis in mid-November 1997
- Korean banks had financed over 50 Thai companies now going bust post-Thailand collapse
- Thailand's crisis had clobbered South Korean financial firms, leaving them short dollars they'd never recover
- Central bank scrambling to cover mess by depositing dollars in Korean banks using foreign currency reserves
- **Bombshell discovery**: South Korea's central bank misleading markets just like Thailand five months earlier
- Official reserves: $57 billion. Real number (after subtracting forward commitments and bank obligations): closer to $20 billion
- Jones memo to Soros HQ dated November 17 warned Korea was "in the late stage of the crisis"
- Dollar debts of South Korean companies understated real liabilities by **$60 billion**, much maturing within weeks

### Jones's Prescient Call Goes Unheeded

- Nine days after Jones memo landed, IMF's top Asia hand flew to Seoul on emergency mission
- Central bank reserves falling at $1 billion per day, now down to $9 billion
- December 3: IMF announced record $55 billion bailout package for South Korea
- Package inadequate — private sector dollar obligations more than twice that size
- By end of December, won had fallen 60% from its level at time of Jones's November 17 memo
- **Despite strong language in memo and follow-up message, Soros team took no action**
- No won short, no repeat of Thailand gains
- IMF officials believed South Korea would escape trouble — may have persuaded Soros team to focus elsewhere
- **Soros's dual persona**: boss wanted to be statesman, not wrecker of nations
- If getting involved in South Korea, it would be as savior, not scourge

### Soros's South Korea Trip: Savior, Not Speculator

- First days of January 1998: Soros traveled to Korea as guest of **Kim Dae-jung**, president-elect
- Camera crews waiting at airport, dined with Kim at his home, affectionately called him "DJ"
- Visited top industrialists, breakfasted with **Michael Jackson** (plotting to take over theme park from bust Korean underwear maker)
- Soros criticized IMF prescriptions — which involved saddling Korea with more debt
- Called for "radical restructuring of industry and financial sector" — cleanup of accounting practices, flexibility for managers in firing workers
- Promised his **Quantum Fund** would invest substantial sums if Korea did these things
- Western investors responded by rushing into South Korean stocks
- Seoul's **KOSPI index** jumped 25% in ten days following Soros's visit

### The Image Contrast

- Press coverage emphasized comparison with Hong Kong atmosphere
- September: one Asian leader (Mahathir) vilified Soros as criminal and moron
- January: another Asian leader giving him red-carpet treatment
- Asked about contrast between Mahathir and Kim, Soros smiled: **"One of them must be wrong"**

## Chapter 9 (continued): Russia — The Messiah Complex

### Soros's Russia Philanthropy and the Principle Crack

- As far back as 1987, before Soviet Union crumbled, Soros set up branch of **Open Society Institute** in Moscow
- 1990s: institute supported educational reform, printing textbooks free of Marxist ideology, millions in grants to scientists
- **István Rév** (Hungarian historian on Soros's philanthropic boards): Soros drawn to Russia by same forces that fascinated Napoleon — "Its vastness, its historical challenge, its backwardness, its perpetually unfulfilled promise"
- Soros made it a principle **not to get involved in Russian investments** — didn't want philanthropy seen as Trojan horse for financial interests
- Allowed **Druckenmiller** and team to take positions, but kept personal distance
- **Spring 1997: he cracked**. Took astonishing financial gamble in Russia, mirroring his errors in Indonesia and South Korea

### Russia's Foreign Capital Rush and Reform Hope

- End of 1996: President **Boris Yeltsin** reenergized economic reform program
- Hedge-fund managers jetting to Moscow, going to Bolshoi Opera, walking through famous **Novodevichy Convent** gardens
- Flood of foreign capital poured in
- Portfolio investment increased from $8.9 billion (1996) to $45.6 billion (1997) — equivalent to 10% of Russia's GDP
- Russian equity index almost tripled in first nine months of year — hottest among emerging markets
- Risks obvious: property rights and rule of law vague concepts in Russia
- From portfolio investors' viewpoint: good bet as long as reformers had upper hand in Yeltsin's government
- If reformers lost out, foreigners could dump shares/bonds and head for exit

### Soros's Svyazinvest Gamble

- Soros staked **$980 million** on venture that was almost totally illiquid
- Going over heads of Druckenmiller and colleagues, joined consortium bidding for 25% of **Svyazinvest** (Russia's sprawling state-owned telephone utility)
- Investment might pay off over long term: Russia had 19 phone lines per 100 people vs. 58 per 100 in U.S. — undeniable telecoms potential
- But **$1 billion–odd stake in state company** not something you could dump easily if Russian politics turned bad
- Entailed type of risk that seemed crazy to most foreigners
- Even amid torrent of portfolio investment into Russia, foreign direct investment never amounted to more than a trickle

### The Secret Loan and Messianic Delusion

- **June 1997** (shortly before Svyazinvest auction due to close): Soros received secret request from Russian government for emergency financing
- President Yeltsin sworn to start making good on backlog of unpaid state wages and pensions by July 1 — needed temporary loan to meet deadline
- Unbeknownst to markets or IMF (monitoring parlous state of Russia's debt), **Soros lent government several hundred million dollars**
- Had he not done so, Yeltsin's brittle legitimacy might have cracked, unpaid workers might have rioted

> "I deliberately chose to expose myself. To be a selfless benefactor was just a little too good to be true. It fed my self-image as a godlike creature, above the fray, doing good and fighting evil. I have talked about my messianic fantasies; I am not ashamed of them…. I could see, particularly in Russia, that people simply could not understand what I was all about…. It seemed to me that to appear as a robber capitalist who is concerned with cultural and political values was more credible than a disembodied intellect arguing for the merits of an open society. I could serve as a role model for the budding robber capitalists of Russia. And by entering the fray as an investor, I descended from Mount Olympus and became a flesh and blood human being." — **George Soros**

### Svyazinvest Victory Turns Pyrrhic

- Soros hoped Svyazinvest privatization would mark turning point for Russia
- Until 1997, Russia's state assets transferred at knocked-down prices to oligarchs, foreign investors excluded
- This time foreigners allowed in, auction won by highest bidder
- When bids opened July 1997, consortium to which Soros contributed did win by offering most money
- **But victory was Pyrrhic**
- Oligarchs who lost auction owned newspapers and TV stations — soon released string of smear stories about winning faction
- Mudslinging dragged on for weeks, forcing three government officials to resign, distracting Yeltsin administration from reform agenda
- Far from helping Russia turn corner to cleaner capitalism, Svyazinvest episode plunged government into chaos

### Asia Crisis Contagion Hits Russia

- Meanwhile, shock waves from Asia arriving
- Banks that lent to Thailand, Indonesia, South Korea began registering losses, forced to pull loans from Russia
- Russian financiers saw war over Svyazinvest meant end of economic reform — joined scramble to get money out
- Asia's economic collapse drove down oil price (Russia's primary export)
- Caught between collapsing export income and capital flight, Russia faced excruciating crunch
- To attract investors, government forced to offer ever higher interest rates on bonds
- **April 1998**: annualized interest rate on short-term ruble bonds hit 30% (even though short maturity reduced risks)
- **May**: yield on **GKOs** (short-term bonds) reached astonishing 70%

### The Hedge Fund Russian Bond Feeding Frenzy

- Chaos following Svyazinvest made Soros's illiquid $1 billion bet look crazy
- But prospect of earning 70% from short-term government bonds seemed different matter entirely
- Soon half the hedge funds in New York salivating
- Three-month bonds with double-digit yields surely bargain of decade
- Russia's finances had risks, but seemed acceptable on short horizon
- West not going to let nuclear power like Russia default and descend into chaos (the argument went)
- If worse came to worst, U.S. would force IMF to increase support
- **June**: **Goldman Sachs** underwrote $1.25 billion issue of Russian bonds — sold out within an hour
- Every macro investor in Manhattan, from Soros to Tiger and down, hungry for Russian investments

### Dwight Anderson's Palladium Play

- Most exotic Russia play of moment had nothing to do with GKOs — was about **palladium**
- Since first trip to Siberia in 1994, **Dwight Anderson** continued building Tiger's palladium position
- Learned to navigate Russia's palladium bazaar: parliament and government export company haggled over how much metal should be sold, then central bank/finance ministry/officials in Noril'sk argued over who could sell how much of allotment
- Anderson nurtured relationship with key selling officials over long meals and whiskeys, buying metal whenever he got chance
- Summer 1998: saw opportunity to break out of this pattern — financial desperation of Russian state could change game for palladium

### Anderson's Audacious Metal Stockpile Proposal

- Anderson approached Russian friends with modest proposal: offered to buy **entire stock of nongold precious metals** held by central bank and finance ministry
- Would take palladium, rhodium, and silver — all of it
- Plan involved delicate logistics: some metal brought to Moscow from Siberia by armored train, entire consignment flown to Switzerland, placed in bank vault with Tiger's name on it
- Tiger would pay **$4 billion** once metal in its hands — amount that would relieve immediate pressure on Russian budget
- Would then sell stockpile gradually into market, sharing profits with Russian government
- Eventual proceeds to Moscow would come in around **$8 billion** (Anderson's estimate)

### The Deal That Almost Was

- Anderson flew to Moscow in July to meet senior official at central bank
- Climate seemed propitious: GKO yields jumped from 70% in May to more than 100%
- Anderson and counterpart got along well; President Yeltsin apparently knew about deal and approved it
- Returning to Tiger offices on Park Avenue after few days, Anderson felt deal of lifetime almost in bag
- Soros and Napoleon could salivate over Russia's limitless romance, but Anderson about to show single hedge fund in New York could buy treasure of country
- Then message reached Manhattan from Moscow: **There would have to be a commission**

### The Commission Impasse

- Anderson looked at request, responded carefully: Tiger had no problem paying commissions on trades (paid them to stockbrokers all the time)
- But Tiger couldn't agree to details of Russian proposal
- Russians wanted **two contracts** for metal sale: official one making no mention of commission, private one laying down how it should be paid into bank in Cyprus
- Russia's parliament and people would only see official version — no questions asked about who kept commission
- Anderson said he had problem with that: **"It's got to be one contract"**
- Didn't matter if payment to Cyprus, Gibraltar, or other haven — but had to be disclosed
- There had to be one contract; Tiger's lawyers and Russia's lawyers looking at same piece of paper, standing up to public scrutiny in West and Russia

### Deal Collapse

- For a while silence from Moscow, then response: Okay, understood — what about paying commission into bank in **Gibraltar**?
- Anderson had to explain himself again: didn't matter if Cyprus, Gibraltar, or other haven — had to be disclosed, had to be one contract
- Tiger's lawyers and Russia's lawyers had to look at same piece of paper, would have to stand up to public scrutiny both in West and Russia
- Messages bounced back and forth between New York and Moscow until eventually clear agreement was impossible
- For Russians: no earthly reason to sell without private commission
- For Anderson: no way to salvage deal of the decade

## Chapter 10: The Enemy Is Us — Long-Term Capital Management

### LTCM's September 1997 Party

- Bank of China building in Hong Kong: heavy and squat (old-fashioned finance), then face-lift from Chinese-American wizard **I. M. Pei** (1990)
- Emerged as soaring, daring, giddy thing: slim stiletto-heeled goddess on catwalk of Hong Kong's financial district
- Architect explained triangular towers evoked bamboo, sectioned shafts of aluminum and glass tapering as they rose into sunlight
- Through miracles of modern leverage, financial institutions growing as quickly as bamboo, sucking money out of world's bond markets and pumping it back in
- Thanks to same leverage, new financial palaces thin sided and hollow — unexpected sideways blow could topple them
- September 1997: confident young hedge fund called **Long-Term Capital Management** (LTCM) — epitome of new financial engineering Pei's structure evoked — picked art gallery at squat old Bank of China premises to throw party
- Indonesia and Thailand struggling with currency crises ensconced in hotel suite not far away
- Malaysia's prime minister waging campaign against speculators
- LTCM seemed to float above region's storm
- Small team of economists earned stunning **$2.1 billion in profits** previous year
- Magic formula appeared to work irrespective of turmoil roiling Asia
- Fund's prestige and prominence reflected in party's guest list: A-team of private-sector bosses and financial officials in town for IMF/World Bank annual meetings

### LTCM's Announcement and Leverage Strategy

- After champagne stopped flowing, economists returned to hotel to find fax of front page of that morning's *Wall Street Journal*
- *Journal* reported decision to return two-fifths of fund's capital (**$2.7 billion**) to outside investors
- In new world of soaring leverage, LTCM had no need for so much client cash
- By boosting borrowing, could maintain towering portfolio on thinner foundation
- Could be ambitious and slender, like I. M. Pei creation

### John Meriwether's Vision and Team

- Founder **John Meriwether** one of first Wall Street executives to see potential in financial engineering
- Rising star at Salomon Brothers (mid-1980s), set out to transform small trading group he managed into "quasi-university environment"
- Plan: hire young stars from PhD programs, encourage them to stay in touch with cutting-edge research, visit finance faculties, go out on academic conference circuit
- Recruited **Eric Rosenfeld** (Harvard Business School professor), then **Larry Hilibrand** (two degrees from MIT)
- By 1990 team included **Robert Merton** and **Myron Scholes** (later won Nobel Prize for pioneering work on options pricing)

### The Salomon Brothers Quant Revolution

- Mid-1980s: most Salomon partners had not gone to college, much less PhD program
- Firm's trading culture personified by **Craig Coats Jr.** — tall, handsome, charismatic stud believed by many to be model for hero in Tom Wolfe's *The Bonfire of the Vanities*
- Coats ran Salomon's government-bond trading old-fashioned way: firm belief in own instincts vs. Meriwether's professors debating whether relationship between two bonds out of normal range or bond price volatility likely to decelerate
- But remarkably quickly, superiority of Meriwether's professors became obvious
- End of 1980s: small quasi faculty accounted for 90% of profits at Salomon
- Coats left Salomon after big trading loss
- Meriwether elevated to vice chairman
- **Quantitative precision had triumphed. End of anti-intellectualism on Wall Street**

### The Salomon Problem and LTCM Launch

- Problem with victory: if Meriwether's hundred-strong department could generate tens of millions of dollars, what was purpose of Salomon's 6,000 other employees?
- Lieutenants complained fruits of brilliance being spread to undeserving corners of firm
- **Larry Hilibrand** (double-MIT lieutenant) campaigned to shutter fancy internal catering service Salomon maintained for benefit of investment bankers, even suggesting investment banking division should be closed entirely
- Push bore fruit in secret deal: to keep rocket scientists happy, Salomon's overlords granted them **fixed 15% of their group's profits**
- By securing guaranteed performance fee, Meriwether created hedge fund within bank
- Creating hedge fund instead of bank merely step away for him
- 1991: Treasury bond scandal embarrassed **Michael Steinhardt** and **Bruce Kovner**, triggered full-blown crisis for Salomon
- Firm's government-bond trader **Paul Mozer** cheated repeatedly in auctions
- Meriwether (responsible for overseeing Mozer) resigned, paid $50,000 SEC fine
- After scouting for opportunities, resolved to set up on his own
- Would reassemble team of rocket scientists, do it without unnecessary trappings of big bank
- Functions like marketing, clearing, settling, operations outsourced — no need to spread professors' trading profits through undeserving back-office departments
- Meriwether saw himself inventing new kind of financial institution for new age
- World in which small brotherhood of academics could earn more than large bank required fresh kind of setup
- Required **"Salomon without the bullshit"**

### LTCM's Launch and Connecticut Base

- February 1994: Meriwether launched Long-Term Capital Management
- Brought along **Eric Rosenfeld**, **Larry Hilibrand**, **Robert Merton**, **Myron Scholes** — in all, eight members of Salomon brain trust joined
- Professors leased space at 600 Steamboat Road in Greenwich, Connecticut
- Same four-story building overlooking Long Island Sound to which **Paul Tudor Jones** had moved recently
- Instead of New York suits and ties, showed up for work in golf shirts and chinos
- Sometimes in lunch hour, bluefish spotted jumping out of sound — team of eager quants would arm themselves with fishing rods and race out in hot pursuit

### LTCM's Arbitrage Approach
<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

### LTCM's Nobel Prize and Expansion into Equities

- October 1997: **Merton and Scholes** won **Nobel Prize for economics** for option-pricing model
- Award seen as vindication of new finance—formula to price risk allowed slicing/bundling of risk
- LTCM celebrated as fulfillment of professors' vision: calculating risk of losses, holding minimal capital, turning price anomalies into profits
- By late 1990s, Meriwether/professors were upstarts; now nearly all investment banks had **fixed-income arbitrage desks** competing with them
- First half 1997: LTCM profits slowed, partners debated shrinking fund vs. venturing into equities

### Royal Dutch/Shell Arbitrage

- LTCM expanded into equity arbitrage—not stock-picking like Julian Robertson's Tigers
- Sought trades with mathematical clarity: two identical securities valued differently, or broken price relationships
- Favorite trade: **Royal Dutch/Shell**—Dutch shares and British shares represented claims on same profits, but British traded at discount to Dutch
- LTCM bought cheap British shares, shorted expensive Dutch ones
- Collected more dividends than paid out; hedged so indifferent to share price movement
- Seized opportunity in vast size—many on Wall Street thought professors overreaching

### Betting on Market Steadiness (Volatility Trade)

- Biggest equity venture: bet on **markets' steadiness**—Morgan Stanley dubbed LTCM "the central bank of volatility"
- Strategy: bet on *how far* market would move, not direction
- Fall 1997: jittery investors paying fat premium for insurance against sharp moves
- Five-year S&P 500 options selling at price implying 19% annual fluctuation vs. typical 10-13%
- LTCM sold call and put options, collecting premiums, believing they wouldn't have to pay out
- As long as volatility remained within usual range, bet couldn't go against them

### Value-at-Risk Calculations and Perceived Safety

- Partners relied on **value-at-risk calculations**
- Maximum likely loss on 99 out of 100 trading days: **$116 million**
- Maximum loss over 21 trading days: **$532 million**
- Would take **ten-sigma event** (one in 10^24) to put them out of business
- Twice-weekly risk meetings gamed out Wall Street crash or Japanese earthquake scenarios

> "We thought we were being conservative." —Eric Rosenfeld

### May-June 1998: First Warning Signs

- May 1998: IMF bailout of Indonesia faltered, Suharto regime collapsed
- East Asia troubles spilled into Japan (first recession since 1974)
- Russia tripled interest rates to halt capital exodus
- Equity volatility indices shot upward worldwide
- Investors fled to safest investment: U.S. government bonds (30-year Treasury yields hit lowest since 1977)

### LTCM's Losses Accumulate

- LTCM's trades premised on irrational panic being corrected by rational arbitrage
- Before May-June: LTCM short Treasuries, long swap rate (betting on convergence)
- World's intensifying crisis created extreme risk aversion, widening spreads
- LTCM betting against equity volatility: single percentage-point rise cost $40 million
- S&P 500 expected volatility jumped from 19% (May 1) to 26% (mid-June)
- Fund lost **6% in May**, **10% in June**—way more than value-at-risk calculations anticipated
- Partners canceled vacations, debated if something fundamental had gone wrong
- July: fund recovered, partners trimmed positions and relaxed, dismissed spring shock as freak misfortune

### August 17, 1998: Russia Defaults

- Monday, August 17: **Russia defaulted** on debt payments to foreigners
- LTCM had little direct Russia exposure, but indirect effects devastating
- Russia's default led to bankruptcy of **High-Risk Opportunities** hedge fund
- Friday, August 21: rumors Lehman Brothers might fail
- Flight to quality intensified beyond May/June—safe government securities rose, risky assets fell
- LTCM bets on convergence of Treasury rates and swap rates: gap widened by stunning **eight basis points** (typically moved less than one basis point daily)
- Similar British government bond spread widened sharply
- Emerging market bets also went wrong
- By end of Friday: LTCM lost **$550 million total**, **15% of capital**

### Partners' Vacation Interrupted

- Mid-August: most senior partners on deferred vacation
- **John Meriwether** in China, **Eric Rosenfeld** in Idaho, **Jim Rickards** (counsel) in North Carolina
- Skeleton crew in Greenwich watched screens in wonder
- LTCM's confident assumptions burning: safe because credit relationships generally stable (now stormy), safe because correlation between strategies was low (now in lockstep), safe because value-at-risk said max loss $116 million/day (now off by $400 million)
- Most fundamentally: believed in **corrective power of arbitrage**—irrational panic would be corrected by profit-seeking traders
- Portfolio burning, traders waited in vain for market to spring back—**Slinky effect suspended**

### Meriwether's Rescue Attempts

- Rosenfeld called from Idaho golf course, knew vacation over
- Meriwether called **Jon Corzine** (Goldman Sachs boss) before boarding flight from China, promised no cause to worry
- Sunday evening: partners discussed stemming losses—liquidating positions difficult in panic
- Rosenfeld phoned **Warren Buffett** to buy LTCM's $5 billion merger arbitrage portfolio—Buffett refused
- Meriwether breakfasted with **Soros and Druckenmiller**: perhaps Quantum might invest in LTCM?
- Meriwether explained positions were bargain for anyone with muscle to hold through turmoil
- **Conditional offer**: Soros would put up $500 million if Meriwether raised another $500 million from other investors

### Scrambling for Capital

- Meriwether explored deal with Salomon Brothers, dispatched **Larry Hilibrand** to Omaha for Buffett
- Made overtures to **Prince Alwaleed** (Saudi Arabia), **Michael Dell**
- Called **Herb Allison** (Merrill Lynch boss)—golf links friendship not enough

> "John, I'm not sure it's in your interest to raise money. It might look like you're having a problem." —Herb Allison

- Advice infuriating but true
- Buffett reacting to LTCM's distress by ordering lieutenants to monitor Berkshire Hathaway's hedge fund exposure
- Salomon Brothers issuing similar edicts—brokerage unit ceased extending loans to almost all hedge funds
- More LTCM scrambled to raise money, more panic spread, more their bets on calm declined
- Running on moving carpet pulling them away from home

### The "Pogo Moment" and Reverse Arbitrage

- Slinky effect suspended; arbitrageurs experiencing **"Pogo moment"**: "We have met the enemy and he is us!"
- Russian blowup caused all main arbitrage players to lose money
- Like LTCM, they scrambled for capital
- In stressed circumstances, arbitrageurs lacked muscle to correct pricing anomalies—faced margin calls forcing them to dump positions
- Partners' faith in arbitrage now **180 degrees off target**—replaced by **reverse arbitrage**
- Unwinding of each arbitrage portfolio damaged all others—cycle self-reinforcing
- Meriwether's Arbitrage Group at Salomon Brothers had performed so badly earlier that bosses resolved to close it; selling hammered other arbitrage outfits including LTCM
- Every LTCM trade went wrong in correlated way—not because economically similar but because similar in types of fund holding them

### LTCM's Hidden Vulnerability: Copycat Trading

- **Eric Rosenfeld**: failure to anticipate trader-driven correlation was fund's central error
- LTCM hadn't foreseen this possibility; risk calculations would have been different
- Another underestimated risk: LTCM's own success created special vulnerability
- Even though LTCM shrouded trades in secrecy, army of imitators pieced together much of strategy
- By spring 1998, LTCM's large portfolio mirrored by even larger **superportfolio created by disciples**
- Every bank/hedge fund that might buy LTCM's positions had already followed Meriwether's example and bought them
- If trade went wrong and Meriwether needed to retreat, **nobody to sell to**
- On one hand: nobody left to buy LTCM's positions (no way up)
- On other hand: shock forcing arbitrageurs to sell would cause LTCM's portfolio to collapse precipitously
- **"Central bank of volatility"** indeed like central bank—its trading presented predators with one-way bet

### August 1998: One of the Most Brutal Months

- By Labor Day: three out of four funds had lost money
- Meriwether and partners lost **44% of capital**, or **$1.9 billion**
- Calculated loss should occur less than once in lifetime of universe
- Meriwether called **Vinny Mattone** (Bear Stearns friend):

> "Where are you?" —Vinny Mattone
> "We're down by half." —Meriwether
> "You're finished." —Mattone
> "What are you talking about? We still have two billion. We have half—we have Soros." —Meriwether
> "When you're down by half, people figure you can go down all the way. They're going to push the market against you." —Vinny Mattone

- Meriwether called Merrill Lynch, UBS, Deutsche Bank seeking capital infusion
- Nobody would cough up $500 million; Soros opportunity vanished

### September Letter and Wall Street Turns Against LTCM

- Meriwether reported losses in investor letter September 2
- Reaffirmed faith in arbitrage, writing of "this unusually attractive environment"
- Letter leaked before last copy faxed; *Wall Street Journal* ran front-page story next day
- Now whole world knew LTCM on deathwatch; every Wall Street player started trading against it
- Most junk bonds rallied early September, but bonds LTCM owned remained dead
- LTCM's small **hurricane bonds** position (securities permitting insurers to sell hurricane risk) plummeted 20% when letter leaked—though hurricane probability/cost utterly unaltered
- Europe: gap between government bonds and market interest rates widened in Britain and Germany for no fundamental reason besides Long-Term's betting

> "It's not about the market anymore; it's about you. If you're long, they're short. If you're short, they're long." —Jim Rickards, general counsel

### Goldman Sachs Rescue Attempt and Alleged Front-Running

- September 13: Meriwether appealed to **Jon Corzine** for help raising $2 billion
- Corzine said yes at extraordinary price: in exchange for $1 billion from Goldman plus promise to raise additional billion elsewhere, Goldman demanded:
  - Half of LTCM management company
  - Full access to fund's strategies
  - Right to impose limits on fund's positions
  - Deal only goes through if Goldman raised money and Long-Term passed detailed portfolio inspection
- Terms meant Goldman would win either way: get half of Long-Term at bargain or get right to inspect trading books (information worth millions)
- Predeal due diligence would allow Goldman's experts to see precisely what LTCM owned, therefore which trades would crater if demise forced dump

### The Inspection Team Controversy

- LTCM sensed setting itself up for abuse but had no alternative
- **Jim Rickards** tried to get Goldman's inspection team to sign nondisclosure; brusquely informed Goldman would sign nothing
- According to Rickards, Goldman's inspectors plugged oversized laptop into LTCM's network and downloaded position details
- Goldman denied this occurred, but proprietary trading desk soon selling positions resembling LTCM's
- Goldman trader in London quoted: "If you think a gorilla has to sell, then you sure want to sell first. We are very clear on where the line is; that's not illegal."
- Corzine conceded possibility Goldman "did things in markets that might have ended up hurting LTCM. We had to protect our own positions. That part I'm not apologetic for."
- Goldman's defense: selling not influenced by privileged knowledge of LTCM's books; Chinese wall separated inspectors from traders managing Goldman's proprietary capital
- No proof to contrary, but some Wall Streeters suspected Chinese wall might be porous

### Federal Reserve Gets Involved

- Meriwether and partners decided time to inform **Federal Reserve** that failure was possibility
- **William McDonough** (head of New York Fed) was on his way out of town
- Fell to **Peter Fisher** (number two) to wade into crisis

### Fisher's Assessment: Sunday, September 20

- Sunday, September 20: Fisher hitched ride in assistant's Jeep from New Jersey to Greenwich
- Expert financial plumber, unflappable, had way of cutting through complexity with simple propositions
- As Fisher listened to Long-Term's positions, no neat solutions came to mind
- LTCM so leveraged, held sprawling portfolio worth **$120 billion**—only beginning of challenge
- What rattled Fisher: Long-Term's portfolio included **extraordinarily concentrated bets**
- Figured Long-Term's position in futures on **British government bonds ("gilts")** might represent half of open interest in that market
- Similarly outlandish position in Danish mortgages
- Portfolio of equity options enormous
- Issue not simply LTCM's collapse causing broad market fall—Fisher worried **particular markets might cease trading altogether**

### Fisher's Calculations: $3 Billion Hit to Wall Street

- According to Long-Term's calculations, seventeen biggest counterparties stood to lose **$3 billion** among them if fund wound up immediately
- If holdings liquidated in rush, losses considerably bigger
- Fisher presumed big Wall Street players had similar trades on own books
- If Long-Term liquidated at speed, damage magnified by huge hit to shadow portfolio
- Speedy and costly liquidation seemed horribly likely
- Past financial collapses: regulators could take charge of remaining assets, avoid fire sale
- But Long-Term different: **hedge fund had no assets for regulators to seize**
- Assets pledged by brokers as collateral against borrowing
- If LTCM defaulted on one loan agreement, **cross-default clauses** would automatically trigger
- Closeout agreements would flutter from thousand fax machines; ownership of positions transferred to brokers—which would dump them rapidly

### Fisher Confronts the Askin Capital Echo

- Sitting in Long-Term's quiet offices, Fisher confronted problem bedeviling failure of **Askin Capital Management**, would haunt regulators next decade
- Firms entangling themselves with dozens of partners can be too complex and intertwined to be buried easily

### The Monday Crisis: Markets Tumbling

- Fisher worried about sudden liquidation consequences
- East Asia in recession, Russia heading for one
- Market turmoil already inflicted sharp Wall Street losses
- Prospect of **$3 billion-plus hit** would have been unlovely at best, especially nasty given Street's compromised immune system
- Already rumors Lehman Brothers teetering; if LTCM's collapse pushed Lehman over, Lehman's collapse would have further consequences
- Precarious state of Wall Street's balance sheets reduced odds of best solution—private-sector takeover saving LTCM from chaotic fire sales
- Jon Corzine called Fisher to warn Goldman's buyer efforts not making progress
- Long-Term losing hundreds of millions of dollars per day
- Lucky to make it to another weekend

### Fisher Arrives Monday: Fears Coming True

- When Fisher arrived at work Monday, felt fears coming true faster than expected
- Markets in Asia and Europe tumbling; Wall Street looked set to follow
- Television commentators speculating President Clinton's videotaped deposition on Monica Lewinsky sex scandal (scheduled for later that morning) would rattle investors
- Fisher found this grimly amusing—truth was word was out about LTCM's rescue attempts
- Each attempt spread knowledge of trouble to another predator
- Every bank, brokerage, hedge fund feeding on bloodied torso
- Salomon executives reported Goldman's Tokyo desk "banging the shit" out of Long-Term
- Goldman executives reported Salomon doing same in Europe
- Around midday: attacks on Long-Term's equity options positions grew so ferocious that options prices implied crash every month
- End of Monday: LTCM lost **$550 million**, **one third of equity**
- First time capital sunk below **$1 billion**

### Fisher's Breakfast Meeting: Tuesday Morning

- Fisher stayed in touch with Goldman, Merrill Lynch, J.P. Morgan bosses
- Kept hoping for private-sector rescue signs
- Clear lone bank unable to perform role safely
- If purchaser bought LTCM's entire portfolio, would have to sell some holdings; knowing this, others would continue selling positions to get in front of inevitable liquidation
- Solution: **consortium to purchase portfolio**
- Each would get piece small enough to hold; hyenas would stop feeding
- Hitch: traditional rivalries among main banks seemed to preclude alliance—unless Fed brokered one

### The Fed Breakfast Meeting

- Toward end of Monday: Fisher invited heads of big three banks to breakfast at Fed next morning
- Once gathered, all three said they favored joint action
- Would protect markets from chaos, less painful for everyone
- Question: how to structure rescue
- LTCM's creditors could each buy bits of portfolio, lifting them out of fund
- Alternatively, consortium could inject capital into fund to stabilize
- After two hours discussion: Fisher asked bankers to go away and develop rescue plan all three could back
- Then Fisher would convene larger meeting at Fed involving wider group of fund's creditors

### The Rescue Package Takes Shape

- By end of day: bankers converged on view that money would have to be injected into Long-Term
- Lifting bits of portfolio out wouldn't work—LTCM's cat's cradle of trades too complicated
- But if new capital injected, who should bear cost?
- Price tag rising: Back in August when Meriwether breakfasted with Soros/Druckenmiller, LTCM needed **$1 billion lifeline**
- Three weeks later: Meriwether asked Corzine to raise **$2 billion**
- Now would take **$4 billion injection** to stabilize portfolio
- Collectively, bankers knew coughing up $4 billion was least bad option
- If let LTCM go down, massive portfolio would crash on markets, costing every major Wall Street player fortune
- But each bank had incentive to free ride—let rivals shoulder recapitalization cost

### Tuesday Evening Meeting at the Fed

- Fisher convened LTCM's sixteen main counterparties at Fed Tuesday evening
- Impossible to conclude deal
- Big three banks had blueprint: sixteen top creditors kicking in **$250 million each**
- Inevitably, smaller banks complained burden should be lighter
- Around 11:00 P.M., with no resolution, Fisher suggested they break until 10 A.M. next morning

### Wednesday Negotiations Turn Ugly

- When bankers' negotiations resumed, no easier than previous evening
- **Lehman Brothers** pleaded balance sheet so fragile couldn't put up $250 million
- Two French banks refused to share burden, each offering only $125 million
- Biggest shock: **Bear Stearns** (Long-Term's lead broker)
- Despite earning millions in fees from Long-Term in good times, **CEO of Bear adamantly refused to put up single dollar**
- **Philip Purcell** (Morgan Stanley chairman) protested Bear's free riding "not *acceptable*"
- **David Komansky** (Merrill Lynch) exploded in Cayne's face
- Discussions grew so ugly that Fisher began gaming out impasse consequences

> "I remember thinking, 'If this thing isn't going to work, I'm going to have to stand on the table and say, 'Don't touch your cell phones. Close the door. We're now going to draft a statement that says there's no deal.'" —Peter Fisher

- Lack of rescue would tip global markets into free fall
- Bankers party to failure should not be allowed to sell ahead of ordinary investors

### The Deal Closes: $3.625 Billion

- In end, Fisher didn't have to jump on table
- Eleven banks agreed to increase contributions to **$300 million each**
- Smaller amounts from Lehman and French brought total to **$3.625 billion**
- Money just about sufficient to declare rescue
- Long-Term would be bought; global markets saved
- Meriwether and partners (who kept so much own money in fund) would see personal fortunes reduced to almost nothing

> "We believed in ourselves. There was no hypocrisy there. I like to say we lost money the old-fashioned way: through honesty and hard work." —Jim Rickards, LTCM counsel

### Post-Rescue Congressional Hearings (October 1, 1998)

- During congressional hearings October 1: House Financial Services Committee vented about threat to economic stability posed by handful of secretive traders
- **Representative Paul Kanjorski** (Democrat, Pennsylvania) suggested nation's foreign enemies could harm U.S. more easily by partnering with hedge funds
- Yet outrage mostly echo of 1994 bond-market collapse debate
- Nation's top regulators forced to recognize hedge funds pose risks, but did little to reduce them

### Greenspan's Defense of Light Regulation

- Tempting to be harsh about failure to respond vigorously
- Back in 1994: regulators argued banks/brokerages too savvy to allow hedge-fund clients wild bets with their money
- Now argument destroyed: Wall Street's finest exposed themselves to LTCM in such extreme way it took Fed intervention to save them
- Yet nation's top regulators continued to resist crackdown on hedge funds

> "Individuals who lend money to others have a very important interest in getting that money back." —Alan Greenspan

- **Alan Greenspan** reminded House hearings, falling back on idea private creditors would check hedge fund excesses
- Not until 2009 Greenspan conceded risk monitoring by lenders was flimsy defense against financial excesses
- Even then, presented concession as though crisis of 2007–2009 had come out of blue—as though LTCM had never happened

### Reasons for Greenspan's Diffidence

- Good reasons for Greenspan's diffidence
- Clamping down on hedge funds wouldn't have ended dangerous trading
- Long-Term too leveraged, overlooked danger trades could implode spectacularly if arbitrageurs forced to dump copycat positions suddenly
- Misjudged precision with which financial risk can be measured
- **But no reason to suppose Long-Term's errors possible only at hedge funds**
- Long-Term's collapse rattled authorities because coincided with frightening losses at investment banks like Lehman Brothers
- Wake of LTCM's failure: Greenspan and regulators could see real challenge was leverage in financial system writ large
- Ironically, this what Soros tried to explain to Congress in testimony four years earlier
- Sure enough, culprits in crisis of 2007–2009 were **leveraged off-balance-sheet vehicles owned by banks** (conduits/structured investment vehicles/SIVs), **leveraged broker-dealers**, **leveraged insurer**
- Hedge funds were not the villains

### Why Didn't Regulators Clamp Down on Leveraged Investors?

- If hedge funds only part of challenge, why didn't regulators clamp down on wider universe of leveraged investors?
- Answer echoes 1994: regulators believed they lacked good way of doing so
- Could not simply announce cap on leverage: ratio of borrowing to capital almost meaningless number
- Failed to capture whether portfolio hedged, whether exposed to risks via derivatives positions
- Could not simply cap hedge funds' value at risk: LTCM's collapse shown this measure misleading
- Frustrating truth: risks in portfolio depended on constantly changing conditions
  - Whether other players mimicking trades
  - How liquid markets were
  - Whether banks/brokerages suffering from compromised immune systems
- Fed's **Peter Fisher** at center of regulatory brainstorming following LTCM
- Could see theoretical case for government controls on hedge funds and other leveraged players
- But seemed so unlikely government would get details right that he never went for action

### The Basel II Experiment

- In next few years, parallel experiment in regulation proved Fisher's hesitation well founded
- Starting 1998: committee of global regulators set out to design modern set of risk controls
- Eventually promulgating **Basel II capital requirements**
- Even though exercise excluded insurers, broker-dealers, hedge funds, concentrating exclusively on banks
- Still chewed up six years, ended in abject failure
- In attempt to write rules capturing subtle risks in banks' portfolios, Basel II framework deferred to banks' own models of how much risk they were taking
- In other words: regulators' bottom line was **banks should self-regulate**
- When crisis hit 2007: European banks that adopted Basel II proved hopelessly fragile
- If regulators tried to control leverage of hedge funds and other shadowbanks, might have done no better than Basel standards

### Greenspan's Fair Verdict for 1998

- Just as in 1994: regulators' unwillingness to impose direct controls on investment banks and hedge funds forced them back to plan B
- Express concern about financial risk to reassure nation dangers are tolerable
- Greenspan mused publicly about dangers of financial modeling, which could get too far ahead of human judgment
- Urged creditors to remember hedge funds might perform well in good times then suddenly blow up when markets hit unexpected volatility
- While acknowledging flaws in modern finance, Greenspan emphasized cost of returning to premodern age
- If banks required to hold capital worth 40% of assets (as they had after Civil War), there would be far fewer episodes of market turbulence
- But capital would be more costly, living standards lower

> "We do not have the choice of accepting the benefits of the current system without its costs." —Alan Greenspan

### The Fair Verdict and What Went Wrong

- In context of 1998: fair verdict
- Benefits of modern finance outweighed risks
- Attempts to reduce risks via government regulation appeared uncertain of success (as Basel experiment suggested)
- Still, with unfair luxury of hindsight, decision to leave risk control to market was wrong
- Banks learned one lesson from LTCM episode: reined in leverage extended to hedge funds (as should have done in wake of Askin's failure 1994)
- But other lessons went unheeded:
  - LTCM's failure shown craziness of insuring whole world against volatility without holding capital in reserve
  - Over next decade, giant insurer AIG repeated same error
  - LTCM's failure exposed fallacy that diversification could reduce risk to virtually zero
  - Over next decade investors repeated miscalculation by buying bundles of supposedly diversified mortgage securities
  - Most fundamental: LTCM's failure provided object lesson in dangers of leveraged finance
  - Yet world's response was not only to let leveraged trading continue
  - **Was to tolerate vast expansion**


<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

### The Tech Bubble as Test of Hedge Fund Philosophy

- Tech bubble of late 1990s tested two competing views of hedge funds
- **Optimistic view**: sophisticated traders analyze prices and push them toward efficiency
- **Darker view**: traders lack muscle to enforce efficiency, prefer riding trends to fighting them
- Hedge funds demonstrated both behaviors: long/short investors (A.W. Jones, Meriwether) sought efficiency; trend followers (Tudor Jones) surfed momentum without claiming fundamental understanding
- If markets truly needed efficiency-enforcing arbitrage, the dot-com bubble was the ultimate example
- Tech start-ups had zero earnings by traditional measures—intrinsic worth was zero
- **Books-A-Million** jumped tenfold in three days after announcing website improvements (Nov 1998)
- **Priceline.com** gained 425% on first trading day—an untested airline ticket site worth more than United, Continental, and Northwest Airlines combined
- Social justification for highly paid investment managers: they enforce efficient pricing and allocate capital to best uses, not to bubbly start-ups with bad business plans

### Tiger's Julian Robertson: The Limits of Arbitrage Against Bubbles

- Tiger and Quantum had ~$20 billion at peak—tiny versus $5 trillion NASDAQ market cap
- Hedge funds too small to deflate bubble alone; needed others to bet the same way
- Heavy losses during waiting period could trigger investor redemptions, forcing fund to unwind position before payoff
- **Keynes**: "The market can stay irrational longer than you can stay solvent"
- **Robertson's response**: declined to fight tech bubble in 1999
- He'd lost money on tech shorts in 1998, concluded there was no safe way to bet against the bubble
- Could short individual companies and hedge general market rise by going long similar stocks—but entire tech sector overvalued, no equivalent basket for hedging
- Robertson compared NASDAQ to "locomotive hurtling down the tracks"—certain to derail, but timing unknown
- After yen losses (fall 1998), Robertson resolved to scale back macro bets and avoid tech sector
- Tiger grew so large it struggled to deploy capital in meaningful stakes
- Concentrated on traditional value stocks: **Federal-Mogul** (auto parts), **Niagara Mohawk** (power company)

### Robertson's US Airways Disaster

- Early 1996: Robertson bought large stake in **US Airways** after cost-cutting turnaround artist appointed CEO
- By summer 1998: stock quintupled—bet paid off spectacularly
- Robertson held on rather than selling despite stake worth $1.5 billion (one-fifth of company)
- Analyst counseled selling part during share buyback (early 1998), but Robertson refused: "It's one of my best ideas"
- Given finite opportunities for supersized value investor, Robertson prepared to hold illiquid positions long after original thesis paid off
- **Risks materialized**: Early 1999, US Airways reported disappointing profits, stock dropped 29% in three weeks
- Robertson predicted stock could triple by year-end as market regained respect for old-economy companies—but it didn't
- July 1999: machinists rejected pay contract; August: work stoppages forced flight cancellations
- Stock continued down—Robertson couldn't sell vast position without triggering free fall
- Tiger became owner rather than investor, forced to seek strategic buyer for large block
- Other value bets souring: **Federal-Mogul** fell 30% in first half of year; **Niagara Mohawk** was flat
- "We are going through a most unusual market where in many instances fundamentals are being ignored" (Robertson, April 1999)

### Tiger's Crisis: Investor Redemptions and Forced Liquidation

- Summer 1999: Robertson's decision to ignore tech boom caused crisis
- Tiger lost 7.3% first half of year; tech-heavy mutual funds up 25%+; day traders in kitchens outperforming Robertson's special-forces unit
- Yen losses (fall 1998) plus latest setbacks strained investor patience
- Net $3 billion withdrawn in six months to March; another $760 million withdrawn end of Q2
- More investors pulled out → more Robertson forced to liquidate holdings
- Once Wall Street knew Tiger was forced seller, predatory instincts returned
- Robertson reported Tiger's top ten stock positions monthly in investor letters—rivals front-ran him
- **June rumor**: Tiger facing $3 billion withdrawals at month-end triggered predatory sales spasm—Tiger lost $72 million in fifteen minutes on steady market day
- Unlike LTCM (brokers calling in loans), Tiger's danger was investors calling in equity
- In both cases, widespread knowledge of holdings contributed to troubles
- Lesson for those advocating hedge-fund transparency: publicity can destabilize markets

### Quantum's Druckenmiller: Tech Bet and Dramatic Reversal

- Start of 1999: **Stan Druckenmiller** shared Robertson's view that tech stocks too high, but acted differently
- Undeterred by momentum, Druckenmiller placed unhedged outright bet against tech bubble
- Picked dozen particularly overvalued start-ups, shorted $200 million worth
- All shot up with violence making escape impossible: "They'd close one day at a hundred and open at one forty"
- Within weeks: position cost Quantum $600 million
- May 1999: Druckenmiller down 18%—first time in long career facing year with significant negative performance
- Druckenmiller's losses twice as bad as Robertson's—inevitable investor chafing
- May: **Haussmann Holdings** cut Soros Fund Management investments by more than half
- Press reported stream of Quantum analysts leaving; rumors Druckenmiller legend over, might take medical leave, Soros tiring of his alter ego

### Druckenmiller's Advantage: Flexibility to Surf the Bubble

- Druckenmiller better equipped for tech boom than Robertson
- Tiger's value-investing tradition made buying into bubble "almost unthinkable" for Robertson
- Druckenmiller's blend of traditional analysis and charts made him less predictable
- Robertson had no patience for momentum investing; Druckenmiller "fully capable of following the fundamentals in one period and surfing the trend in the next"
- May 1999: Druckenmiller allocated Quantum capital to new hire **Carson Levit**, who loaded up on dot-com stocks
- Skeptic who shorted bubble now climbed aboard bandwagon
- July 1999: Druckenmiller attended annual tech/media conference in **Sun Valley, Idaho**—festival of new-economy bullishness with Hollywood moguls, presidential contenders, Silicon Valley whiz kids
- Even **Warren Buffett** (whose value style hammered by bubble) seen chatting with Bill Gates and Michael Bloomberg
- Druckenmiller returned converted, allocated more capital to Levit and hired second tech enthusiast **Diane Hakala** (aerobatic pilot hobby)
- Levit and Hakala piled into "radioactive shit that I don't know how to spell"

### Quantum's Tech Surge and Robertson's Forced Sales

- Tech stocks took off like rocket: **VeriSign**, **Qualcomm**, **Gemstar** hailed as heroes of new era
- First half 1999: Quantum trailed Tiger; now Quantum benefited from Tiger's misfortune
- Tiger investor withdrawals forced Robertson to sell stocks
- Robertson dumped vast stake in **South Korea Telecom** (bought before bubble)
- Pressure of Robertson's selling caused South Korea Telecom to drop one-third (July-August)
- Carson Levit bought into liquidation on the cheap—stock promptly tripled
- Last months 1999: Druckenmiller made more surfing tech than shorting sterling eight years earlier
- Quantum went from down 18% (first five months) to up 35% by year-end
- One of great comebacks in hedge fund history—nothing to do with pushing markets to efficient level

### Other Hedge Funds and the Tech Bubble

- Most hedge funds grappled with tech bubble rather than fighting it
- Early 1999: army of short sellers fought **America Online** over "bubbly new way of accounting"
- AOL treated marketing expenditures as investment (counted against revenues bit by bit like machinery cost), not immediately recognized cost
- Short sellers won accounting argument but lost shirts on investment
- **Mary Meeker** (Morgan Stanley, "Queen of the Net"): old-school value investors trained on Ben Graham and David Dodd might have trouble seeing value in AOL-type company that reports losses
- Banker at new-economy gathering: "No traditional Graham and Dodd investor invested in AOL. They shorted it. And got fucked. They're learning the new model."
- **Greenlight Capital** (David Einhorn) took large short position in **Chemdex** (Sept 1999, trading at $26)
- Chemdex: business-to-business network for chemical sales, earned commission but booked entire value of goods exchanged as revenue
- Dec: Queen Mary declared "We think Chemdex has got what it takes"
- Feb: stock risen more than sixfold to $164
- Late 2000: Chemdex collapsed to $2 per share—too late to help Einhorn, forced out before bubble burst with enormous losses

### Hedge Funds Generally Rode the Bubble

- Despite periodic suspicions short sellers can manipulate markets, tech market of 1999 swatted away hedge-fund skeptics easily
- Manipulation occurred elsewhere: companies cooking books, auditors turning blind eye, investment banks engaged in shameless hype about tech companies
- Seeing no hope of bucking mania, hedge funds mostly jumped on for ride
- Some bought bubble believing hype or because style was trend-following
- Some reasoned Fed's extraordinarily loose monetary policy meant hot asset would attain stratospheric valuations
- Some bought IPOs because insider's game: investment banks created scramble for tech stocks by parceling new issues cheaply, virtually printing money for funds with IPO access
- Hedge funds no more prone to ride bubble than other money managers—but not more contrarian either
- While bubble building, only bravest value investors foolhardy enough to fight it

### Tiger's Final Collapse

- Bravest and foolhardiest: **Julian Robertson**
- Tiger lost 17% Q3 even as momentum surfers reaped extraordinary profits
- Hemorrhaging of investors continued: end of Sept, net $1.3 billion yanked away
- Tiger fell from $21 billion peak (Aug 1998) to $9.5 billion just over a year later
- $5 billion decline due to clients voting with wallets
- Not just money losing for Robertson—Tiger was his family, personal network of power brokers and friends
- He'd run special-forces unit, led team-building excursions out west—not used to defeat or ignominious rout
- Low moments: called old lieutenant **John Griffin** (now running own hedge fund)—"John, can you believe that I got a letter from so-and-so who has been in Tiger since 1982? He says he's buying a house. He needs his money back. He's just lost faith in me."
- Robertson announced investors could redeem capital twice yearly rather than four times
- Mild restriction compared to later lockups, but Robertson backed down after investor protests
- Investors protested: proved loyalty keeping money through terrible year, why be chained to *Titanic* now?
- Robertson conceded they had point, but next generation learned: reduce mismatch between yankable capital and illiquid investments by permitting less frequent withdrawals

### The Death Spiral: Predatory Trading Accelerates

- Unable to lock in money, Robertson forced to sell positions whether liquid or not—became sitting duck
- Rivals knew he had to unload, went short in anticipation
- Aug-Oct: rumors of Tiger's unraveling mounted
- **US Airways** short sales rose from 1.6 million to 3.8 million shares, driving battered stock down another tenth
- **Federal-Mogul** short sales leaped from 3.7 million to 6.5 million shares, forcing stock down 80%
- Robertson sold ~$40 billion of stocks and $60 billion of other positions over past year
- Some considered it miracle Tiger still standing
- **Philip Duff** (Tiger's COO): "How many financial institutions could have a $100 billion downsizing of their balance sheet? Few of those would probably survive."

### Robertson's Capitulation

- End 1999: Robertson's tone telegraphed end coming
- Pleaded with investors: great technology can change lives without generating profits
- Pointed out managers of companies in Tiger portfolio buying stock back (regarded as cheap); tech firm managers eagerly selling stakes in own enterprises
- "We are in wild runaway technology frenzy: meantime most other stocks are in a state of collapse" (Dec)
- "I have never seen such a dichotomy. There will be a correction."
- Jan 2000: Robertson uncorked frustration at "irrational public"—"This is the public that in the month of December drove the unprofitable companies in the NASDAQ up some 38 percent. There has to be a day of reckoning."
- Day of reckoning came March 10, 2000: NASDAQ crested, air whooshed out of bubble
- Too late—Robertson made decision to exit, too beaten to change it
- March 30 (NASDAQ already 15% off peak): Robertson broke news to investors
- After months assuring light at end of tunnel, confessed sick of waiting
- Rational valuation measures taken backseat to "mouse clicks and momentum"—no stomach for more punishment
- Market stayed irrational longer than he stayed solvent (Keynes warning)
- Time to bring curtain down on Tiger

### Quantum's Nervous Victory and Druckenmiller's Exit

- While Tiger suffered final phase of bubble, Quantum enjoyed nervous victory
- Terrific tech profits late 1999 rescued Druckenmiller from down-year humiliation
- But anyone could see run would end eventually
- Quantum's weekly research meetings: Druckenmiller worried bubble could burst anytime, discussion revolved around how bust might be anticipated
- As if to reinforce nervousness, tech-heavy NASDAQ fell sharply start of Jan, then turned around and vaulted to new heights—volatility hair-raising
- Feb: watching biotech firm **Celera Genomics** skyrocket, Druckenmiller told Quantum trader market was insane, needed to get out quickly
- "I just want you to know, I'm selling everything out"
- Soros: "This is fucking nuts." / "I'm really glad you're doing it. I haven't been comfortable with this."
- Druckenmiller dumped tech holdings, focused on currencies—potential moment of triumph
- Quantum's supremo got out before bubble burst, back to strong suit as macro trader
- Markets conspired to taunt Druckenmiller almost as cruelly as they'd tormented Robertson
- First: Druckenmiller stuck on wrong side of Europe's fledgling currency (euro)
- Next: NASDAQ stocks he'd sold continued to rush upward
- **Carson Levit** and **Diane Hakala** still running tech subportfolios, surfing bubble—all of sudden big man's anxieties shifted
- Earlier worried bubble might blow up in face; now worried about losing face for doubting new economy, misjudging euro
- Now these kids and radioactive stocks making fool of him
- Not first time Druckenmiller turned on dime: bought all tech stocks back, gave Levit and Hakala room to run
- For while, good times rolled again

### The Final Crash and Druckenmiller's Exhaustion

- March 10: NASDAQ turned, many Quantum stocks fell faster than market
- Druckenmiller huge buyer of firm called **VeriSign** (lost almost half value in month), plummeting so hard difficult to sell out
- "I knew I was dead" by end of March
- Quantum lost ~one-tenth of capital
- Pivoting aggressively too many times = failed to escape before party ended
- Druckenmiller left for vacation in Florida
- One year earlier, led Quantum back from behind; now lacked will to do it
- Like friend Julian Robertson, too drained to go on
- Though Robertson's decision to pull curtain on Tiger seemed mistimed, Druckenmiller realized he envied Robertson's new freedom
- "Money is supposed to be enjoyed, but if I can't enjoy two weeks with my kids, what's the point of it all?"
- Had carried Quantum on shoulders twelve years—enough
- "I'm tired, exhausted. I fought out of the hole last year; I just can't do it"
- **Soros** recognized desperation he'd once felt himself running Quantum alone
- Compared himself to sick person with parasitic fund swelling inexorably inside body
- Druckenmiller saying for some time: wished Quantum not so large, needed exit, could not go on forever
- In end, Soros reflected, Druckenmiller only freed himself by blowing up fund—expensive method of escape, but certain

### Soros Shuts Down Quantum as Aggressive Hedge Fund

- April 28: Soros convened press conference
- Quantum down 21% for year; assets at Soros Fund Management fallen by $7.6 billion since Aug 1998 high of $22 billion
- Announced **Stan Druckenmiller** leaving after dozen years; Quantum henceforth managed as sedate, low-risk endowment
- Within one month, two largest and most storied hedge funds pulled down shutters
- "We have come to realize that a large hedge fund like Quantum Fund is no longer the best way to manage money. Markets have become extremely unstable."
- Soros appeared to draw line under industry he'd helped invent—but couldn't have been more wrong
- Too early to write epitaph for hedge funds

## Chapter 12: The Yale Men

### The Robin Hood Foundation Gala (2001)

- June 1, 2001: 2,920 people attended Robin Hood Foundation gala at Jacob Javits Convention Center
- **Paul Tudor Jones** conceived charity in wake of 1987 crash
- After thirteen years: distributed over $90 million to organizations fighting poverty, teen pregnancy, illiteracy in NYC
- 2001 gathering promised to take crusade to next level
- Lavish event mixing disco vibe with rain-forest aesthetic; green poles, projected treetops, shifting green light
- Celebrities: **Meg Ryan**, **Keith Hernandez**, **Tom Brokaw**—and many hedge-fund managers
- Caterers worked with paramilitary intensity; traffic cops with fluorescent batons directed servers
- Proof Soros's epitaph for hedge funds delivered prematurely
- **Stan Druckenmiller** himself was sponsor (returned to markets almost immediately, now running own firm **Duquesne Capital Management**)
- Titans turned out at gala, paying $5,000 per ticket, bidding lustily
- One guest: $540,000 for lunch with leading financial mogul
- Another: $260,000 for "Be a Star" package (part in Russell Crowe's *A Beautiful Mind*, walk-on in Drew Barrymore's *The Duplex*, dinner with Catherine Zeta-Jones and Michael Douglas)
- Paul Tudor Jones's wife **Sonia** bid $420,000 for yoga lesson with Madonna and Gwyneth Paltrow
- Jerry Seinfeld urged auction off item; once selling over, slice of wall dropped away, cannons spewed confetti
- **Robert Plant** (Led Zeppelin) strutted onto dance floor
- By evening's end: Jones's foundation pulled in $113.5 million—hedge-fund wealth become social force

### Hedge Funds and University Endowments

- Greatest philanthropic impact: not charities bankrolled, but profits accrued to endowments invested with them
- Early 2000s: *billions* of hedge-fund earnings flowed into university coffers
- Boosted ability to finance scientific research to scholarships for poor students
- Bonanza changed outlook for learning and character of hedge funds
- Taking in institutional money, hedge funds grew larger, slicker, more methodical—emerging as real industry

### David Swensen of Yale: The Endowment Pioneer

- Pioneer of alliance between endowments and hedge funds: **David Swensen** of **Yale University**
- Tall, angular, ascetic, cerebral—"stiff-backed midwesterner"
- Possessed above all by fierce sense of moral purpose
- Growing up River Falls, Wisconsin: founded recycling club through church group; mother and sister Lutheran ministers
- Ambition: follow state's progressive political tradition, be elected to Senate
- After enrolling Yale's economics PhD program, took different turn
- Befriended future Nobel laureate **James Tobin**
- Got to know Wall Street's preeminent bond firm **Salomon Brothers** (provided market data for dissertation)
- Developed passion for finance and Yale environment
- 1980: Salomon immediately hired Swensen after completing doctorate
- Thrived on competitive culture of Wall Street
- Helped make financial history following year: played role in creation of first **currency swap** (deal between IBM and World Bank allowing IBM to hedge exposure to Swiss francs and German marks)
- 1982: lured to **Lehman Brothers** to run bank's fledgling swaps desk
- 1985: former professors lobbied him to take over Yale's troubled endowment
- Accepted happily, gave up investment-banking bonuses for book-lined office on campus (pay cut 80%)
- Years later, Wall Street admirer remarked Swensen could have been billionaire running hedge fund
- "What's the matter with you?" / "A genetic defect"

### Swensen's Vision: "Absolute Return" and Diversification

- When Swensen took over Yale endowment, more than four-fifths of assets in US stocks, bonds, cash
- Only one-tenth in "alternative investments"—resembled most other college endowments
- Young man returning from innovative Wall Street world: seemed tame
- Affront to research of mentor **James Tobin** (advanced idea portfolio diversification = one free lunch in economics)
- Modern financial system: diversification should mean more than broad mix of US bonds and equities
- Assets like foreign equities, real estate, private equity, oil, gas, timber offered ways to add equity-type returns while diversifying risk substantially
- Another asset took Swensen's fancy: **"absolute return"**—over next years term entered investment lexicon, became synonym for hedge funds
- Moralist in Swensen had no desire to help hedge-fund managers earn fortunes
- But economist impressed by design of hedge-fund incentives
- Knew larger investment fund = harder for manager to generate returns, so disliked fees tied to volume of capital managed (preferring performance fees accounting for most hedge-fund revenues)
- Recognized performance fees alone encourage too much risk (managers get fifth of upside, pay no equivalent penalty if blow up)
- Sought out hedge-fund managers with own savings in funds, encouraged to discover many
- What really interested Swensen: scale and source of hedge-fund profits
- Hedge funds promised equity-sized returns uncorrelated with market index, offering free lunch of diversification

### Swensen Initially Rejects Tom Steyer's Farallon (1987)

- Took while for Swensen to recognize potential in hedge funds
- 1987: two years after assuming helm at endowment, received visit from Yale alumnus at homecoming football game
- Visitor said he had small fund on West Coast; perhaps Yale might want to invest?
- Swensen and deputy **Dean Takahashi** listened to pitch
- "We're not interested. We'll never be interested."

### Tom Steyer and Farallon Fund

- Supplicant: **Tom Steyer**, hedge fund called **Farallon**
- Sported sweeping red-blond parting, jaunty sideburns, faded woven wristbands
- Though grown up in New York, exuded vibe of adopted home San Francisco
- Ebullient, funny, comfortable in own skin
- Could fill conversation with mental and athletic juice, running with ideas like soccer star
- Came equipped with another quality appealing to Swensen later: acute sense of right and wrong, colored everything from lifestyle to business approach
- Long after Steyer built Farallon into one of world's biggest hedge funds, renowned for beat-up car, habit of flying commercial, utter indifference to fashion
- Office: desk in middle of open-plan hallway
- Behind: breathtaking panorama of San Francisco (but Steyer kept blinds down)
- Founded Farallon 1985, same year Swensen took over Yale endowment
- Motivated partly by desire to escape Wall Street for West Coast life, partly by sense of justice
- Young analyst at **Morgan Stanley**: upset to discover investment-bank advisers paid for being wrong
- Sounding convincing mattered more than actually being right (objective simply extract fees from clients)
- After stint at Stanford business school, worked at **Goldman Sachs** for merger-arbitrage unit run by **Robert Rubin** (future Treasury secretary)
- Suited him better: Goldman got paid only when Goldman right (though distribution of profits among employees sometimes generated arguments)
- Way Steyer saw things, setting up independent fund = logical next step
- Had begun at firm that took no responsibility for bad investment calls
- Moved to firm that took responsibility collectively but didn't always recognize individual's contribution
- Now by starting freestanding fund, would be out on own—no buffer between quality of investment calls and rewards

### Steyer's Merger Arbitrage Strategy

- Steyer rented cheap space in downtown San Francisco with couple desks (one for himself, one for partner)
- Would ride elevator to office at 5:30 in morning, clutching coffee and doughnut, ready to analyze merger action at start of NY trading day
- Investment style practiced: same learned at Goldman Sachs
- When takeover bid announced, stock in target company would move most of way to bid price
- Example: trading at $30, bid for $40 → might shoot to $38
- Presented Steyer with choice: if bought stock and merger consummated, pocket $2 per share; but if merger called off and stock fell back to old price, forfeit $8
- Knowing whether to risk $8 to make $2 required special skill
- Had to judge whether antitrust regulators would block merger, or shareholders revolt, or another suitor emerge stage left (perhaps pushing stock above $40)
- Steyer pursued work with competitive passion sometimes seemed overboard
- After taking losses in 1987 crash, started showing up at 3am, accompanied by wife (feared for his stability)
- Despite hit in 1987, Steyer did extremely well
- Arbitrageur analyzing mergers from Goldman Sachs desk can analyze them as well from San Francisco desk (especially when body and soul tied up in performance)
- Buying target companies in deals that would be consummated, eked out profits month by month
- By shorting acquiring firms, hedged out risk from general market movements

### Steyer Expands Beyond Merger Arbitrage

- Toward end 1980s, Steyer expanded horizons
- Partly survival strategy: takeover boom skidded to halt when junk-bond market collapsed 1989, leaving merger arbitrageurs with few mergers to analyze
- But Steyer playing offense too: junk-bond collapse created opportunity to apply analytical skills in different context
- Companies at center of junk-bond market filed for bankruptcy one by one
- Investor who could figure out which piece of busted debt likely to profit handsomely
- To make matters better, pension funds, mutual funds, other institutional investors = forced sellers of junk (rules forbade holding bonds of companies in default)
- Compelled to concede bargains to nimble players like Farallon
- When **Drexel Burnham Lambert** (kingpin of junk-bond market) filed bankruptcy 1990, Steyer bought large slice of debt at cents on dollar
- When sold stake 1993, Farallon's portfolio chalked up 35% profit
- With Drexel transaction: scored dazzling double (profited from mergers made possible by Drexel's bonds, profited again from Drexel's implosion)

### Steyer Creates "Event-Driven" Hedge Fund Model

- Steyer created what later known as **"event-driven" hedge fund**
- Specialized in events causing existing prices to be wrong—moments when disruption suddenly rendered market's settled view inoperative
- Moment before takeover bid: company's share price embodies verdict of investors who projected future earnings (price efficient, analyzed to death already)
- Moment after takeover bid: old calculations scrambled
- Analysts must look at size of takeover premium, time until likely realized, rate at which should be discounted, etc.
- Similar fashion: event like bankruptcy scrambles yesterday's consensus on value of company's bonds
- Challenge: look afresh at cash flows each busted bond likely to generate
- Even before Drexel coup, news of Steyer's performance reached ears of **David Swensen**
- Steyer making excellent money irrespective of whether stock market up or down—offered diversification
- Steyer generating profits by focusing on occasions settled prices scrambled
- To financial economist attuned to limits of efficient-market hypothesis, success did not look merely lucky
- Two factors enough to make Swensen reconsider initial refusal to invest in Farallon
- Before went further, Swensen had to take measure of Steyer the man
- Wanted partners with integrity, wanted something more
- Beating market only possible for people with sort of obsessive passion
- "Great investors tend to have a 'screw loose,' pursuing the game not for profit, but for sport"

### Yale Invests in Farallon (1990)

- Yale did due diligence, found Steyer had all qualities endowment could hope for
- Guy not running hedge fund because craved luxury (just had to look at office)
- Guy shared Swensen's passion for pure compensation incentives: insisted Farallon employees keep liquid savings in fund so would feel pain if lost money
- Steyer also embraced convention of **"high-water mark"**: if fund was down, would take no further fees until earned money back for investors
- Fall 1989: Swensen flew to San Francisco
- Visited Farallon's scruffy office, approved of what he saw
- Over cheap lunch with Steyer and another Farallon partner **Fleur Fairman**, Swensen repeated earlier verdict Yale would not invest
- Hedge funds would stiff clients if strategies went wrong
- Rather than working without compensation to earn capital back (as "high-water mark" promised), hedge funds would simply close shop, reopen under new name with fresh set of investors
- "Look, the reason we don't want to do this honestly is in this format, if you lose money, you won't want to earn it back. You'll close down and start a new fund. That's the problem with the whole format."
- Steyer might have argued back, but Fairman beat him to it
- "That's a bunch of bullshit!" she exclaimed
- Swensen could see she was furious
- "If you think that's who we are then we don't want your money anyway!" Fairman carried on
- "You have no idea who we are! It's just ridiculous that you'd say that!"
- Better response than Swensen could possibly have wished
- Had found integrity he sought: Fairman took decency so seriously flew off handle when questioned
- Jan 1990: Yale invested with Farallon
- University injected $300 million into Steyer's fund, boosting capital to total of $900 million
- Kick-starting gradual change in social impact of hedge funds

### Yale's Hedge Fund Allocation Grows

- Swensen's partnership with Steyer began repositioning of Yale, ultimately affecting investment style of nearly all endowments
- Until Farallon deal, Yale had smattering of holdings in private equity and "real assets" like real estate, but nothing in hedge funds
- Half decade later (1995): allocation to hedge funds jumped to 21%, with another 31% in private equity and real assets
- Other universities followed, with lag
- Typical university endowment: allocation to hedge funds rose from nothing in 1990 to 7% in 2000
- Years after dot-com crash, endowments experimenting with hedge funds rewarded particularly well
- July 2000-June 2003: S&P 500 lost 33% of value while HFR index of hedge funds gained 10%
- Yale itself up 20% over period
- Couple years later, when university celebrated twentieth anniversary of Swensen's arrival, his investment decisions celebrated for generating **$7.8 billion** of $14 billion in Yale endowment—amount by which he'd outperformed average university fund during tenure
- Fully $7.8 billion: staggering number!
- With Swensen eclipsing storied educational philanthropists like **Harkness** and **Mellon**, hedge funds became more than vehicles for rich to get richer
- By 2009: roughly half capital in hedge funds came not from individuals but from institutions

### The New Era: Hedge Funds as Industry

- Rush of endowment money ensured no need to write epitaph for industry
- Start of 2000: Soros proclaimed hedge-fund era over, assets stood at $490 billion
- End 2005: stood at $1.1 trillion
- Soros's epitaph at least partially apt for his own type of trader: first years of new century relatively lean time for macro hedge funds
- But event-driven funds like Farallon made up for that
- Farallon's assets ballooned from $8 billion (2002) to $16 billion (2006); imitators crowded in
- **Och-Ziff** (created by another veteran of Robert Rubin arbitrage group at Goldman): grew from $6 billion to $14 billion over same period
- **Perry Capital** (another Rubin offshoot): grew from $4 billion to $11 billion
- This "Rubin school" soon exceeded Commodities Corporation three in terms of asset size
- By 2006: Caxton, Tudor, Moore marshaled combined total of $35 billion, $6 billion less than total for Farallon, Perry, and Och-Ziff
- Host of other products of Rubin arbitrage group (including **Frank Brosens** of **Taconic Capital**, **Eric Mindich** of **Eton Park**)

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Event-Driven Hedge Funds: Appeal and Hidden Risks

### Why Endowments Loved Event-Driven Funds

- Event-driven funds delivered **understandable, unvolatile returns** uncorrelated with market indices—the "holy grail" of institutional investing
- **Farallon** exemplified the model: zero down months from 1990-1997, **Sharpe ratio 3x higher** than stock market
- Returns came from analyzing specific situations with edge: legal intricacies of bankruptcies, merger terms, understanding which bankruptcy judge would rule how
- **Transparency advantage**: Endowment committees could understand subordinated debt analysis better than macro theory about "Kondratiev waves"
- Institutional investors had rules forcing them to sell defaulted bonds, creating profits for those who stayed—**Steyer and imitators benefited from hobbled competitors**
- Event-driven funds used **little leverage** (unlike Long-Term Capital), making blowup risk seem remote
- Farallon's **consistency was legendary**: avoided dot-com bubble by sticking to merger-arb and takeover battles, hedging market risk

> "Event-driven hedge funds were producing understandable, unvolatile returns—returns, moreover, that reflected pure investment skill and were uncorrelated with the market index. This was the holy grail, the elixir that endowment consultants called alpha."

### Hidden Vulnerability in Event-Driven Strategies

- Even stars like **Farallon had vulnerabilities few suspected**
- Event-driven returns partly reflected **willingness to buy illiquid investments**—if busted junk bonds have value, it's because most investors are frightened to buy them
- **Illiquid assets are hard to exit**: If you buy a bank in Indonesia or make a mistake, you can't get out easily
- In liquid markets, prices are efficient and second-guessing is hard; **in illiquid markets, bargains exist but mistakes are costly**

## Farallon's Indonesia Adventure (2001-2006)

### The Bank Central Asia Opportunity

- By late 1990s, Farallon operated from fashionable San Francisco office, expanding globally
- 1998: Launched **merger-arb operation in London**, rivaling Och-Ziff and Perry Capital
- Bought stake in **Alpargatas** (Argentine textile/shoe maker), restructured debt, rehired 2,000 workers
- November 2001: **Farallon set out to buy Bank Central Asia (BCA)**, Indonesia's biggest bank

### Liem Sioe Liong's Crony Empire

- **Liem Sioe Liong** had been Indonesia's richest man, close friend of dictator **Suharto**
- Liem's empire accounted for **5% of Indonesia's output**
- **Flour business model**: Government sold him imported wheat at subsidized price, then bought it back from his mills at markup—controlled 90% of instant-noodles market (via **Indofood**)
- Prospered in coffee, sugar, rubber, cement, rice, cloves through similar arrangements
- **BCA** was the nation's largest bank, embodiment of Indonesia's **crony capitalism**

### Post-Suharto Collapse and Farallon's Entry

- 1997 currency crisis triggered **slow-motion revolution**: Suharto government fell, Liem's political protection collapsed
- Rioters smashed Liem's property; businesses went bust as loans from BCA failed
- Government rescued BCA to stem depositors' panic
- **Farallon saw opportunity**: Government desperate to sell, limited competition (most financiers scared off), **IMF pressuring Indonesia** to offload assets cheaply

### Andrew Spokes's Analysis

- **Andrew Spokes** (recruited from Goldman Sachs Hong Kong) led due diligence
- Initially cautious: **"We were a little off piste"**—sounded like James Bond skiing avalanche in tuxedo
- Post-9/11 fears: Indonesia vulnerable to Islamist extremism; even **CalPERS and Goldman tightened limits** on Indonesian exposure
- Ray Zage (Farallon's Indonesia point man) viewed airport customs-to-taxi stretch as "natural kill zone"

> "I remember Ray observing it would be great not to be mowed down there," Spokes recalled matter-of-factly.

### Value Over Panic: The Investment Case

- Spokes focused on **cash flows, not chatter**: When market prices cease to guide, decide based on fundamentals
- **Three key facts** made BCA attractive:
  1. Since nationalization, rotten loans to Liem enterprises replaced with **recapitalization bonds**—BCA depended on government repayments, functioning more like **government bond fund** than bank
  2. BCA had **cheap capital from retail depositors** (bargain-basement leverage)
  3. **Free option on Indonesia's recovery**: If economy picked up, BCA could make profitable loans again
- **Political risk mispriced**: Post-Suharto leadership couldn't afford to cheat foreign investor in high-profile deal—reputation would be "mud indefinitely"

### Winning the Bid

- Late 2001: Farallon submitted **$531 million offer**
- Competed against consortium led by **Standard Chartered**
- March 2002: **Government announced Farallon won**—hedge fund from "latte land" bought control of top bank in world's largest Muslim country
- Conspiracy theories blossomed: Was Farallon a front for U.S. government? Trojan horse for Liem revival?

### Results: Blessing for Indonesia

- Farallon installed new chairman, brought consultants, coaxed bank out of Suharto era
- By 2006 exit to Indonesian partner: **BCA share price up 550%**
- Like Argentine shoe company, **Farallon showed it could do well by doing good** in tough country
- **Market psychology shifted**: Swashbuckling hedge fund dashing into Indonesia turned heads in New York/London
- Year before BCA purchase: **$286 million** net portfolio investment into Indonesia
- Year after: **$1 billion** came in; year after that: **$4 billion**
- **Event-driven fund created an event**, helping turn economic tide for 240 million people

## Farallon's Colorado Water Debacle (1994-2004)

### Gary Boyce's Water Scheme

- **Gary Boyce**: Colorado rancher, flamboyant horse trainer, dreamer about childhood valley wealth
- Plan: Buy land in **San Luis Valley**, pump water from aquifer beneath to supply Boulder, Colorado Springs, Denver
- Farallon's **Yale endowment partnership** made it alert to "real assets" like water—Steyer invested

### The San Luis Valley Reality

- Southern Colorado valleys as remote as Jakarta's alleys
- Four-hour drive from Denver to Alamosa (True Grits Steakhouse, Trop Arctic Lube Center, Tecate/Bud Light posters)
- Boyce's ranch house: adobe with hollow walls, mother-of-pearl shirt studs, ornate pistols on desk
- **Boyce credentials**: Grew up poor in valley, three-time Colorado dirt-biking champion, veteran of **water politics** (founded newspaper *Needle* to fight earlier developer), trained horses for wealthy Virginians, married MGM heiress

### The Political Battle

- 1994: Boyce bought ranch with Farallon/Yale backing, outbidding **Nature Conservancy**
- $3 million environmental study; lobbying in Colorado legislature
- Boyce collected signatures for **two referenda**: consumption meters on wells, user fees for some water types (to establish fair price)
- $400,000 on advertisements
- **Farmers revolted**: Outraged at user fees, claimed sandy soils would clog meters
- November 1998: **Boyce's initiatives defeated by large margin**—four years, $20+ million spent, project failed

### Legal Quagmire and Controversy

- Farallon tried exit via Nature Conservancy deal (end of 2001)
- **Boyce blocked exit** by filing suit against Farallon
- Boyce's argument: Water scheme still viable; premature exit damaged his stake value
- Colorado senator **Wayne Allard** accused Yale of profiting at taxpayers' expense (bankrolling Nature Conservancy purchase)
- Demanded Yale lower $31.3 million asking price—**even though Yale was passive investor**
- Allard suggested Farallon misled Yale about environmental costs (referendum failed due to user fees/meters, not environmental flaws)

### The unFarallon Campaign (2004)

- 2004: Farallon won legal battle, concluded Nature Conservancy sale
- Yale donated $1.5 million to subsidize cost to Colorado taxpayers
- **Bizarre protest coalition** emerged: "unFarallon campaign" on college campuses
- Protesters dressed as **crony capitalists**, featured "transparency fairy" in feathered mask at Yale
- **unFarallon website** cited Farallon investments in:
  - Coal-fired power (Indonesia)
  - Workers suffering (Argentina)
  - Tiger salamander habitat (California golf course ponds)
  - **$3 million stake in Halliburton** (Cheney's old firm)
- Activists demanded Farallon's "secretive mastermind" meet to discuss "ethics of investment practices"

> "We are stakeholders in the investments you make with university money. We do not want our universities to profit from investors that harm other communities."

### David Swensen's Defense

- Steyer pleaded he cared about strong business values, noted website was "factually inaccurate"
- April rally at Yale president's office: mock water extraction, broken coal-fired power plant
- **Swensen engaged protesters** after Advisory Committee meeting: tall, wiry figure in fleece vest explaining transparency was impractical
- To compete successfully in markets, **investors must protect proprietary secrets**—needed to be "highest-quality limited partner possible"
- Students unmoved: **"I think it's more important to look at Yale as the highest-quality global citizen"**

### Political Irony

- Students targeted **two least appropriate people**: Swensen (John Kerry backer) and Steyer (Democratic candidate supporter, not Cheney acolyte)
- Swensen missed billionaire chance due to "genetic defect" (turned down wealth for public service)
- **But hedge funds had grown with endowment help—couldn't expect immunity from college politics**

## Lessons: Vulnerability of Event-Driven Bargain Hunting

### The Core Problem with Illiquid Investments

- Colorado episode exposed vulnerability in Farallon and **ambitious bargain-hunting funds generally**
- **Bargains lurk in quirky places**: junk-bond details, postcrisis Indonesia, rancher/farmer feuds in remote Colorado valley
- To invest successfully, **need to understand terrain traps**—young hedge funds sometimes lack manpower to survey adequately
- If Farallon spent more time in San Luis Valley, might have realized **Gary Boyce was unsatisfactory partner**
- In fast-growing fund (doubling assets every 4-5 years), **hard to grow in-house expertise as fast as incoming capital**

### Deeper Vulnerability: Illiquid Asset Valuation

- Event-driven returns **partly reflect willingness to buy illiquid investments**
- Busted junk bonds have value **because most investors are frightened** to buy—if you decide to sell later, assets hard to exit
- Same with Indonesian bank: **mistakes can't be undone easily**
- In ordinary liquid markets: prices fairly efficient, second-guessing hard
- **In illiquid markets**: bargains plenty but **mistakes extremely costly**

### Accounting Quirks Flatter Performance

- Hedge funds buying illiquid assets benefit from **accounting quirk** that can flatter performance
- Hard to know what illiquid asset is worth—**lack continually updated price discovery** from constant trading
- Funds with illiquid assets don't report profits—they **estimate them** (no objective price, must use subjective value)
- In some cases, funds may **exaggerate returns** (game not sustainable)
- Even honest funds **"smooth" results**: estimate illiquid asset value every few weeks; if rises 5% then falls back, recorded simply as flat—**sharp volatility unreported**
- Result: **Risk-adjusted returns look wonderful** because some risk goes unreported

### Crisis Risk: Illiquid Assets Collapse Hardest

- **Biggest danger**: In crisis, illiquid assets collapse hardest
- Moments of panic: investors crave easily sold securities, shun rest ruthlessly
- **Long-Term Capital's apparently diverse portfolio** concealed single bet that world would be stable—when wrong, unrelated positions collapsed simultaneously (many boiled down to **premium for holding illiquid assets**)
- Event-driven funds may be taking concentrated bet on illiquid investments
- **1998**: LTCM paid ultimate price for this risk
- **2008**: Buyers of illiquid assets paid heavily again


<!-- pp. 281-300 -->

## D. E. Shaw's Post-LTCM Recovery and Limits

### D. E. Shaw's LTCM Losses
- **D. E. Shaw** suffered losses in bond-market turbulence during **Long-Term Capital Management's** 1998 collapse
- Firm sold part of trading book at a loss that wiped out all gains from that year's other strategies
- Shaw learned dangers of highly leveraged fixed-income strategies in liquidity crunches
- Abandoned bond arbitrage temporarily, though returned to it by 2002

### Paul Tudor Jones and Quantitative Trading at Tudor

#### Early Computer Trading Systems
- **Paul Tudor Jones**, rock-and-roll trader and **Robin Hood** founder, invested profits in computer-trading project
- Early systems had names like **Madonna** and **Material Girl** — statistically crude, less exciting results
- By early 1990s Jones matured: married, settled in Greenwich, company became more institutional
- Hired **James Pallotta** (Boston stock picker) and **Mark Heffernan** (ex-Goldman trader, "greatest discretionary trader in Goldman Sachs empire")

#### Sushil Wadhwani Arrives (1995)
- **Sushil Wadhwani** joined Tudor from Goldman Sachs in 1995
- Economist and market creature: taught at **London School of Economics**, served on **Bank of England** monetary policy committee
- At Goldman, worked as investment strategist advising proprietary traders and external clients including Paul Tudor Jones
- Learned limits of pure economic thinking by rubbing shoulders with real traders

> "Contrary to what a team of modern-portfolio theorists might imagine, identifying an illogical price anomaly was only the start of a trader's thought process; the next step was to identify a trigger—a reason why the anomaly might correct."

- Triggers: upcoming election, psychological tipping point in charts, institutional investor behavior changes
- Wadhwani's mission: build machine that mimicked discretionary traders' eclectic thinking

#### Building the Trading Model
- Created naive model combining economic indicators, institutional cash positioning, options market signals
- Watched Jones and Heffernan trading, probed them on reasons for their moves
- Refined model by observing how they combined familiar factors in different ways
- Position sizing: calculated "z score" — higher confidence of winning = larger bet
- Model needed flexibility in *type* of trades, not just sizing
- In turbulence, weight sentiment measures (options market) more heavily
- In recession, negative data points have larger impact than in good times
- Needed multiple programs: LTCM-style arbitrage for stable times, trend-following for unstable times
- Ideal: devise ways to shift between strategies automatically

#### Wadhwani's Departure and Legacy
- Left Tudor for Bank of England in 1999 before fully building vision
- First version: **Techno-Fundamentals**, trend-following system, ran successfully from late 1997
- Returned to task at **Wadhwani Asset Management** (London, 2002)
- Tudor's program trading continued developing
- By 2008: more than fifty people working on computerized trading, algorithms driving $3+ billion of Tudor's $17 billion capital
- Rock-and-roller with Bruce Willis sneakers accomplished major transformation

### Limits of Tudor's Achievement
- Systems not as original as those developed by **James Simons's** team at **Renaissance Technologies**
- Tudor's system built by economist from Goldman based partly on instincts from Goldman trader
- Revealed institutional problem: No matter how brilliant Wadhwani and Heffernan, they came from financial establishment where others likely developed similar strategies
- Handful of prized experts moved among handful of firms — each move reduced odds any firm would build truly unique system

### Jim Simons Takes Different Path
- Hired established scientists and mathematicians, not young quants Shaw favored
- Not Wall Street veterans
- Limited cross-fertilization with rivals by locating in **Long Island**, away from New York/Greenwich/London hedge-fund centers
- No use for ideas from academic finance
- Faculty in **East Setauket** initially read academic finance journals weekly, then abandoned as fruitless
- Renaissance researchers built systems in a class of their own

> "I can only look at them and realize that you have the gods of the business and then you have mere mortals like me," — Wadhwani

## Renaissance Technologies: Peter Brown and Robert Mercer

### 1993: Brown and Mercer Join
- Came from **IBM's research center**, drove much of **Medallion Fund** success over next years
- Eventually took reins when Simons retired

#### Contrasting Personalities
- **Peter Brown**: magnesium flare of energy — slept five hours/night, riffed passionately on topics, rode unicycle around office
- **Robert Mercer**: icy cold poker player, never recalled having nightmare, IBM boss jokingly called him automaton
- Before Renaissance, worked on cryptography (their real achievement)
- Upended related field: computerized translation

### Computerized Translation Breakthrough

#### Traditional Approach vs. Brown-Mercer Method
- Traditional programmers spoke foreign languages, understood grammar/syntax from inside
- Taught computers like teaching schoolchildren: "la fille" = "the girl", "les filles" = plural
- **Brown and Mercer**: didn't speak French, wouldn't wade into syntax/grammar
- Got **Canada's parliamentary records** (thousands of pages of paired French/English passages)
- Fed material into IBM workstation, told it to figure out correlations

#### Pattern Recognition Process
- Scrubbed data for "bad tics" (like $16 instead of $61 in financial data)
- Canadian Hansard contained misprinted words that might confuse translation program
- Computer searched for patterns: English word equally likely translatable into any of 58,000 French words initially
- Once checked through twinned passages, most English words appeared in only some: nearly 99% uncertainty eliminated
- Series of subtle tests: English word most likely corresponds to French word in same sentence position
- Couplings emerged: *lait*/milk *and* *pourquoi*/why
- Other correlations softer — multiple algorithms needed, combing data repeatedly

> "Only in this way can one hope to hear the quiet call of *marqué d'un asterisque*/starred or the whisper of *qui s'est fait bousculer*/embattled."

#### Reception and Impact
- **Institute for Defense Analyses** code crackers wouldn't find method surprising
- Brown and Mercer used "expectations maximization algorithm" invented by **Leonard Baum** (same Baum who worked for IDA then Simons)
- "Statistical machine translation" natural to code breakers, greeted with outrage by traditional translation programmers
- Reviewer scolded: "crude force of computers is not science"
- At translation experts meeting: "We were all flabbergasted.... People were shaking their heads and spurting grunts of disbelief or even of hostility"
- "Where's the linguistic intuition?" — "Yes that's the point; there isn't any"
- **Fred Jelinek** (IBM manager overseeing Brown and Mercer): "Every time I fire a linguist, my system's performance improves"

### Brown-Mercer Join Renaissance (1993)
- Once IBM program figured out Canadian Hansard, could translate other material
- Presented with French newspaper article, zipped through database matching phrases with decoded material
- Results outclassed competing translation systems by wide margin
- Within years, statistical machine translation celebrated as intellectual revolution
- Canadian political rhetoric proved more useful than suspected — lesson about artificial intelligence

### Lesson About Computers vs. Humans
- Early translation programs tried teaching computers vocabulary/grammar (how people learn)
- Computers better suited to different approach: learn to translate English/French without paying attention to rules
- Don't need to understand verb declensions or adjectival inflections before approaching political speeches
- Prefer to get speeches first, penetrate code algorithmically
- No trouble committing millions of sentences to memory
- Learn languages in chunks without grammatical rules crutch
- Example: remember English translations for "la fille est intelligente, les filles sont intelligentes" and dozen variations
- Don't necessarily need to understand "fille" is singular form of "filles", "est" and "sont" different verb forms

> "Contrary to the harrumphing of the IBM team's critics, the crude force of a computer's memory can actually substitute for human notions of intelligence and science. And computers are likely to work best when they don't attempt to reach results in the way that humans would do."

### Implications for Medallion Fund
- Reasons for fund's spectacular success are secret
- Clear that Brown and Mercer's programming approach fundamentally different from other hedge-fund programmers
- **Tudor**: Wadhwani trained machine to approach markets in manner making sense for human traders
- **Brown and Mercer**: trained themselves to approach problems in manner making sense for computer
- **D. E. Shaw**: frequently start with market theories, test against data
- **Brown-Mercer**: fed data into computer first, let it come up with answers
- Shaw's approach recalls programmers who taught computers French grammar
- Brown-Mercer approach resembles code crackers without option of starting with grammar book
- Presented with apparently random data and no clues, sift repeatedly for patterns, exploiting computer power to hunt ghosts invisible to human eye

### Renaissance's Quantitative Rivals and Ghost Hunting

#### Danger of False Patterns
- Computer may find fake ghosts — patterns existing by chance with no predictive value
- **Eric Wepsic** (statistical arbitrage at D. E. Shaw) example: **Super Bowl**
- Used to be said: if original National Football League team won, market would head upward
- As statistics, relationship might hold; as common sense, meaningless coincidence
- Dangerous to trade on statistical evidence unless intuitively explained

#### D. E. Shaw's Approach to Correlations
- 1990s: systems detected curious correlations between previously unrelated stocks
- Cable companies, media companies, consumer electronics firms all responding to strange new force field
- Evidence alone would suggest dismissing as statistical fluke
- Once realized correlations reflected intuitive sense (technology euphoria pushed into all these industries), seemed more tradable
- Signals based on intuition have further advantage: understanding why they work helps know when they might cease, less likely to keep trading beyond usefulness

> "Wepsic is saying that pure pattern recognition is a small part of what Shaw does, even if the firm does some of it."

### Renaissance vs. D. E. Shaw: Different Roots
- **D. E. Shaw**: grew from statistical arbitrage in equities, strong roots in fundamental intuitions about stocks
- **Renaissance**: grew from technical trading in commodities, tradition treating price data as paramount
- Shaw hired quants of all varieties, usually in twenties
- Crucial early Renaissance years shaped by established cryptographers and translation programmers — experts distinguishing fake ghosts from real ones
- **Robert Mercer** echoes Wepsic's wariness about false correlations:

> "If somebody came with a theory about how the phases of Venus influence markets, we would want a lot of evidence.... But we add that 'some signals that make no intuitive sense do indeed work.' Indeed, it is the nonintuitive signals that often prove the most lucrative for Renaissance."

> "The signals that we have been trading without interruption for fifteen years make no sense.... Otherwise someone else would have found them."

## Renaissance Campus Culture

### Physical Environment (Late 2000s)
- Outgrown rented premises in **Long Island High Technology Incubator** building
- Moved to campus with gym, lighted tennis courts, pond with bulbous gold-fish, big skylight in entrance hall splashing sun onto slate staircase
- Felt like upmarket science facility — comfortable, low-key, eerily clean
- Office door article: "Why Most Published Research Findings Are False"
- Windowless rooms housed racks of computer servers with elaborate key systems
- Most striking feature: **openness**
- Other quantitative hedge funds enforced fierce internal Chinese walls, doling information on need-to-know basis
- Renaissance atmosphere altogether different
- Scientists roamed corridors freely, constrained only by danger Peter Brown would crash into them on unicycle
- Mirrors positioned at critical corners so you could see if Brown was coming

### Open Collaboration Philosophy
- Simons believed passionately in open atmosphere
- Like **Institute for Defense Analyses**: closed to outsiders to protect secrets, open inside to promote teamwork

#### The Big Meeting (Tuesday Mornings)
- Entire faculty of ninety+ PhDs gathered
- Every refinement to **Medallion's** trading program began with presentation
- Researcher explained idea, showed simulations of how it would blend with other signals already in system, answered questions
- Colleague might ask how proposed signal would have fared during LTCM crisis
- Another might wonder performance during low volatility period
- After Big Meeting, scientists free to wander into proponent's room, ask follow-up questions
- Peer-review period ended with **Small Meeting**: only scientists with remaining questions showed up
- **Brown and Mercer** decided whether to give green light
- Final check: **Henry Laufer**, veteran ghost hunter from 1980s, retained title of chief scientist and veto right

#### Compensation System Reinforcing Teamwork
- Researchers' pay tied to profits of entire firm, not narrow results of subunit
- Collaboration written into firm's technology infrastructure
- At IBM, Brown and Mercer created system allowing multiple programmers to work simultaneously
- Repeated trick at Renaissance: researcher could adapt in-house programming language to express new idea
- In computing as in everyday speech, neologisms useful
- Into collaborative architecture, faculty fed reams of data modern society generates
- More finance went global, more statistics from foreign markets fed into system
- More business went digital, more new data available — e-commerce sales, Web-surfing habits, etc.
- Computerization of finance created vast information windfall
- Old days: possible to track stock price trade by trade
- Now: possible to see each bid and offer for each stock — including those never consummated
- More possibilities expanded, more they exceeded reach of few minds
- Collaborative faculty at Renaissance could manage complexity and thrive on it

### The Russian Defection Crisis (2003)

#### Employee Loyalty System
- Culture of teamwork involved risk: presumed no team member would leave with trading secrets to set up rival
- Like "The Firm" in John Grisham's novel, Renaissance thought carefully about employee loyalty
- Instructed job applicants: if they joined, could never work elsewhere in financial industry
- Generally didn't hire from Wall Street partly because anyone who left one team of traders might later leave second
- Enforce noncompete and nondisclosure agreements: researchers required to invest 1/5 of pay in **Medallion Fund**
- Money locked up as bail payment for four years after departure
- Helped that firm based in quaint **East Setauket**, miles from competitors
- Once researcher installed kids in local schools, didn't want to go anywhere

#### Recruiting Soviet Prodigies
- In drive to hire best brains, Renaissance discovered achievement of old Soviet Union
- Country recruited brightest kids from fifteen republics, transported to **Institute of Physics and Technology in Moscow**
- Separated from families, underwent intensive training
- Prodigies who survived this assault course found themselves internationally marketable after Soviet system disintegrated
- Renaissance recruited one Russian, he recommended another
- Soon sizable Russian caucus in East Setauket faculty

#### Behavioral Consequences
- Leaders never paused to ponder behavioral consequences of Soviet upbringing
- Kids raised in failing political system likely to assume authority is corrupt
- Person's only obligation: look out for himself
- Kids separated from parents more likely to mature as hardened individualists
- After spending long enough on Renaissance faculty to master secrets, two Russian researchers presented Simons with ultimatum
- Refused to sign firm's noncompete agreement, demanded higher pay
- If Simons refused, would quit and join rival

#### The Threat
- Simons refused to be blackmailed, Russians left to join another hedge fund
- Looked like catastrophic blow on face of it
- Because of open structure at Renaissance, Russians understood a lot about how system worked
- If started trading on Renaissance's signals, would siphon off part of its profits
- Like pirates making generic copies of pharmaceutical company's blockbuster therapy
- Patents don't protect financial innovations like medical ones
- Simons's legal remedies uncertain

#### Medallion Survives
- Remarkable thing: **Medallion's** performance continued leaving rivals in dust
- Like magician who drinks poison and survives, Simons emerged looking more mysterious than ever

#### How Survival Was Possible
- Part of answer may lie with Renaissance's lawyers
- Suing Russians and new employer may have deterred them from rolling out rival system at full speed
- 2006 settlement laid down Russians would cease trading
- But lawyers not whole answer: Russians operated rival system for 2-3 years
- During those years Medallion did extremely well — profits probably higher still without alleged intellectual property theft
- Lesson: infrastructure of Renaissance as important as its research
- Research itself advances constantly
- Takes enormous time and money to set up systems absorbing trillion bytes of data daily
- Make data accessible and malleable to researchers
- Turn research findings into hundreds of thousands of automated trades going off without glitch in markets from Spain to Singapore
- While Russians struggling to create halfway comparable platform, faculty at Renaissance moving on
- Each Tuesday in East Setauket brought another Big Meeting, another set of fresh ideas
- Russians running to catch up with fast moving target

## Impact on Hedge-Fund Industry

### Medallion as Formula One Race Car
- Like Formula One race car auto firm might build
- Most customers never got chance to climb inside
- Existence of mouth-watering machine encouraged them to buy ordinary vehicles
- Fund trading short-term signals cannot afford to get too large (liquidity and time constraints prevent putting too much on each trade)
- Medallion closed to new outside investors in 1993
- By 2000s Medallion or so in fund consisted almost entirely of employees' money
- Very existence of Medallion had halo effect on rest of industry, offsetting blow to reputation of black-box trading from Long-Term Capital collapse

### Institutional Money Flows into Quantitative Trading
- Each time Simons's picture appeared on financial magazine cover, more eager institutional money flooded into quantitative trading systems
- Simons capitalized on phenomenon
- 2005: launched **Renaissance Institutional Equities Fund**
- Designed to absorb eye-popping $100 billion in institutional savings
- Only way huge amount manageable: branch from short-term trading into more liquid longer-term strategies
- Pure pattern recognition works best for short-term trades
- Followed that Simons offering fund relying on different sorts of signal — ones already mined by D. E. Shaw and other rivals
- By summer 2007, new Simons venture raked in more than $25 billion
- Making it one of largest hedge funds in world
- Then financial crisis hit — like almost everybody else, Simons felt consequences

*OceanofPDF.com*

## Chapter 14: Premonitions of a Crisis

### The Alpha Factory Era

#### Industry Transformation by Mid-2000s
- Scale and persistence of hedge funds' success transforming industry structure
- First generation seen as freakish geniuses with possibly lucky, certainly not reproducible returns
- By 2005: more than 8,000 hedge funds sprouted
- Long track records of established funds made hard to dismiss enviable returns as good fortune
- Old talk of luck and genius faded
- New lingo took place: at conferences Phoenix to Monaco, consultants/gurus held forth about scientific product called **alpha**
- Alpha could be explained: strategies like merger arbitrage or D. E. Shaw's statistical arbitrage delivered uncorrelated, market-beating profits in understandable, replicable, manufacturable way
- Era of manufacturer arrived — innovation and inspiration gave way to new alpha factory

#### Long/Short Equity Stock Picking
- By early 2000s, no longer much doubt long/short equity stock picking (as practiced by **Julian Robertson's Tiger**) could deliver market-beating returns
- Challenge: implement successfully
- Dozens of Tiger look-alikes sprang up, many run by men who worked for Tiger
- Eager industry of hedge-fund consultants and funds of funds emerged to allocate capital to most promising

#### Robertson's Tiger Seeds
- Biggest sponsor of Robertson clones: Robertson himself
- After shuttering Tiger in 2000, turned offices into incubator for "Tiger seeds"
- Managed his money, benefited from coaching, used prestige of association to raise more capital from outsiders
- Under old Tiger model, Robertson maintained personal control of investment calls
- Now let protégés run their own shows — switched from inventing investment technique to franchising it
- Switch provided lucrative final chapter to illustrious career
- By 2006 reinvented Tiger complex managing $16 billion
- Premises on Park Avenue grew bigger than ever

### Multistrategy Hedge Funds

#### The New Factory Mindset
- Purest expression: **multistrategy hedge fund**
- Rather than claiming edge in particular investment style, began from principle you could develop edge in whatever style you liked
- Just had to hire the people
- Like pharmaceutical giant vacuuming up ideas from university researchers and biotech start-ups
- Multistrategy factories collected multiple alpha-generating strategies under one roof
- Blended together to diversify away risk
- Shifted capital among various styles according to market conditions
- Factories talked little about invention, lot about process
- Viewed hedge funds less as vehicles for financial creativity than as financial products

#### Citadel Example
- **Chicago-based Citadel** emerged as prime exponent
- Goal: "to see if we can turn the investment process into widget making"
- **Ken Griffin**, Citadel's thirtysomething boss, keen consumer of management texts
- Staff sneaked glances at tomes on desk so they could brace themselves for next six-step plan
- Pushed people out of company with mechanical determination
- Liked comparing hedge funds to buses: People get on, people get off, bus keeps rolling forward

#### Growth of Multistrategy Funds
- Grew from babies to behemoths in blink of eye
- **Citadel**: Griffin started trading convertible bonds from Harvard dorm room
- Start of 2000 still just-me-one: running about $2 billion
- Age of manufacturer arrived, Citadel took off
- Assets swelled to $13 billion by 2007
- Could charge clients almost anything: expenses amounting to more than 5% of capital before 20% performance fee
- Griffin's personal earnings said to be second-highest in industry (just behind James Simons)
- Let it be known Citadel would one day compete with Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley

#### Other Examples
- **Eton Park Capital Management** (launched 2004 by ex-Goldman merger arbitrageur **Eric Mindich**)
- Another example of multistrategy growth
- Mindich raised $3 billion in assets before even opening doors
- Four years on, managing $11 billion
- During 1990s, all top hedge funds struggled with burden of bigness
- Many returned capital to investors
- By 2007 alpha factories managing $5 billion+ accounted for 60% of assets in industry
- Magazine published list of hedge funds in "Billion-Dollar Club" — if not on list, you were nobody

#### Logic and Implementation
- Powerful logic to rush to bigness
- Small companies may excel at generating ideas, big companies excel at implementation
- Once hedge-fund industry progressed through garage-workshop phase, took sleek professional outfits to bring inventions to market
- Successful alpha factories boasted state-of-the-art computers executing lightning trades
- Legal departments understanding rules in multiple countries
- Treasury departments negotiating best terms from brokers
- Marketing departments churning out glossy monthly reports to satisfy high-maintenance institutional investors
- Edge lay in efficiency of platforms rather than originality of ideas
- Natural to use platforms to support multiple alpha-generating strategies
- Multiple strategies meant new funds could manage huge amounts of money
- Multistrategy format responded to customer pressure too
- Fund-of-funds industry (collected money from endowments/pension funds, allocated to hedge funds) amassed almost $400 billion in assets by 2005
- Partly by promising to shift capital nimbly among different hedge-fund strategies as market conditions altered
- MBA-minded hedge funds saw it: could cut out middleman
- If endowments looking for product shifting flexibly among strategies, multistrategy hedge funds would build the widget clients wanted

### Warning Signs

#### Too Much Money Too Fast
- For all its logic, sudden growth of alpha factories made wise observers feel uneasy
- Too many people making too much money too fast
- Opportunistic consultants staged workshops on how to open hedge fund
- Book called *Hedge Funds for Dummies* appeared in stores
- Grandees with no known background in asset management (such as **Madeleine Albright**, former secretary of state) jumped into industry
- Frenzy recalled extremes of leveraged-buyout boom in 1980s or dot-com mania in 1990s
- Surely this bubble could not last? Wasn't it bound to end painfully?

### Amaranth: Model Alpha Factory

#### Background and Structure
- Emerged mid-2000s as very model of modern alpha factory
- Founder **Nick Maounis**: convertible-arbitrage specialist by background
- Hired experts in merger arbitrage, long/short equity investing, credit arbitrage, statistical arbitrage
- 2002: following collapse of corrupt energy company **Enron**, snapped up several stranded employees to open energy-trading operation
- Made standard arguments for mission creep: blend of alpha-generating strategies would diversify away risk
- Amaranth would move capital aggressively among strategies as market conditions shifted

#### Energetic Shape-Shifting
- Fund's energetic shape-shifting was point of pride
- First months after Amaranth's September 2000 launch: nearly half capital focused on merger arbitrage
- Year later: strategy cut to practically zero, more than half of Amaranth's capital focused on convertible arbitrage
- Scroll forward another year: portfolio began shifting into bond trades, then statistical arbitrage and energy
- Seemed no good reason for pension plan to hire fund of funds when could go directly to Amaranth
- Bypassing middleman's fees, particularly since Amaranth's results were excellent
- First three full years of operation: returned 22%, 11%, 17% — this at time when S&P 500 mostly heading downward

#### Hollowness Beneath Appearance
- For all Amaranth's glittering appearance, certain hollowness about it
- Contrary to marketing patter, Maounis had no clear edge in deciding which strategy to shift into
- Upped allocation to investment styles that worked well recently
- Cut back on those that fared poorly
- But no way to identify which strategies would succeed in near future
- Moreover, precisely because alpha had become commodity, dozens of rival factories driving down returns by manufacturing same thing
- Amaranth's shape-shifting less about cleverly timing market cycles than desperately searching for next trick to keep profits from tanking
- Because Maounis allocating capital to specialist traders whose books difficult to understand, his decisions necessarily affected by instinct
- Gut feelings about various traders on team could sway decisions dangerously

### Brian Hunter and Natural Gas

#### Hunter's Background
- Dangers came together in shape of young Canadian named **Brian Hunter**
- Standing 6'5", occasionally donning **Calgary Flames** jersey
- Graduate degree in math
- Imposing physically and intellectually
- Earnest, soft-spoken, unfailingly calm
- From moment landed at Amaranth in 2004, returns from trading natural gas stood out conspicuously

#### The Natural Gas Anomaly
- Spotted anomaly in winter gas prices
- Unlike oil (shipped in tankers), natural gas delivered mainly in pipelines
- Pipeline supply routes cannot easily be changed to fill unexpected local shortages
- Result: gas prices volatile
- Time and again, blast of cold weather caused household heating demand to spike
- Face of rigid supply, prices would leap upward
- Hunter's discovery: options whose value would shoot up in shortage strangely cheap — represented bargain weather insurance
- Loaded up on options, figured classic asymmetrical trade
- Most he could lose was small cost of buying options
- If shock hit market and gas price spiked, could earn many times more than that

#### Alternative Strategy: Futures Spreads
- Another way of cashing in on same insight: buy pair of futures contracts
- Go short summer contract, long winter contract
- Betting narrow spread between two would widen if winter prices leaped upward
- Strategy worked in recent winters
- November 2004 came good again
- Price of natural gas jumped to around 80% above summer low point
- Amaranth cashed in handsomely

#### Spring 2005 Dilemma
- Many of Amaranth's strategies faring poorly
- Convertible arbitrage hit wall, showed no sign of recovering
- Maounis invested heavily in statistical arbitrage, telling colleagues wanted piece of James Simons's action
- Little to show for it
- One star act in Amaranth lineup: Brian Hunter and winter gas
- But in April, Maounis learned Hunter offered $1 million bonus to sign on with rival firm **SAC Capital**
- Feeling back against wall, Maounis took chance
- Rather than lose star player, promoted him
- Hunter became cohead of Amaranth's energy desk, gaining authority to place own trades
- Meanwhile, Maounis pumped up share of firm's capital allocated to energy desk from 2% previous spring to around 30%
- With these two decisions, Maounis effectively bet company on thirty-two-year-old trader who'd been with him barely one year
- In go-go atmosphere of mid-2000s, this was sort of thing that happened

### Hunter's Deutsche Bank Disaster

#### Promotion More Remarkable Given Background
- Hunter came to Amaranth from **Deutsche Bank**, where supervised gas trading
- December 2003: trading group lost $51 million in single week
- Hunter's response: nothing if not brazen
- In suit later brought in New York state court, Hunter ascribed loss to "an unprecedented and unforeseeable run-up in gas prices"
- As though failure to foresee market's behavior rendered him blameless
- Pointed to "well-documented and widely known problems" with Deutsche Bank's trading and risk-management software
- Made it hard to exit losing trades — as though taking excessive risks could be laid at door of Deutsche's managers
- Hunter also argued: even though group registered loss, he himself earned $40 million for bank during 2003
- Therefore deserved bonus
- By February 2004, Deutsche Bank's managers concluded no place for Hunter on their trading team
- This was man whom Amaranth now promoting

### Hurricane Katrina and Rita (2005)

#### Four Months After Promotion
- Maounis had cause to celebrate
- Hunter continued to bet winter gas prices might spike
- Suddenly mother of all weather shocks arrived
- August: **Hurricane Katrina** slammed into Louisiana coastline
- Flooding New Orleans, ravaging gas-production rigs in Gulf of Mexico
- Next month **Hurricane Rita** followed
- Nation's gas supply hit again
- By end of September, natural gas prices hit record
- Effect on Amaranth's returns dramatic
- Having been down 1% in first half of 2005 because of sluggish performance of most strategies
- Amaranth up 21% by end of year
- Average hedge fund mustered return of just 9%
- Hunter and gas trades earned $1.26 billion
- Accounting for just about all of Amaranth's profits
- Hunter reportedly pocketed tenth of that
- Thanks to performance, Amaranth's assets swelled to about $8 billion
- Making it world's thirty-ninth-largest hedge fund
- Annual Christmas mailing, Amaranth sent clients toy gasoline pumps and card quoting **Benjamin Franklin**

> "Energy and persistence alter all things."

- Seldom had one of Founders been taken so out of context

### The Risk Problem (2005-2006)

#### Katrina and Rita as Freak Events
- On any reasonable reckoning, Hurricanes Katrina and Rita constituted freak events
- Whereas Hunter ready to blame unforeseeable extremes for Deutsche Bank losses, happy to take credit when unforeseeable extremes made him hero
- Maounis grew increasingly enamored of young star
- Seemed to view Hunter as convertible arbitrage trader transported to different space
- Generating profits while taking little risk
- No way winter gas would fall below summer gas price
- Potential losses appeared limited
- Amaranth's risk department only reinforced Maounis's conviction
- At one point, member of risk team responsible for natural gas assured Maounis that Hunter was greatest commodity trader he had ever witnessed
- Hunter had no difficulty persuading Maounis to allow him to move family and trading team to native Calgary
- Commuted to Canadian office in Ferrari, though sometimes snowy conditions forced use of Bentley

#### First Months of 2006
- Hunter's successful run continued
- Trades earned profits of roughly $2 billion between January and end of April
- Again driving nearly all of Amaranth's performance
- At time when average multistrategy hedge fund up just 5% since year's start
- Amaranth up roughly six times more
- Maounis began to say that although failed to strike gold in statistical arbitrage, discovered another secret weapon just as potent
- Yet to some savvy observers, Hunter's extraordinary profits cause for alarm
- No way Hunter could be generating this sort of money without taking outlandish risks
- Besides, darker worry
- With rise of new alpha factories, hedge-fund capital devoted to energy trading soared from around $5 billion in 2001 to more than $100 billion in 2006
- Trades were growing crowded
- Thanks to flood of capital, any strategy making sense to energy specialists at hedge funds almost bound to come good as others piled in
- But could also blow up if stampede reversed itself

### Hunter's Massive Position (Early 2006)

#### Extreme Version of Phenomenon
- In case of Brian Hunter, extreme version of phenomenon seemed to be occurring
- Weight of his *own* money might be driving profits
- Amaranth allowed him to ramp up positions in niche market
- By end of February, Hunter held astonishing 70% of natural-gas futures contracts for November 2006 delivery on **New York Mercantile Exchange**
- About 60% of contracts for January 2007
- By means of enormous position, Hunter betting November gas would fall in value and January would rise
- So long as added aggressively to wager, view likely to be self-fulfilling
- After all, not clear strategy was making money because market fundamentals were on his side
- By early 2006, gas output recovered from devastation of hurricanes
- Mild winter weather reducing gas demand
- By April quantity of gas held in storage nearly 40% above previous five-year average
- Under these circumstances, success of Hunter's bet on summer/winter spreads seemed hard to explain
- Except when looked at astonishing growth in positions
- By around end of April, Amaranth owned upward of 100,000 NYMEX contracts
- More than 40% of total outstanding for all months on exchange
- Hunter was momentum trader who traded on his own momentum

#### May 2006: Blackstone's Second Thoughts
- In May 2006, team from private-equity giant **Blackstone** visited Hunter in Calgary
- Blackstone ran one of longest-standing funds of funds
- Had invested $125 million in Amaranth
- Now having second thoughts
- Amaranth might be up whacking 13% in April alone
- But size of Hunter's profits showed taking dangerously large bets in volatile market
- Amaranth's risk control department calculated: because winter gas prices would never fall below summer prices, most Hunter could lose in single month was $300 million
- Tolerable 3% or so of equity
- But Hunter's own trading rendered assessment obsolete
- Spread between summer and winter gas widened from $1.40 in mid-February to $2.20 in late April as Hunter built positions
- Meaning plenty of room for spread to shrink disastrously
- Besides, small size of gas market — and fact main buyer of Hunter's positions was none other than Hunter himself — created liquidity issue
- Hunter would have nobody to sell to if needed to get out of position
- Blackstone informed Amaranth it would withdraw capital at next opportunity
- Penalty fee for short-notice redemptions, but Blackstone happy to pay it

#### Meanwhile, Maounis Reckoning with Reality
- Finally reckoning with fact star trader overreached himself
- Told Hunter to cut back on risk
- Easier said than done
- Nobody wanted to buy Amaranth's contracts
<!-- pp. 301-320 -->

## Chapter 14: Amaranth's Collapse (continued)

### The Final Days

- **Brian Hunter's** massive gas positions became impossible to unwind—by May's end, Amaranth was down over $1 billion, nearly 4x the risk department's estimate
- Hunter tried to reduce positions but couldn't exit without crippling losses—waited for something to bail him out
- Late July 2006: Hurricane rumors allowed Hunter to jack up bets, widening summer/winter spreads and triggering the collapse of **MotherRock**, a rival hedge fund with the opposite bet
- August: **Nick Maounis** gave Wall Street Journal interview praising Hunter's risk management; one veteran compared Maounis's faith to "that of a jilted lover"
- August losses triggered margin calls; predatory rivals began targeting Amaranth's positions

### September 14, 2006: The Breaking Point

- **Thursday, September 14**: Amaranth lost **$560 million in a single day** as spread collapsed
- Evening meeting at Maounis's home: top brass agreed they needed to raise capital immediately to meet margin calls
- Maounis called **Goldman Sachs** to buy the energy portfolio; other officials reached out to banks desperately
- **Saturday morning**: squadrons of investment bankers descended on Amaranth's Greenwich office, parking lot jammed with fancy cars, teams devouring Pop-Tarts in pantry
- Goldman made offer, then **Merrill Lynch** made offer
- Early Monday morning: looked like deal with Goldman was set—Long-Term Capital plotline repeating itself

### J.P. Morgan Torpedoes the Deal

- **J.P. Morgan's** brokerage department had lent Amaranth money to finance gas trades, holding futures contracts as collateral
- With collateral value doubtful, Morgan uncertain of repayment
- Law gave J.P. Morgan right to pursue Amaranth's assets through bankruptcy courts and claw back assets from firms that bought them
- Legal uncertainty made Goldman's deal "unthinkable"—Goldman wanted Morgan to promise not to come after them through bankruptcy courts
- Morgan balked; deal faltered

### Ken Griffin and Citadel Step In

- **Ken Griffin** (boss of **Citadel**, multistrategy fund) working out at home in Chicago when he got email: Amaranth down 50% in a month
- Griffin thought of **Vinny Mattone's** advice during Long-Term Capital: "If you are down by half, you are not going to recover"
- **Charles Winkler** (Amaranth COO, former Citadel employee) called Griffin asking for help—"We need a bridge loan and a couple hundred million to stay in business"
- Griffin began marshaling Citadel's resources to buy the firm's gas book—multiple risks: trade logic, financing, counterparties, computer systems
- **Multistrategy edge**: efficiency of the platform would be tested—could Citadel's systems handle buying a large chunk of the entire gas market?
- Griffin arranged 40 Citadel staffers into groups; sent two lieutenants to Greenwich (looked half the age of investment-banking rivals)

### Citadel's Speed Advantage

- **Tuesday morning**: J.P. Morgan executive called proposing deal—Morgan would waive clawback rights if it could be 50% purchaser of Amaranth's positions
- Griffin accepted; new challenge arose about other creditors
- **Bob Polachek** (one of two Citadel staffers in Greenwich) worked through previous night checking all Amaranth brokerage statements—assured Griffin no undiscovered holes
- **5:30 AM**: sale of Amaranth went forward
- Triumph for Citadel's investors and execution platform—hedge fund stole deal Wall Street had regarded as its own
- J.P. Morgan and Citadel took ownership; portfolio value started recovering as predatory traders cut bets
- Citadel eventually earned **~$1 billion profit** from transaction
- **Griffin's plan to build next Goldman Sachs** had taken significant step forward

### Broader Implications: Hedge Funds in Bubble Territory

- Amaranth's collapse confirmed hedge funds had entered **bubble territory**—grown too fast for available talent
- Under pressure to perform, funds granted inexperienced traders leeway to blow up spectacularly
- **Multistrategy format** made this danger especially acute—veterans like **Stan Druckenmiller** and **Louis Bacon** understood risk because they traded daily and their own savings/reputation were at stake
- New alpha factories structured differently: believed in **delegation**—boss couldn't be expert in every risk
- Once risk decisions delegated down the chain, multistrategy funds contended with mild version of problematic incentives plaguing large banks/brokerages
- Traders want bonuses; bonuses won by betting big; central risk department seldom controls wizards who acquire aura of invincibility
- By time Amaranth folded, **$6 billion of investors' equity** had gone up in smoke—larger than Long-Term Capital incineration

### Calls for Regulation—And Why They Missed the Point

- **Charles Grassley** (Senate Finance Committee chairman) wrote Treasury Secretary **Henry Paulson** demanding to know why hedge funds allowed to operate with secrecy
- Amaranth had disclosed strategies in monthly reports—it was the **lack of secrecy** that made it a target once market turned
- Wall Street Journal survey of private economists found majority favored tougher oversight; popular measure was compulsory registration with **Securities and Exchange Commission**
- Not clear what registration would achieve
- **Result of Amaranth's failure**: American taxpayers suffered no harm; no round-the-clock crisis meeting at NY Fed; no apparent damage to financial system
- Pension funds that lost money were angry, but Amaranth represented tiny share of their assets
- Effect no greater than bad day for S&P 500
- **Market had disciplined Amaranth for its errors while inflicting minimal damage on wider economy**—no regulatory clamp could have done better

> "What Brian is really, really good at is taking controlled and measured risk" —Nick Maounis, Wall Street Journal interview, August 2006

### The New Fear: Hedge Funds as Systemic Risk or Firefighters?

- Since Long-Term Capital's demise, Wall Street worried about next hedge-fund blowup
- Event had taken place; scars barely visible
- Critics continued to worry leveraged monsters could ignite systemic fires—after all, Long-Term Capital had done so
- But **Citadel's lightning purchase** proved another side: hedge funds might occasionally ignite fires, **but they could also be firefighters**

## Chapter 15: Riding the Storm

### Daniel Sadek and the Subprime Machine

- **Daniel Sadek**: born Lebanon 1968, scarred by civil war gunshot wound and flying metal
- Left Lebanon for France, landed in California at 18—gas station attendant, car salesman
- Around 2000, scales fell from eyes selling Mercedes to mortgage-business customers
- Discovered he could get home-loan license without taking classes (would need 1,500 hours to be barber)
- By 2005, **Quick Loan** had 700 employees—one of top 50 **"subprime" lenders** (customers too risky for normal mortgages)
- Marketing: "No income verification. Instant qualification!!" "You can't wait. We won't let you."
- California Department of Corporations recorded complaints including fraud and underwriting errors
- Sadek acquired house on coast, Vegas apartment, necklace, flip-flops, long hair, fast cars, restaurant investments, movie company
- Bankrolled production **Redline**—"action flick loaded with cars, chrome, and silicone"
- During filming/promotion, cast demolished >$2 million of Sadek's sports cars
- "Fear nothing; risk everything," ran movie's tagline

### Kyle Bass Identifies the Bubble

- **Kyle Bass** (hedge-fund manager in Dallas) heard about Sadek's filmmaking—story confirmed Bass's suspicion
- American mortgage market in grips of something truly wild—bubble exceeding anything in hedge-fund industry
- Between 2000–2005, volume of risky subprime loans **quadrupled**
- Growing share flowing to people who could not repay: "Prior bankruptcy. Tax Liens. Foreclosures. Collections and Credit Problems. OK!"
- Another Quick Loan ad suggested firm actively seeking deadbeats
- Sadek's attitude summed up by movie: catapulting Porsche Carrera GTs—"That's the guy you want to bet against"
- Around time Amaranth blowing up, Bass and **Hayman Capital** figured out how Sadek's mortgages were packaged and sold as **mortgage bonds**—shorted large quantity, settled back and waited

### Michael Litt's Epiphany

- **Michael Litt** (cohead of **FrontPoint Partners**, large alpha factory): light went on visiting mortgage desk at **Lehman Brothers**
- New gigantic trading floor; group of traders teasing one of their buddies
- Tailor measuring men for $6,000 suits—guy ordered **only one** (positively wussy to self-respecting mortgage jock)
- Later, on plane from London, Litt read **Bank for International Settlements** report explaining how sophisticated finance suppressed market volatility
- Something wrong: looking out window, could see **Greenland** outline—had once been hospitable to human settlement, then frozen over
- At 40,000 feet suddenly hit him: **Volatility low because world awash with wild money**; abundant liquidity giving false sense of stability due to magical structural improvement
- Investors from Asia to Arabia wiring billions to fund managers in NY, buying every piece of paper Lehman's mortgage desk could sell
- Smart folks at BIS missing the freeze that would follow
- Litt rebalanced **FrontPoint's portfolio** to get ready for shock
- Fall 2006: firm bet against subprime mortgage sector, took bearish stance in several other strategies

### John Paulson: The Unconventional Contrarian

- **John Paulson**: neither tall nor short, handsome nor plain, eager nor standoffish—"Mr. Average"
- Harvard Business School 1980 → management consultancy → **Odyssey Partners** (early hedge fund) → **Bear Stearns** (mergers/acquisitions)
- 1994: launched tiny hedge fund in Park Avenue building incubating several hedge-fund start-ups
- Grew capital from $2 million (inception) → $600 million (2003) → $4 billion (2005)
- Only 7 analysts on staff; amassed personal fortune in quietest way possible
- Loner and contrarian—no doubt of own ability, no need for affirmation
- Specialized in **merger arbitrage** focused on long odds: bet against mergers expected to be consummated (collecting modest premium), or in favor of ones where market might be shocked by surprise bid
- Also made money **calling turns in the cycle**—when economy booming, looked to go short, and vice versa
- **Paolo Pellegrini**: tall, elegant Italian with heavy-framed glasses and perpetually amused twinkle—spent years chasing fruitlessly offbeat ideas; "I'm a romantic type"
- When Pellegrini signed on as Paulson's analyst for financial companies (2004), realized for first time his unconventional style was welcomed

### Capital-Structure Arbitrage

- Paulson's skill lay in **detail of positions**
- **Capital-structure arbitrage** started from fact various bonds issued by company might be treated differently in bankruptcy
- **Senior bonds**: first claim on company's remaining assets, paid back first
- **Junior bonds**: make do with whatever left over
- Long as company healthy, investors didn't focus on this dull legal nuance—senior and junior bonds traded at similar prices
- But if economy weakening, opportunity arose: assess which companies heading for bankruptcy (cyclical industry, too much debt), then short junior bonds that would get hit most if company went down
- Sometimes hedged position by going long senior bonds

### Early 2005: Hunting for the Weakest Spot

- Paulson felt economic cycle getting ready to turn downward
- Bonds bought at discount during previous recession now trading at silly heights
- Financial markets frothy thanks to long period of low interest rates
- Paulson began hunting for **best way to bet against bubble**—wanted to find American capitalism's weakest spot
- Thing that would blow up loudest/fastest if economy slowed even a little
- **Dream target** would combine all standard vulnerabilities: cyclical industry, loaded with too much debt, debt sliced into senior/junior bonds (so Paulson could short junior ones where all risk concentrated)
- Experimented with shorts on car-company bonds (theory: consumers taking out car loans they couldn't afford)
- Shorted insurance company and couple of home lenders
- Risk: car companies, insurers, home lenders all had value as franchises—buildings, brands, customer relationships—so even if collapsed under debt weight, would probably still be worth something
- If Paulson was going to be contrarian, wanted to short something that could be **totally wiped out**
- **Spring 2005**: hit on right target

### Mortgage Securities: The Perfect Short

- Target was **mortgage securities**—combined every imaginable charm for short seller
- Home prices (and therefore mortgages) certainly **cyclical**, even though American public convinced home prices could only go upward
- Home prices built on huge mountains of household debt; moment families hit hard times, unable to make payments
- Division of junior from senior debt: Paulson had never seen anything like feast mortgage industry served up
- Lenders like **Daniel Sadek** generated mortgages sold to Wall Street banks
- Banks turned these into mortgage bonds; other banks bought bonds, rebundled them, sliced resulting **"collateralized debt obligation"** into layers
- Most senior ones rated rock-solid **AAA**; next **AA**; down the line to **BBB** and lower
- Might be 18 tranches in percent increments
- If mortgages in collateralized debt obligation paid back 95%+ of what owed, BBB bonds fine (first 5% losses absorbed by even more junior tranches)
- But once non-payments surpassed 5% hurdle, BBB securities would start suffering losses
- Since BBB tranche only 1% thick, **nonpayment rate of 6% would take whole lot to zero**
- In contrast to auto-company bonds, no franchise value to worry about—**pile of loans with zero payout is worth, simply, zero**

### April 2005: Paulson's First Bet

- **April 2005**: Paulson placed first bet against mortgage securities
- Bought **credit default swap** (insurance policy on bond's default) on **$100 million worth of BBB-rated subprime debt**
- Huge asymmetry in risk/reward: paid **$1.4 million for year's worth of insurance**; if securities wiped out, stood to pocket full $100 million
- Question was whether odds of default were good
- Can get juicy payout betting on single number in roulette, but that's because chances of winning are abysmal
- To figure out odds, Paulson turned to **Paolo Pellegrini**, the offbeat Italian

### Pellegrini's Research: Zero Would Mean Zero

- Armed with **$2 million research budget**, Pellegrini bought largest mortgage database in country, hired outside firm to warehouse numbers, brought in extra analysts to figure out past behavior of default rates
- **First discovery not encouraging**: Pellegrini and Paulson begun by thinking families with unpayable mortgages bound to default
- But Pellegrini saw catch: **so long as house prices continued heading up, homeowners would be bailed out by option of refinancing**
- **Second discovery**: mortgage-industrial complex argued house prices (summer 2005) appreciating at **15% annually**, would never fall across country in synchronized way
- Had never happened before, so bonds backed by bundles of mortgages drawn from different states regarded as relatively riskless
- Because Pellegrini was newcomer to mortgage game, **unburdened by this article of faith**
- Number crunching showed basis was shaky: if adjusted house prices for inflation, there had been national slumps in both 1980s and 1990s
- Every reason to suppose extraordinary run-up of early 2000s would be followed by another downturn
- Moreover, to block option of refinancing, not actually necessary for house prices to fall; if prices merely went flat, home owners would lack collateral to take out new/larger mortgages
- **Pellegrini's analysis**: zero house-price appreciation would eventually lead to **mortgage default rate of at least 7%**, wiping out value of all BBB bonds
- Verdict summed up in phrase: **"Zero would mean zero"**

### Early 2006: Conviction Builds

- By early 2006, Paulson's initial mortgage bets had failed to make money; some investors muttering he had strayed beyond competence
- But more Paulson contemplated Pellegrini's research results, more convinced he had found **opportunity of a lifetime**
- House-price appreciation slowing as Fed's interest rate hikes pushed up cost of mortgages
- Odds of flat house prices had to be at least even: **like betting on red in roulette game**
- But potential reward was **70 or 80 times the stake**—double payout from betting on single roulette number
- Paulson drew up simple table describing what he could do
- If set up fund with $600 million capital, spent 7% taking out insurance on BBB mortgage bonds:
  - Worst case: loss of **$42 million**
  - Mild default rate (30%): fund would gain **341%**, or **$2 billion**
  - Default rate of 50%: gain **568%**, or **$3.4 billion**
  - Default rate of 80% (Paulson considered highly likely): fund would gain **909%**—astonishing **$5.5 billion**
- When Paulson explained this to investors, few thought he had gone crazy (909%? When did that ever happen?)
- But Paulson not deterred
- **Summer 2006**: set up new hedge fund to do exactly what table said, seeding partly with own money, enlisting Pellegrini as comanager

### July 2006: Wall Street Creates the ABX Index

- Challenge was how to do trades in size Paulson now wanted
- Could bet against mortgage bonds by borrowing and selling them short (cumbersome operation)
- Or buy insurance policy (credit default swap from bank)—but depended upon finding bank interested in selling
- **Great good fortune, July 2006**: Wall Street's top investment banks created easier option
- Hoping to earn stream of trading commissions, launched **subprime mortgage index** (ABX)
- Paulson now found that, on any given day, easy to buy insurance on, say, **$10 million of subprime paper**
- Week or two later, took call from one of big banks—man on line was **ABX trader**
- "What's your picture?" trader demanded—willing to deal with Paulson in size; how many millions' worth of subprime bonds did he want to buy insurance on?
- Paulson considered—didn't want to scare trader off; if guy knew how much insurance Paulson really wanted, surely would not be stupid enough to sell without first moving price against him
- "Five hundred million," Paulson ventured
- "Done," trader responded
- "Another five hundred million," Paulson said
- "Done," man repeated—wasn't flinching in the least
- Then said again, "Tell us your total picture"
- "Call me again tomorrow," Paulson said; next day bought insurance on another **$1 billion of subprime bonds**
- First half of year, hustled to lay hands on $500 million of this stuff
- Now, in just two days, bought **four times that quantity**
- "Tell us your picture," trader said again
- Paulson thought to himself: **this is the holy grail**; remembered **Soros's words**: Go for the jugular
- **"I'll do another three billion," he said**
- At this, silence on line; trader agreed to another billion, then balked at doing any more
- But by calling around other banks, Paulson established positions totaling **$7.2 billion for his credit fund**
- End of 2006: launched second fund with same strategy

### February 7, 2007: The Tide Turns

- Few weeks later, tide turned for Paulson
- Afternoon of **February 7, 2007**: **New Century Financial Corp.** (country's second largest subprime lender) made startling announcement
- Fourth quarter earnings (due out next day) would have to be postponed because firm still calculating losses—shock given expected to report healthy profit
- Turned out **New Century's subprime loans** blowing up still faster than skeptics feared; some borrowers unable to make **first payments**
- Same day, **HSBC** (British bank, third-largest subprime lender in US) announced would set aside **$10.6 billion in loan-loss reserves** because of busted mortgages

### Morning of February 8: $1.25 Billion in One Day

- Following morning, as share prices of New Century and HSBC tumbled, Paulson sitting at desk when head trader informed him **ABX index had slid 5 points**
- Because of massive positions, **1% decline in ABX handed Paulson profit of $250 million**
- In single morning netted **$1.25 billion**—about as much as **Soros** had earned from wager against sterling
- End of that month, when Paulson reported February results, office received phone call from incredulous client
- **"Is this a misprint? It's 6.6 percent, right, not 66 percent?"**
- Results were not a misprint
- Once house prices stopped appreciating, overindebted families began turning in keys—BBB-rated mortgage securities worth practically nothing
- Within months **New Century** had declared bankruptcy; **HSBC** had sacked its US executives
- Every blow to mortgage industry was bonus for Paulson
- Hot day in summer, Paulson in middle of meeting with pair of potential clients when colleague came in and whispered something in ear
- Paulson abruptly excused himself, leaving guests in stuffy conference room
- Returned after few minutes, could not wipe wide smile off face
- Visitors eventually asked if there was somewhere else he needed to be
- Unable to contain himself, Paulson divulged secret
- **"We just got our marks for the day," he blurted out. "We made a billion dollars"**

### Paulson's Success: Policy Errors Exploited

- Paulson's memory of **Soros's injunction to go for the jugular** was more fitting than he realized
- **Subprime bubble was 21st-century version of policy errors earlier hedge funds had exploited**
- **1970s**: incompetent central banks stoked inflation, allowing commodities traders to ride glorious trends
- **1990s**: central banks committed to untenable exchange-rate pegs macro traders attacked gleefully
- **By 2000s**: inflation and unsustainable currency pegs were gone; passing of these follies made way for new one
- Because inflation vanquished, central banks felt free to stimulate economies with **low interest rates**, rendering money cheap and creating conditions for asset bubble
- Because exchange rates now stable, Wall Street emboldened to take other sorts of risk, **leveraging itself up and further adding to bubble**
- Each new era brought fresh kind of blunder, creating fresh opportunity for traders too
- **Heyday of macro hedge funds might be over, but new heyday of credit hedge funds had arrived**
- **John Paulson was the new George Soros**

### The Other Side: Who Was Buying?

- Famous macro trades yielded extraordinary profits because there were **willing suckers on other side**
- In 1992, it was British government
- Paulson's subprime mortgage trade required sucker: could only build vast short positions on mortgages if somebody else was buying them
- Mystery was who these buyers were—and why so eager to throw away money

### When Mortgage Bubble Burst: Hedge Funds vs. Banks

- When mortgage bubble burst in 2007-2008, extraordinary losses cropped up all over financial system
- **Daniel Sadek's** handiwork, millions of other loans that smelled equally putrid, packaged and sold to investors from Japanese insurers to Norwegian pension funds
- Inevitably, some hedge funds caught holding subprime garbage too
- Couple of medium-sized outfits (**Peloton Partners** and **Sailfish Capital**) sank under weight of mortgages
- **Peloton** hardly model of financial prudence: London-based managers became famous when secretary stole **£4.3 million** from accounts without realizing anything might be amiss (told jury at trial bank account felt "one or two million light")
- Still, by any reasonable reckoning, **hedge-fund sector as whole survived bubble extraordinarily well**
- By and large, avoided buying toxic mortgage securities and often made money shorting them
- **2007**: hedge funds specializing in asset-backed securities (category including mortgages) were **up 1% on average** (according to **Hedge Fund Research**, Chicago)
- In other words, **completely dodged the subprime bullet**
- Meanwhile, **hedge funds as whole gained 10% during year**—not bad for crisis

### Who Did Lead the Buying? Banks and Investment Banks

- If hedge funds mostly recognized subprime assets for garbage they were, who did lead buying?
- Answer, to large extent, was **banks and investment banks**—firms such as **Citibank**, **UBS**, and **Merrill Lynch**
- On first inspection, this seems strange—firms proud of trading desks that managed proprietary capital
- Yet, unlike hedge funds, banks and investment banks bought subprime mortgages by bucketful
- **Citibank's losses** so astronomical US government forced to rescue it, buying more than third of shares
- **UBS** ended up needing lifeline from Swiss government
- **Merrill** sold itself to **Bank of America** to avoid going down
- Whereas failure of hedge funds like Peloton and Sailfish (like earlier failure of Amaranth) cost taxpayers nothing, failure of **Citi** and peers imposed enormous burdens on government budgets and world economy

### Four Reasons Banks Fared Worse Than Hedge Funds

#### 1. Capital Requirements Became a Crutch

- **Banks** that take deposits (Citi, UBS) required by regulators to hold **minimum amount of capital** to shore up solvency
- Should have made banks more resilient than hedge funds when mortgage bubble imploded
- But **capital requirements, while necessary, can become crutch**
- Rather than running books in way rigorous analysis suggests will be safe, **banks sometimes run books in way capital requirements deem to be safe, even when it isn't**
- **Subprime mortgages** presented classic example
- Bonds backed by toxic mortgages given top **(AAA) rating**, partly because rating agencies paid by bond issuers (dulled incentive to be critical)
- Once AAA seal of approval affixed to subprime assets, banks happy to hold them because **capital requirements allowed them to do so without putting aside much capital**
- **Regulation and ratings agencies** thus became **substitute for analysis of real risks** in mortgage bonds
- Because hedge funds in habit of making own risk decisions, **undistracted by regulation and ratings**, frequently fared better

#### 2. Hedge-Fund Incentives vs. Bank Incentives

- **Hedge-fund incentives** not perfect—managers keep 1/5 of profit in good year but don't give back 1/5 of losses in bad year; may be tempted to gamble recklessly
- But **hedge funds have powerful advantage**: managers generally have **own wealth in their funds**, giving strong reason to control risks effectively
- By contrast, **bank proprietary traders** do not risk personal savings in pools of money they manage
- Instead, bank traders often own **company stock**
- But value of that stock driven by variety of different profit centers within bank
- If prop desk loses money, errors will be diluted by other business lines
- **Stock may react marginally or not at all**
- **Effect too weak to change prop traders' incentives**

#### 3. Multiple Profit Centers Distracted Executives

- Third reason banks fared poorly in credit bubble: **those multiple profit centers distracted executives**
- Banks' proprietary trading desks coexisted alongside departments that advised on mergers, underwrote securities, managed clients' funds
- Sometimes **scramble for fees from these advisory businesses blurred banks' investment choices**
- Again, subprime story illustrated this problem
- **Merrill Lynch** said to have sold **$70 billion worth of subprime collateralized debt obligations (CDOs)**, earning fee of **1.25% each time**, or **$875 million**
- Merrill's bosses obsessed about standing in **mortgage league tables**
- Chief executive **Stan O'Neal** prepared to finance home lenders at no profit in order to be first in line to buy their mortgages
- To feed CDO production lines, Merrill and rivals kept plenty of mortgage bonds on hand
- When demand for CDOs collapsed in early 2007, **banks stuck with billions of unsold inventory** they had to take onto balance sheets
- Banks therefore became major investors in mortgages as **unintended by-product of their mortgage-packaging business**
- When scramble for commissions distorts investment choices in this way, **hardly surprising investment choices are horrendous**

#### 4. Hedge-Fund Culture vs. Bank Culture

- Final explanation for banks' fate hinges on **culture**
- **Hedge funds** are **paranoid outfits**, constantly in fear that margin calls from brokers or redemptions from clients could put them out of business
- They **live and die by their investment returns**, so focus on them obsessively
- Generally run by **charismatic founder**, not by committee of executives
- If they see threat to portfolio, can **flip positions aggressively**
- **Banks** are **complacent by comparison**
- Have **multiple streams of revenue** and funding secured
- **Deposit-taking banks** have sticky capital enjoying government guarantee
- **Investment banks** felt (wrongly, as turned out) access to funding from equity and bond markets made them all but impregnable
- **Contrast between hedge-fund paranoia and bank complacency** emerged most clearly in years after Russia's default and Long-Term Capital crisis in 1998
- For most part, **hedge funds** responded to shock by **locking up investors for longer periods** and negotiating **guarantees from brokers to stabilize their capital**
- Meanwhile, **banks** trended in opposite direction: **buffers of equity capital fell by about 1/3 between mid-1990s and mid-2000s**
- Even in 2006-2007, when mortgage bubble was bursting, **many banks too sluggish to adjust**
- Sold **John Paulson billions of dollars of mortgage insurance via new ABX index**, but did not stop to ask themselves what Paulson's buying might tell them

### Bear Stearns: The Ironic Twist

- Contrast between banks and hedge funds summed up by story of **Bear Stearns**—even though there was twist
- Bear Stearns had reputation as **vigilant manager of trading risks**—exactly kind of institution that would not be expected to buy poisonous mortgage securities
- But by mid-2000s, Bear emerged as **number one packager of mortgage-backed securities on Wall Street** (up from third slot in 2000)
- To keep sausage factory going, Bear bought up **subsidiaries that made subprime loans directly to home buyers** (both in US and Britain)
- Inevitably, this expansion **shifted managers' attention**: less focused on what mortgages might be worth than on how to create lots of them
- Meanwhile, in 2003, Bear devised ambitious **"10 in 10" strategy** for asset-management division: revenues and profits from this unit would rise to 10% of Bear's total by year 2010
- Never mind fact Bear's asset-management subsidiary was starting down road from position of insignificance
- Again, this **pursuit of fee income helped seal Bear's fate**
- Bank **hurriedly assigned unqualified executives** to build out asset-management business by launching **internal hedge funds**
- Some of these funds **loaded up on subprime debt**
- Misjudgment set Bear on path that led to collapse following year—and to **Federal Reserve being forced to absorb $29 billion of Bear's toxic securities**

### Bear's Internal Hedge Funds: Product of Bank Culture

- Failure of Bear's internal hedge funds could be seen as evidence of hedge funds' riskiness
- But truth is **Bear funds were product of bank culture, not hedge-fund culture**
- Like other hedge funds launched under umbrella of large banks, Bear funds **managed by people seeded within large firm, not by entrepreneurs who launched independent ventures**
- They **raised capital with help of parent bank's network and brand** (lowered barriers to entry that freestanding hedge funds must reckon with)
- They knew if they failed, **parent bank might bail them out** (softening their vigilance)
- **Investment thesis** of Bear funds underlined their **close ties to mother ship**
- Two funds run by **Ralph Cioffi**, who previously worked on Bear's sales desk, peddling mortgage-backed securities to institutional clients
- His plan for hedge funds: **buy those same mortgage-backed securities and leverage them up by astonishing 35 to 1**
- Sort of risky bet that made sense to **deep-pocketed, fee-hungry parent**—would have been less likely to fly with real hedge fund

### Ralph Cioffi: Not a Hedge-Fund Manager

- **Ralph Cioffi himself** was not sort of figure who could have launched own hedge fund easily
- As salesman, had virtually **no experience in controlling portfolio risk**—indeed, some Bear executives argued he should not be allowed to do so
- **Paul Friedman** (COO of Bear's fixed-income desk): "There were a fair number of skeptics internally who couldn't figure out how this guy—who was bright but had never managed money—was now going to be running money. He knew nothing about risk management, had never written a ticket in his life that wasn't someone else's money"
- Likewise, Cioffi **short on managerial ability**
- In brief stint as supervisor, had performed disappointingly
- Even with Bear smoothing the way, Cioffi had **trouble handling administrative challenge of running hedge fund**
- Failed to secure approval of fund's independent directors before buying securities from other divisions of Bear Stearns
- **Paperwork in such disastrous state** that law firm had to be brought in to investigate
- In complaint that summed up trouble with hedge-fund subsidiaries within banks, investor protested it had put money in Bear's funds because of **parent firm's reputation for managing its own risks** and claimed Bear treated outside clients differently
- Truth was Bear and other banks that jumped onto hedge-fund bandwagon **less intent on risk management than on leveraging their brands**
- If you wanted reason why Bear's internal funds blew up, whereas most regular hedge funds avoided subprime trap, **answer was culture**

<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## The 2007 Credit Crisis Continues

### John Paulson's Triumph and Bear Stearns' Near-Collapse

- **John Paulson** made billions from the mortgage bubble while his former employer **Bear Stearns** teetered on bankruptcy
- Bear's non-hedge-fund internal hedge funds, marketed on the **Bear Stearns brand**, collapsed in June 2007
- Bear felt compelled to rescue them with emergency loans—vindicating the view that deep-pocketed parents reduce vigilance
- **Paulson's flagship mortgage fund** gained 700% cumulative by end of 2007, net of fees
- His firm generated estimated $15 billion in profits; Paulson personally pocketed $3-4 billion—"the man who made too much"
- When Paulson recommended changes to Treasury secretary **Hank Paulson's** bank bailout plan, Congress gave him Soros-level deference
- Rep. **John Tierney** (MA): "I was thinking we probably had the wrong Paulson" in charge

### Ken Griffin and the Sowood Crisis (July 27, 2007)

- **Ken Griffin** of **Citadel** was vacationing in France when the subprime crisis escalated
- Friday, July 27, 2007: subprime troubles morphed into broader credit crisis
- **Sowood Capital Management**, a $3 billion Boston hedge fund, caught fire and faced margin calls
- Sowood had *avoided* subprime securities—boss **Jeffrey Larson** came from Harvard endowment
- Larson had run $3 billion of Harvard's $20 billion endowment, then launched independent multistrategy fund **Sowood** in 2004 (70 employees)
- Early 2007: Larson sensed default rates rising, bought "senior" bonds and shorted riskier paper—a capital-structure arbitrage like Paulson's
- Subprime losses at Bear Stearns seemed like good news, not a threat
- Early July: Larson injected another $5.7 million of personal savings into Sowood

### Sowood's Collapse

- Other leveraged players deleveraging after mortgage losses began dumping nonmortgage positions
- Third week of July: Sowood's corporate bond holdings suffered serious losses
- **High-quality bonds dumped first** when traders deleveraged indiscriminately—capital-structure arbitrage logic collapsed
- Larson sought emergency capital from Harvard; Harvard deemed it too risky
- Friday morning, July 27: news of Sowood's troubles spread, traders positioned for a contagious spiral
- Margin calls forced Sowood to dump corporate bonds in fire sale, hitting other bond funds and driving market down
- Self-fulfilling fears: bonds fell hard that afternoon
- Even after market close, Sowood continued losing money in after-hours trading

### Sunday Rescue: Citadel Buys Sowood's Book

- Sunday lunchtime: **Jeff Larson** called **Ken Griffin**
- Larson recalled how Citadel had bought **Amaranth's** trading book the previous year
- By 7:00 AM Monday, Griffin and team worked through the night and bought Sowood's entire trading book
- Larson told investors: "Citadel offered the only immediate and comprehensive solution"
- Sowood's two funds down 57% and 53% for the month; Harvard's endowment took $350 million hit
- Deal calmed fears of position dumping; bond market recovered 4%+ that day
- One hedge fund imploded, threatening systemic fire; another hedge fund (Citadel) acted as fireman

### Bear Stearns Under Pressure (August 3, 2007)

- August 3: ratings agency announced Bear Stearns' debt might be downgraded—first time a Wall Street firm's health questioned in the crisis
- Bear's stock fell hard; bosses convened conference call to calm investors
- Bear CFO: credit markets behaving "in the most extreme manner" he'd witnessed; "he fucking blew the market up"
- CNBC's **Jim Cramer** hours later: "It is time to get on the Bear Stearns call!" excoriating the Fed—"We have Armageddon"

### The Quant Quake Begins (Mid-July to August 2007)

- Second half of July: computerized equity trading systems stopped performing well, some losing money
- Quants discovered something disturbing: signals themselves no longer working
- Programs betting on momentum in stock prices fizzling
- Programs betting momentum would reverse fizzling
- Programs betting cheap stocks with low P/E ratios would outperform expensive ones fizzling
- **All these bets fizzling at once**
- Someone (or several quants) liquidating holdings after losing money on mortgages, needing to raise cash
- Forced selling drove prices against anyone with comparable portfolio

### Mike Mendelson and AQR (End of July)

- **Mike Mendelson**, ex-Goldman quant, now ran **AQR** (founded 1998)
- AQR managed $10 billion in hedge funds + $28 billion traditional funds
- Founder **Cliff Asness** contributed to academic literature on pricing anomalies
- AQR's losses in late July modest, but Mendelson heard another big quant fund suffered bad loss
- Erring on side of prudence, he trimmed leverage
- Then first days of August: AQR's models started working again
- Whoever liquidating quant positions must have stopped

### Monday, August 6: The Storm Intensifies

- Mendelson at routine meetings, then checked performance on BlackBerry at Subway sandwich shop
- Numbers all red and large: AQR lost **tens of millions** in past three hours
- Mendelson realized quant deleveraging happening on monstrous scale—or several quants bailing at once
- **Leverage mechanics**: if fund has $100 capital supporting $800 positions, 5% loss leaves $60 capital and $760 positions
- Leverage rockets from 8:1 to 12:1 after 5% loss
- Another 5% loss next day drives leverage to infinity and beyond (capital becomes negative)
- **Death spiral**: third 5% setback makes leverage infinite, fund capital negative
- Mendelson sketched hyperbolic curve on notepad showing how leverage could accelerate upward
- Only way to survive: keep leverage on flat, left-hand portion of curve
- If AQR down 5%, might have to sell almost two-fifths of positions to keep leverage stable

### The Quant Meltdown Spreads

- Similar dramas playing out at other quant funds
- Most were **not** like **Jim Simons's Medallion**—trading well-known anomalies, not esoteric secrets
- "There is no E=MC² under the hood" (Asness)
- Even Simons's large institutional fund traded on understood signals; everyone read same academic papers, made same bets (momentum, value)
- Normal times: crowding didn't matter—dozens of ways to measure "value"
- But crowding did cause panic during selloff: one big fund's selling caused losses at others
- Quantitative strategies grown large enough to shove prices around
- Once rival funds started incurring losses, hyperbolic curve logic forced them to sell too
- Monday afternoon: Mendelson saw how bad things could get—not just AQR selling to stabilize leverage, but racing other quants to cut portfolio size

### Tuesday, August 7: Accelerating Losses

- Next day even more brutal than Monday
- AQR's models lost money twice as quickly, firm dumped billions of positions
- Technology made liquidation faster than earlier years; bad news: rivals could liquidate just as quickly
- Every quant firing torpedoes at every other quant; rumors of funds down 10%+ or worse
- At Renaissance campus (Long Island), **Jim Simons** huddled with lieutenants, tweaking model parameters like pilot navigating hurricane
- **Cliff Asness** (AQR founder) blew up in office, smashed computer screens
- **Ken Griffin** called, now with reputation for buying corpses out of car wrecks
- Asness: "I looked up and saw the Valkyries coming and heard the grim reaper's scythe knocking on my door. I did my best to run to the light"

### Policy Makers in Parallel Universe

- Tuesday, August 7: Fed's interest-rate committee warned about inflation risks
- Wednesday: President Bush visited Treasury, said "[I]f the market functions normally, it will lead to a soft landing"
- Thursday: tone from Washington changed—because of carnage in quant funds, but also trouble from Europe
- **BNP Paribas** suspended redemptions from three internal money-market funds, citing "complete evaporation of liquidity"
- Subprime losses scaring markets; **European Central Bank** responded with $131 billion emergency liquidity
- Thursday afternoon: Fed chairman **Ben Bernanke** turned office into makeshift war room, lieutenants dialing in from vacation locations
- Early Friday morning: Fed reversed earlier inflation emphasis, pledging to provide cash "to facilitate the orderly functioning of financial markets"

### Mendelson Sees Light at End of Tunnel

- Greenwich, Tuesday: Mendelson calling brokers and friends—anyone who might know how other leveraged funds positioned
- Business dominated by handful of firms: **Jim Simons's** new fund ($25+ billion institutional money), **Highbridge Capital** (J.P. Morgan subsidiary), **D. E. Shaw**, **Barclays Global Investors**, **Goldman Sachs Asset Management**
- Mendelson wanted to know how much big players cut leverage
- If they got down into flat part of hyperbolic curve, selling pressure would end and storm over
- Working phones all day Tuesday, reached buddy just after midnight
- Guy rushed back from vacation, exhausted, blabbering, at end of tether—about to liquidate whole book
- Mendelson ticked one firm off list, hit phones again next morning

### Thursday Evening: Only One Player Left

- By Thursday evening, Mendelson figured only one big player hadn't cut leverage yet
- Guessed it might be one of Goldman Sachs hedge-fund subsidiaries: **$5 billion Global Equity Opportunities Fund**
- Goldman executives decided fund's positions too big to sell, so leverage rocketed up as bets hammered
- When market opened Friday, one of two things would happen: fund liquidates (hitting other quants for fifth straight day) or gets recapitalized by parent

### Friday Morning: The Turn

- Friday morning: Mendelson couldn't care less about Fed's inflation stance
- Looking at own trading model—within minutes, generating profits
- Performance screamed that Goldman subsidiary rescued, quant liquidations ended
- AQR began to releverage as quickly as possible; more it could catch upswing as money flooded back, more it could make up for past four days
- Following Monday: Goldman Sachs announced publicly it recapitalized Global Equity fund with $3 billion fresh money

### The Quant Quake's Abrupt End

- Quant quake of August 2007 ended as abruptly as it started
- Friday and Monday: great days for models, most quants recouped at least part of losses
- But drama prompted new debate about hedge funds
- Agonizing outlasted market disruption
- Amaranth and Sowood rescued by fellow hedge fund—hard to argue sector destabilizing
- Hedge funds dodged mortgage bullet, suggesting better money managers than banking rivals
- But equity market storm surely a warning: most sophisticated hedge funds lost control of models—"rocket scientists blew up their rockets"

### Critics from Within: Andrew Lo and Richard Bookstaber

- Most persuasive critics came from within hedge-fund establishment
- **Andrew Lo** (MIT professor, ran own hedge fund) published widely cited postmortem on quant quake
- **Richard Bookstaber** (MIT alumnus who worked at several major funds) pressed warnings from recent pessimistic finance book
- Lo and Bookstaber: rise of leveraged hedge funds created new threat
- Trouble in mortgage or credit markets could saddle multistrategy fund with losses, forcing equity liquidation
- Distress could leap from one sector to next; financial system as whole riskier
- Linked warning to gloomy view of hedge funds' investment performance
- Too many quant funds chasing small market anomalies—crowding diminished returns, drove funds to use dangerous leverage to maintain profits

### Was There Truth to the Pessimism?

- Some truth: during LTCM crisis, credit markets in turmoil but quantitative equity funds fine
- Rise of leveraged traders helped explain why fire jumped the fire wall this time
- But one thing to say crowding a problem in moments of turmoil, quite another to assert it forced down returns in good times and made dangerous leverage inevitable
- Lo's paper presented returns from one quant strategy (buy stocks doing badly, sell ones doing well)—profits from this simple contrarian model deteriorated since 1995
- Apparently substantiating case that hedge funds had no choice but to employ more scary leverage
- But basic contrarian strategies not central to quant quake—quants themselves could see limited profits
- Big money in quant funds: other strategies (sell expensive growth stocks with high P/E ratios, buy cheap dowdy ones with low ratios)
- Price gap between growth stocks and value stocks showed little sign of narrowing in years leading up to 2007
- Asness: "We are fond of saying that if these strategies are truly horribly overcrowded, then someone has apparently forgotten to tell the prices"
- Other quants made versions of same point: **Marek Fludzinski** (hedge-fund company **Thales**) tested virtually identical trading strategies to see if presence of one would erode the other's returns—remarkably, it did not
- Suggesting crowding not actually a problem
- True: uncrowded bets could suddenly feel intensely crowded in moment of turmoil
- But held for virtually all trading strategies, not just quantitative ones
- "Of course, 'good investing gets clocked as some investors rush for exits' is not as catchy a story as 'quant brainiacs follow their computers to a well-deserved doom,' so I'm probably not going to win this battle in the media" (Asness)

### Was Systemic Risk Real?

- If quant strategies not as crowded as critics suggested, and scary leverage not inevitable, what of charge that hedge funds increased risk of broad systemic blowups?
- Lo-Bookstaber critique needed qualification
- During first three days of quant quake, signals in traders' models performed abysmally, but broader market remained calm
- Average American household with nest egg in index fund would have noticed nothing
- Undermining notion this was crisis for whole financial system
- Fourth day of quant quake: market did suffer hard fall, but reflected crisis in credit markets more than tremors in quant land
- Great thing about liquidating market-neutral strategies: effect on overall market neutral
- For every stock quants sold, they covered short position
- It was true that if Goldman Sachs had not rescued subsidiary, deleveraging would have lasted longer, potentially forcing multistrategy funds to dump positions in other markets and spreading trouble
- But way things actually turned out: market punished overleveraged traders while broader system suffered little harm
- "This was how capitalism was meant to discipline its children. No regulator could have done better"

### Mike Mendelson's Verdict

- Final analysis: hard to disagree with Mendelson's verdict on quant quake
- "A bunch of us lost a bunch of money and had a really tiring week, which sucked, believe me. But I don't think it was a big public policy issue"

<!-- pp. 341-360 -->

## The Asymmetrical Payout Problem

### The Trader's Calculation vs. The Policymaker's View

- Policy makers focused on whether letting Lehman fail would bring calm or chaos — estimated 50/50 odds
- From a trader's perspective, this calculation was naive: **50% chance of calm meant chaos was virtually certain in practice**
- **Asymmetrical payout**: In calm scenario, markets flat; in chaos scenario, hedge funds make killing by shorting everything
- Rational hedge funds would bet aggressively on collapse, making collapse inevitable

> "You knew Lehman Brothers would be kickoff for a big down move. You knew that." — **Paul Tudor Jones**

- Lehman was the **daisy chain** of interlocking transactions — everyone understood the system was leveraged to its eyes
- The sheer symbolism of Lehman's implosion (survived Depression and world wars) would trigger panic
- **Question mark mentality**: "The optics of that would be so bad that everyone was going to shoot first and ask questions later"

### Sunday's Cascade: Frozen Assets and Legal Panic

- News of Lehman bankruptcy leaked Sunday lunchtime
- American hedge funds belatedly realized Lehman's London operation would declare bankruptcy under **British law** — segregated accounts now frozen
- Hedge-fund lawyers rushed from Hamptons weekend homes, calling outside counsels on speed dial
- Investors called in panic demanding exposure sizes — nobody had clear answers
- **Eric Rosenfeld** (Long-Term Capital partner): "I couldn't believe it. I was shocked. I was almost hyperventilating. How could they do this?"

### Paul Tudor Jones: Perfectly Positioned, Worst Day of His Life

- Monday: S&P 500 fell 4.7% by close — Tudor rode it down perfectly in his trading book
- But Tudor had $100 million frozen in Lehman's London operation (withdrawal request arrived one day late)
- Wrote off entire sum as loss — turned out to be least of his problems

### Tudor's Emerging-Market Disaster

- Tudor made egregious mistake allowing emerging-market credit team to build giant portfolio
- Banks in **Kazakhstan, Russia, Ukrainian dairy farms** — significant portion of flagship BVI fund
- Initial opportunity: loans to emerging markets gave exposure to strong currencies + high interest rates compensating for default risk
- Other hedge funds piled in, driving up currency and loan market, boosting returns
- Once Lehman collapsed, true risks revealed: storied U.S. banks couldn't raise money, banks in Kazakhstan/Russia faced certain trouble
- **Emerging-market portfolio lost ~two-thirds of value**, costing Tudor over $1 billion

### The Illiquidity Trap

- Unlike futures trading (always had "stop" to exit if losses began), emerging-market loans were **utterly illiquid**
- After Lehman bankruptcy, nobody wanted to buy loans at any price

> "I realized that our emerging-market trading book was going to get absolutely hammered and there was nothing I could do about it… That was the worst moment of my whole life." — **Paul Tudor Jones**

- Reflected on 1929 parallel: "I used to always think, 'Holy cow, how'd these guys in 1929 lose it all? How could anybody be so boneheaded?'… I see how these guys in '29 got hurt now. They were not just sitting there long the market. They had things that they couldn't get out of."

### Tudor's Final Reckoning

- Emerging-market losses dwarfed gains from his own trading book
- Up 6-7% for the year before Lehman — ended down 4% by year-end
- Forced to impose "gates" suspending investor withdrawals
- **Paul Jones** promised to narrow Tudor's focus, stick to liquid markets — age of diversified alpha factory perhaps receding

## The End of the Investment-Bank Model

### Lehman's Fatal Structure

- Lehman and rivals borrowed billions in short-term money markets, used it to buy hard-to-sell assets
- When crisis hit, short-term lending dried up instantly
- Everyone could see investment banks might face crunch — fear was self-fulfilling
- Commercial banks have government deposit insurance + Fed emergency lending; **investment banks had no safety net**

### Merrill Lynch: Fire Sale to Bank of America

- Weekend of Lehman's fate, **Merrill Lynch** CEO **John Thain** shuttled between NY Fed and meetings with **Ken Lewis** (Bank of America)
- Negotiations culminated 1:00 A.M. Monday morning: Thain agreed to sell Merrill for $29/share
- Year earlier, Merrill rebuffed Bank of America offer worth $90/share
- With investment-bank model in tatters, willing to deal at massive discount
- One of Wall Street's oldest names collapsing into Main Street commercial bank — "as if Wal-Mart were buying Tiffany's"

### Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs: The Death Watch

- Bear, Lehman, Merrill gone — only **Morgan Stanley** and **Goldman Sachs** remained
- Both relied on short-term funding + extremely high leverage — vulnerable to bank run
- Stock prices permanently at top of CNBC screen in "death watch"
- **AIG** trouble made things worse: by writing **credit default swaps**, AIG sold protection against bond defaults
- Created crazy risk-taking incentive: locate ambitious trading operation inside well-capitalized firm, imbue traders with invulnerability sense
- AIG's credit default swaps lost billions when default likelihood spiked post-Lehman
- Tuesday, September 16: government forced to rescue AIG, lending $85 billion

### Morgan Stanley Rumor Crisis

- Day after AIG rescue, rumors Morgan exposed to AIG mess drove Morgan stock down 42% by midday
- Hedge funds clamored to get assets out, desperate to avoid another Lehman-type trap
- **John Mack** (Morgan CEO) raged against short-selling conspirators — repeat of battles Bear Stearns and Lehman waged against hedge funds

### Ken Griffin's Probability Tree

- **Ken Griffin** (Citadel) calculated odds his hedge fund might fail
- Leveraged capital 10+ to 1 (less aggressive than investment banks' 30-to-1, but well over single-digit normal for hedge funds)
- Issued small quantity of five-year bonds — market for **credit default swaps** on Citadel debt allowed traders to telegraph anxieties about liquidity
- **Griffin's probability tree**: Morgan Stanley 50% survival; if Morgan down, Goldman 95% likely to follow; if Goldman failed, Citadel almost 100% collapse (forced selling by Morgan/Goldman would destroy Citadel's holdings)
- **Citadel's survival odds: ~55%**

> "That's a pretty bad day—when you realize twenty years of your work now comes down to whether or not some firm that you have no influence over fails." — **Ken Griffin**

### The Short-Selling Ban

- Following Lehman's summer path, Morgan and Goldman lobbied regulators to clamp down on short sales
- Awkward demand: Morgan and Goldman were short sellers themselves, built flourishing prime-brokerage business financing hedge fund short sales
- Frenzied Wednesday aftermath: both firms worked phones; by end of day, NY senators **Chuck Schumer** and **Hillary Clinton** calling SEC chairman to demand short-selling ban
- Thursday: **SEC chairman Christopher Cox** expressed doubts but Treasury Secretary **Hank Paulson** insisted: "You have to save them now or they'll be gone while you're still thinking about it"
- ~1:00 P.M.: **Financial Services Authority** (London) announced 30-day ban on short selling of 29 financial firms
- Goldman's trading floor: ~3 dozen traders stood, placed hands over hearts, sang "The Star-Spangled Banner" (playing over loudspeaker)
- That evening: SEC banned short selling of ~800 financial companies

### Impact of the Ban

- Brought Morgan and Goldman brief breathing room but amounted to **frontal government assault on hedge funds' viability**
- Stock-picking funds lost hundreds of millions: "We went from playing chess to rugby at halftime" (Tiger cub complaint)
- Claim ban protected financial system was stretch — included Internet incubators, retailers
- Investment banks not out of woods — immediately resumed lobbying
- During good times, Morgan and Goldman reveled in not being deposit-taking banks subject to Fed oversight
- **Swift U-turn**: demanded to be swept under Fed's purview for guaranteed emergency lending access
- Evening of Sunday, September 21: Morgan and Goldman got wish — Fed extended protection, vulnerability ended

### Citadel's Near-Death Experience

- Classified as hedge fund, Citadel did NOT get same Fed lending access
- Government **kicked it in the teeth** via short-selling ban — cost dearly
- Built giant portfolio of **convertible bonds**, hedged by shorting stocks
- Idea: options embedded in bonds underpriced relative to underlying equity
- Ban made it impossible to hedge new convertible positions — demand for convertible bonds cratered
- Citadel left with shocking losses
- End of September: main funds down 20% for month; as equity base shriveled, leverage ratio went up
- Since 1990 creation, Citadel grown from nothing to $15 billion assets, 1,400 employees — now survival in question

### Griffin's Two-Front War

- If cut leverage by selling convertible holdings, rivals would see desperation and start squeezing portfolio
- If did nothing, would run out of cash and unable to meet margin calls
- Additional danger: if trading partners worried about Citadel survival, would mark down estimated value of derivatives contracts, forcing Citadel to cough up cash until coffers empty
- Like brokers did to **Askin Capital**, **Long-Term Capital**, and every failing institution since

### October Rumors and the Death Spiral

- First weeks of October: Citadel fought two-front war
- Jettisoned assets not part of main strategies, raising capital without telegraphing distress
- Closed derivatives contracts with other firms, replacing with exchange contracts (exchange wouldn't squeeze)
- Where not possible to close derivatives, took comfort in **state-of-the-art back office**
- Unlike many hedge funds, Citadel maintained computer infrastructure, data feeds, financial models to track daily value of every derivative purchased from bank
- Better understood what derivatives worth, harder for counterparts to push marks against it
- Recalling Long-Term Capital's promise to operate without back office ("Salomon without the bullshit"), Citadel staffer joked Long-Term had things upside down — LTCM partners were the bullshit

### Citadel's Key Advantage: Matched Funding

- Unlike investment banks (willing to do lion's share of borrowing on extremely short-term), **Citadel's treasury department** more careful
- Analyzed mix of assets in portfolio, calculating how long would take to sell each kind
- Lined up blend of loans with same mix of maturities
- Idea: only rely on overnight funding to extent had assets that could be sold overnight; harder-to-sell investments backed by harder-to-yank borrowing
- **Citadel's five-year bond issuance** (unusual for hedge fund) part of this focus on borrowing long-term
- Griffin's team also negotiated bank loans locked in for up to a year
- Even crisis not going to push Citadel into death spiral of fire sales — at least in theory

### The Reality: Margin Calls and Rumors

- Hard to feel confident — Citadel planned for crisis but not crisis on this scale
- Nothing could insulate from what was going on around it
- Other hedge funds (less secure financing) faced margin calls forcing convertible bond dumps — selling weight caused Citadel to suffer losses
- Rumors Citadel might go under surfaced at dizzying speed
- Citadel hit with margin calls; Fed calling trading partners asking exposure sizes
- Truth: Fed calling around Wall Street telling banks not to pull loans — whether this saved Citadel or fueled rumor mill debatable
- Some days in October, CNBC parked truck outside Citadel Center — new deathwatch beginning

### Friday, October 24: The Conference Call

- Morning: **Dan Dufresne** (young Griffin lieutenant, head of treasury) set off to catch train to office
- Took call on cell from European bank: "Just so you know, there are rumors that are picking up momentum in Europe that the Fed is in your office in Chicago, organizing a liquidation of your assets"
- Dufresne decided to get cab — not discussing alleged demise on crowded commuter train
- Voice pressed: "I'm hearing from our guys in London that this is happening. Is it? I'm sure it's not, but you need to know that it's picking up speed"
- Dufresne assured contact just another rumor — talked ~10 minutes, got another call (same rumor again)
- By time reached desk at Citadel Center, third and fourth calls
- Colleague **Gerald Beeson** in office early, peppered with questions from European trading desks since 5 A.M.
- Dufresne and Beeson suspected financial journalists gotten hold of rumor, bouncing it off everyone they knew
- Rumor spreading faster than Citadel could douse it

### The Bailout Rumor

- **James Forese** (Citigroup's head of capital markets) placed call to Griffin
- According to rumors Forese hearing, Griffin visiting Fed in Washington looking for bailout
- Credit default swaps on Citadel bonds trading at distressed levels — signaling more trouble than Lehman on eve of bankruptcy
- After dialing Citadel, Forese put on hold for a minute, then Griffin picked up and started talking
- "You're calling me for one of three reasons. One, to see if I'm alive. Two, to see if we have any money…"
- Forese cut him off: "The reason I'm calling is to offer you help. If you need to liquidate portfolios and need someone to discreetly handle that, you know we would do that for you"
- "We're losing a lot of money. But we've got a lot of liquidity." — Because Citadel locked up long-term funding with counterparts, not facing margin calls; back-office systems meant banks less aggressive in moving marks
- Besides, sold plenty of assets to raise cash — more proactive than Bear or Lehman in preventing leverage from spiraling upward

### Forese's Advice: Get Your Story Out

- Forese wondered if all this enough: "You guys are getting killed in the rumor mill"
- "I know. I can't get rid of the rumors" — making people think Citadel about to dump convertible bonds portfolio
- Threat of fire sale driving down prices, compounding Citadel's difficulties
- Every time Citadel executive got panicky call from trading counterpart, explained why rumors false
- No matter how many panicky callers Griffin's team assuaged, rumors growing more hysterical
- "You need a good window to get your story out" — Forese
- "I don't know what the forum for that is" — Griffin
- Last thing wanted: stage conference call appearing to confirm market's worst suspicions (Bear and Lehman had done calls, did no good)

### The Bond Call Strategy

- Forese remembered Citadel issued some five-year bonds
- Without signaling panic or anything out of ordinary, firm could convene phone call for bondholders
- Doing call in that format would give message extra weight — Griffin could get in trouble with regulators if gave bondholders anything other than truth, making assurances believable
- "That's a pretty good idea" — Griffin allowed; hung up and summoned lieutenants

### Preparing the Message

- Around 10:30 A.M., Griffin's inner circle convened around whiteboard
- Somebody jotted down half-dozen points Citadel needed to get across
- Griffin wanted **Gerald Beeson** (super-charged COO) to do most talking
- Another note added to whiteboard: "Speak slowly"
- "How many call-in lines?" — When big company like Coca-Cola held quarterly investor call, usually ~250 lines; Citadel had only handful of bondholders
- "Five hundred" somebody ventured
- "A thousand" — Beeson countered
- Call scheduled for 3:30 P.M., but no way could begin on time
- Well over thousand callers attempted to dial in — traders, investors, financial reporters
- **Culmination of Citadel deathwatch**, biggest financial drama since Lehman's failure
- On some Wall Street trading floors, call played over loudspeakers
- 25-minute delay as more phone lines arranged
- Those who managed to get in treated to grating techno music

### Beeson's Pitch

- Eventually Beeson began pitch: Yes, true Citadel's two flagship hedge funds down 35%
- But firm long way from running out of cash — financing secured, untapped $8 billion credit line, no way would go under
- **Adam Cooper** (Citadel general counsel) held up sign in front of Beeson: "To call this a dislocation doesn't go anywhere near the enormity of what we've seen"
- Emphasized Citadel would still survive: "We will prosper in the new era of finance" — Griffin added, mustering all confidence he could manage
- After 12 minutes, call was over

### The Aftermath

- Griffin got off phone, went to answer staff questions in town-hall meeting
- Beeson spent afternoon on series of calls with reporters, hammering home same message
- Citadel moved aggressively to raise cash; credit lines all secured
- Even though government rescued Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs while leaving hedge funds in cold, Citadel not going under
- Next day: CNBC truck gone from usual position outside Citadel Center — fires doused (for time being)

## Citadel's Losses Continue

- Next several weeks: Citadel's losses continued
- End of year: two flagship funds down stunning 55%; $9 billion evaporated (equivalent of at least two Long-Term Capitals)
- Though nobody said so, **Citadel's humiliation was model of how financial sector should work**
- Investors risked capital with Griffin, rewarded for years, forced to take extraordinary losses — exactly as should happen
- Financial system not destabilized, taxpayers not called upon to throw Citadel lifeline
- Episode showed leveraged trading firms with billions under management do NOT necessarily need government rescues when markets go berserk
- **Careful liquidity management can substitute for Fed's safety net**

### Investment Banks vs. Citadel

- Old-line investment banks built castles of leverage on foundations of short-term loans
- When crisis came, whole edifice toppled
- **Griffin shared paranoid culture of hedge funds** — leveraged himself more cautiously, relied less on short-term loans
- When moment of truth came, Citadel survived
- Upstart Goldman imitator could be better for financial system than real Goldman — not to mention incomparably better than Bear Stearns or Lehman Brothers

## Citadel's Experience and the Wider Industry

- Citadel's experience dramatized wider experience in hedge-fund industry
- Hedge funds danced through minefields until Lehman's September collapse, then whipsawed in panic that followed
- Based strategies on short selling — government banned that
- Based portfolios on leverage — leverage dried up as brokers hoarded capital
- End of 2008: most funds lost money; almost 1,500 went bust; many titans found reputations justly deflated

### The Hedge-Fund Carnage

- Even worst period of history, hedge funds proved their worth
- Industry as whole down 19% in 2008, but S&P 500 fell twice that much
- Unlike banks, investment banks, home lenders, others — **hedge funds imposed no costs on taxpayers or society**
- Point largely lost amid crisis — bursting of hedge-fund bubble left no room to think about policy meaning
- Titans flown so high that spectacle of fall mesmerizing

### Examples of Fallen Titans

- First half 2008: **Phil Falcone** (Harbinger Capital) returned 43%, stalked *New York Times*
- September: lost >$1 billion in week thanks to Lehman collapse + SEC short-selling ban
- February 2007: alpha factory **Fortress** went public amid great fanfare, creating $10.7 billion paper wealth for helicopter-riding chiefs
- December 2008: Fortress assets collapsed by almost a third, forced to fire two dozen portfolio managers
- **John Meriwether** and **Myron Scholes** (Long-Term Capital veterans) set up new hedge funds in 1999 that did well for several years
- End of 2008: both near precipice
- **Chris Hohn** (Children's Investment Fund) finished 2008 down 42%, seemed to lose intellectual moorings: "Quite frankly activism is hard" — as though surprised by discovery

### The Redemption Crisis

- Stunned by reversals, investors scrambled to get money out
- Hedge funds might have fallen far less than S&P 500, but customers expected them to be up in any sort of market
- Even macro hedge funds (gave up only small sliver of earlier gains months after Lehman) not exempt from storm
- Had to contend with $31 billion net redemptions because everybody withdrawing cash from everybody
- Hedge funds responded with tool Tudor resorted — **locked investors in by suspending quarterly redemptions and "gating" their money**
- Sometimes investors lucky to be taken prisoner: gates averted need for disastrous fire sales, accompanied by suspension of management fees
- Other times gates outrage: one prominent fund charged departing investor fee for early redemption, then blocked redemption, refused to return fee, carried on charging management fee

### Size Matters in Performance

- Larger hedge funds tended to be more peremptory and arrogant — frequently bigger funds had worst performance
- Big alpha factories stuck in losing positions when liquidity dried up
- **Tom Steyer's Farallon**: managing $36 billion at start of 2008, shriveled to $20 billion in 2009
- Meanwhile nimbler boutiques (closer in spirit to Steyer of previous decade) frequently escaped with minor scratches
- **Rock Creek Capital** (savvy fund-of-funds) calculated hedge funds with assets <$1 billion down relatively modest 12% in 2008
- Funds Rock Creek tracked with $1 billion to $10 billion in assets down 16%
- Those with >$10 billion down 27%

## The Mystique Survives

- For all losses, **hedge funds' mystique survived crisis**
- Repellent and attractive, objects of envy and yearning
- Remained wizards of modern capitalism's favorite pastime: unabashed pursuit of money
- November 2008, after two months of market pandemonium: five hedge-fund barons called to testify in Congress
- What promised to be show trial: billionaires scolded for upending economy
- Some way through proceedings, unexpected tone emerged
- Peering down from dais, **Representative Elijah Cummings** (Democrat of Maryland) recounted neighbor's reaction to day's hearing
- Not reproach, accusation, or even pity — simple question tinged with awe:

> "How does it feel to be going before five folks that have gotten more money than God?"
<!-- pp. 361-380 -->

## Conclusion: The Arguments Against Regulation

### The Case Against Hedge Fund Regulation

- **Hedge funds manage risk better than rivals** — they recognize setbacks faster and liquidate before secondary effects hit the financial system
- Government should encourage hedge funds to thrive and absorb more risk, shifting high-stakes asset management away from too-big-to-fail institutions
- **Chief policy prescription: Don't regulate**

### Objection 1: Performance Fees and Perverse Incentives

- **20% performance fee criticized since the 1960s** — allegedly promotes wild punts with clients' capital
- Academic criticism: **incentive fees induce deceptively smooth returns** that conceal blowup risk
- Example: Fund takes in $100, invests in S&P 500 index, earns $5 selling options to buyers insuring against market collapse. If collapse occurs, fund gets wiped out. But over 5-10 years, odds favor no collapse — fund beats S&P 500 by 5 percentage points annually and manager appears brilliant
- Critics argue rogues will exploit this when performance fees reward trickery
- **Counterargument: Investing in hedge funds is safer than investment banks**
  - Hedge funds have managers' own wealth in the fund alongside clients
  - Investment banks distributed **50% of net revenues** as salary and bonuses — far larger incentive for excessive risk than hedge fund's 20% performance fee
  - Bank compensation is variable and set by managers without shareholder consultation; hedge fund fees are fixed ahead of time

### Hedge Funds vs. Mutual Funds

- **Hedge funds appear expensive**: 1-2% management fee + ~20% performance fee
- But must distinguish **alpha** (skill-based returns) vs. **beta** (market exposure returns)
- S&P 500 index exposure costs 10 basis points; actively managed mutual fund charging 1% fee is effectively charging **90 basis points for alpha**
- **Study after study finds active mutual-fund managers do not beat the market** — charging 90 basis points and delivering nothing
- Their **fee per unit of alpha is infinite**

### Do Hedge Funds Deliver Value?

- Hedge funds make money by:
  - Trading against central banks not in markets for profit
  - Buying from price-insensitive forced sellers
  - Taking the other side when big institutions need liquidity
  - Sensing asymmetrical opportunities
- Talented investors, free of institutional impediments, powerfully motivated by performance fees, can rack up impressive profits
- History of hedge funds necessarily biased toward winners; perhaps average hedge fund loses money or alpha gets gobbled up by fees

**Evidence from Yale and Hennessee**: Best data comes from **Roger Ibbotson** (Yale School of Management), **Peng Chen** (Ibbotson Associates), and **Kevin Zhu** (Hong Kong Polytechnic University)
- Study covers hedge funds between January 1995 and December 2009
- Corrects for **survivorship bias** (excluding failed funds) and **backfill bias** (funds report only after excellent year)
- After adjustments: average hedge fund returned **11.4% per year**, or **7.7% after fees**
- Crucially, **7.7% net return included 3 percentage points of alpha**
- **Hedge funds generate profits beyond market exposure despite fees**

### Hedge Funds vs. Private Equity

- Both structured as private partnerships with leverage and performance fees
- Private equity firms increasingly start hedge funds and vice versa
- **Key difference**: Hedge funds buy mispriced securities; private equity improves firm management
- **Academic verdict**: Venture capital funds generate alpha of 4-5% per year; **buyout funds generate returns little different from S&P 500**
- Private-equity funds demand investors commit capital for up to a decade (clear disadvantage vs. hedge funds)

### The Real Value of Hedge Funds

- For ordinary savers, mutual funds that mimic an index remain best option
- For large investors, hedge funds compare well with rivals
- Not more prone to insider trading or fraud
- Deliver real value for clients
- **Harvard and Yale endowments** returned 8.9% and 11.8% annually (1999-2009) despite credit crisis losses — universities can afford more science facilities and merit scholarships, philanthropies have more to give
- If hedge funds serve rich clients well and contribute to wealth gap, the answer is **progressive taxation**, not smothering their trading

### Objection 2: Trend-Following and Market Destabilization

- Longstanding criticism: **trend-following hedge funds drive prices to illogical extremes**, destabilizing economies

**Counterargument: Most hedge funds stabilize markets**
- Arbitrage funds and statistical arbitrage drive prices toward rational levels
- **Julian Robertson-style stock pickers** move stocks closer to best estimates of value, allocating capital to firms that will use it productively
- Commodity traders responding to gluts/shortages **stabilize markets** — their responses generate price signals that force healthy adjustment
- Example: Commodity trader bids up oil on news of African coup, signaling motorists to economize before unsustainable consumption pushes prices even higher

### When Markets Overshoot

- Markets sometimes do overshoot; trend-following hedge funds can contribute
- **2007 oil example**: Price rose from $61 to $96 (probably fair response to emerging markets demand). But in first half of 2008, oil rose to **$145** — level probably exceeding fundamentals
- Currency traders sometimes send rational signals, sometimes drive currencies to irrational extremes
- **Soros-Druckenmiller sterling trade** fits rational category — Germany's postunification commitment to high interest rates made sterling peg untenable
- **Thailand's 1997 devaluation** also rational — growing trade deficit incompatible with pegged exchange rate
- But **Indonesia 1997** ran small trade deficit with flexible rate, yet suffered bigger devaluation than Thailand due to political instability panic

**Could hedge-fund regulation dampen trend-following?**
- Restrictions would limit contrarian trend-bucking as well as trend-following trading
- No data to prove net effect
- Despite tradition of trend-following from **Commodities Corporation** to **Paul Tudor Jones**, hedge-fund regulation would probably exacerbate markets' tendency to overshoot
- **Hedge funds more likely to be trend bucking** due to structure:
  1. Free to go short as well as long
  2. Judged on absolute returns (mutual funds measured against consensus-reflecting indices)
  3. Performance fees provide resources and incentives for contrarian bets

**Paul Jones example**: Even self-described trend follower recognizes contrarian potential
- Knows investors react to information gradually (pension funds, insurance funds, mutual funds, individuals absorb developments on own timescales)
- Prices respond incrementally rather than in one jump
- Precisely because Jones understands momentum, he has knack for sensing when it's gone too far
- He's the **last person to exacerbate a trend** — once move becomes overextended, he's looking to profit from reversal
- Bet against trend on Wall Street before 1987 crash
- Bet against trend in Tokyo 1990
- Declared in summer 2008: **"Oil is a huge mania... It is going to end badly"** weeks before bubble burst

**European exchange-rate crisis**: Soros and Druckenmiller didn't simply lead attack pack — they bet French franc would resist devaluation pressure
**East Asian crisis**: Hedge funds helped precipitate Thailand devaluation (trade deficit made peg illogical). Rupiah crash driven by Indonesians rushing to expatriate money, not hedge funds. Far from jumping on bandwagon, **Soros team pushed back unsuccessfully**. Another hedge fund, **Tom Steyer's Farallon**, helped begin Indonesia's turnaround with contrarian purchase of Bank Central Asia

> "The point is not that hedge funds are never guilty of herding — clearly there are times when they are... But the point is that, because of their structure and incentives, hedge funds are more likely to be contrarian than other types of investors. The regulatory lesson is contrarian too. The best way to dampen trend following is not to constrain hedge funds. It is to let them go about their business."

### Summary: The Case for Not Regulating

- Hedge funds **not especially prone to insider trading or fraud**
- Offer **partial answer to too-big-to-fail problem**
- **Deliver value to investors**
- **More likely to blunt trends** than other investment vehicles
- Regulators should want to encourage hedge funds, not rein them in

### The One Persuasive Argument for Regulation

**When hedge funds grow too large, regulation becomes warranted**
- Case for hedge funds is a case for **entrepreneurial boutiques**
- When funds cease being small enough to fail, regulation warranted
- When funds become public companies, they give up private-partnership structure effective in controlling risk — case for regulation becomes stronger
- Even though **~5,000 hedge funds failed 2000-2009** without triggering taxpayer bailout, **Long-Term Capital Management** serves as warning
- No public money subsidized LTCM's burial, but Fed was concerned enough to convene the undertakers

**How large warrants regulation?**
- No simple answer
- **Systemic consequences depend on when failure occurs**
- LTCM triggered Fed intervention partly because it happened when markets already scared from Russia's default
- Amaranth's failure had no systemic consequences because Wall Street was comfortably awash in easy money

**Three clues to whether failure triggers intervention**:
1. **Size of capital**
2. **Extent of leverage**
3. **Types of markets traded in**

### LTCM's Red Flags

**First test — size of capital**:
- LTCM capital: **under $5 billion** (half the size of Amaranth)
- Not unthreatening on this test

**Second test — leverage**:
- LTCM leveraged **25 times** — sudden collapse would cause **$120 billion worth of positions** to be unloaded on markets
- Fund's derivative positions created another **$1.2 trillion of exposure**

**Third test — market liquidity**:
- LTCM traded in **esoteric and illiquid** markets
- Fire sale could cause markets to freeze completely

**Combination triggered Fed intervention**:
- As of 1998, **$120 billion portfolio attached to enormous derivatives book** was large enough to trigger regulatory concern, given post-Russia panic and participation in illiquid markets

### Amaranth and Sowood: No Red Flags

**Amaranth** ($9 billion capital):
- Large but not enormous hedge fund
- Leverage normal, so total portfolio smaller than LTCM's
- Natural-gas trades nearly all conducted on exchanges (easily liquidated)
- **No red flags in any of three categories** — not surprising Amaranth's failure generated more newspaper headlines than financial system shocks

**Sowood** ($3 billion fund with leverage):
- Troubles concentrated in relatively liquid corporate bond market
- Small enough to fail

### 2007 Quant Quake and Citadel: Revealing Lessons

**Quant funds 2007**:
- Deployed **at least $100 billion capital** in strategies that went wrong
- Leveraged **~8 times**, producing combined superportfolio of **at least $800 billion**
- Yet total exposure not worrisomely large — **passed third test with flying colors**
- Traded exclusively in **superliquid equity markets** — could cut leverage rapidly when crisis came

**Citadel** ($13 billion capital, leveraged 11 times):
- Portfolio of **$145 billion**, not counting derivatives positions
- Total exposure worrisomely large
- But **passed third test**: had big book of over-the-counter transactions with other firms that could be difficult to exit
- Citadel held illiquid positions and backed them with medium/long-term borrowing — **managed its liquidity as LTCM tried to do, but more successfully**
- By backing investments that couldn't be sold instantly with loans that couldn't be yanked instantly, avoided tumbling into death spiral of forced selling in illiquid markets

> "The lesson is that portfolios above a certain threshold may prompt regulatory concern; but if regulators are satisfied that the firm's liquidity is well managed, they should leave it to go about its business."

### A Tiered Regulatory Framework

**Tier 1** ($120 billion threshold):
- When hedge-fund company builds total leveraged assets over **$120 billion**, undergo regulatory cross-examination about size of derivatives positions and liquidity management
- Threshold somewhat arbitrary, but markets have grown considerably since LTCM
- Setting bar at $120 billion seems appropriately cautious

**Tier 2** ($200 billion threshold):
- Second level of oversight: scrutiny of leverage
- If risk-weighted asset calculations suggest capital buffer too thin, fund required to add extra padding
- Cautious bar: at $200 billion, hedge fund still considerably smaller than investment bank like **Bear Stearns** ($350 billion assets as of 2006)

**Tier 3** (going public):
- If hedge fund goes public, presumption of competent risk management should be softened
- Firm should attract more frequent and insistent attention from regulatory examiners

**Result**: Framework would leave **nearly all hedge funds outside the net**
- As of January 2009, *Institutional Investor* listed only **39 hedge funds worldwide with capital over $10 billion**
- Other ~9,000 funds left alone unless unusually high leverage got them over $120 billion threshold
- No need to register with government agencies or comply with time-consuming oversight
- Unburdened by compliance costs, vast majority free to grow and thrive, taking over risk currently managed by too-big-to-fail behemoths
- Small number of genuine risks to financial system handled differently — **treated as though they were investment banks**

### The Historical Parallel: Merchant Banks to Investment Banks

In 1949, when **Alfred Winslow Jones** set up his hedged fund, merchant banks (Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Lehman Brothers) were:
- Private operations deploying partners' capital flexibly, like today's hedge funds
- Managed risk ferociously (speculating with their own money, not others')
- Largely unregulated

Over next half century, investment banks:
- Sold shares to public
- Opened offices around the world
- Not because sprawling public enterprises are superior platforms for managing risk, but because **rewards to leaders were irresistible**
- Every investment bank that went public unlocked millions for partners (swapped illiquid ownership stakes for liquid stock)
- Every expansion into new market created fresh opportunity to risk shareholders' capital and collect 50% quasi performance fee if risks proved lucrative
- **Incentives pushed investment banks to take ever greater risk**, until eventually they paid the price
- By end of 2008, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became bank holding companies, admitting they could survive consequences of public-company status only if Fed backstopped them

**Today, hedge funds are the new merchant banks** — Goldmans and Morgans of half a century ago:
- Focus on risk equally ferocious
- Equally lightly regulated
- **Same logic that tempted old merchant banks to go public will seduce some hedge funds**
- Already handful have sold shares; doubtless more will follow
- When that happens, hedge funds will pose threat to financial system they've wrongly been accused of posing in the past
- **The wheel of Wall Street turns. Greed and risk are always with us.**


