### Chapter One: Big Daddy - Endnotes

#### A.W. Jones Background

- **Britt Erica Tunick**, "Capital Gains: The Firms in Our Sixth Annual Ranking of the World's 100 Biggest Hedge Funds Manage an Altogether Staggering $1 Trillion," *Alpha* (May 2007)
- **Steve Fishman**, "Get Richest Quickest: In the Precarious Hedge-Fund Bubble, It's Either Clean Up—Or Flame Out," *New York*, vol. 37, no. 41 (November 22, 2004)
- **Peter Landau**, "The Hedge Funds: Wall Street's New Way to Make Money," *New York* vol 1, no. 29 (October 21, 1968): pp. 20–24
- **Adam Smith**, *The Money Game* (Vintage Books, 1976), p. 41
- **John Brooks**, *The Go-Go Years* (Weybright and Talley, 1973), p. 128
- Jones's early life from author interviews with children **Anthony Jones** and **Dale Burch** (May 22, 2007)
- State Department records: Jones worked as clerk/export buyer 1924-1926, statistician/analyst for investment counselor 1926-1928
- **Charles Kindleberger**, *The World in Depression* (UC Press, 1986), p. 132
- Jones marriage January 17, 1932; previous marriage and custody battle detailed in letter from Jones to American consul general **George S. Messersmith** (March 22, 1932, National Archives)
  - Research contributed by **Harold Hurwitz** (historian of Germany's anti-Nazi Left), **Peter Lowe** (Leninist Organization leader nephew), **Mark Hove** (State Department Historian's Office)
- Jones's wife used multiple names/pseudonyms: "Hannah Koehler," "Nelly"
- **Neu Beginnen** group (often called "the Org") later changed name
- State Department confidential memorandum (February 20, 1933)
- **Mary Carter Jones** interview (Henry Street Oral History Project, 1993, box T2:23): "I was doing this illustrating when I met my husband, and he said, 'How can you draw those things when you can marry me?'"
- Mid-1930s: Jones working for Leninist Organization/Neu Beginnen in New York (per Hurwitz)
  - State Department possibly funding Jones as intelligence asset (embassy records Paris 1937-1939 show "rent allowance" payments)
  - April 1944: State Department considered military deferment for Jones, suggesting ongoing connection

#### Spain and Academic Career

- Jones-Spain trip documented in joint report: **Alfred W. Jones** and **Mary Carter Jones**, "War Relief in Spain: Report to the American Unitarian Association" (American Friends Service Committee, 1938)
- **Adam Smith** introduction to *The Money Managers*, ed. **Gilbert Edmund Kaplan** and **Chris Welles** (Institutional Investor Systems, 1969), p. xiii
- Jones's 25th Harvard yearbook (class of 1923): interest in sociology stemmed from Germany experience — "I came home in the midst of the Depression to try to find out if anything like that could happen here" (p. 450)
- **Alfred Winslow Jones**, *Life, Liberty and Property: A Story of Conflict and a Measurement of Conflicting Rights* (J.B. Lippincott, 1941), p. 23
- **Alfred Winslow Jones**, "The Free Market and the Future," *Fortune* 25 (April 1942), pp. 98–99, 126, 128
- **Adam Smith**, *The Money Game*, p. 11: quotes **Edward Crosby Johnson II** (Fidelity founder) — "The stock market is like a beautiful woman—endlessly fascinating, endlessly complex, always changing, always mystifying. I have been absorbed and immersed since 1924 and I know this is no science. It is an art.... It is personal intuition"
- **Alfred Cowles III** and **Herbert E. Jones**, "Some A Posteriori Probabilities in Stock Market Action," *Econometrica* 5(3) (July 1937): 280–94
- Jones's 25th anniversary Harvard yearbook (1948): extensive political views/gardening discussion, finance not mentioned
- Jones quote in 50th Harvard class report: "With a wife and two children, I needed something more lucrative, and turned to Wall Street"

#### Fund Performance and Structure

- Jones returns 1961-1964 data from unpublished "Basic Report to the Partners" (May 31, 1961), provided by **Robert Burch IV** (Jones's grandson)
  - 1962-1963 data from press accounts, notably **Carol J. Loomis**, "The Jones Nobody Keeps Up With," *Fortune* (April 1966), pp. 237–47
- **Roger Lowenstein**, *Buffett: The Making of an American Capitalist* (Broadway Books, 2001), p. 118: Buffett investors in 1957 enjoyed 16-fold return over 13 years
  - Jones up just under 15-fold same period, but other 13-year periods show him up 17-fold
- Jones office description from interviews with **Richard Radcliffe**, **Clark Drasher**, **Banks Adams**, **Richard Gilder**, **Alex Porter**, **Alan Dresher**, **Walter Harrison**, **Carlisle Jones**
  - **Barton Biggs**, *Hedgehogging* (John Wiley & Sons, 2006), pp. 81–85: "Alfred Jones understood the performance game and the value of getting an edge from research before anyone else did" (p. 83)
- Jones hated committee meetings; **Mary Jones** (Henry Street Oral History): "My husband hated going on committees in wars—he just loathed it"

#### Investment Innovations

- Jones possibly inspired by **Ben Graham's** investment partnership (long/short, performance fees, leverage)
  - **Richard Radcliffe** (joined 1954): alternative inspiration was legendary broker **Roy Neuberger**
  - **Adam Smith** unpublished profile of Neuberger: arrived Wall Street 1920s without college degree, balanced long/short investments, portfolio emerged unscathed from 1929 crash
  - Neuberger told Smith: "He was starting a real hedge fund, and I became his broker"
- **Gilbert Edmund Kaplan** and **Chris Welles**, *The Money Managers*, pp. 112–13
- Jones "Basic Report to the Partners" (May 31, 1961)
- Short selling historically seen as disreputable; **Martin T. Sosnoff**, "Hedge Fund Management: A New Respectability for Short Selling," *Financial Analysts Journal* (July–August 1966), p. 105
- Until 2007: shorting only permitted on uptick; profits from short sales taxed as ordinary income (up to 90% 1951-1964)
  - Top rate on regular income: 91% (1951-1964), lowered to 70% (1965), stayed there until 1968
  - Capital gains rate: 25% during this period
  - **Seward & Kissel** (Valentine law firm): figured out departing partners could be paid with shares carrying unrealized gains, avoiding tax
  - **John Tavss** (tax lawyer): Valentine "could take almost any problem and start spouting out potential solutions. He would come up with five ideas immediately"
  - **Craig Drill**: "Everyone in the hedge fund business who knew about this was very quiet about it for ten, or twenty, or thirty years"

#### Regulatory Environment

- **Securities Act of 1933**: exemption for "transactions by an issuer not involving any public offering"
  - Investment partnerships had to limit partner numbers to avoid "public offering" designation
- **Investment Company Act of 1940**: exemption for partnerships <100 partners with no public offering
  - Limits on leverage, short selling, high fees
- **Investment Advisors Act**: prohibits "compensation to the investment advisor on the basis of a share of capital gains"
  - Hedge funds argued they advised <15 clients (the partnership was the "client," not individual partners)
  - If SEC had rejected this and forced registration, it "would probably have crushed them"
- **Richard Radcliffe**: "We always were afraid of getting regulated, and the way we would have been regulated would have been if we had too many partners there.... We got up close to a hundred, and we decided that we should have another fund. And we even separated out the investment strategies to make it look as if we were not just trying to get around the rules"
- **Clark Drasher** offered similar account
- **John Brooks**, *The Go-Go Years*, p. 144
- **Alfred Cowles**, "A Revision of Previous Conclusions Regarding Stock Price Behavior," *Econometrica* 28, no. 4 (October 1960)

#### Academic Challenge and Decline

- By 1965: Jones's chartist faith under attack from academics
  - 1949 *Fortune* essay: Jones singled out **Nicholas Molodovsky** as "the most scientific and experimental of technical students" with "nearly perfect" predictions (two exceptions)
  - 1965: **Molodovsky** (editor of *Financial Analysts Journal*) commissioned paper from **Eugene Fama** — "Random Walks in Stock Market Prices"
  - Fama compared chart following to astrology, popularizing random-walk theory
  - Direct attack on Jones's premise; especially painful as Jones/Molodovsky were close
  - Molodovsky introduced Jones to **Richard Radcliffe**, later hired by Jones
- 1968: **Donald Woodward** (chief operating officer) willing to say categorically stock selection, not market timing, was key
  - "Our judgment about the prevailing market trend has not been our strong point" — "Heyday of the Hedge Funds," *Dun's Review* (January 1968), p. 76
- Jones's secrecy: never told children about first marriage (discovered accidentally when Anthony married Austrian)
  - Never mentioned Berlin period to Radcliffe despite decade-long employment
  - Broker who founded hedge fund: "We knew that Jones was making a fortune and that people who were associated with him were doing extremely well. But we didn't know how he was doing it" (Kaplan/Welles, pp. 115–16)
  - Not until 1966 (17 years after fund launch) were Jones's techniques described in financial media

#### 1966 Fortune Article Impact

- **Carol J. Loomis**, "The Jones Nobody Keeps Up With," *Fortune* (April 1966)
- **Alex Porter** recalls reading Loomis article, calling Jones's office, speaking with **Don Woodward**, joining 1967
  - First ran model portfolio, then worked for Jones directly until early 1970s
- Partner **Dean Milosis** estimated Jones's personal income in 1968 ("Heyday of the Hedge Funds," p. 76)
- Comprehensive regulatory questions description: **Joseph P. P. Hildebrandt**, "Hedge Fund Operation and Regulation" (unpublished J.D. thesis, Harvard, April 15, 1969)
  - Also **Carol Loomis**, "Hard Times Come to Hedge Funds," *Fortune* (January 1970)

#### 1969-1970 Crash

- Year to June 1, 1966: S&P 500 up 1%; following year up 7%; year after that up 10%
  - Jones funds ran on May 31 financial year; comparison with S&P 500 June 1 returns
- **Clark Drasher**: "I don't think I really took this volatility thing seriously. Maybe I didn't give a hoot about it. I told Jones it was not a real measure of risk. I didn't like it because often something I wanted to do in bulk was restricted because of the volatility factor. A lot of mathematical baloney went on. All this attempt to be scientifically precise makes you feel good, but at the end of the day you made money if your selections were good or not.... Most of the time we were not balanced. We would get carried away in rising markets. You'd have to be short much of anything in the 1960s. So when the bad times came in 1969 we got hit"
- **Banks Adams**: "When the 1960s came and the markets were going straight up, those [volatility] numbers were just useless. Let's take Texas Instruments: It didn't fluctuate, it was going straight up. Telephones proved to be more volatile than Texas Instruments, which was doubling and tripling every year. A. W. Jones's thinking came out of the 1940s and 1950s"
- **Edwin Burke Cox**, *Trends in the Distribution of Stock Ownership* (University of Pennsylvania Press, 1963), pp. xiii, 211
- **Adam Smith**, *The Money Game*, p. 209
- S&P 500 fell 23.4% during Jones's crash period; Jones's larger losses reflected >100% long exposure
- **Dale Burch** interview: Jones's response to 1969-1970 crash

