## Chapter Two: Tony Cilluffo and the Rise of Short Selling (continued)

### The Cultural Resistance to Short Selling

- **David Rocker** (Steinhardt analyst): "To make money on the short side you have to be a scrapper. The government is against you. The media was against you; it was un-American to be short. The company management was against you. Advances in stock prices tend to be long and gentle, whereas falls are sharp and short. And so most days when you go in the office, the short seller is taking it in the nose."
- Short selling faced institutional, cultural, and structural headwinds throughout the 1960s-1980s

### Tony Cilluffo's Unique Intelligence

- **Michael Steinhardt** on Cilluffo: "Tony was, as you've heard, very unusual because of his ability to express himself unequivocally. In such a way that he was vulnerable…It was that vulnerability that made you respect him when he was right and when he was wrong, and made you think he was a man of courage and conviction."
- Cilluffo's conviction was mysterious—he had street smarts and intelligence "from a different source" than formal economics training
- His intelligence "came from a different source and his judgments came from a different source"
- With Kondratiev waves: "With conviction and a little bit of naïveté. I don't think he knew too much. But he knew what he had to know. Why he felt as he did was a mystery because he couldn't articulate it."

> "All I bring to the party is twenty-eight years of mistakes." — Fellow investor quoted by Steinhardt

### The Research-Driven Edge at Steinhardt, Fine, Berkowitz

- **Howard Berkowitz**: "We were all research analysts, we were all very intense in our management process, we knew about the companies we visited, we understood what was going on. Markets were less efficient back then."
- **Jerry Fine**: "We were, in my opinion, 100 percent research driven."
- The firm's edge came from intensive company visits and fundamental analysis in less efficient markets

### The Rise of Institutional Trading

- **1960**: Big savings institutions accounted for just 25% of NYSE turnover
- **1969**: Institutions accounted for more than half
- **Mid-1980s**: Institutions reckoned to account for 80-90% of stock-exchange turnover
- **Block trading targets**: 30% of total turnover by 1980, 50% by 1984

### Steinhardt's Information Edge from Block Trading

- As a major block trader, Steinhardt sat on trading desks at major firms, giving him access to market-moving information
- **Merton Miller and Franco Modigliani** (1961): "No buyer or seller (or issuer) of securities is large enough for his transactions to have an appreciable impact on the then ruling price."
- **Eugene Fama** acknowledged specialists with privileged knowledge of unfulfilled orders could outperform, but failed to see the impact of block trading
- Block traders like Steinhardt now had access to information about big trades that would move prices—the value of this information increased with block size

> "I used to generate vast amounts of commissions relative to my capital because I did all sorts of things that generated huge commissions for my own purposes that I felt had some circular benefit: You generate commissions, you get good ideas, you have the ability to be more liquid than the next guy because the broker will buy your stuff when he needs to and not the next guy's stuff; and you get a better call on new issues and research." — Michael Steinhardt

### Trading on Information Flow

- **1986 example**: Goldman Sachs analyst recommended Southwest Airlines stock to Steinhardt's traders the night before the recommendation went to other Goldman clients
- Steinhardt once bought a large "dislocated block" of Equity Funding, sensed insider trading, investigated the seller's identity through Goldman, discovered it was an insider, and canceled the buy order
- "Usually the seller doesn't know his ass from his elbow. Are there occasions when he does? You bet."
- **Early 1980s**: Steinhardt was Goldman Sachs's largest account as a mere hedge fund—required "intimate relationships with the people at the trading desks at the major firms"

### The Broker's Perspective

> "If he [the broker] had something coming, if he knew he had a huge seller, he would say to me, 'You know, it wouldn't be a bad thing for you to get short on blah blah blah.' Why would he want me to get short on blah blah? Because he had a huge seller and he knew, at some point, he was going to trade that stock down. And if he had me as a buyer covering my short, it would be good for him; it would be, almost certainly, good for me because I would be buying it lower." — Michael Steinhardt

### The Statistical Edge of Long/Short Funds

- For a **long/short hedge fund** investing heavily in bonds, the assumption that odds of making a positive return in any given year are one in two seems "roughly fair"
- Different from normal mutual funds (stocks move up more years than they fall)
- Steinhardt agreed to SEC court order in Seaboard insider trading case (1976)

### Regulatory Efforts and Their Limits

- Reforms attempted to eliminate insider advantage, but Steinhardt remained skeptical: "It's impossible to disseminate information exactly homogeneously"
- **Anise C. Wallace**, "Pullback at Block Trading Desks," *New York Times*, December 24, 1987

## Chapter Three: Paul Samuelson's Secret

### The Random Walk and Efficient Markets

- **Justin Fox**: *The Myth of the Rational Market* discusses the rise of efficient-market theory
- **Peter L. Bernstein**: *Capital Ideas Evolving* traces the evolution of financial theory
- **Paul Samuelson**: "Fama's theory of the random walk and mine are not the same. Mine is that there are no easy pickings.… If you read the numerous papers I have written on the efficient-market hypothesis, you will realize it is not a dogma. If you can get information early, before it is widespread, you can't help but get very rich."

### The Rise of Quantitative Finance

- **Commodities Corporation** founded 1969 alongside other early quant firms
- **Morris Markovitz** was the Apollo graduate who pioneered portfolio theory
- **Princeton-Newport** created 1969—another outstanding early quantitative firm (see William Poundstone, *Fortune's Formula*)
- **1964**: Paul Cootner published *The Random Character of Stock Market Prices*, compiling all efficient-market papers to that date

### Helmut Weymar and Commodities Corporation

- **F. Helmut Weymar** described his motivation: "I was particularly taken by the theme and role of the hero in the western canon. If one is contemplating heroism, it helps to be driven by existential angst, and mine was palpable during my 20's and 30's."
- Former employee bluntly: "Helmut wanted to be king of the world, basically. He got interested in art and then he stopped doing it because he thought, 'I'll never really make a splash in the art world.' So he did it because he needs and wants to be superior to others and be seen as superior to others."
- Weymar offered intellectual excitement—**Jan Kunz** and **Irwin Rosenblum** described him and **Frank Vannerson** as brilliant, unconventional thinkers

### The Near-Death and Survival of Commodities Corporation

- Commodities Corporation survived early losses because **Nabisco** wanted continued access to Weymar's cocoa forecasts and Vannerson's wheat forecasts
- Nabisco held a senior claim on remaining assets—would reclaim $500,000 in liquidation, leaving other investors with only $400,000 of their original $2 million
- Having been "virtually wiped out," other shareholders allowed the firm to continue trading

### Money Management Discipline

> "Valuable as market analysis and data generation may be, money management discipline is even more important to successful speculation.… Most successful speculative derivatives traders generate more losing trades than profitable trades. They are successful only because their gains on positive trades are substantially larger than their tightly controlled losses on negative trades." — Helmut Weymar

- **Paul Tudor Jones** began his hedge fund Tudor with seed capital from Commodities Corporation
- Jones would make young traders "write an analysis on why this happened and how it's not going to happen again" after near-blowouts
- **Elaine Crocker** (senior manager, later president of Moore Capital): "The kickout forced you to liquidate your positions and get out of the market for thirty days. During this period you would plot the history of your trades in the period leading up to your losses and see whether you had violated your own trading philosophy. Most of the time, the answer would be yes."

### Academic Resistance to Trend Following

- **Mid-1980s**: MIT theorist **Robert Fano** wrote a paper questioning the random walk—colleagues warned submission would brand him "a crackpot"
- **Scott Irwin** vividly recalled the difficulty of getting views on trends published in academic journals

### Frank Vannerson's Trend-Following Innovation

- **Vannerson**: "Happily blessed by an inquiring and open mind, Frank overcame the bias of his Princeton economics training"
- Vannerson noted: "The academics were slow to come around. I think currencies did it, where trends were so obvious a child could see them."
- Vannerson believed he created the first automated trend-following system: "I am pretty sure I was the first to put the whole thing together"
- **Ed Seykota** at Hayden Stone developed a similar system around the same time—"friendly rival"
- **Dennis Dunn** of Dunn & Hargitt may have created such a system in the late 1960s
- The launch prospectus mentioned research into price trends only in passing—Commodities Corporation aimed to market superior fundamental knowledge, not computerized trend following

### Michael Marcus and the Shift from Fundamentals

- **Marcus** was the first non-PhD trader, hired despite **Amos Tversky** objecting
- "I created a certain amount of controversy. The whole idea was that this would be the best and brightest. I wouldn't have been hired if it wasn't for Amos pushing. Once I was hired, I wouldn't say that I faced considerable opposition. Some of their PhDs hadn't done as well as they had hoped."
- **Morris Markovitz** recalled Marcus's lavish spending: private jet for Hawaii wedding, cautious in business but extravagant for personal pleasure

### Helmut Weymar's Defense of Fundamentals

- Weymar objected that Marcus paid great attention to fundamentals, so the shift away from Commodities Corporation's initial faith in fundamental analysis was less stark than suggested
- But Weymar's initial trading followed fundamentals-dominated chart analysis while Marcus traded the opposite
- **Marcus**: "The trend followers used to say that the fundamentals were embedded in the trend and that you could make more money if you waited until the fundamentals were being acted upon and causing a trend in one direction."
- The contrast with the founding prospectus (emphasizing econometric modeling, no mention of trends) is conclusive

### The Floor Trader's Advantage

> "You had advantages on the floor. Your advantage was that you knew a lot about the technical insides of one market. You could see who was buying, who was selling, how the orders were getting filled, where the stops were. The drawback was that you were pinned down to that market. If you were trading grains, and soybeans were having a fabulous move, you would miss out. I later decided that you were better off giving up that technical advantage and having the opportunity to pick and choose among a number of markets." — Michael Marcus

### Libertarian Culture at Commodities Corporation

- Several libertarians at the firm
- **Markovitz**: "There was a lot of the antiauthoritarian, libertarian sentiment. I think a lot of people in the business who weren't that way when they started became that way. I think it accelerates your awareness when you study the markets, analyze them, you see when the government interferes with the markets, ninety-nine times out of a hundred there is no benefit and it just creates problems."

### The Inflation Crisis and Commodities Boom

- **1970s inflation**: Price controls on lumber discussed by **Barry Bosworth** and **William Poole**
- **Jeffry A. Frieden**: *Global Capitalism: Its Fall and Rise in the Twentieth Century*
- **1979**: Gold above $300/ounce in summer, above $800 in winter—far from the $35 mandated by Bretton Woods
- Post-1973, companies began insuring against price spikes via futures markets—"unprecedented high hedging levels relative to speculation"

### The Grain Wholesaler Loophole

- Commodities Corporation arranged a loophole with a grain wholesaler to access markets

### The White Book and Trend Persistence

- Traders studied the **"White Book"**—a summary of trading ideas from **Amos Hostetter**, revered elder statesman
- **Burton Rothberg** also emphasized Vannerson's influence: "Commodities Corporation really learned that trends always go further than you think. There was a lot of mathematical work on this by Frank Vannerson, and we found that over the short term trends tended to continue at every level. The theory was that unless you had a really good reason, you want to stay with the trend."

### Academic Validation of Momentum

- **Richard J. Sweeney** (1986): "Beating the Foreign Exchange Market"
- **Louis P. Lukac, B. Wade Brorsen, Scott H. Irwin** (1988): "A Test of Futures Market Disequilibrium Using Twelve Different Technical Trading Systems"
- **B. Wade Brorsen and Louis P. Lukac** (1990): "A Comprehensive Test of Futures Market Disequilibrium"
- **Narasimhan Jegadeesh and Sheridan Titman** (1993): "Returns to Buying Winners and Selling Losers: Implications for Stock Market Efficiency"—belief in momentum became mainstream

### Bruce Kovner Joins Commodities Corporation

- **Marcus** met Kovner when Kovner was driving a taxi part-time and trading part-time
- "I was astounded by the depth and breadth of his knowledge. I would try to come up with something esoteric and arcane that would impress him, and he was right there and knew about it and could talk about it. Here was a guy working part-time and driving a taxi, but he was a colleague already."
- **Paul Samuelson** on Kovner: "My comment was, 'Bruce Kovner couldn't afford to be president of Commodities Corporation.'"
- **Irwin Rosenblum**: "He was extremely ambitious and had all the requisite skills needed to fulfill those ambitions. He was brilliant, verbal, and confident and possessed of a great deal of personal charm. Helmut was totally taken by him."

### Kovner's Focus on Direction Over Efficient Prices

- Kovner emphasized Weymar's original efforts to estimate the "efficient" price for a commodity were less fruitful than Marcus's directional judgment
- Trying to estimate the "right price" was "difficult and potentially dangerous, since it could lead to obstinacy in trading"
- "As a trader of a leveraged fund you had to be centrally concerned with path rather than end points."

### The Importance of Technical Analysis

- **Roy Lennox** (hired by Kovner 1980): "When I got the job with Bruce, I called up his assistant for some reading suggestions before I came. One of the books he had her send me was about reading charts. I thought, 'Oh my god, I was taught in business school that charts don't work, that markets are efficient.' But then Bruce told me that charts are just representations of market psychology and therefore extremely valuable, and indeed indispensable, for trading."

### The Influx of Outside Money

- **Late 1970s, early 1980s**: Influx of outside money into Commodities Corporation
- **Helmut Weymar** opposed managing outside money, but traders like Kovner wanted to take it
- **Markovitz**: "We had been arguing for at least a year, a couple of years, about trading outside money. Helmut was nervous that once he let traders out of his control, they might leave."

### Paul Samuelson's Rejection

- Commodities Corporation tried to hire **Paul Samuelson** but he declined
- **Elaine Crocker**: "When he came down to Princeton to meet Helmut, Helmut told him, 'Remember, you will lose money at some point.' Afterwards Paul wrote a thank you letter, claiming that he had paid for dinner and been told he would lose money."

### The Firm's Decline and Absorption

- Commodities Corporation continued for many years, eventually absorbed into Goldman Sachs in 1997
- Heyday ended early 1980s
- Lost money on trading in 1981, but Weymar allowed administrative expenses to grow unsustainably: $15 million (1981) → $23 million (1982) → $27 million (1983)

## Chapter Four: The Alchemist (George Soros)

### The London School of Economics and Early Influences

- Historian **Ralf Dahrendorf** (LSE director 1974-1984) described the intellectual climate and Soros's early life
- Source: **Michael T. Kaufman**, *Soros: The Life and Times of a Messianic Billionaire*
- Soros reckoned he needed $500,000 to be financially independent

### The A.W. Jones Model

- Soros knew Steinhardt, Fine, and Berkowitz (hedge fund founded 1967), but **A.W. Jones** was the chief role model
- "Double Eagle was modeled after AW Jones"
- Soros's junior partner **Jim Rogers** had worked for Neuberger & Berman, A.W. Jones's main broker
- Soros's exposure to A.W. Jones reinforced by Rogers's experience

### Reflexivity and Misconceptions

> "The key to reflexivity is a misconception of reality, and this is where the fundamental misconception of economic theory comes in. The theory is that people act in their self-interest, but the fact is that they act in what they perceive to be their self-interest, and their best interest is not necessarily what they believe is in their best interest." — George Soros

### The Case for Mortgage Trusts (Reflexivity Example)

- Soros's investment note "The Case for Mortgage Trusts" (reprinted in *The Alchemy of Finance*) explained reflexive logic:
  - Trust starts with 10 shares worth $10 each, earns $12 income on $100 capital
  - High yield attracts five new investors paying $20 each for shares
  - Investment fund now has $200 capital
  - Assuming new capital works as efficiently as first tranche, trust earns $24 split among 15 shareholders
  - Per-share earnings rise from $1.20 to $1.60 after new capital injection
- Soros observed acquisitive conglomerates with strong stock prices could pay for acquisitions using newly valuable equity; acquisitions meant higher earnings and stronger stock; cycle repeats

### Jim Rogers and Global Perspective

- **Rogers** wanted to invest globally rather than become president, aiming to be a "gnome of Zurich"
- After leaving Soros in 1980, Rogers became known as a commodities guru and author of *Investment Biker*

### The Quantum Fund Performance

- Quantum Fund performance through 1985 given in Soros, *The Alchemy of Finance*, p. 150

### Currency Overshooting Theory

- Not all economists believed currencies tended toward equilibrium
- **Rudiger Dornbusch** (MIT, 1976): "Expectations and Exchange Rate Dynamics" published in *Journal of Political Economy*
- Dornbusch argued currencies overshoot in response to monetary shocks due to interplay between sticky goods prices and fast-adjusting capital markets
- This was a minority view within academic macroeconomics through the 1980s
- **Kenneth Rogoff** (IMF chief economist, 2002): "If there is a consensus result in the empirical literature, it has to be that nothing, but nothing, can systematically explain exchange rates between major currencies with flexible exchange rates."

### Soros's Currency Trading Logic

- Soros argued economists exaggerated the extent interest rate shifts would drive currencies to equilibrium
- US trade deficit implied low demand for investment capital and low interest rates; speculators should shift money out of dollars to higher-yielding currencies, weakening the dollar and reducing the trade deficit
- But speculators cared less about interest earned on dollars than about the dollar's trend
- **November 1984**: Fall in US interest rates followed (after short pause) by jump in the dollar—market logic said if the dollar didn't drop in response to falling interest rates, the upward trend must be robust and it was time to buy

### Soros's Risk Management System

- Soros loosely observed a rule: took more risk with recent profits than with capital
- This encouraged big risk-taking in periods when he was in sync with markets while forcing a cooler approach when weaker
- Similar to Commodities Corporation's risk-control system (reining in traders after capital losses)

### Trading Reflexes and Instincts

- **Gary Gladstein** (Soros Fund Management, 1985-1999): "We had someone in for lunch in George's private dining room, upstairs on thirty-three, and something connected and he immediately just went over and picked up the phone and told the trader to put on a position.… He could completely reverse himself."

### The Plaza Accord (September 1985)

- Soros confessed he bought yen "by the skin of his teeth" before the Plaza Accord
- Critics wonder if Soros was tipped off about Plaza, perhaps by European banking sources
- But Soros bought yen massively **after** the Plaza announcement—proves he didn't see it coming
- **September 6, 1985**: Previous diary entry mentioned dollar shorts at baseline
- Buying occurred in the five days after Plaza

### Political Antennae as Edge

> "It's easier, in a way, to understand the mentality of the authorities than it is to understand the market, because the market is more anonymous.… So I would say, perhaps, that my application of boom-bust thinking has been in understanding how the authorities are acting more than the market itself." — George Soros

- Soros knew political leaders and economic officials
- **Richard Medley** organized a Washington conference (November 1985) featuring top policy makers from Plaza-accord countries
- Senator Bradley insisted Soros be allowed to attend despite the conference being oversold
- **Gary Gladstein**: "The board of Quantum was primarily European private bankers. They were very well connected, very well respected, and from time to time I know George would call them and ask them their thoughts."

### The Quantum Fund's Leverage After Plaza

- Additional buying between September 27 and December 6
- **Gary Gladstein** (joined October as chief administrative officer) was astonished by the portfolio leverage

### Soros on Soros

> "If a story is interesting enough, one can probably make money buying it even if further investigation would reveal flaws. Then later, if you discern the flaw, you feel good, because you are ahead of the game. So I used to say, 'Jump in with both feet; take one out later.'" — George Soros

### The Alchemy of Finance Reception

- **Anatole Kaletsky**, "Thursday Book Review: The Alchemy of Finance," *Financial Times*, July 16, 1987
- **Paul Tudor Jones**: "George Soros is one of the most profound thinkers in the markets. The book was a highly intricate piece of analytics. Looking at the interlocking relationships. He knitted things together; it was an education."
- **Jim Chanos**: The book "really went into the whole feedback loop on perceptions and how they are important in the marketplace. For the first time he put in what traders knew to be true, but in a framework that you could think about; that you could debate and test."
- **Scott Bessent** (later worked for Soros): "I remember in my twenties and I read this and couldn't believe someone would invest this way. You would have some of these and these, short some of those. His risk management was in his head. No fund-of-funds person would have given him any money."

### Soros's Office Culture

- **Jim Chanos** (operated out of Soros's offices late 1980s): "It was the quietest place you've ever heard. The most raucous you heard was during lunch, when people yelled at the cook for making jerk chicken for the second time that week.… Steinhardt was much different. People screaming. Michael firing people. It was truly a different atmosphere."

<!-- pp. 421-440 -->

## Chapter Five: Top Cat (Notes - continued)

### Julian Robertson and Tiger Management

- **Julian Robertson** built Tiger Management into one of the most successful hedge funds through stock-picking prowess combined with macro awareness
- Robertson's approach: influenced by **A.W. Jones**, who taught that stock selection could work even when market direction was uncertain—pick longs and shorts independently
- Between 1980-1997, Tiger beat the S&P 500 in 14 out of 18 years, with Tiger rising 21.6% in 1988 despite being less than 70% net long
- Tiger's performance relied on balance between long and short positions, not pure directional bets

### Tiger's Culture and Method

- Tiger operated as an open, collaborative trading floor—analysts sat in center of L-shaped room with constant information flow
- No privacy: expected arrival at 7 AM, departure at 5 PM, no personal calls—only discussing companies, ideas, industries, news
- Robertson encouraged vigorous debate: analysts would present bull and bear cases, Robertson made final call
- **Lou Ricciardelli** recruited from White House to Tiger
- Tiger created **Puma fund** in 1986 to accept money from well-connected businesspeople who wanted access—regulators never blocked this channel for information flow from company executives

> "Julian sat in the center of the L. It was just a blast. We were all close to one another, and Julian was right there. We all overheard each other's conversations. It was just a constant flow of information and ideas. And you had one of the greatest investors ever right there."

### Robertson's Management Style

- Extremely symmetrical in praise and criticism—lavish public praise for good work, aggressive confrontation for flawed analysis
- Called ideas either "best ever" or "worst ever"—no middle ground
- Despite stock-picking success, Dwight Anderson noted Robertson lacked 40 years of commodity/macro experience, relied heavily on analysts for those areas
- **Arnold Snider**, Tiger's drug-stock analyst, left in late 1993—marked beginning of series of high-profile departures

### The Small-Firm Effect and Market Efficiency

- **Small-firm effect**: mid-1970s research showed small company stocks outperformed large companies
- **January effect**: outperformance concentrated in first two weeks of January
- Both findings appeared to damage efficient-market theory—returns weren't supposed to reflect firm size or calendar vagaries
- Speculators arbitraged these anomalies away after discovery
- **G. William Schwert** (2002): small-firm effect disappeared, January effect halved since identification—confirming efficient-market predictions

## Chapter Six: Rock-and-Roll Cowboy

### Paul Tudor Jones II - The Trader

- 1984 survey identified only 68 hedge funds; estimated fewer than 100 existed 1973-87
- By 1990: hundreds of funds; by 1992: thousands
- **Ten billion-dollar funds** (1994): Big Three (Soros, Steinhardt, Robertson), Commodities Corporation trio (Odyssey Partners/Leon Levy & Jack Nash, Omega Partners/Leon Cooperman), Ardsley Partners/Philip Hempleman, John W. Henry

### Jones's Trading Philosophy - Assessing Human Psychology

- Jones focused on 30 years of consistent profits by "assessing human reaction" to information
- **Fear and hope** drive markets—Jones studied crowd psychology and positioning
- Key insight: understanding how many people hold the same position reveals vulnerability to sudden reversals
- If many traders are long the same position, reversal could get "very ugly very quickly"

### The Jones Pit Technique

- Jones would wait for quiet moment in trading pit, then scream as loud as possible that he's ready to sell huge quantity
- Started panic by "yelling fire in a movie theater"—everyone sells, creating the crescendo
- Jones then bought back what he sold at lower prices, completing the order
- **Physical presence in pit** gave psychological edge over remote traders

### Jones's Market Timing Philosophy

> "Under- or overvaluation is only part of the battle. The key thing is to be able to time one's entry into a position at the precise moment when the market is about to move in your favor. Markets can stay undervalued, say, for months and years at a time."

- Jones chose **technical analysis over fundamental analysis** when forced to pick
- Timing mattered more than valuation—don't waste resources in positions that might not move

### Predicting the 1987 Crash

- **Peter Borish**, Jones's 27-year-old research chief, tracked 1920s bull market against post-1982 bull market in April 1986
- Started both countdowns in February 1985 and October 1982—four years after sentiment lows (1921 recession, 1979 Carter financial crisis)
- Borish expected crash in **February 1988** initially; by June 1987 predicted it would come then
- **Portfolio insurance**: embedded derivatives that forced selling on every down-tick, creating cascade effect when stocks fell

### Jones and the 1987 Crash

- Jones made most profits going long the bond market (like **Louis Bacon**, who was up 40% in 1987)
- **Bruce Kovner** made more money on bond position after crash than from shorting stock market
- Jones understood the derivatives accident waiting to happen with portfolio insurance

### Japan Trade - 1990

- January 1990: short-term Japanese interest rates at 7.25%, longer bonds yielded considerably more
- **Barron's Roundtable** (February 1990): Jones correctly predicted Nikkei would rebound after falling to 36,500 (breakout point from previous November)
- Jones predicted weak rebound would lead to further falls
- **May 1990**: Jones predicted with "uncanny accuracy" that Japan had "long way to go yet on the downside"—slide wouldn't resume until late summer
- Jones predicted 20% fall in Nikkei would wipe out $800 billion of wealth (35% of Japan's GDP), triggering "enormous economic contraction"
- Japan's economy remained stagnant for much of the following decade

### Cotton Farmer Psychology

- Jones remembered **year-end hedge-selling pressure** by cotton farmers regardless of fundamental market conditions
- Farmers clung emotionally to hope that prices would improve if they waited
- "Those hopes were usually dashed, but the phenomenon gave us something to exploit"

### Visibility and Style

- Jones learned value of visibility from **Eli Tullis**, cotton trader mentor in New Orleans apprenticeship
- Tullis's attitude: "The hell with it, I'm going to take them head on"—everyone knew his position
- **1988 Wall Street Journal** profile captured Jones's dramatic pit trading on February 25 at Chicago Board of Trade Treasury bond futures pit
- Jones's trader appeared "gesturing frantically to sell all at once 1,000 contracts—with a face value of about $95 million"
- Local traders looked at each other: "Who's buying?" Answer: "Nobody"—drove price lower, Jones bought back cheaply
- Estimated profit: **$3 million**

> "The man is such a good psychological trader. He knows exactly when the market is acting exhausted so he can move in."

### James Elkins on Jones

- **James Elkins** (president of Elkins/McSherry) on Jones's timing: understanding when market exhaustion allows entry with minimal risk

<!-- pp. 441-460 -->

## Chapter Eight: Hurricane Greenspan (continued — endnotes)

### Soros Sterling Trade: Profit Estimates and Execution Details

- **Druckenmiller's recollection**: Soros's snide comment about loving the trade led to doubling position size, roughly doubling profit
- **Gerry Manolovici** (Soros equity specialist): After lira devaluation, Schlesinger said other countries missed devaluation opportunity — Soros "went nuts" scouring for credit to short
- Soros: "This is the moment, they are capitulating, go for the jugular" — both Soros and Druckenmiller made phone calls searching for counterparties
- **Druckenmiller**: "We really went after this thing and kept going and going like the Energizer bunny"
- Soros struggled to find counterparties willing to sell sterling — they had limits on exposure
- **Louis Bacon** on Soros calling him: "Having George talk was like having a demigod coming down from on high to talk to you"

### Sterling Profit Calculations

- **Total selling**: $27 billion (includes $4.1 billion by other central banks that would have to be repaid by Bank of England under ERM rules)
- **Sterling's fall**: 14% immediate, fluctuated around that through December (trough in March 1993 was 16% down, costing British taxpayers over $4 billion)
- **Estimates vary widely**:
  - Druckenmiller: Sold ~$7.5 billion on behalf of Quantum (excludes his side account)
  - Soros (one month later): Almost $10 billion total sterling sales
  - Former Soros employees give "substantially higher estimates"
- **Profit calculation**: If $10 billion position exited at 14% profit = **$1.4 billion**
- By late October, Soros's profits on sterling stood at **$950 million** (but he expected further falls, so eventual profit likely larger)

### Banks vs. Hedge Funds in Currency Markets

- **Key banks that lost**: Citicorp, J.P. Morgan, Chemical Banking, Bankers Trust, Chase Manhattan, First Chicago, Bank America
- **Hedge funds outperformed banks** despite managing far less capital
- **IMF Capital Markets report** (post-ERM collapse): Hedge fund positioning "served as a signal for other institutional fund managers to re-examine their own positions"
- IMF: "Although hedge funds have less than $10 billion in capital, their potential influence on forex markets [was] larger"
- Hedge funds were "leaders in the currency trades, with banks that executed their trades then copying them on their own books"

### Other Notable Trades

- **Swedish trade**: Conceived by **Robert Johnson**; kept secret ("By then at least we learned to keep our mouth shut")
- **France**: Soros warned **Jean-Claude Trichet** about franc vulnerability, chose not to take a position to maintain constructive relationship with French authorities

> "I warned him that he's liable to be attacked, and I said, 'I'd like to be helpful and therefore I will not take a position.' This had doubly unfortunate results: I lost what was a profit opportunity, and I annoyed the French authorities even more with my comments than I would have done by speculating against the franc." — George Soros

- Soros lesson: **"Speculators ought to keep quiet and speculate"**

> "I fight for many causes in my life, but I don't particularly feel like defending currency speculation." — George Soros

