## Chapter Eight: Hurricane Greenspan (endnotes begin)

### Michael Steinhardt's 1994 Crisis

- **Background**: Early shadowbanks focused on government bond market (later made loans to companies/home buyers)
- **Broker leverage**: Goldman Sachs provided Steinhardt leverage "overjoyedly"
- Steinhardt's leverage on **U.S. government bonds** was "exceptionally high"; European bonds ~20:1; overall fund leverage likely <10:1
- **Goldman partner**: Leon Cooperman (formerly asset management boss); **Salomon partner**: Stanley Shopkorn (head of equity trading)

### Hedge Fund Industry Size (1993-1994)

- Estimate: **~3,000 hedge funds** (from International Advisory Group, Nashville)
- This excluded offshore funds
- **John Meriwether** left Salomon Brothers in 1993, raised **$1.2 billion** for **Long-Term Capital Management**

### Greenspan's 1994 Rate Hikes

- January 31, 1994 Congressional testimony warned of **rate hike** coming
- **Greenspan's message**: "It was like banging a pot" — unusually explicit
- **Vincent Reinhart** (senior Fed economist): Greenspan's anticipation of equity-market reactions matched by surprise at bond market response
- **February 3-4, 1994**: Federal Open Market Committee transcript shows rate decision
- **By February 8**: Ten-year bond yield jumped to **5.98%** (24 basis points up from month start)

### Quantum Fund's 1993-1994 Performance

- **1993**: Big profits on yen-dollar rate; acutely sensitive to exchange rate/trade talk links
- **January 1994**: Druckenmiller's bet against yen worth **$25 billion** — demonstrated confidence and Quantum's rapid growth since sterling
- **Yen trade blew up in February** — fortunate Druckenmiller sold European bonds in January 1994
- Combined with successful copper trade, survived turbulent 1994 without losses
- **February 11-15**: Ten-year Treasury yield moved from 5.88% to 6.20%

### Steinhardt's Bond Market Losses

- **March 3, 1994**: Wall Street Journal reported Steinhardt took "Big Hit" from bets on foreign debt
- **European risk**: $7 million per basis point (some reports lower, but Steinhardt's autobiography figure taken as authoritative)
- **Steinhardt**: "We were losing money and I couldn't quite catch my breath... It was as if we were playing yesterday's or last year's game"
- **John Lattanzio**: "Michael being very upset. I just want to sell them. I just want out. It's over, just sell them. And the guy not being able to execute it and sell them"

### Steinhardt's Knowledge Gap

> "My great problem, as humbly acknowledged, was I didn't know what I was talking about. I didn't know the names of the securities, the names of the French ten-years... I didn't know who made the markets and all this other stuff... I didn't know that there could be substantial differences between the French bonds and the Germans and the gilts and the Americans... Was I ever dumb and cocky." — Michael Steinhardt

### David Askin's Collapse

- **Askin's claim**: "Most managers are not as comfortable as we are with prepayment risk, nor the structural risk inherent in this market. We understand it, we can measure it, and we can hedge it"
- **Bankruptcy trustee finding**: Askin **lacked analytical models** to determine if portfolio was market neutral
- **No evidence** of proprietary prepayment model on Askin's computer; no employee could verify its existence
- When Askin tried to accept low prices for securities, **impossible to unwind**: Instruments held by other brokers as collateral, brokers had hedged with offsetting trades too complex to unwind

### Political Response to 1994 Bond Crisis

- **Al Ehrbar** (Fortune): "The Great Bond Market Massacre"
- **Greenspan** (February 28, 1994): "We had a far greater impact than anticipated"
- **Vincent Reinhart**: Blinder's protest against "yellow suspenders" (hedge fund traders)
- **President's Working Group on Financial Markets** (September 27, 1994): Report on market price dynamics and systemic risk
- **Congressional hearings planned** on hedge funds (March-April 1994)
- Paper by **Don R. Hays** (Wheat First Securities) circulated April 5, 1994

### Steinhardt's 1994 Struggles Continue

> "I was really miserable. And I was miserable, I would say, in the second quarter and into the third quarter. I couldn't get out of it, even when I was pretty much out of the bonds, I couldn't ever quite mount a successful offensive. Every time I started something, it just didn't work." — Michael Steinhardt

- **Employee account**: Steinhardt would "intellectually hedge himself" — dismiss trader's idea as "dumbest idea he's ever heard," then say "do whatever you want" and leave, creating no-win situation
- **1995 reported earnings**: $500 million (but Steinhardt's records show 26.8% returns on $2.7 billion assets = **over $700 million profit**)
- **Commentary claim** that 1994 losses outweighed career gains is **not borne out** by internal records

### Hedge Fund Withdrawals (1995)

- **Forbes** (September 26, 1994): "Alan Greenspan pushed Michael Steinhardt—and a lot of other hedge fund operators into a corner. Many of them will not survive. Will Steinhardt?"
- **Bruce Kovner** (June 1995): Returned **$1.3 billion** of Caxton's $1.8 billion AUM after closing two foreign funds ($800M GAM fund, $450M U.S. fund)
  - Stated: "The lower liquidity in currency, fixed-income, and commodity markets hurt our performance"
- **Louis Bacon's Moore Capital**: Also suffered withdrawals; poor performance compounded by acrimonious split with senior lieutenant
- **Quantum**: "We find that our size is hindering us" — Soros also experienced client difficulties

### Academic Research on Hedge Fund Performance

- **Inverse correlation**: Size and investment returns negatively correlated (later research finding)
- **PerTrac Financial Solutions** (2009): Hedge funds managing <$100M made 13% annually (1996-2008) vs. 10% for those running >$500M
- **Republic New York Securities survey** (130 hedge funds): Five-year performance data
- **Yale School of Management study** (offshore hedge funds, 1989-1995):
  - Returned 13.3% vs. S&P 500's 16.5%
  - **Much less risky**: Annual standard deviation 6.1% vs. 16.3% for S&P 500
  - S&P 500 stock index swings explained only 36% of hedge fund swings
- **Franklin R. Edwards study** (1989-1998, overlapping period):
  - Hedge fund volatility: 5.75% (equally weighted) and 8.94% (value weighted)
  - S&P 500 standard deviation: 13.2%
  - **Positive finding for hedge-fund alpha** reported in conclusion

