## Chapter Nine: Soros Versus Soros

### Russia's Transition and Norilsk

- **Norilsk**: "Stalin's Siberian Hell" — thrived despite hideous legacy
- Russian companies built on "bones" of forced labor; ability to profit from privatization
- **Paul Tudor Jones**: "I cross myself every time I think about that helicopter ride"
- **Thorpe McKenzie** and **Dwight Anderson** interviews

### Emerging Markets and Capital Flows

- **Arturo Porzecanski** (Kidder Peabody, 1993): Only hedge funds willing to overlook Peru's default record and buy debt
- **Peter Henry** (Stanford, 2007 article): Challenged pessimistic consensus on capital-account openness
  - Previous tests found **little relationship** between capital market openness and growth
  - **Henry's insight**: Test was wrong — letting in foreign capital creates **one-off lowering of borrowing cost**, not permanent acceleration
  - Should expect **permanent increase in income level**, not growth rate
  - **Temporary growth effects were powerful**: In 3 years after stock market opening, average annual growth of real wages in manufacturing increased **7x**
  - Control group (economies that didn't open) experienced **no wage acceleration**
- **Ross Levine, Norman Loayza, Thorsten Beck** study: Doubling private credit in average developing country = **2 percentage point rise in annual economic growth**
  - After 35 years, economy would be **twice as large** as without ample borrowing opportunities

### Soros Fund Management's Asian Crisis Involvement

- Data from **Gary Gladstein** (former CAO and managing director)
- **Arminio Fraga** interviews
- **Graciela Kaminsky and Carmen Reinhart** paper (Federal Reserve and IMF) published in *American Economic Review*

### Thailand Crisis (January-February 1997)

- **Participant quote**: "It was really kind of a bombshell statement to make. Talk about being pathetically ignorant when you say that to the three guys from Soros"
- **Rodney Jones**: Confident Soros team established initial position in **late January** (sources differ on late Jan vs. early Feb timing)
- **Bank of Thailand data**: Full measure of reserves (includes forward-market operations) fell **$4.4 billion in February**
  - No forward data for January, but **$2 billion sale by Soros Fund Management** appears to have driven substantial proportion of Thai reserve decline
- **Druckenmiller**: "When I shorted it, it cost nothing. Like the British pound the first time, like half a percent"

### Soros's Internal Debate on Thailand

- **Rodney Jones memo** (February 12, 1997): Laid out Thailand's acute vulnerability
  - Thai central bank held only **$36 billion in reserves**
  - Private sector owed **$85 billion** to foreigners who would want money out in panic
  - Implied determined attack on baht would quickly force devaluation
- **Robert Johnson** (economist who advised on sterling): Ran into Soros at Davos end of January 1997, appeared unsure whether Thai trade worth bothering with
- Soros not paying sufficient attention to repeat 1992 "go for the jugular" moment

> "By selling the Thai baht short in January 1997, the Quantum Funds managed by my investment company sent a signal that it may be overvalued. Had the authorities responded, the adjustment would have occurred sooner and it would have been less painful. As it is, the authorities resisted and when the break came it was catastrophic." — George Soros, *The Crisis of Global Capitalism*

### Tiger Fund's Thailand Position

- **Contact confirmed** between Druckenmiller and **Paul Jones**
- **Tiger's position size**: Recalled by **Dan Morehead** (executed Tiger's macro trades) and **Rob Citrone** (Tiger's macro analyst, thinks position was "considerably larger—as big as $5 billion")
  - Traders more likely to know real position than analysts
- **May 14 reserve leakage**: **Rodney Jones** put at $6.5 billion
- **Paul Blustein**: $10 billion (total loss of reserves in all of May = $18.3 billion per Thai central bank data)
- **Rodney Jones**: Soros didn't go bigger due to "fear of crazy reaction" — couldn't be sized as aggressively as sterling (developing country, harder to understand reaction function)
- **David Kowitz**: Worried about government countermeasures in February — "They were shooting bullets at us... It was a bit stressful, and I probably would've folded, but Stan Druckenmiller, he doubled down. It was a famous call"

### Soros Team's Baht Profits

- **Dan Morehead calculation**: Tiger's $1 billion selling would have accounted for **2/3 of reserve decline** on last day before peg broke (akin to Quantum's role in sterling 1992)
- **Soros team sales**: $500M of baht position in June 1997, $2.5B in Aug-Sep, another $500M toward year-end
  - Positions created around Jan 20-24 ($2B) and May 14-15 ($1.5B)
  - Using average exchange rates for six-month forward market: **Total earnings ~$750 million**
- **Tiger's profit estimate** (per Dan Morehead): Also ~$750M, though **Rob Citrone** believes profits exceeded $1 billion

### Soros's Broader Asian Strategy and Criticism

- **David Kowitz**: Soros "wants to be remembered as a great statesman. Being blamed for the destruction of pathetic third-world countries wasn't helpful for that"
- **September 21, 1997** (Hong Kong speech): Soros revealed Quantum was **long the rupiah**, explaining markets overshot on Indonesia and Indonesian government's consistent reform gave him confidence
- **Kowitz**: Reflecting on rupiah trade — "We often heard 'These big speculators can go into these small markets and manipulate them for their profit,' but we never saw it that way. For us it was always extremely dangerous"
- **Druckenmiller and Fraga**: Earned $200-300M on smaller Asian currency trades in 1997 — Asian calls made money even though Thailand and Indonesia roughly canceled out
  - Most important smaller trade: **Short position on Malaysian ringgit** worth $1.5B (took profits early when ringgit started falling)

### IMF and Korean Crisis

- **Arminio Fraga** called **Stan Fisher** (IMF #2) after visiting Korea in November
- Fisher: IMF staff had been there and "don't think this is a problem"
- **Edwin Truman** (Federal Reserve): Was in Seoul with Fisher shortly after Jones's visit — by then Fisher knew South Korea was in trouble (less likely his influence accounts for Quantum team's reluctance to short)

### Soros's Reputation Damage

- **Robert Johnson**: "George's purpose for years was production, and it moved to distribution. He was intuitively a speculator, but his heart was all tied up in his philanthropy"
- **Rodney Jones**: "Mahathir had done psychological damage. Soros no longer wanted to be the bad speculator"
- **Robert Johnson on Malaysia**: George accused of being Trojan horse — philanthropy in eastern Europe seen as cover for pecuniary gain
  - "Very sensitive about that. If the president invited him to Korea and then he bounced Korea, it would create a scar that might be permanent"
  - "Never went to Malaysia until well after the argument with Mahathir"
  - Once showed up in official capacity, "started blanking out that part of the grid for those who were taking positions"

### South Korea Post-Crisis

- **Soros statement** (January 6, 1998): Called Korean crisis "fixable"
- **KOSPI index**: Rose from 396 to 506 between January 5-15
- **Michael T. Kaufman**: *Soros: The Life and Times of a Messianic Billionaire*

### Svyazinvest Investment

- **Gary Gladstein** (managing director, Soros Fund Management): "That was a terrible investment. We didn't do much due diligence on it. George decided he wanted to take a position, because George operates from his gut and he felt good about it at the time"
- Soros (looking back): Calls secret loan to Russia "a somewhat questionable maneuver"

> "I got involved because I was, in effect, betting the government was making the transition from robber capitalism to legitimate capitalism... I was combining two considerations—a political one, which was to help to transform the economy into legitimate capitalism, and a financial one, which was to make a profit. Obviously, they didn't combine well." — George Soros

- **Robert Johnson**: "He felt that if he was a beacon of investment in Russia, others would follow and the capital inflows would transform the society and integrate them into the here's a philanthropic side of George that started to interfere with the speculative one"

### Russia Collapse

- **Julian Robertson** (July 7, 1998 letter to investors): "With yields at 102 percent, we are being well paid to take the risks of owning sovereign Russian debt"
- **Dwight Anderson** interviews on Russia

